<html><head><title>Is Kohl in control?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>

<h1 align=center>Is Kohl in control?</h1>


<br>HELMUT KOHL has long made it clear what he hopes his place in history will be. Of course he wants to be remembered as the chancellor who united Germany--but even more than that, he wants to be recognised as the statesman who did most at the end of the 20th century to bring Europe closer together. If economic and monetary union (<font size=-1>EMU</font>) happens, and proves a success, that ambition will be fulfilled: the largest share of the credit will indeed be due to him. But there is another side to the euro. If <font size=-1>EMU</font> doesn't happen, or goes forward but proves a failure, that will just as surely be Chancellor Kohl's doing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The possibility that <font size=-1>EMU</font> might be postponed, or even abandoned, seemed more thinkable this week than for some time. For the moment, it remains only that, a possibility. Financial markets still predict that the single European currency will arrive on schedule. But the difficulties ahead are greater than the markets appear to think. What is clearer than before is the scale of the challenge confronting Mr Kohl himself, not so much in Europe as at home in Germany.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Germany's latest unemployment figures, released last week, were startling. They showed a rise of 510,000 in the space of a single month, bringing the total to 4.7m, more than 12% of the workforce. True, these "unadjusted" figures need to be heavily qualified. Normal seasonal adjustment brings the monthly rise down to 160,000; Germany has had an unusually cold winter; other special factors, including a change in tax allowances, may also have helped to inflate the total. Nonetheless, the figure was worse than the gloomiest prediction and dreadful by any standard. The German economy is even weaker than had been supposed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This has great implications for <font size=-1>EMU</font>. A crucial question throughout, posed now with added urgency, is this: how much longer can <font size=-1>EMU</font> float silently above the fray of German politics? The opposition blames unemployment on the government's austerity measures--but few as yet draw the obvious connection between those policies and the government's determination to meet the target for public borrowing in the Maastricht treaty. If unemployment climbs towards 5m, more politicians will surely begin to calculate that there are votes in attacking <font size=-1>EMU</font> in its own right. Recent polls show that the <font size=-1>SPD</font> has drawn level with Mr Kohl's <font size=-1>CDU</font>, and that the <font size=-1>SPD</font>'s most popular politician is Gerhard Schr&ouml;der, an <font size=-1>EMU</font>-doubter. If Mr Schr&ouml;der becomes the party's candidate for chancellor in the election of autumn 1998, he could conceivably make that vote a referendum on the single currency.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Meanwhile, Germany's economic problems interact with the Maastricht plan in another way, only adding to Mr Kohl's difficulties. The treaty's target for public borrowing this year is 3% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>. Recently, but before the new unemployment figures were known, Germany's government increased its forecast for the deficit to 2.9% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>--a hair's breadth below the permitted ceiling. Again before the new unemployment figures, forecasters at the <font size=-1>OECD</font> said they expected Germany's deficit to be 3.4% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> this year. On the government's own calculations, it seems, the target will now be difficult to reach; on everybody else's, more than just difficult.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This matters not because the deficit target reflects some pressing economic need. Judged in narrow economic terms, in fact, the deficit-ceiling is not merely unnecessary but positively dangerous. And it was already clear that if <font size=-1>EMU</font> were to go ahead, at least one of the Maastricht criteria (the one for public debt) would have to be all but ignored. Germany's fiscal embarrassment matters for another reason: it will affect the politics of <font size=-1>EMU</font>. Mr Kohl had presumably been counting on Germany's meeting the borrowing target. He could then have insisted that it be applied somewhat rigorously to others. That would have made it easier to keep Italy out, at least to begin with, making <font size=-1>EMU</font> more palatable to German opinion. Now it begins to look as though Mr Kohl may have to choose between waiving the deficit criterion, in which case Germans may ask whether <font size=-1>EMU</font> is such a good idea after all, or insisting upon a strict interpretation of the target, in which case the start of <font size=-1>EMU</font> would have to be put back.
<br></p><p><b><b>What Maastricht hath decreed</b>
</b><br>This last possibility is one that Europe's officials cannot yet bring themselves to contemplate (see <a href="eu6364.html">page</a>). They insist that the treaty has spoken, and that is that. In fact, the treaty seems to say that if Germany's borrowing exceeds 3% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> next year, <font size=-1>EMU</font> should go ahead without Germany. (No provision allows Ireland, Finland, Luxembourg and the Netherlands, all well-placed to qualify, to hang on until Germany and France are ready.) But this too, of course, is unthinkable. So Europe's <font size=-1>EMU</font> planners remain frozen in their accustomed state of intellectual paralysis: bound to do something they may well be unable to do, forbidden therefore to start asking what might be done instead. A postponement would be risky in several ways, but it would at least give Europe's policymakers an opportunity to review and improve their present flawed design.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The dilemma that may soon face Chancellor Kohl is of his own devising. Whenever he has confronted a great issue, he has done the same: establish a point of no return, march past it, never mind about popularity and let the details take care of themselves. This was how he dealt with Germany's relationship with the West when he first came to power. Then he applied the method to German unification. Now he is trying to do the same with <font size=-1>EMU</font>. The drawbacks of pressing on regardless have become all too clear in eastern Germany: the "detail" of converting Ostmarks at the wrong rate has cost hundreds of thousands of jobs. With a certain justice, the economic implications of that mistake have now come to haunt the chancellor as he surges on with his third and greatest task, and may in the end be instrumental in defeating him.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Once more, says Mr Kohl, concentrate on the vision, and see to the details later. As their economy reels, Germany's voters may yet decide that <font size=-1>EMU</font> is one vision too many.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
