<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>A fast buck
</h2>(See <a href="bw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>The ascent of the <b>dollar</b> paused after finance ministers and central bankers from the Group of Seven rich countries, meeting in Berlin, declared that its two-year recovery and recent sharper climb had gone far enough. But the impact of their words, backed by no action, was short-lived: by February 12th the dollar had reached a 34-month high against the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark. Sterling also rose against the German currency, reaching a four-year high. 
<p>The <b>Dow Jones</b> industrial average hit a record high. In Tokyo even the Nikkei perked up. Meanwhile Japanese investors have been flocking abroad. In 1996 they bought a vast quantity of foreign bonds, and some shares, spending in the process a net &#165;9.33 trillion ($75 billion), the most in five years and 20% more than in 1995.
<p>Can the American economy do no wrong? In the United States <b>business productivity</b>jumped in the fourth quarter by 2.2% at an annual rate after a flat third quarter, the biggest improvement in four years (though for the year it was a sluggish 0.8%). Business failures were stable for a third year. The rise in unit labour costs slowed to 1.4%, and despite more jobs the unemployment rate ticked up in January from 5.3% to 5.4%, nearing the 5.5% minimum considered necessary to keep inflation at bay.
<p><h2>Changing course
</h2><b>Big tobacco </b>is looking more favourably on the notion of a cash settlement with its legal tormentors. The chief executive of <font size=-1>B.A.T</font> said in a television interview that the British tobacco company might consider a settlement in return for "a peaceful life". But it is not peace yet. In North Carolina this week American tobacco firms challenged the right of the Food and Drug Administration to clamp strict new limits on the sale of cigarettes to young people.
<p><b>Pearson</b>, a British media group and part-owner of <i>The Economist</i>,<i> </i>said improper accounting at an American publishing subsidiary may knock &#163;100m ($163m) off 1996 profits. 
<p>Anglo-Dutch <b>Unilever</b> announced record earnings. But it has also put its profitable specialty chemicals businesses up for sale, a divestment that could yield &#163;5 billion ($8 billion), to concentrate on its core consumer products and food operations. Unilever's pre-tax profits rose 15% to &#163;2.66 billion last year. 
<p>In America <b>ITT</b> appeared to be mobilising to fight off last month's $6.5 billion takeover bid by Hilton Hotels. <font size=-1>ITT</font> rejected Hilton's offer and said it might sell some inessential assets to raise the value of the company and sharpen its focus on gaming and lodging. One item in the <font size=-1>ITT</font> portfolio that may be for sale is New York's Madison Square Garden entertainment complex.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Westinghouse Electric</b> came close to completing its long-term plan to shed its industrial past and turn itself into a leading entertainment and media group in America, with the purchase of two country-music cable channels for $1.55 billion. The purchase gives Westinghouse's <font size=-1>CBS</font> television network a belated move into cable and also close links to Gaylord, which owns the Grand Ole Opry in Nashville.
<p>Only in France, perhaps, could a privatisation get so muddled. Lagard&egrave;re, the winner in last year's contest to take over <b>Thomson-CSF</b>, a state-owned defence-electronics firm, has complained to the Council of State about the way its bid was handled. Its victory was snatched away after a public outcry at its plans to sell Thomson's multimedia arm to a South Korean firm.
<p><b>Western Resources</b> won its hostile $2 billion bid for rival Kansas City Power & Light to create a power utility with 2m customers and $3 billion in revenues. But Western's hostile $3.5 billion offer for <font size=-1>ADT</font> is going less well. The home-security company filed a lawsuit attacking its bank, Chase Manhattan, for supporting the bid.
<p><b>Jan Timmer</b>, who brought Philips back from the brink of bankruptcy, quit the supervisory board to which he was appointed only a few months ago after Cor Boonstra took over the job of president. Philips reported a loss of 591m guilders ($312m) in 1996, after three years of profits. 
<p>The European Commission has begun an investigation into sales practices used by <b>Michelin</b> after allegations that the French tyre group is using its dominant position in France and other European countries to tie dealers to its products.<WWHead><p><b>Jammed Airways</b></p>
<p><b>British Airways</b> marked its ten years as a private company with a record third-quarter pre-tax profits of &#163;113m ($185m), up 8.7% over the 1995 period. It also celebrated with &#163;10 Concorde tickets. 
<p>Nine airlines, headed by United Airlines and Lufthansa, are forming a global alliance to counter the proposed pact between <b>British Airways</b> and <b>American Airlines</b>. The participating carriers may offer a single frequent-flyer programme, together with joint reservations. American Airlines was meanwhile bracing itself for a possible strike after its pilots rejected a pay offer.
<p>Spain's state-owned airline, <b>Iberia</b>, produced a three-year plan in its march towards privatisation, aimed at raising productivity by more than 40% and cutting costs. The Italian government said that <b>Alitalia</b>'s losses in 1996 would amount to around 1.3 trillion lire ($788m).
<p>If you are going to have bad luck, have it in America. A biker who said the cruise control of his <b>Harley Davidson</b> jammed, causing him serious injury, was awarded a nifty $9.9m in compensatory damages against the company by a Superior Court jury in New Jersey.

</td></tr></table></center>
