<html><head><title>Dan Coats, senator for charity</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

LEXINGTON
<h1>Dan Coats, senator for charity</h1>

IN A time of soundbites and vanity, of cynical venality, it makes a change to meet Dan Coats. Rather than talk in slogans, this senator speaks like the insurance lawyer he once was. Rather than grab the spotlight, he has contrived to hide in the shadows of two other Indiana Republicans, Dan Quayle and Richard Lugar: quite an achievement, really, when you consider how small those shadows are. Far from being venal, Mr Coats recently announced that, rather than beg for money for his re-election campaign, he would give up his Senate seat in 1998. And, far from being cynical, Mr Coats devotes his energy to a Utopian idea: that charities and volunteer enthusiasm can break the back of poverty. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All of a sudden, this has made him a hot figure. Back in 1995, when Mr Coats suggested using tax credits to reimburse people who give to anti-poverty charities, almost nobody took notice. In early 1996, only one serious candidate (Lamar Alexander) echoed Mr Coats's views. Towards the end of the campaign, Bob Dole did embrace a modest charity break. But right up until election day, as one Coats staffer says, "We were pretty lonely."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No longer. In January Mr Coats announced a grand "Renewal Alliance", featuring 21 congressmen who aim to shift the fight against poverty away from government and towards churches and voluntary organisations. Outside Congress, three prominent Republicans (Mr Alexander, Mr Quayle and William Bennett) have launched their separate schemes to privatise compassion too. Not to be outdone, Bill Clinton is planning a summit on volunteerism for the spring. It will feature three ex-presidents (George Bush, Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter) and one near-president (Colin Powell, who will be in charge), as well as one currently in office. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the face of it, this charity-fest seems odd. Politicians run governments; but charities are proud of their status as non-governmental organisations. Politicians have the power to demand taxes and make laws; the whole point of volunteerism is that it is voluntary. Politicians need to get elected, and for this they need cash; so most of their policies are designed to help the middle class and moneyed lobbies, not charities. And yet, despite these awkward facts, Mr Coats's unaccustomed prominence could have been predicted.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After Ronald Reagan's crusade against the state, George Bush tried to round out the Republican message by promoting volunteerism. Now, after Newt Gingrich's anti-government drive, Republicans want to sound cuddly and positive, not negative and mean; helping charities take over the job left by government's retreat is the perfect way to do this. The Coats idea allows Republicans to be for small government and big-heartedness at the same time. Rather than send taxes to Washington's bureaucracy, send your money to a friendly charity, they cry; close the sluggish Department of Housing and Urban Development, but let the home-building volunteers of Habitat for Humanity multiply. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This makes for winning rhetoric. And, up to a point, it makes for winning policy. In recent years, social scientists have stressed that government should think about the moral consequences of what it does, not just the material ones. The needy do not merely require shelter and food; if they are to fend for themselves, they must be encouraged to acquire a taste for work and discipline. The trouble is that, though this may be true, government cannot foist its morals on the poor without compromising liberty. This is where charities come in. Unlike government, they are powerless to compel involvement; because of this, they can insist on moral standards from those they help without infringing freedom. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is a marvellous thing. By championing charities, Americans may resolve the dilemma at the heart of modern liberalism: how to reconcile liberty with authority, social tolerance with social discipline. According to the conventional wisdom, this dilemma threatens to divide the Republican Party into warring camps. Yet moralism and freedom come together in Mr Coats's emphasis on charities.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So much for theory. The question is whether charities are really better at tackling poverty than government. They have the freedom to impose morality, which is good. But they lack economies of scale. Many charities spend a quarter of their budgets on fund-raising and other administrative costs. The Department of Health and Human Services, by contrast, claims that such costs account for less than 5% of its anti-poverty spending. Mr Coats retorts that charities can draw on the unpaid zeal of volunteers. If a charity's "budget" included not merely financial contributions but free labour and gifts in kind, the chunk taken by fund-raising might suddenly look puny. "Just visit the Gospel Mission, five blocks from here," the senator declares. "See for yourself if charities are inefficient!"
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And so, on a cold Washington night, Lexington walked into a run-down hall, filled with former crack addicts in various stages of rehabilitation. The boss is a doctor who has turned to charitable work out of Christian zeal; the doctor's wife has put her heart into redecorating the drab rooms; upstairs volunteers teach computer skills; a toothless man, dragged off the street in a drunken coma just a year ago, repays the institution that dried him out by cooking everybody supper. On a budget of just $1m a year, the mission treats and houses 120 addicts at a time, and offers free classes to 500 others. Touring this mission, it is impossible not to hope that tax credits would help its work. After 30 years of government-led efforts to eradicate poverty, it is time to try something different. 
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?855968400,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
