<html><head><title>Ecuador's post-modern coup</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/ir.gif" width="224" height="26" alt="International" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Ecuador's post-modern coup</h1>

<font size=1>QUITO
</font><p>THE people of Latin America will put up with austerity, but not when it is meted out by populists who also seem arrogantly and ostentatiously corrupt. That combination caused the downfall of Brazil's Fernando Collor in 1992, and of Venezuela's Carlos Andres Perez a year later. Now it has undone a third elected president, Ecuador's Abdala Bucaram.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Only six months into office, and within weeks of launching a harsh economic stabilisation plan, he was suddenly bundled out. With the country paralysed by a general strike, massively backed by business as well as labour, on February 6th Congress voted, by 44 votes to 34, to sack Mr Bucaram for "mental incapacity". It used to be generals who ousted Latin American presidents. This time, the army, after a brief show of support round the presidential palace, decided not to use force to sustain Mr Bucaram, and he was doomed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The strongest claimant to his job was Rosalia Arteaga, his vice-president, who at the army's urging had briefly taken over. But after hectic backroom negotiations, Congress repeated (by 57 votes out of 82) an earlier decision to appoint its own speaker, Fabian Alarcon. A smooth Quito lawyer and professional politician of the elastic centre, he is required to hold a presidential election within 12 months, though he will stay in office till August 1998. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In all this, the army showed more respect for the constitution than did Congress, listening harder to public opinion and the ambitions of its members. It could have impeached Mr Bucaram, but that would have taken time and a two-thirds majority, which his enemies initially lacked. A speedy simple-majority vote to sack him for "mental incapacity" was easier. Mr Bucaram may have rejoiced to be known as <i>El Loco</i>, the madman; but he was sane enough in pointing out that "Congress is not a psychiatrist". And in brushing aside Ms Arteaga, Congress at best--and she, another lawyer, denied even that--was exploiting a drafting error in the constitution, which specifies that the vice-president takes over if a president is temporarily unable to act, but does not say who should if that inability is permanent. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Legally dubious as it was, Mr Bucaram's overthrow was overwhelmingly popular. A thuggish and vulgar populist from the port of Guayaquil, who delighted in insulting his opponents, his election last year (with 54% of the votes in a run-off) was a slap in the face for Ecuador's political establishment. But in six months he managed to unite almost all the country against him. Partly that was because he opted for drastic economic surgery, including hefty rises in the subsidised prices of cooking gas, electricity and petrol as part of a plan that was meant to culminate in an Argentine-style fixed exchange rate--an idea which few economists thought right for Ecuador. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This hit Ecuador's poor majority hard. Worse still, Mr Bucaram also presided over rampant and highly visible cronyism and corruption. The American ambassador last month complained publicly that demands for backhanders for customs clearance and contracts would deter foreign investment; a statement which, even if unintendedly, seems to have galvanised the political elite into action against Mr Bucaram.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet his removal does not solve Ecuador's problems. Indeed, it may have made some of them worse. On paper Mr Alarcon has the support of parties across the spectrum. But their commitment may prove shallow--especially if he tries to take the tough decisions needed to stabilise the economy. Apart from ordering the army to take over the customs administration, his first measure was to revoke Mr Bucaram's subsidy cuts--while in the same breath calling on Ecuadoreans to prepare for "sacrifices", a call that got a dusty answer from the unions. Francisco Swett, an economic consultant, reckons that if nothing is done to reduce a fiscal deficit heading for 5% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>, inflation will double this year to 50% and growth could be negative.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Alarcon's supporters claim that the negotiating skills that landed him his new job will enable him to achieve the policy consensus that Mr Bucaram never bothered to seek. That could allow Ecuador to continue to muddle through. But rather than back-room deals, the country needs thoroughgoing reform. A deeply conservative place, it has avoided the guerrilla wars, political violence and large-scale drug trafficking that plague its larger neighbours, Colombia and Peru. But it remains an economic backwater. And its political system is chaotic, with 14 parties holding seats in the 82-member Congress, deep regional cleavages (notably between Guayaquil and inland, mountainous Quito), and frequent clashes between legislature and executive. Almost heedless of the constitution as they replaced Mr Bucaram, Mr Alarcon and his backers have to earn legitimacy through delivering better government. If they fail, Ecuadoreans may yet come to see Mr Bucaram as a martyr.
<br>
<br>
