<html><head><title>Sweating for that euro</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/eu.gif" width="105" height="26" alt="Europe" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Sweating for that euro</h1>

<font size=1>BRUSSELS
</font><p><p><b>Behind a front of grim optimism, some of the single currency's keenest
<br>proponents are starting to doubt that it will take shape on time</b></p>
<br>IT IS so hard to keep saying nothing. The chief engineers of Europe's single currency still intone the mantra that, under the Maastricht treaty, it will start life on January 1st 1999, and that all European Union countries meeting the treaty's "convergence criteria" (except for Britain and Denmark, which can "opt out" if they wish) will adopt it. The business of deciding who qualifies will take place in early 1998, on the basis of economic figures for 1997. The grim word from the European Commission is that it will apply "the treaty, the whole treaty and nothing but the treaty."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet the silence is becoming untenable in the face of a steady drip of contrary speculation--and figures that can no longer be wished away. Plans to exclude Italy and the other Mediterranean countries from the first wave of the euro are discovered, discussed and disowned. New--often conflicting--economic figures are released almost every week. A seemingly endless string of gambits are proposed by France, Belgium, Italy and the rest to massage their debt figures and squeeze their 1997 budget deficits below the Maastricht ceiling of 3% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>; so far, the Union's compliant statisticians have been loth to cry foul, though there remains some doubt about whether Italy's partially repayable euro tax, designed to raise 0.6% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> in 1997, will pass muster. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The latest bombshell was, however, not detonated by any of the usual suspects but by the most important, and seemingly most dependable, country of all, Germany. A huge jump in German unemployment in January to 4.7m, 12% of the workforce, has pushed the total well above the assumptions in German economic forecasts for the year. Those forecasts had already been revised upwards to show a budget deficit of 2.9%, barely below the Maastricht ceiling. After the January jump in unemployment, hardly any independent forecasters expect this year's budget deficit to be under 3%; most predict 3.5% or more. In addition, Germany looks highly unlikely to meet the debt criterion: even the most elastic interpretation, which would waive the 60%-of-<font size=-1>GDP</font> minimum requirement so long as the figures are moving the right way, cannot do the trick. Germany's public debt has been steadily rising for the past five years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The falling <font size=-1>D</font>-mark may still rescue the German economy; some commission insiders say they expect it to boost <font size=-1>GDP</font> by 0.4%. But given high unemployment and a faltering recovery, it will be exceptionally hard for the government to cut spending or raise taxes any further--indeed, it plans to reduce taxes. Worse, German ministers have repeatedly insisted that the 3% Maastricht ceiling must be rigidly adhered to, even though the wording of the treaty is sufficiently vague to allow let-outs if an excess is deemed temporary and exceptional. It might be possible to "fine-tune" the numbers to below 3%. But the risk is that Germany, which largely devised the Maastricht criteria, could be hoist with its own petard.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A single currency without Germany is, of course, unthinkable. So if the German deficit figures for 1997 prove intractable, the wiggle room in the treaty may have to be used. But there are two big snags. One is that the German constitutional court insisted, when it approved the ratification of the Maastricht treaty, that the convergence criteria should be strictly applied--so any fiddles would be likely to prompt swift court challenges. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Far more difficult, however, is the second snag: the ambitions of Spain, Portugal and Italy to join in the first wave. Germany's declared position on this is studiously neutral. But German bankers and even ministers privately make little secret of their determination that Italy, at least, and probably Spain and Portugal too, should be kept out. Indeed, the criteria were partly designed to this very end. Letting in these countries, many German officials feel, could fatally weaken the euro and make it far harder to sell the abandonment of the beloved <font size=-1>D</font>-mark to the German public.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until recently, the Germans had hoped that some figleaf--an undertaking, for instance, to offer entry in 2001 or 2002--could be found to persuade the Mediterraneans to accept exclusion in 1999. That hope was already looking forlorn, not least because the Italian and Spanish governments have reacted so fiercely whenever it has been mooted. What would sink it altogether would be the failure of Germany itself to meet the Maastricht criteria. It might technically still be correct to argue that Germany is far closer to a genuinely sustainable convergence than Italy or Spain--but such arguments cut little ice down south.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That leaves only two options. One is to let a bigger bunch into the euro club, perhaps all the Mediterranean countries, bar Greece. But fears that this would mean a weak euro, that it may prove unacceptable both to the German public and to financial markets, and that it will be challenged in court all make this option unappealing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hence the second option: admit defeat in 1997 and delay the single currency, preferably for only a year or two. Eurocrats still feel obliged to assert that delay remains unthinkable--there is, indeed, no provision for it in the treaty. The German chancellor, Helmut Kohl, no less, has argued that any delay might well blow up the entire euro project. Yet one official close to the negotiations observes that an extra year or two would do no more than recognise that, since the Maastricht treaty was signed, Europe has been through a wrenching recession. The European monetary system in its day was delayed at the last minute, though only for three months. There are plenty of <font size=-1>EU</font> precedents for "stopping the clock", whatever treaty rules may say.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Delaying the euro would, even so, be decidedly problematic. Once this has happened, after all, why should it not happen again--meaning, in effect, that the project could be postponed indefinitely? How would the financial markets be managed in the meantime? There must be a risk that delay would push up the value of the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark, further hampering the German recovery. Delay might harm governments in the 1998 elections due in both France and Germany. It might even put off the start of negotiations to enlarge the European Union eastwards, though these are bound anyway to last several years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Worst of all, a delay might do little to solve the problems that caused it in the first place. Governments would immediately be tempted to slow down their efforts to meet the Maastricht criteria, meaning that they could face the same troubles all over again in 2000 or 2001. It would be no easier, and could be harder, to keep out the Mediterraneans. Yet there is a more optimistic view, too. Delay could make genuine convergence more feasible across Europe, especially if governments carried out needed reforms of both product and labour markets (see <a href="eu6365.html">page</a>). In the longer run, the euro might then have a bigger chance of working.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Every way of getting to the euro presents obstacles. But some of them are now looking insuperable. Not so long ago, delay seemed most unlikely. As 1997 wears on, it is beginning to look distinctly possible.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
