<html><head><title>The unemployment conundrum</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/eu.gif" width="105" height="26" alt="Europe" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>The unemployment conundrum</h1>

<font size=1>BRUSSELS
</font><p>TO CRITICS, one cause of rising European unemployment is easy to identify: the approach of the single currency. The Maastricht criteria, say the carpers, is forcing governments to tighten fiscal policy at the wrong time in the economic cycle; and the prospect of a more competitive single market when the euro arrives is making companies cut costs--and payrolls. Hence some of the hostility to the euro across Europe.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The logic is shaky, though. Continental Europe was suffering from high unemployment long before the single currency hove into view (see <a href="eu1.gif">chart</a>). John Major, the British prime minister, recently pointed out in a speech in Brussels that over the past 20 years America had created 36m new jobs, of which 31m were in the private sector; in the same period the European Union had created only 5m jobs, of which just 1m were private.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This long-term trend suggests that the bulk of Europe's unemployment is structural, not cyclical. That is, it reflects over-regulated product and labour markets, rather than inadequate demand or tight fiscal policies. The fiscal tightening for Maastricht has had at most a marginal effect. Moreover, reductions in public spending and borrowing were long overdue--and have produced offsetting benefits in falling interest rates that should have helped to boost economies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is not obvious, either, that the single currency will shrink the number of jobs when it comes. Indeed, if it helps to force structural changes on companies and obliges governments to unpick regulations, it could eventually help create jobs. In some ways, continental Europe may be going through what Britain experienced in the early 1980s, when restructuring and deregulation of labour and product markets pushed up joblessness--for a while. But Britain now has the lowest jobless rate of any big European country.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The real risk with the euro is not that it will produce an upsurge in unemployment. It is that, if countries have not freed their labour markets and are also denied fiscal flexibility, some could suffer badly in the event of an "asymmetric shock"--one that hits one country more than others. Here, paradoxically, is the best economic argument for delaying the single currency. Not so as to enable countries to meet the Maastricht criteria, but to give them more time to deregulate their sclerotic economies. Whether politicians are brave enough to take that on is another matter.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?855968400,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
