<html><head><title>Kohldom creaks</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/eu.gif" width="105" height="26" alt="Europe" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Germany
<h1>Kohldom creaks</h1>

</b></p><font size=1>BERLIN
</font><p>"TWILIGHT of the chancellor" . . .
<br>"The beginning of the end". German newspaper headlines show the door is wide open to criticism of Helmut Kohl. With joblessness rising way past alarm-bell levels and government plans to sort out Germany's squeezed finances splitting the chancellor's conservative coalition, Kohldom is creaking. Mr Kohl himself, still a popularly reassuring figure, insists he has not decided whether to stand for office again next year, but the pressure to make his position clear is growing within his own camp. Adverse rumours have surfaced about Mr Kohl's health, quickly denounced by a seemingly robust chancellor as shabby invention. Yet the spotlights are playing, as never before, on possible successors. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There was more than sauciness in the reply of Oskar Lafontaine, the Social Democratic leader, to a recent Kohl thrust in parliament that to call for the chancellor's departure is hollow routine for an opposition chief. "That is true, Mr Chancellor," said Mr Lafontaine. "But your problem is, there are more and more people on your own side who also want you to go." Indeed, the big change in Germany is the doubt expressed in government ranks over Mr Kohl's capacity to tackle surging unemployment, now at 4.7m (above 12%), the highest level since the 1930s. Mr Kohl's reaction to the problem seems to be a shaking of the head, an admonition to those who have jobs to forgo any increase in real income, and a plea for Germany's now shaky consensus between employers, unions and political leaders to be revived.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In short, Mr Kohl seems at a loss. His aura further dims in the disobliging shadow of Ludwig Erhard, Germany's "economic miracle" worker from the 1950s who has been reaping rich praise on what would have been his 100th birthday. With St Ludwig hovering above, Mr Kohl's plight looks all the sadder. The sweeping tax cuts contained in an ambitious tax-reform plan for 1999 have splintered his ruling coalition, as have controversial plans to ensure that Germany can keep paying for retirement pensions. These are conflicts the Kohl of old might have smothered at birth. And now a euro-trap may be closing around him, not least because the expense of soaring unemployment endangers German efforts to meet budget-deficit conditions for joining Europe's planned single currency.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ordinary Germans have been slow to spot possible links between their social problems and the euro, despite continuing popular reluctance to give up the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark. But Mr Kohl, the euro's standard-bearer, clearly fears the voters might start making the connection. His concern showed in a fatherly performance on French television last Sunday, when he soothed French nerves over Germany's role in Europe. Anyone who tried campaigning against the euro in Germany's general election due late next year, he told his French audience, was doomed to "dramatic defeat".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why? Because Germans prized the peace and stability provided by full European integration above all else, <font size=-1>D</font>-mark included. In tarring Social Democrats with the anti-euro brush (only Gerhard Schr&ouml;der, their possible candidate for chancellor, is in fact openly positioning himself for an assault on the new currency), Mr Kohl made clear he would cast them as enemies of Europe's stability, the Germans' dearest goal. But jobless figures could still have the last say. The federal labour office does not exclude a further rise. At best, an average for the year of 4.2m (still 11%) is expected. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is true that criticism of Mr Kohl coming from his Christian Democratic Union (<font size=-1>CDU</font>) falls well short of revolt. People remember that long ago in 1989 Mr Kohl was battered and almost counted out, then barged back as the hero of German unification and has until lately reigned unchallenged. So, like Mr Schr&ouml;der, conservative chieftains too are just positioning themselves. The most obvious is Wolfgang Sch&auml;uble, party boss in the Bundestag, the lower house of parliament. Then come Volker R&uuml;he, the defence minister, and Edmund Stoiber, Bavaria's prime minister.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"What people want is not less Kohl, but more Kohl," contends Friedbert Pfl&uuml;ger, a young <font size=-1>CDU</font> stalwart. The summons is for a Kohl with answers--a decisive Kohl addressing economic issues. Readiness to cross the chancellor in his fraught 15th year in office comes more from young <font size=-1>CDU</font> barons in the German <i>L&auml;nder</i> (states) than from his cohorts in the Bundestag, who mostly still regard him as their best bet for staying in power next year, and certainly a surer bet than those preening themselves to succeed him.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whispering about his health, made louder by speculation in <i>Der Spiegel</i>, a news magazine, that treatment he has undergone for a prostate ailment points to cancer, may indeed be the underhand political nonsense he says it is. Physically, Mr Kohl shows no signs of slowing. To help him recover his poise, and to stop short the end-of-reign gossip, his keenest coalition supporters want him to commit himself by this spring at the latest to standing for another term. Yet, one way or another, jobs and the euro will prove the ultimate test of his authority.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
