<html><head><title>About face</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Scottish Tories
<h1>About face</h1>

</b></p><font size=1>EDINBURGH
</font><p>WHEN Stephen Dorrell, the health secretary, and Michael Forsyth, the Scottish secretary, contradicted each other on February 10th over what the Tories would do if a Labour government set up a Scottish parliament, they were merely giving a foretaste of the troubles to come for the Tories north of the border if they lose the general election. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Dorrell told the <i>Scotsman</i> newspaper that the Tories would get rid of Labour's devolved parliament. Unfortunately for Mr Dorrell, Mr Forsyth had already decided that a better argument was to warn Scots voters that, once an Edinburgh parliament had been set up, they would be stuck with it. The Scottish Tories found this approach effective in 1992, when they claimed that votes for the Scottish National Party (<font size=-1>SNP</font>) could be more than mere protest votes--they could actually lead to independence. The Tories reckon that this tactic prevented the <font size=-1>SNP</font> from winning three Conservative seats.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Forsyth plans to repeat the trick, this time to stop Labour from winning his own constituency in Stirling. John Major agrees with Mr Forsyth's tactic, and smacked down Mr Dorrell on February 11th, insisting repeatedly that only Mr Forsyth and himself had responsibility for constitutional "policy". Describing Labour's plans as "extremely damaging", Mr Major added: "It is not an omelette that could be readily unscrambled."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This inelegant metaphor conceals a sensible long-term strategy. Most Scottish Tories assume that Labour will win both the election and the referendum on the Scottish parliament which Tony Blair, the Labour leader, plans to hold before putting a devolution bill through Westminster. If their anti-devolution posture is twice rejected by voters, the Scottish Tories will then have the awkward task of formulating a manifesto to run for election to the very parliament they have opposed. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"I cannot imagine us standing on a platform of seeking to abolish it," observes one senior Tory. Pledging to make devolution work by keeping taxes down looks more likely to be a vote-winner, especially if the Scottish Labour Party is bent on putting taxes up. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tory <font size=-1>U</font>-turns on devolution are nothing new. Under Edward Heath, the party became pro-devolution in 1968. Margaret Thatcher reversed that stance in 1976. Since then, the tiny band of pro-devolution Scottish Tories have kept their mouths shut. But now they see their chance of grabbing back some of the limelight. One such is Arthur Bell, a Lanarkshire businessman who is also an unpaid adviser to Mr Forsyth. Mr Bell says he would be keen to become the Scottish Tory party chairman if there were a vacancy after the election.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, this job is in the gift of the Tory party leader. Mr Major's successor might think, like Mr Dorrell, that there are more votes to be won in England than lost in Scotland by promising to unscramble the devolution omelette. Such a strategy might appeal to English voters who felt that Labour's failure to deal with the West Lothian question (see Bagehot) gave the Scots too much say in England's business. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such a development would strengthen the hand of those Scottish Tories who think that their best future in a devolved system lies in declaring independence from the British Tory party in much the same way as Bavaria's Christian Social Union is independent of Germany's Christian Democrats. The two parties operate in alliance only in federal elections.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But neither this strategy, nor a naked appeal to English nationalism, is likely to attract Scottish Tory heavyweights such as Malcolm Rifkind, the foreign secretary, who campaigned for devolution in the 1979 devolution referendum. If Labour gets its way over devolution, the Tories will need some smart thinking and fast footwork if they are not to end up as split over devolution as they are over Europe. 
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
