<html><head><title>Green or red?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Labour and the environment
<h1>Green or red?</h1>

</b></p>IN THE race for electoral advantage, Tory and Labour politicians have long tried to prove they are tougher than each other on bad things like crime and inflation. Less noticed, they are now engaged in another race: to prove they are nicer than each other on the environment. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until recently, the Tories appeared to be winning this contest. John Gummer, the environment secretary, was last year awarded a prize for the "<font size=-1>MP</font> who has done most for the world's environment". He has opposed the building of new out-of-town shopping centres, for example, and called for tough international action to stop global warming. Last month Charles Secrett, director of Friends of the Earth, an environmental lobby group, accused Labour of lagging behind the Tories on green issues.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now Labour appears to be closing the gap. Next week Tony Blair, Labour's leader, will hold a private meeting with the leaders of Britain's biggest environmental groups to reassure them of his green intentions. Michael Meacher, the party's spokesman on environmental protection, recently promised to deliver the "first truly green government Britain has ever seen".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Are these just warm words? For most voters the environment is less important than other issues such as health, crime and the economy. But both parties recognise that for certain groups, such as the young, or families living in polluted city streets, greenery could prove a crucial vote winner.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The art of wooing green voters, therefore, is to appear greenest on issues which involve little confrontation with other economic or political interests. Thus John Gummer has been able to take a lead on global warming, because the collapse of the country's coal industry has already given Britain an enviable record, by international standards, of reducing emissions of greenhouse gases. He has been more cautious about proposing any measures to curb the use of cars. That might annoy millions of British drivers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour's environmental policy is following a similar pattern. On global warming the party is proposing a 20% cut in carbon-dioxide emissions by 2010, a tough target by international standards but one which will not require drastic measures in the immediate future. Mr Meacher has proposed a new international convention to regulate the use of chemicals which appear to be causing a world-wide collapse in men's sperm counts. He also wants to set up an "environment taskforce" to encourage young people to conserve the countryside and perform other green activities.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But to the annoyance of environmentalists, Labour is proposing an immediate cut in the rate of <font size=-1>VAT</font> on fuel from 8% to 5%. Although fuel taxes discourage consumption of energy, and hence reduce pollution, the party has long complained that high rates of <font size=-1>VAT</font> on fuel hit poor families disproportionately. Once in government, the party will also come under pressure not to impose environmental rules on industries which it has long sought to defend. The coal industry, for example, has recently been complaining about proposed controls on sulphur emissions, arguing that they would cost around 8,000 of the 18,000 coal-mining jobs left in the country.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In one area of environmental policy, however, the Labour Party may be able to out-green the Tories. An increasingly popular argument used by environmental groups these days is that green regulations are not just good for the environment, but good for jobs. Tough regulations, they argue, create markets for firms which sell environmentally friendly technologies, or which clean up the mess caused by polluting industries.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Tories have been sniffy about this argument, suspicious of any attempt to load more regulations on business. Labour politicians, however, seem to have welcomed it with open arms. Last month Mr Blair spoke of the need to "stimulate the development of new green industries." Labour last year criticised the government for delaying controls on volatile organic compounds, a type of air pollutant. It argued that this would "jeopardise" the ability of the country's environmental-technology industry to win a big share of foreign markets in pollution-control equipment. Mr Meacher points out that the worldwide market for such green technologies, currently worth around $250 billion a year, is expected to grow to $300 billion by 2000.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour may have promised not to raise public spending if it is elected, but it has made no promise not to toughen regulations on business. In some countries critics of environmental campaigners have given them the nickname "watermelons"--because, while green on the outside, they are red on the inside (ie, they favour government intervention in the economy). Are Labour politicians watermelons too?
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
