<html><head><title>Reverend moneybags</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Religion and economics
<h1>Reverend moneybags</h1>

</b></p><font size=1>LIVERPOOL
</font><p>GOD, according to many British churchmen, does not think too much of Mammon. The main fault of the way we run capitalism, they reckon, is that it leaves too many people out of work and in poverty. So says a report on employment drawn up by clergymen from the main British and Irish Christian churches due to be published in April.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A foretaste of the kind of political rage the report is bound to kindle came last month. David Sheppard, the Anglican bishop of Liverpool, who chairs the committee of clergymen overseeing the compilation of the report, criticised Tory and Labour politicians for supposedly putting the concerns of comfortably-off people ahead of the problems of the poor. Both parties promptly smacked him down.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Actually, neither party ought to be annoyed--the clergy are as entitled as anyone else to chuck their tuppence-worth into public debate. But politicians might have more respect for their views if the churches used their resources and influence to create jobs and wealth to deal with the poverty that they are rightly worried about. In the following rather impressive example, one clergyman has. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When Derrick Walters arrived as Dean of Liverpool's Anglican cathedral in 1983, he found the church surrounded by dereliction and rarely visited by local people. It is close to Toxteth, where nearly half the people were unemployed. In 1981, some rioted, burning buildings and injuring 700 policemen.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Walters took a businesslike approach. "I believe in competition and the private enterprise system," he says. He started with the cathedral, hiring cleaners to spruce it up. He set up a gift shop and a restaurant, which made it into the Egon Ronay good-food guide. These moves so boosted attendance, and revenues, at the cathedral that Mr Walters was able to double the number of people working there to 70.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Next he turned his attention outside. He drew up a plan for houses and built them with &#163;4.8m from Barclays Bank and &#163;2.4m from the Housing Corporation, a government agency. Flats for 400 students, an art school for John Moores University, offices, and more houses followed, bringing the total spent on the area to about &#163;20m.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This impressive enterprise brought him into contact with government ministers such as Michael Portillo, Michael Heseltine, and Margaret Thatcher, then prime minister. Mr Walters used these connections ruthlessly to push forward the regeneration of 45 acres of near-derelict housing in Toxteth, which he named "Project Rosemary". The site now boasts a 260-bed women's hospital and 250 new houses, a quarter of them privately owned. About &#163;65m of public and private money has been spent, creating 2,000 jobs. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Walters does not see himself as a property developer, but as someone who opens doors for others. In 1990, for example, fears arose that J.F. Renshaw, a local marzipan and cake-icing manufacturer, might close and transfer production to another factory in the south-east of England. Mr Walters helped the company to get government subsidies for a &#163;14m investment to shift all its work to Liverpool instead, securing 200 jobs in Toxteth. "It was down to the enthusiasm and persuasive powers of Dean Walters," says Fred Connolly, Renshaw's operations director.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Walters hopes these abilities will be enough to convince the Millennium Commission to stump up &#163;25m, and private firms to cough up another &#163;30m, for a grandiose pavilion on Liverpool's waterfront to house shows and businesses in the media industry, creating an estimated 1,200 jobs. The commission is expected to announce its decision next week.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Oddly, the churches' April employment report barely mentions Mr Walters's schemes, despite the fact that some of its contributors have visited his projects. Andrew Britton, a former director of the National Institute of Economic and Social Research, the report's main author, says that, although there are a lot of enterprising people in the church, the churches preferred to concentrate on their role in training schemes and running job clubs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This seems like a missed opportunity. Mr Walters's example is a good one, and carries more credibility than sweeping complaints about unemployment or calls for giant schemes to ameliorate poverty. True, Mr Walters seems to have been as adept at milking the public purse as at generating new private investment. But the same could be said of many businessmen, and Mr Walters does seem to have put what money he has raised, from whatever source, to very good use.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
