<html><head><title>Beep beep beep</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Archaeology
<h1>Beep beep beep</h1>

</b></p>EACH year, about 400,000 items of archaeological interest are dug up, from shards of pottery to great hoards of gold and silver. The most spectacular find of recent months is a stash of 486 coins dating from the English civil war, found at Tregwynt, Pembrokeshire, in September.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But there is talk of mutiny among the 30,000 people who use metal detectors, and who find most of this buried loot. February 14th was the deadline for objections to proposed new rules to replace the ancient law of "treasure trove". Some metal-detecting enthusiasts are indeed objecting, convinced that the new rules are the first stage in a plot to ban their hobby, as has happened in countries such as Ireland and Sweden.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The law of treasure trove, which some historians think was brought to Britain by invading Anglo-Saxons in the fifth century <font size=-1>AD</font>, gave the crown the right to seize items of precious metal if they appeared to have been deliberately hidden. Over the centuries, a tradition has developed of rewarding finders who handed in such treasures. If items are ruled not to be treasure trove, or if no museum wants them, they are given back to the finders.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At present, only about 20 finds a year are claimed by museums. The new rules, drawn up under the Treasure Act passed by Parliament last year, aim to double this number by defining a wider range of archaeological finds as "treasure", and by removing the need to show that they had been hidden. The new law makes it a criminal offence, punishable by up to three months in prison or a fine of &#163;5,000, to fail to report a finding of treasure within 14 days.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Treasure-hunters are divided over the proposed new rules. Dennis Jordan, president of the National Council for Metal Detecting, says that by making some small concessions, the government has now won the reluctant agreement of most of his members. His organisation is suggesting only relatively minor changes to the new rules. But some groups have broken away from the council, accusing it of being too conciliatory.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Among the rebels is Nigel Mills of <i>Treasure Hunting</i> magazine. Like others, he objects strongly to the criminalisation of those who fail to report their finds, and says 14 days is not long enough to seek advice on whether finds are covered by the new law. If it is so important to keep such treasures for the nation, Mr Mills asks, why are museums not being obliged to display them, instead of leaving them in storage, as often happens?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Roger Bland, an official at the British Museum who was involved in drawing up the new rules, insists there is no plot to ban metal detecting. The objectors are exaggerating the likelihood of anyone being jailed or fined heavily, he claims. Such punishments would apply only in the most serious cases. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If the courts interpret the new rules sensibly, and if museums try harder to co-operate with the metal-detecting fraternity, then those who uncover Britain's historical treasures will be encouraged to continue reporting their finds. If not, some may be tempted to keep their mouths shut and pocket their discoveries.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
