<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<p><b>Price war</b> &nbsp; Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, said Eddie George, governor of the Bank of England, was now advising him to raise interest rates by only a quarter percentage point, having said in December that they should go up by a half point. There was an unexpectedly sharp rise in the headline inflation rate, to 2.8% in January, from 2.5% in December. Underlying inflation was unchanged at 3.1%. The official unemployment count fell by 67,800 to 1.815m. 
<p><br><b>Euro plea</b> &nbsp; Mr Clarke asked businessmen not to try to force the government into a European single currency after the chairman of Unilever, a consumer-goods group, said that his company would reconsider future investments in Britain if it stayed out.
<p><br><b>No ill wind</b> &nbsp; The Labour Party said it had received legal advice that its proposed windfall tax on privatised utilities could not be challenged under domestic law and would withstand any challenge in the European Court of Human Rights.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><br><b>Alert 1</b> &nbsp; The government appointed a senior judge to investigate<b> </b>accusations of child abuse at Ashworth Hospital in Merseyside, after a police raid uncovered porn videos.
<p><br><b>Alert 2</b> &nbsp; The High Court in London was sealed off by armed police while they searched for a woman who had pointed what appeared to be a gun at a senior judge.
<p><br><b>Teaching a lesson</b> &nbsp; Gillian Shep hard, the education secretary, announced plans to give schools the power to sack teachers whose pupils' test results were poor.
<p><br><b>Acting up</b> &nbsp; A British film "The English Patient", got 12 nominations for America's top film prizes, the Academy Awards--more than any other film.
<p><br><b>Bird feed</b> &nbsp; The Royal Society for the Protection of Birds said that poachers were trapping thousands of British birds and exporting them to southern Europe for use in dishes like greenfinch tagliatelle and linnet p&acirc;t&eacute;.
<p><br>

