<html><head><title>Tobacco outclassed</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Tobacco outclassed</h1>

<p><b>This may be the American tobacco industry's worst year. What was once seen as an elegant pastime is now on the point of being treated as drug-taking</b></p>
<br>BEING "carded" is part of growing up in the United States. Without a driving licence or similar identification document (<font size=-1>ID</font>) to show that they are over 21, the young can buy nothing stronger than root beer. In a few days' time, if government plans go ahead, it will not be just drinkers who have to carry <font size=-1>ID</font>. Any smokers who look younger than 27 will be required to prove that they are over 18 before they can buy cigarettes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>ID</font> rule (and the introduction of 18 as a national minimum age rather than a state-by-state requirement) is due to go into effect on February 28th. It is the first of a series of regulations issued by the Food and Drug Administration, and intended to reduce smoking among young people. Two years ago the <font size=-1>FDA</font> asserted that nicotine, the main addictive component of tobacco smoke, is a drug and that the agency therefore had jurisdiction over it. Further regulations will come into force in August (see below).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These are just the first of the shocks that will hit the tobacco business this year. Because they will directly affect customers, the <font size=-1>ID</font> requirements will be widely noticed, but the more punishing blows from the industry's point of view may come later, when a series of lawsuits--some for medical expenses incurred by states, others for the suffering of individuals and groups of people--come to trial. In addition, there is a strong possibility of criminal indictments for conspiracy against executives from some of the big companies. And a stream of leaks from within tobacco companies has been revealing past deceptions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The big tobacco firms are fighting back in the way that served them well for 40 victorious years, pouring their wealth into potent, relentless legal teams. But they are also starting to talk of striking deals--anathema for those 40 years, and a sure sign that, this time, victory is less certain.
<br></p><p><b><b>First strike</b>
</b><br>Just possibly, the industry may yet thwart the regulators. On February 10th a judge in Greensboro, North Carolina, heard arguments from lawyers representing the largest American tobacco companies and several advertising groups seeking to have the rules summarily dismissed. They dispute the <font size=-1>FDA</font>'s authority to regulate tobacco, arguing first that Congress would need to give it specific authorisation, which it has not done, and second that cigarettes are not medical devices and therefore do not come under its general remit. On a different tack, they argue that to ban and restrict advertising would be to limit free speech, in defiance of the first amendment to the constitution. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The judge has now retreated to ponder these arguments and the <font size=-1>FDA</font>'s reply, promising a ruling in five weeks or so. Whatever his decision, the losing side will immediately appeal, sending the case up to the court of appeals in Richmond, Virginia. This court has previously shown itself willing to accept advertising bans vaguer than those proposed by the <font size=-1>FDA</font>. And, since health and safety regulations are conventionally left in place until proved faulty, the Richmond court would probably reverse any suspension imposed by the Greensboro judge while it made up its mind. Again, whatever it decides, appeal is inevitable and the case is likely to end up before the Supreme Court in 1998. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The tobacco lobby takes courage from a 1996 Supreme Court decision rejecting a Rhode Island ban on alcohol advertisements that touted price. But the other set of arguments, about the <font size=-1>FDA</font>'s authority over cigarettes, matters more. If the <font size=-1>FDA</font>'s claim were to be upheld, the agency would be in a position to impose stricter rules later on, if it missed its goal of halving the number of teenagers taking up smoking each year. The tobacco industry believes that the <font size=-1>FDA</font> wants a total ban on smoking. David Kessler, the head of the <font size=-1>FDA</font>, who has led its assault on tobacco, insists that he and the agency recognise a ban would be impossible. Given that 40m Americans already smoke, that is just as well. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>FDA</font>'s case has been much strengthened by a series of revelations by whistleblowers within cigarette companies. Their tales suggest that the manufacturers have sometimes manipulated the level of nicotine in cigarettes. The cigarette companies have always argued that nicotine is simply an incidental part of a natural product. However, such manipulation implies that the purpose of a cigarette is indeed to deliver a set "dose" of nicotine. 
<br>Evidence of manipulation continues to emerge. On February 10th <font size=-1>NBC</font> reported a story about Philip Morris. Some of the company's employees claimed in the network television broadcast that, in the late 1980s, the company had taken nicotine extracted from tobacco used to make a low-nicotine brand and added it to tobacco in a different batch of cigarettes. These extra-strength cigarettes were sent out to smokers as free samples. The company had previously told federal investigators that it had thrown away all the extracted nicotine. This denial may come back to haunt it as part of a Justice Department investigation of possible conspiracy. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Besides the <font size=-1>FDA</font> rules, tobacco's opponents have several more bombshells to lob. Norwood Wilner, the lawyer who won the first legal victory in a negligence case against a tobacco firm on behalf of a smoker, in Florida last year, has lined up a sequence of similar cases. The first, on behalf of the family of Jean Connor, a smoker who died in 1995, is scheduled for April, and will add conspiracy charges to the mixture, alleging that R.J. Reynolds suppressed and distorted information in order to encourage people like Mrs Connor to smoke. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Bigger lawsuits lie ahead. The first state Medicaid suit is due to go to trial on June 2nd. The attorney-general for Mississippi is suing tobacco companies to recover the cost of paying for looking after poor people made ill by smoking. Florida, Texas and Washington are all likely to follow this year, and more are mustering for 1998. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All these suits will try to meet the tobacco companies' argument that smokers should take responsibility for the consequences of their addiction. Another sequence of state-level suits will seek damages for the harm done by the addictive qualities of nicotine, rather than by diseases such as lung cancer and emphysema. Lawyers in these suits, who represent enormous "classes" of people harmed by nicotine addiction, are drawing on much of the same evidence of nicotine manipulation that has strengthened the <font size=-1>FDA</font>'s hand. Originally, a single suit, known as <i>Castano</i> after a person who had died of lung cancer, grouped all the potential litigants into a single vast nationwide class. That class action was ruled invalid in May 1996. Hydra-like, <i>Castano</i> is resurgent as numerous state-level class actions. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The threat of criminal investigation by the Justice Department is the hardest to gauge at the moment, but is potentially lethal. As well as the recent Philip Morris example highlighted by <font size=-1>NBC</font>, investigators are examining whether tobacco company bosses committed perjury when they swore before Congress during hearings in 1994 that nicotine was not addictive. These investigations could produce indictments which would send individual tobacco-company bosses to prison. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The cumulative effect of all these threats is to make the tobacco industry talk about striking a deal with its tormentors. Martin Broughton, chief executive of <font size=-1>B</font>.<font size=-1>A</font>.<font size=-1>T</font> Industries, a British firm which owns Brown & Williamson, the third-largest tobacco company in America, said earlier this month that such a deal--large payments in exchange for immunity from further lawsuits--looked attractive. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Last year one of the lawyers leading the Mississippi suit floated the idea of an act of Congress that would wring $160 billion over 20 years from the tobacco industry, as well as adherence to the <font size=-1>FDA</font>'s proposals on curbing youth smoking, in exchange for freedom from further lawsuits and from <font size=-1>FDA</font> regulation. Philip Morris denied any interest in such congressional settlements, but the industry no longer presents a united front. Earlier in 1996 Liggett, the smallest of the large American cigarette firms, broke ranks to strike a similar deal on its own. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If the anti-tobacco lobby gains the whip hand, it too may start to split. Tobacco's enemies will discover that maintaining an alliance becomes harder when you are no longer on the defensive. The industry will doubtless exploit any divisions. Deciding how far to hold out when striking deals will be a fresh problem--albeit a more rewarding one than it has faced before. 
<p>


<h2>Tobacco rules</h2>
<p>AS FROM August 28th, the <font size=-1>FDA</font>'s new rules will: 
<ul
<br><font size=-1>&#149;</font>&#160;restrict cigarette vending machines to places where under-age people never go, such as private clubs;
<br><font size=-1>&#149;</font>&#160;ban free samples, packs with fewer than 20 cigarettes and sales of single cigarettes;
<br><font size=-1>&#149;</font>&#160;insist that coupons for cigarettes are exchanged in person in a shop, not through the mail;
<br><font size=-1>&#149;</font>&#160;ban cigarette billboards from with-in 1,000 feet (300 metres) of schools;
<br><font size=-1>&#149;</font>&#160;insist that cigarette advertisements have no pictures or colour (leaving them only the aptly named "tombstone" format of black words on white paper), except in magazines which have few young readers or in places where youngsters never go;
<br><font size=-1>&#149;</font>&#160;ban gifts in exchange for tokens from cigarette packs;
<br><font size=-1>&#149;</font>&#160;ban all sorts of branded free gifts such as baseball hats and <font size=-1>T</font>-shirts.
</ul
<p>A year later, the <font size=-1>FDA</font> will ban cigarette manufacturers from sponsoring sports in the name of their brands. 
<br>

<p align=center>
