<html><head><title>Stitched up</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/fn.gif" width="360" height="26" alt="Finance and Economics" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>The City of London
<h1>Stitched up</h1>

</b></p>FOR much of this century, Britain's Labour Party has been at war with the City of London. Nationalising industry and taxing the rich have been policies with limited appeal to a square mile chock full of millionaire shareholders. Recently, Labour has done much to change this, cosying up to all sorts of City worthies. Yet in one respect, at least, Labour seems to be in danger of committing what for it would be a novel sin: being captured by City interests.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The issue is financial regulation. Labour has already announced plans for reforming Britain's two-tiered regulatory structure. It wants to scrap the three self-regulatory organisations (<font size=-1>SRO</font>s)--so-called because their governing boards are partly drawn from the businesses they regulate--which are charged with patrolling the City's investment-banking, fund-management and personal-investment industries. Labour would do so by folding them into the Securities and Investments Board, London's chief financial-markets watchdog. This, Labour hopes, will cut the costs of regulation and simplify the system.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For Labour, this seems like canny politics. By attacking self-regulation it can present its policies as tough ones, aimed at cleaning up a sector whose reputation has been besmirched by dodgy sales practices and a string of high-profile fraud trials. But the City need not be unduly alarmed. For, as Labour admits, its reform plans are not as radical as they seem. One of the three <font size=-1>SRO</font>s, the Personal Investment Authority, is hardly a self-regulator: the majority of its board members are not practitioners. And many bankers, who once were wedded to self-regulation, would now gladly trade it for a better system. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nor are Labour's proposals quite so far-reaching as previously threatened. Not long ago Alistair Darling, then Labour's City spokesman, was talking heatedly about creating a commission to regulate the banking industry, stripping control from the Bank of England. Mr Darling wondered in 1995 whether Britain ought to have separate banking and securities industry regulators when there is increasing overlap between the two industries.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That sentiment finds echoes among some regulators because a clutch of mergers have left the City's watchdogs--which are still divided along old industry lines-- struggling to cope with huge new financial conglomerates. Michael Taylor, a former bank supervisor at the Bank of England, has proposed one way of tackling this problem. He advocates setting up one regulator to deal with consumer matters, particularly affecting small investors, and a second to worry about the stability--but not about the business practices--of banks and investment houses in their dealings with one another. Mr Taylor's ideas have some fans. Both Colette Bowe, boss of the Personal Investment Authority, and Richard Farrant, her counterpart at the Securities and Futures Authority, argue that this set-up would give consumers better protection while making regulation more efficient. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So why has Labour backed away from these proposals? The answer, perhaps, is that the critics of the scheme have more influence than its backers. The Bank of England, which came under attack for its handling of the 1995 collapse of Barings, a merchant bank, is unlikely to welcome a radical review of financial regulation. That might have the humiliating result of depriving it of banking oversight altogether.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Alternatively--and worse still from the bank's point of view--the Old Lady might gain additional and unwelcome responsibilities for policing accident-prone securities firms as well as banks. "Many people would say that the Bank already considers regulation to be a poisoned chalice," says Mr Taylor. In December, Howard Davies, the Bank's deputy governor, argued against radical changes to Britain's regulatory structure on grounds of cost and disruption. The Bank may have found a useful ally in the Securities and Investments Board. That agency would be stripped of some of its powers under Mr Taylor's proposals. It prefers Labour's ideas, which would give it greater influence. All of which leaves Labour with some peculiar bedfellows.
<br>
<br>
