<html><head><title>Slave to the rhythm</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width="371" height="26" alt="Science and Technology" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Slave to the rhythm</h1>

<p><b>Living organisms could not function without clocks inside them. But those clocks are not always comfortable with the strains of modern life</b></p>
<br>WILLIAM PALEY, an 18th-century British philosopher, believed that all living things were created by a divine watchmaker. Darwin showed that he was wrong. But he was not as wrong as all that, for most creatures, from bugs to ballerinas, are full of clocks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many cycles in the human body recur every 24 hours: hormones ebb and flow, organs seethe and rest, and--most noticeably-- sleep follows wakefulness. As long-distance air travellers know to their discomfort, these cycles are well ingrained. They are called circadian rhythms (from the Latin <i>circa dies--</i>about a day), and their role is to match a body's functions to what is appropriate for the hour. If they get out of synchronisation with each other, they can affect a person's mood--particularly by inducing depression. To stop this happening, they are regulated by a master clock.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The site of this clock is well known. It is a collection of cells in the suprachiasmatic nuclei (<font size=-1>SCN</font>), two pinheads of tissue buried in the base of the brain. But biologists are only now discovering how the neural clockwork operates, and what happens when it goes wrong.
<br></p><p><b><b>The eyes have it</b>
</b><br>One thing has been clear for some time: the external signal that resets the clock (gradually with the seasons, or more rapidly with air travel) is light. If a creature is put into continuous darkness (or, in the case of a person, shut away without any clocks or windows, and allowed to switch the light on and off as desired), then its master clock "free runs"--in the case of people, at about 24.5 hours a cycle--and its circadian rhythms drift away from the 24-hour norm.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What was obscure until recently was how this adjustment is brought about. It was known that the light which causes it enters through the eye (and not, for example, through the skin), because damage to a nerve that runs between the retina and the <font size=-1>SCN</font> prevents the resetting from taking place, and because profoundly blind people usually suffer severe circadian disturbances and recurrent insomnia.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Charles Czeisler, who runs the Circadian, Neuroendocrine and Sleep Disorders Medicine Section at Brigham and Women's Hospital, in Boston, has found that a significant fraction of such sightless people retain their <font size=-1>SCN</font> response to light. This suggests that the clock uses different light detectors from those employed in vision--a finding supported by Russell Foster, at Imperial College in London.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dr Foster works on genetically engineered mice. One of his experimental mouse families lacks receptor cells for normal sight in the retina. The pigments these receptors (known as rods and cones) contain are there to detect light and turn it into electrical impulses for the brain to process into a picture of the outside world. Even without these receptors, however, such mice still use external light to control their circadian rhythms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What is the structure in the eye that enables this to happen? Dr Foster may have found it in the Atlantic salmon. He was studying salmon visual pigments because of the ease with which fish eyes can be obtained in bulk. When he analysed them, he discovered a new one that was very different from those present in ordinary retinal cells. He has dubbed this pigment "vertebrate ancient opsin", and he suspects-- since it seems to have no role in vision--that it may be the missing link in the connection between the eye and the <font size=-1>SCN</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That connection is easily stimulated: it does not take much light to manipulate the body's timekeeping. Dr Czeisler has found that even a few hours in an artificially lit room (which is far dimmer than sunlight) are enough to alter the hands of the circadian clock. Indeed, the body seems to respond to light most when it is weak--after dusk and just before dawn.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is not so surprising, for these transition points between day and night are the most critical periods for the <font size=-1>SCN</font>. They are the times when the nuclei have to send out signals to bring about appropriate changes in physiology. Exposure to weak light in the evening, just as the <font size=-1>SCN</font> are settling down to the night shift, tends to cause them to recall the rhythms of the day. Indeed, Dr Czeisler believes this may explain why many people find it difficult to fall asleep until the wee, small hours of the morning. And when they do eventually descend into the arms of Morpheus, he notes, they tend to do so in bedrooms sheltered behind thick walls, and with small windows. They are thus shielded from the stimulus of the dawn's early light, and find it just as hard to wake up again.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On top of this daily tinkering with the clock by the luxuries of civilisation, there is evidence for longer-term effects. According to Thomas Wehr, a researcher at the National Institute of Mental Health in Bethesda, Maryland, men (though not, for some reason, women) who live in cities have lost their capacity to adjust their circadian rhythms to the seasons. Long winter nights should mean longer biological nights--with extended production of the night-hormone melatonin, which regulates sleep (see <a href="st4159.html">page</a>). But this is not the case in men. Their biological nights remain more or less constant throughout the year, and Dr Wehr suspects this is because male clocks are dulled by life under the lights. In a more seasonal species than humans, this would have serious implications for things like reproduction. What it is doing to metropolitan men is unclear.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Interesting though these observations of behaviour are, none of them help to explain how the clock itself actually works. For that, it is necessary to take it to pieces and examine the mechanism.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Taking living people's biological clocks to pieces is not, of course, allowed. Instead, Steven Reppert, of the Department of Developmental Chronobiology at another Bostonian hospital, Massachusetts General, works on rats. He has recently shown that some of the thousands of cells in rat <font size=-1>SCN</font> can act as independent clocks, keeping their own time--though how they co-ordinate their timekeeping in order to send out a coherent signal is still a mystery.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tracing the biochemistry of this cellular timekeeping in rodents is just beginning. Joseph Takahashi, who works at Northwestern University in Evanston, Illinois, believes he has found one of the genes responsible for part of it. By using mutation-inducing chemicals, he has created a strain of mice whose rhythms are seriously awry. Dr Takahashi refers to the gene he has succeeded in damaging--and which seems to control the timing of mouse behaviour--as "<i>clock</i>". He is now trying to isolate it, in order to discover what the protein produced from it looks like, and how it works.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But it is not only mammals that have biological clocks. Circadian rhythms are just about as universal as biological phenomena get: they are found in bacteria, plants and fungi, as well as most invertebrates. Since they are so widespread, they probably have a common origin. And since evolution rarely throws anything useful away simply to replace it with something that works the same but is different, experiments on other species should lead to insights into human body clocks.
<br>Jeffrey Hall and Michael Rosbash at Brandeis University in Waltham, Massachusetts, and Michael Young at Rockefeller University in New York, have worked out many of the details of the clock in the fruit fly, <i>Drosophila</i>. They have, in particular, identified two proteins which seem to put the tick-tock into <i>Drosophila'</i>s clock. These proteins are known as "Period" and "Timeless".
<br></p><p><b><b>How flies time</b>
</b><br>During the hours of daylight, the concentrations of Period and Timeless build up inside certain brain cells that are the insect equivalent of the <font size=-1>SCN</font>. Then, under cover of darkness, individual molecules of Period and Timeless link up and waltz off to the nuclei of the cells they are in. Here they act in a peculiar way. They shut down the genes that carry their own blueprints, hence stopping their own production. As a result, the number of protein couples in each cell thins out as the night progresses, and by the time morning arrives so few Period and Timeless molecules remain in each cell that the genes come back on and the cycle starts again.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A flash of light in the night, however, can reset a fly's clock instantly. It does so by destroying the molecules of Timeless (though no one yet knows how). As a result, Period is left alone in the nucleus. Since it cannot operate without its partner, the genes for both proteins are turned on early and the clock is reset forward.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Period and Timeless partnership is thus a simple, self-winding mechanism. And a similar system has been found in a creature even less attractive than <i>Drosophila</i>--the bread mould <i>Neurospora</i>. Its clock has been teased apart over the past few years by Jay Dunlap and Jennifer Loros at Dartmouth Medical School in Hanover, New Hampshire, beginning with their isolation of the timekeeping gene <i>frq</i> in 1989. The model Dr Dunlap and Dr Loros have developed goes one step further than the <i>Drosophila</i> findings. It shows how the workings of the clock may, by stimulating the formation of particular enzymes, control the timing of other activities such as the production of energy or the formation of the delicate filaments that carry the mould's spores.
<br></p><p><b><b>Dark moods, light spirits</b>
</b><br>If the evolutionary argument is correct, the proteins involved in the clocks of <i>Drosophila</i> and <i>Neurospora</i> probably have counterparts in mammals. That would enable experimenters to ask the right questions straight away rather than flailing around, as it were, in the dark.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This could be important. Discovering what makes the circadian clock tick would be a big step towards understanding how it drives other cycles in the body, such as the sleep-wake cycle. The clock and the sleep-wake cycle are distinct mechanisms. But, like interlocking cogs, they move together throughout the day. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Occasionally, though, they come uncoupled, as happens in jet-lag, shiftwork and old age. The consequences of this can be more than loss of sleep and a hard day's night. Those with seasonal affective disorder (<font size=-1>SAD</font>)--about 5% of people in the West--suffer from depression and chronic sleepiness between October and April, apparently because short winter days with late dawns push their circadian clocks ahead of their sleep-wake cycles. And when Dr Czeiler and Simon Folkard, of the University of Wales in Swansea, deliberately decoupled the circadian clocks and sleep-wake cycles of 24 healthy young adults, they found that their subjects reported daily bouts of the blues.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why adjusting the 24-hour pacemaker should alter mood remains to be found out. Robert Moore, a doyen of the subject (he helped discover the role of the <font size=-1>SCN</font>) is now at the department of psychiatry at the University of Pittsburgh. He is looking for structural changes in the post-mortem <font size=-1>SCN</font> of patients with <font size=-1>SAD</font><t--mode> </t--mode>and similar disorders. He has also begun to study the function of normal <font size=-1>SCN</font> using high-resolution brain-scanning techniques such as positron-emission tomography and magnetic-resonance imaging.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whether these techniques will work is still unclear. Looking at structures a millimetre across inside a living brain will test them to the limit. But if they do, they should shed a little more light on the subject. And a little more light may be all that is needed to master the master clock.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
