<html><head><title>Shift worker</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width="371" height="26" alt="Science and Technology" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Shift worker</h1>

FOR a hormone normally associated with darkness, melatonin has been enjoying a lot of limelight lately. But despite the hype that has cast it as a new panacea--able to cure everything from <font size=-1>AIDS</font> to Alzheimer's--there is no scientific evidence that it can do anything except rock the body's internal clock. This, however, makes it a powerful treatment for those maladies arising from airline travel or shiftwork.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Melatonin is made in the pineal gland, in the middle of the brain. Descartes considered this gland to be the seat of the soul, and though the pineal has rejoined the ranks of mortal organs since the 17th century, its importance in daily biological rhythms is increasingly appreciated.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In almost all species studied, the hormone's presence is an indication that it is night. It is produced during the hours of darkness under instructions from the body's master clock, the suprachiasmatic nuclei or <font size=-1>SCN</font>, and then switched off by the morning light. But, in one of the numerous feedback loops that control bodily activities, the level of melatonin itself helps to regulate the <font size=-1>SCN</font>. This means that manipulating melatonin levels artificially can reset the body clock.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Josephine Arendt, in the chronobiology laboratory of the University of Surrey, in Britain, has been working out the treatment best suited to overcoming the needs of the weary traveller. She has found that five-milligram doses of melatonin taken at critical times are enough to shift the clock by 90 minutes a day. In a study of 500 volunteers, four days of extra melatonin (combined with the natural adjustment that would have taken place anyway) was usually able to synchronise people's sleep with their environment. But the timing of the doses must be exact. Those who pop pills indiscriminately, often for melatonin's hypnotic effects, risk setting their clocks awry and destroying their sleep altogether.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The proven benefits of melatonin extend beyond jet-lag. The alertness and moods of night workers are often impaired if their circadian rhythms fail to swing between shifts. Dr Arendt has found that melatonin taken early in the morning after the first few sessions of a week-long night shift will help workers sleep better on their days off and work more effectively at night.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The highest-flying use for melatonin, though, looks as if it will be in space. The circadian clocks of astronauts suffer a double whammy of jet-lag and shiftwork. Since a space shuttle's orbit takes 90 minutes, crew members pass through 16 sunsets and sunrises each day. This completely disorients the <font size=-1>SCN</font> even of America's space heroes: astronauts on board a shuttle sleep almost two hours less than when they are back at base, and they resort to sleeping pills nine times more often than those who remain grounded. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Charles Czeisler (see <a href="st4161.html">main story</a>) has just begun to investigate the effects of melatonin on shuttle-crews. Experiments aboard next year's Neurolab mission on the shuttle <i>Columbia</i> will be the ultimate test, and a chance for melatonin to live up to some lofty expectations.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?855968400,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
