<html><head><title>A survey of technology in finance</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><h3>A survey of technology in finance</h><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table><H1>Fixing what is brokin</H1><P><I>Why, but not when, Wall Street will go wired</I><p ><br>CHARLES SCHWAB is neither easily impressed nor prone to hype. The eponymous stockbroking firm he founded in 1974 was intended to take advantage of America's scrapping of fixed commissions in securities trading. He believed that consumers would be enticed by cut-price dealing. And he embraced technology and remote service-delivery as the means to a lower cost base. "We were a pure transaction company," he recalls.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For more than two decades Mr Schwab has had the satisfaction of watching his firm grow at an annual compound rate of more than 20%. It now has more than 3.8m active investor accounts. Yet Mr Schwab is not complacent. He declares recent technological developments to be miraculous. Innovations such as the Internet, voice recognition and faster communications have transformed what his and other firms can do for their customers. "For every call we get to do a transaction, we now get ten wanting some other service," says Mr Schwab.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The rush of new services has been remarkable. An individual armed with a personal computer and modem can gain access to an astonishing array of price information and analytical software, often by tapping into a single Internet site. Much of the information that is now given away free of charge was only recently the privileged domain of giant financial firms and markets. This year has seen a race among brokers to offer on-line electronic share dealing services: e.Schwab now vies with, among others, e.trade and Lombard, two "virtual" discount-broking firms. Nowhere, it seems, is the shape of the future of finance more obvious.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Pause for a moment, however. Charles Schwab was among the first of a new class of stockbrokers in the mid-1970s, the so-called discounters, which undercut the high charges imposed by established full service firms with their networks of brokers and their expensive research base. Not surprisingly, given their low prices, they quickly found a dedicated following. Nearly two decades later, however, discounters have a share of the retail market of only around 25% (big institutions still deal predominantly with full-service firms, though they often get discounted prices from them).<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The reason for the discounters' failure to take over the retail market completely is nothing to do with technological shortcomings. Mr Schwab first offered an on-line trade order service more than a decade ago: "It was a horse and buggy compared to today's Internet services," he concedes, "but it worked." Yet it was not widely taken up. Many retail customers did not own a computer until recently, so were unimpressed by such a high-tech service: a case, perhaps, of cart before modem.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Rather, discounters have had limited success because they have focused on a commodity service, executing trades, that appealed strongly only to a minority of self-confident investors. Most retail customers wanted some advice as well as execution; that is why many remained with their traditional, more expensive, brokers, including Wall Street giants such as Merrill Lynch and Smith Barney.<p><b>A tidy bundle</b><br>These firms justify higher charges by offering such products as investment research and a personal relationship with a broker alongside order execution. That business model has proved just as resilient as that of bank branches. Mr Schwab, for one, does not expect it suddenly to dwindle. He is moving his firm up-market, away from straight execution and towards more valuable services such as investment planning and performance analytics.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Because plenty of investors prefer traditional methods for making their trades, just as plenty of bank customers still wander into branches to write paper cheques, firms such as Schwab and Quick & Reilly themselves envisage keeping a blend of access points, mixing branches, 24-hour telephone centres and direct computer links. On-line accounts represent only around 1% of the total American brokerage market, reckons Diogo Teixeira of The Tower Group, a consulting firm. But, like many brokers, he thinks that the computer will take an increasing share.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Therein lies an important clue about how the business of stockbroking may develop. Accept that execution is akin to cheque-processing in banking: a necessary utility function that adds little value. How, then, can brokers make money&#063; One answer might be to control access to a vital ingredient such as price information. Organised financial exchanges and brokers have long known this. As Jay Smith, founder of Leading Market Technologies, a financial software firm, comments, "Many exchanges have in effect taxed access to price information rather than trading activity or volume."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But computer networks such as the Internet defy any institution's ability to monopolise information. In America upstart firms such as Quote.com already provide a bewildering array of information in return for a minuscule monthly subscription fee. Even the crusty London Stock Exchange has discovered the power of networking. Earlier this year it lost a court battle to prohibit real time electronic dissemination of its prices by Tradepoint, a rival share-trading organisation with little more than a few computers to its name (and which still has few trades to its credit). The whole point of network computing is that it costs almost nothing to distribute information.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That means that intermediaries such as stockbrokers must add value in some other way if they are to be useful to their customers. Logic points to those areas into which Mr Schwab and his sort are moving: financial planning, research and analysis.<br><b><p>Spot the difference<br></b>Discounters such as Quick & Reilly already offer investment software of astonishing power and flexibility. These days, offering customers analytics and access via a computer is seen as a standard service for brokers in America. As Peter Quick, president of Quick & Reilly, says, "The point is to make life easier for our customers." There is little to choose between their products and those of their more expensive rivals.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, in recent months those rivals have reluctantly felt bound to follow their competitors into cyberspace. In April Prudential Securities launched an on-line service allowing customers to review their accounts, check prices and exchange e mail with their stockbroker. Merrill Lynch launched a similar service last month. Neither allows investors to enter trading instructions remotely, however; orders must still be keyed in by a stockbroker.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nevertheless, this jockeying is helping to erode any meaningful distinction between discount and full-service broking, reckons Ken Landes, a consultant with Coopers & Lybrand. If execution and price information are increasingly low-value commodity businesses, and if most brokers can offer snazzy software, what else might justify high brokers' fees&#063; Only two things spring to mind: research (that is, investment ideas) and better products (that is, proprietary funds or software analytics).<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Plenty of investors might then ask an obvious question. What is, say, excellent research worth in itself&#063; That could be the key to unbundling traditional full-service broking. And if it is unbundled for retail customers, why not for institutional ones too&#063; There has already been pressure for more transparency, for instance over "soft" commissions which involve brokers giving computers and so forth to favoured clients.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Traditional firms with their heavy fixed costs will no doubt fight to keep customers in their traditional relationships. They may even use the same technologies that their competitors see as the key to their undoing. A traditional stockbroker often neglected some of his clients simply because he lacked the ability to keep track of more than, say, 40 people. Something as simple as e-mail can change that, according to Doug Alexander, president of Reality Online, a software firm: "Technology helps brokers to communicate faster and more easily with personalised e-mail for, say, a research idea on a share in which the customer has previously expressed interest." Add some modern portfolio tracking systems, and a diligent stockbroker might be able to manage the affairs of 300 people, not 40.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, as discount brokers have already discovered, investors change their habits only slowly, even when they are offered what appears to be a compelling deal. That is why, in the end, Mr Schwab is among those who are wary of predicting the speedy demise of traditional broking: "Change won't happen overnight, mostly because many more people have to understand that they now have new choices." Coopers' Mr Landes, however, thinks that the arrival of mature networking technology has fundamentally altered the economics of broking. He predicts traumatic competitive convulsions in the next few years.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Both men could be correct. Thanks to the impact of technology, stockbroking seems sure to change in major ways. Thanks to people and their persistent habits, it is hard to predict the timing of technology's impact. Thus, the idea of fully automated agents running people's portfolios in linked electronic financial markets may not be far-fetched; it is merely far off. How far off is hard to gauge. But judging by the speed with which the Internet is growing, it may be nearer than you might think.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?846288000,sur">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="tf6.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
