<html><head><title>A survey of technology in finance</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><h3>A survey of technology in finance</h><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table><H1>Understanding cyberspace</H1><P><I>Networks challenge conventional business models</I><p ><br>IN ITS detail, it is more than a single mind can grasp. But the rapid evolution of cyberspace is recognised by most people as a change of great significance. In the space of a few weeks, firms have gone from obscurity to worldwide fame and riches. Spin-offs, start-ups, alliances, takeovers: all have been seen of late in the muddled and colliding worlds of virtual and terrestrial financial services.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, the importance of cyberspace for finance cannot be assessed in isolation from the physical world. Is Security First, a pioneering virtual bank, a threat to Citibank, an established global consumer franchise&#063; Is Microsoft a potential rival or a necessary ally of today's banks&#063; Should Merrill Lynch and its sort fear Wit Capital, a cyberspace investment bank that is helping small companies to raise capital without paying fat fees to a Wall Street underwriter&#063; Does InsWeb, a virtual insurance marketplace, signal the end of the human insurance agent&#063; Will Mondex, a digital cash system, lose out to Visa's smart cards&#063;<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such questions are among many raised by the obvious potential of electronic networks to upset the economics of today's sales and distribution mechanisms in finance. Secure information distribution is the key to cost-cutting. Smarter use of information is the key that will unlock new revenues. Firms that can successfully combine the two have a good future. Pure intermediaries will have a much more difficult time.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One problem is that nobody knows how the economics of cyberspace will develop. How will people behave&#063; Cyber-stores have discovered that consumers are happier buying some things than others. Wine and books sell; general household goods do not. Houses are scarcely in the picture, although cars have found a niche. Financial products are now making their appearance, with bank accounts and insurance policies at the forefront.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until people in large numbers exhibit preferences, what should would-be electronic salesmen do&#063; Usage of the Internet is growing fast, and its users are better-off, better-educated and younger than the average American (see <a href="tf6.gif">chart</a>), with all that promises for new business opportunities. But it will probably be a decade before the Net really counts. Security First, America's first federally insured virtual financial institution, is a case in point. From a standing start in October 1995 its deposits have shot up to around $14m this year. One analyst predicts that even a gradual slowdown to a merely opulent rather than explosive growth rate would still take its deposits to $400m by the beginning of 1999. But even then, the bank will scarcely dent America's existing banking market.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So those who would serve customers in cyberspace--whether as payment processors, credit-card brands or digital-money providers--all face a horrid dilemma. They know that if they race too fast to build infrastructures they might simply repeat past investment mistakes in technology. But they also know that cyberspace will eventually be like the real world, in that it will have room only for a few widely accepted and fungible systems. Most of today's names will surely lose out.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Financial-services firms are not good at coping with rapid change--or an uncertain future. Lewis Levin, who runs Microsoft's desk-top finance business, reckons that change so far has rattled many financial firms and caused them to look in the wrong direction for their competitors. "There has been plenty of sniping by financial institutions about technology companies trying to come into their business. But the real battle is between financial firms, some of which are already netting big gains from being better at deploying technology."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Levin is sceptical about the ability and desire of technology firms to compete with, say, banks: "Is Microsoft going to lend money&#063; Not likely. Will it try to gather assets&#063; I don't think so. Or manage assets&#063; Ditto. These are other firms' core skills." Scott Cook, chairman of Intuit, a leading financial software firm, echoes this view, noting that "lower distribution costs will have a dramatic effect on economics and on how and where people buy financial services. But the effect on whom you buy from will be less radical."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The banks are moving in. Already some 300 American banks have Internet sites; that number is expected to triple by next year and to double again by 1999. But, partly thanks to concerns about security on the Internet, only a few are offering more than information and simple inquiry facilities. Solutions to the security problem may continue to hold up Internet banking, though only for a short time. Within five years, a few hundred firms will be offering full banking services on the Internet.<br><b><p>Phoning home<br></b>One much-touted vision is that the Internet offers a chance to solve a long-standing problem: paying bills electronically. A pure electronic medium is technically and financially attractive for both billers and payers. However, as Bill Gorog, chairman of <font size=-1>US</font> Order, a specialist technology firm, points out, "There are already 30m people in America who use touch-tone telephones to check their account balances. If you want to encourage use of electronic channels for bill payments, then the telephone is already in most people's homes."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A new generation of smart telephones is appearing, pushed by telephone companies hoping that customers will buy additional services such as caller identification. These telephones contain a keyboard and enough computing power to ensure that a decade ago they would have passed for home computers. They can be used for everything from telephony to checking the weather forecast, trading shares and paying bills. And it is simple to equip them with a slot for reading and writing information on to a credit card equipped with a computer chip of its own. That information might be no more than a credit-card balance. But there is no reason why it should not be digital money. (See <a href="tf7.gif">chart</a>)<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is a natural combination of devices and explains why many observers think that the telephone will probably become an increasingly important channel for financial services. Some 40m telephones are sold annually in America. A range of super-smart telephones will reach shops later this year, selling for a fraction of the price of a home computer. The Internet must thus be set in some context. As Diogo Teixeira, of The Tower Group, comments, "Major event though it is, the Internet is only a small proportion of overall electronic channels in financial services."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Consider Britain, where Direct Line, a telephone-based insurer, grew from nothing to dominate the car-insurance market in the space of a few years; and First Direct, a telephone bank, served customers so much better than traditional banks that it changed the whole industry. Sharelink, a telephone stockbroker that fell on hard times and has since been acquired by Charles Schwab, also had a big initial impact on its industry. Internet firms might have similar effects in years to come. But until computers are in every home, they will fight against other mass electronic channels.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is indeed plenty of room for those other channels to increase their impact on financial services. Mr Gorog says that electronic bill-payment is at a similar stage to electronic credit-card authorisations in the early 1980s. The technical solution was available as early as 1981; it brought down the cost of an authorisation to 15 cents, compared with 55 cents for the manual process. Yet, reluctant to invest in equipment, banks and merchants took years to embrace the electronic channel, delaying its ubiquity until the late 1980s.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Similarly today, there are few technological barriers to electronic payments. But there are quirky hurdles of the kind that often slow down progress. For instance, behind many supposed "electronic" bill-payment services stand armies of cheque-writers who generate the paper payments that must reach billers. The reason&#063; Many billers are reluctant to accept electronic payments because their systems are built around capturing customer information from the magnetic ink printed on cheques. Firms such as <font size=-1>US</font> Order are finding a ready market for computers designed to stand between billers and such payment networks as those owned by Visa and MasterCard, translating instructions into forms acceptable to both sides. Meanwhile the postal system remains clogged with bills moving back and forth.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Internet, then, is likely to be only one of several channels through which customers do electronic business with financial-service providers. Its existence has certainly accelerated the development of electronic payments systems, although these are being designed to work across several channels rather than solely in cyberspace. As Intuit's Mr Cook concludes, "We're probably talking about a decade or two before we will see significantly new ways of doing things."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In one crucial respect, however, the Internet remains different from what has gone before. It is the medium which is helping to make information available in previously opaque industries. It allows people (including those who run financial firms) to compare prices and providers, to scrutinise what once they would have meekly accepted. In time it will probably develop into a formidable marketplace in which digital money, paperless transactions and instant flows of information combine in compelling simplicity.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One possibility raised by the sudden ubiquity of cheap and immediate price information is that exchanges will increasingly find themselves out of a job. Some firms, such as Merrill Lynch and Fidelity, are so large that they almost constitute exchanges themselves. In America, electronic systems such as Instinet (a subsidiary of Reuters) that automatically match buy and sell orders have found ready acceptance by large institutional investors. The tiny Arizona Stock Exchange is an electronic securities market which fails to match 95% of the orders placed there, but which has minimal operating costs and recently opened a window on to the Internet. It is a small leap to imagine financial markets that directly connect buyers and sellers.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, exchanges offer one vital advantage over existing electronic markets: liquidity. The ability to deal in rough market conditions is a crucial one to investors and is the one feature guaranteed by the professionals who trade on exchanges. With reduced liquidity, investors face far greater uncertainty. In itself, the ability to see prices is a welcome innovation. But it does not outweigh the reassurance of the ability to deal in bad times.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of course, in time, exchanges themselves have the option of dismantling their physical infrastructure and moving the liquidity they represent into cyberspace. If new electronic competitors appear which, by attracting sufficient business, threaten entire physical markets, then this may well be what happens. But this is likely to be a gradual process.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is not just exchanges that are challenged by the rise of the Internet and other electronic ways of doing business. So are their regulators. Indeed, regulatory interference is easily the greatest threat to the potential of electronic commerce and finance. Cyberspace will need regulation in some form, if only in its legal codes and transaction protocols that will require trusted referees. It would be a shame, however, if today's regulators hindered tomorrow's markets by jumping in before they understand what they are doing.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?846288000,sur">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="tf7.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
