<html><head><title>A survey of technology in finance</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top>
<h3>A survey of technology in finance</h>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>

<H1>War on Wall Street</H1>

<P><I>Firms are running an intellectual arms races</I><p >

<br>WHEN it comes to technology, a restructured bank branch or a broker's cool Web site are at the low end of the spectrum. For the fancy stuff, visit one of Wall Street's trading rooms. Amid the din and bustle it is striking that machines are omnipresent: telephones for barking orders, screens for watching data, televisions for absorbing news.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Only a few years ago, trading rooms were still relatively primitive. Many consisted of little more than banks of desks with telephones, each with a screen hired expensively from a data provider such as Reuters or Telerate. Traders scribbled orders on paper slips that were passed to back office for confirmation and settlement. Because market data was costly, only big firms could afford to buy it. They competed with gusto, buying mainframe computers and manipulating masses of data to try to create a trading advantage.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These days, high finance has gone high-tech. Data is much cheaper. Vendors such as Reuters, Knight-Ridder and Bloomberg allow firms to feed all their information into open computer systems. There it can be analysed at will. Mathematicians and quantum physicists have taken seats once occupied by seat-of-the-pants barrow boys. Head traders talk fondly of their "black boxes", proprietary engines that run trading portfolios of great complexity. Some trading rooms have gone so far as to automate order flows; J.P. Morgan's equity trading works in a seamless electronic environment.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Over the past decade trading instruments have multiplied too. Derivatives have gone from obscurity to ubiquity (with occasional infamy along the way). Swaps, already a big business by the mid 1980s, have since exploded into an enormous one and are now indispensable to corporate finance. Financial firms are using improved telecommunications to run their operations continuously, passing trading positions from one time-zone to another.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These changes have sent powerful shocks into other financial businesses. Fund management, for instance, has been turned upside down by derivatives, for these allow managers to do such unprecedented things as hedging specific bets, investing internationally or tying their fortunes to a stockmarket index. Funds can invest in a much wider variety of liquid assets than a few years ago using a technique known as "securitisation" that pools assets such as credit-card receivables into securities that can be sold to investors.On the face of it, it might seem that technology has already had its biggest impact on Wall Street. Not so, says Jay Smith, whose firm, Leading Market Technologies, supplies analytical software for traders. As the advantage of simply owning data has shrunk, firms have embraced a "smart weapons" strategy in search of the best applications. Hence the huge demand for people skilled at analysing data sets. "There is an arms race among a financial elite," says Mr Smith. "The weapons range from hiring the best quantitative brains to building the most flexible and helpful software platforms."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One effect has been that big financial firms such as Morgan Stanley and Goldman Sachs have acquired huge appetites for both historical and real time data. Increasingly, they are building high speed databanks on their own premises and asking vendors to supply them with entire databases.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What they do with all this data provides another reason for thinking that technology has far from run its course in Wall Street. By analysing price series, firms hope to find relationships that link one asset's future performance to another's. They also test statistical properties such as price volatility-- not hard for a single fixed-rate bond, but tricky for a 30-year mortgage bond, and devilish for an entire portfolio of such instruments. These efforts may be part of a complex attempt to model how a financial market works, or how a portfolio might respond to changes in interest rates. That takes a phenomenal amount of computing power.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The detail of what big trading firms do may be daunting, but the principle is less so. Financial models represent the intellectual software of finance. The model-builders are trying to write programs that confer a competitive advantage over other firms. Advantage was once derived by getting data faster than rivals. These days, the advantage lies in the brainpower and associated computing power that firms can mobilise. It is no longer the receipt of data that determines which firm uses it most profitably; instead it might be how quickly a firm spots a pricing anomaly hiding in a data series. Wall Street firms vie with military defence laboratories not just for the brightest <font size=-1>P</font>h<font size=-1>D</font>s, but also for the lead in technologies that make possible the easy visualisation of large amounts of data.
<br><b><p>The risk factor

<br></b>The spread of ever more sophisticated high technology across Wall Street offers one big reason for concluding that intellectual progress in finance is far from slowing down. Indeed, there are signs of the opposite. Modern finance is based upon a body of theory invented largely since the second world war.  But most of the theory's neat equations make assumptions that are impossible in the real world, so there is a constant tension between the theoretical underpinnings and the daily practice of finance.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One area where this tension has been fruitful is that of risk management. As firms have built huge trading operations, they have assumed complex interlocking exposures. Some financial instruments, particularly options, are notoriously difficult to price, simple formulae notwithstanding. Yet a firm might hold a trading book made up of thousands of different options. Assuming that it can aggregate its positions across possibly dozens of different trading books, what is its overall risk&#063; The answer clearly calls for both technical and computational skills. But it also requires a judgmental sense of risk that can differ from one institution to another. This has proved a catalyst for a new revolution in finance.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ron Dembo, who runs Algorithmics, a specialist risk-management software firm based in Toronto, is among those bridging the divide between financial theory and practice. He questions some established risk-management techniques, particularly a common approach known as Value at Risk (<font size=-1>VAR</font>). <font size=-1>VAR</font> was embraced by bankers and their regulators because it offers a measure of a firm's overall exposure to market risk. And it is indeed useful for understanding how much a given instrument or portfolio might lose or gain over a period of time.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But according to Mr Dembo, <font size=-1>VAR</font> has several serious drawbacks. One is that it relies heavily on past volatility as a guide to future volatility. Yet this has been shown to be a poor predictor of a portfolio's actual behaviour. A second objection is that the technique is of limited use at a strategic level, for it does not allow meaningful comparisons across financial markets and is therefore no help for the allocation of capital.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To understand this, consider two trading desks, each with a standard measured <font size=-1>VAR</font> of $10m. One desk deals in New Zealand equities, the other in American Treasuries. Are these operations equally risky&#063; Certainly not, says Mr Dembo. Each market is different, not least in liquidity. The future behaviour of risk factors (yields, correlations) and their volatility also differs in each market. In other words, risk depends on more than just historic correlations: it depends on the period over which it is measured and the trader's corresponding assessment of, say, a market's liquidity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This problem is familiar to fund managers. To measure performance across markets they long ago invented benchmarks, typically an index, which reflect the peculiarities of each market. Mr Dembo argues that traders should be measured similarly; it so happens that Algorithmics has built software to do just this. In every market there is an almost riskless trade that will yield a small but positive return. That trade should be a natural benchmark against which a trader's actual transactions can be measured. Obviously if a firm chooses a benchmark trade with a high expected return, then a trader must assume more risk if he is to perform in line. Thus this approach recognises different appetites for risk. And it captures otherwise elusive factors such as liquidity risk and how this varies over time.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Algorithmics' conceptual breakthrough was to realise that many of the benchmarks adopted by businesses (including financial ones) are too inflexible to be good measures of either risk or performance. For instance, many firms adopt a fixed target for annual return on equity. Yet an appropriate measure should recognise that changing market conditions can mean that what was a fine return at one moment might be poor at another. A useful benchmark should reflect that.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The best way to measure traders' performance across different markets is to measure them against the different benchmarks appropriate to those markets. The consequences of doing this with <font size=-1>VAR</font> are profound. For one thing, a trading operation can construct performance measures and comparisons that make it easier to assess individuals as well as to run the business with the right amount of capital. That is a crucial step in risk management, for firms today still have little clear idea of whether they are allocating too little capital (perhaps exposing themselves to ruin) or too much (wasting resources).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Second, it redefines risk, for risk now becomes the risk of underperforming the benchmark. Mr Dembo calls this Benchmark Value at Risk (<font size=-1>B-VAR</font>). Because it is based on guessing and then formalising sensible likely future courses for each benchmark, it is a mixture of the judgmental and the quantitative that mirrors the real world far better than approaches that do little more than extrapolate the past into the future.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is insights such as Mr Dembo's which support this survey's claim that finance's intellectual revolution is still in its early phases. Some will argue that this "software" is not technology at all, but simple evidence of human ingenuity. However, none of it would be possible without the broader infrastructure of modern technology. And in so far as it relies upon fast and reliable computation as its practical foundation, intellectual software is inseparable from the microchips which give it life.
<br>



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html">
<i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?846288000,sur">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="tf8.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>

