<html><head><title> All Tories now </title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top>
<h3> A survey of Britain's new politics</h>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>

<H1>All Tories now </H1>

<P><I>Labour and the Tories have much in common these days. For one thing,
neither party offers Britain the ideas it needs </I><p >

MUCH should be at stake in Britain's forthcoming general election. The
Conservative Party has been in power for the past 17 years, first under
Margaret Thatcher, then under John Major, and the country has changed profoundly
as a result. Now the long Tory reign seems about to end. A revitalised
Labour Party, led by Tony Blair, offers a new vision, and has a commanding
lead in the opinion polls. Politics is uncertain, of course--in 1992 the
polls confidently predicted a Labour victory--but such is Labour's lead
this time, such the Tories' unpopularity, that it would be remarkable rather
than merely surprising if Mr Major were returned to Downing Street.
<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Surely, therefore, the next election will indeed mark a turning-point
in British politics, no less than the election that first brought Margaret
Thatcher to power? Until recently, Labour was unelectable; now it seems
unstoppable. But whichever party wins, voters are about to choose for the
first time in nearly 20 years between electorally viable yet strongly contrasting
ideas about how the country should be governed. <BR>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;That is how it ought to be. If you take the parties strictly at their
word, however, it isn't so. Judged by what the Tories have done and by
what Labour promises to do, surprisingly little appears to be at stake.
Voters, it seems, will soon be asked to choose between five more years
of conservatism under John Major and five more years of conservatism under
Tony Blair. What makes New Labour unstoppable is that it has turned Tory.
<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr Blair's admirers would say that this is nonsense. New Labour, they
point out, repudiates the Tories' record. Mr Blair says that the Conservatives
have spent their time in power not merely governing badly but &quot;tearing
apart the fabric of the nation&quot;. Tory policies have favoured the lucky
few. The less fortunate, those least able to take care of themselves, have
paid the price. Public services have been starved of resources; the welfare
state has come under withering attack. The Tories stand for ruthless individualism;
man's better instincts, his need for community and for social cohesion,
have been denied or denigrated. Slavish regard for market forces has replaced
industrial policy. The rights of workers have been trampled. Britain's
manufacturing industries have shrivelled. Privatisation was a fraud on
taxpayers and consumers. The rich have prospered: the poor, the hopeless,
the insecure and the unemployed have multiplied. <BR>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Britain, says Labour, has become a coarser and crueller place. The Tories
have diminished the country economically and morally. What will New Labour
do? It will start to put all this right. <BR>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If Labour's description of the Tory legacy were true, and if Labour
really meant to do something about it, drastic measures would indeed be
required. The distance between the Tories' policies and Labour's radical
new alternative would be great. The fate of the country really would hinge
on the next election. 
<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;But consider Mr Blair's most definitive statement of policy to date:
&quot;New Labour, New Life for Britain&quot;, the party's provisional manifesto.
Acknowledging--no, emphasising--that Labour used to make promises that
neither the party nor the electorate expected it to keep, Mr Blair takes
care to promise less, while challenging voters to hold him to his word.
These little promises, &quot;New Labour's early pledges&quot;, have been
printed on little cards, which sceptics are being urged to keep by them,
the better to check up on New Labour in power. The cards promise that Labour
will:&nbsp;</P>

<LI>cut class sizes for five-, six and seven-year-olds to 30 or less, using
money saved from phasing out the assisted-places scheme (subsidies for
children attending private schools);&nbsp;</LI>

<LI>halve the time between arrest and punishment for persistent young offenders;&nbsp;</LI>

<LI>treat an extra 100,000 patients in the National Health Service by saving
&pound;100m on red tape;&nbsp;provide jobs or training for 250,000 people
under 25, paid for by a &quot;windfall tax&quot; on the utilities;&nbsp;</LI>

<LI>set tough rules for public spending, to keep inflation and interest
rates low. </LI>

<P>For the moment, do not ask whether these promises make sense. Never
mind whether the savings from the assisted-places scheme would pay for
smaller class sizes; whether faster punishment for some offenders would
mean slower punishment for others; how, exactly, the <FONT SIZE=-1>NHS</FONT>
money is to be saved; how a once-and-for-all tax can finance an ongoing
expense, or whether the utilities will raise prices (a tax on consumers)
in order to recoup it. Never mind, for the moment, whether Labour can keep
its most important promise, to curb public spending. Instead merely weigh
the five promises against, as Labour would have it, those pitiless years
of fabric-tearing. The analysis and the prescriptions are orders of magnitude
apart. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It is as though Boris Yeltsin, promising
to dismantle Soviet central planning, had announced a small cut in the
staff of Gosplan, to be phased in over five years; or as if Nelson Mandela,
promising to erase the legacy of apartheid, had said that efficiency savings
in school administration would be used to buy books (really quite a lot
of books) for black children. Mr Blair's modest pledges are what you would
expect of an incumbent government fighting on a steady-as-she-goes platform.
Not only that, the policies are Tory-hued: with the possible exception
of the first (phasing out assisted places) none would be out of place in
the next Conservative manifesto. The fifth, and much the most important,
pledge--the promise to contain public spending-- will certainly be in it.
<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Of course, Labour says, or implies, that
it will do many other things too. There is no British problem, real or
imagined, that Mr Blair does not promise to address. But firm-sounding
commitments (already less than &quot;pledges&quot;, you understand) are
becoming less firm. The promise to introduce a minimum wage, for instance,
has been hedged by a plan to refer practical questions (including whether
the minimum would be high enough to raise anybody's pay) to an inquiry.
Even on constitutional reform--the only significant exception to the view
that New Labour offers a Tory programme--the promise to create a Scottish
parliament with tax raising powers in the first year of a new government
has been softened by a promise to have a referendum on the subject. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Many of these vaguer goals, aims, challenges,
commitments and assorted non-pledges, so far as they mean anything, actually
out-Tory the Tories. The proto-manifesto calls for quicker ways to sack
teachers who are not up to the job; for benefits to be withdrawn from unemployed
people who refuse training or a job; for new controls on noisy neighbours,
truants and children out at night. There are plenty of leftist-sounding
half-promises too, suitably dressed up in anti-Tory rhetoric, but these
are consistently the vaguest non-pledges of all. Labour says it will develop
a &quot;successful and modern industrial policy&quot;. So it should, you
might think, if the supposed devastation of British industry is to be repaired.
But what this policy would actually do (apart from introducing &quot;tough
rules on the non payment of small-business debt&quot;) remains unclear.
</P>

<P><B>Let every rule be a tough rule<BR>
</B>Occasionally, and cautiously, New Labour still applies the word &quot;socialism&quot;
to its ideas. Judged by his pledges and non-pledges, suitably discounted,
Mr Blair is certainly no socialist. Were it not for constitutional reform,
the question would be: is he anything more than a one-nation Tory in denial?
<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If Mr Blair were indeed only a remodelled
Edward Heath, that might not be such a bad thing. Nor, for that matter,
would it subtract very much from his achievement in changing the Labour
Party. Judged on policy, Bleathism would undoubtedly be preferable to the
backward and in places absurd Labour programme it has replaced. In electoral
terms, moreover, it may be exactly what the country wants. A great deal
of evidence--starting with the margin that pollsters add to the Conservatives'
count to reflect the shame people feel at supporting them-- suggests that
the median British voter is indeed a Tory who dares not speak his name.
Give us low taxes, he pleads, but save us from our guilt. New Labour is
listening. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;And let nobody say that this transformation
of Labour was a small or timid thing. If Mr Blair has done nothing but
shift his party to the ground occupied by the Tories before 1979, that
is a remarkable achievement, albeit one he is unwilling to boast about.
Three years ago, who could have imagined Labour's old socialist soldiers--the
David Blunketts, Clare Shorts and John Prescotts--preaching enterprise
and incentives? Never mind their embarrassment: they are doing it. This
was a feat that required of Mr Blair all the authoritarian brutality and
tactical guile of a Margaret Thatcher. No wonder she admires him. This
extraordinary politician might even be able to prevent Labour in power
drifting back to the space it has vacated in opposition. </P>

<P><B>Breaking the mould, etc<BR>
</B>As you would expect, Mr Blair has anticipated this line of attack (if
that is what it is). New Labour says, and Mr Blair may well believe, that
it is much more than old Tory. The reformers dismiss any effort to locate
New Labour on the traditional left-right spectrum: such thinking is simply
pass&eacute;. &quot;New Labour is neither old left nor new right&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.
We offer a new way ahead, that leads from the centre, but is profoundly
radical in the changes it promises&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;. The individual
does best within a strong and unified society, where we acknowledge that
success depends not just on the striving of the individual but on working
together. seeks to apply that principle entirely afresh to a different
and changing world.&quot; <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In this appeal to the role of &quot;society&quot;
(contrasting with Margaret Thatcher's memorable claim that there is no
such thing) and in the emphasis he places on notions such as &quot;community&quot;
and &quot;stakeholder&quot;, Mr Blair appears to believe he has a big new
idea, one that transcends old political categories. So he asks to be judged
not just on his pledges and non-pledges, which are only work in progress
after all, but by this larger organising vision and where it might lead.
<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Tories have failed on their own terms,
argue New Labour's radical centrists: they have failed to create a dynamic
economy. But, unlike the Tories, New Labour understands why they have failed.
The conditions of success, even success defined as narrowly as the Tories
have defined it, include a sympathetic understanding of the social roots
of prosperity, and the state's role in tending them. This is where constitutional
reform comes in. Only by aiming for a broader idea of success, one that
gives communities a voice and makes social cohesion a top priority, can
Britain hope to succeed in material terms. Community and enterprise are
not pulling in opposite directions, as both the Tories and old Labour believed:
the truth is that neither can succeed without the other. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Such wispy, consoling talk really isn't new,
although enough time has passed since 1979 to make it seem so. But put
the question of provenance to one side. What matters is whether Labour's
new (to them) vision makes better sense than the Tory alternative, such
as it is--or whether different ideas altogether are the best way forward.
Have the Tories failed to create a more dynamic economy? If so, was it
because of their narrow-minded concentration on the individual and neglect
of society at large? Perhaps New Labour is half-right: perhaps a more dynamic
economy has been achieved, but at too high a social cost. What are the
policies that Britain needs now to address the Tories' failures? <BR>
</P>

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?843260400,sur">Search</a>
