<html><head><title> All Tories now </title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top>
<h3> A survey of Britain's new politics</h>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<H1>The state we're really in </H1>

<P><I>The past 17 years have done the British economy a power of good</I>
</P>

<P>CRITICS of the government's economic record have plenty of material
to work with. Since 1979 Britain has suffered two severe recessions. When
Margaret Thatcher took office, 1.2m (just 4% of the labour force) were
out of work; now the total stands at 2.1m (nearly 8%). The rise in long-term
unemployment, especially damaging both socially and economically, has been
far greater. On average, the economy has grown by about 1.9% a year since
1979. That is faster than the growth of 1.5% a year between 1973 and 1979,
but not much so, particularly when you recall that during the earlier period
the economy was hit by two oil-price shocks. Between 1960 and 1973, the
economy grew at a little over 3% a year. So much for the Thatcher miracle.
<BR>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Britain's overall economic performance has been poor not only in relation
to its own past, Labour argues, but also in relation to the record of other
countries. Mr Blair and Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, never tire
of pointing out that since 1979 the economy has fallen from 13th to 18th
in &quot;the global prosperity league&quot; (see <A HREF="chart1.gif">chart
1</A>). This, they say, is the price that Britain has paid under the Tories
for bad macroeconomic management, persistently low investment and a chronically
underskilled workforce. <BR>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Arriving at a detailed balance-sheet of economic success and failure
is a complicated business: there will always be plenty of room for disagreement.
However, even allowing for that, Labour's broad assessment of the Tory
years is grossly misleading. The crucial point is that the trend of economic
growth has slowed in almost all industrial countries since the mid-1970s--but
the slowdown in Britain has been very much milder than almost anywhere
else. That may sound like a puny achievement. It is anything but. Until
about 1979, Britain's economic decline relative to other countries was
precipitous; since then, the decline has been arrested, and there are now
signs that Britain is improving its position. If so, no other British government
in modern times can claim as much. <BR>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;How can the view that Britain's relative decline has stopped be reconciled
with the further slippage down Labour's &quot;prosperity league&quot;? There
are several difficulties with that measure. One is that the top of the
table now includes Japan, Hong Kong and Singapore, countries that were
all below Britain in 1979. It is a pity that Britain has done badly relative
to those three stars--but the same is true of most other industrial countries
and all other European ones (ie, those which may best be compared with
Britain). <BR>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Another problem is that the measure ignores demography: a country with
a fast-growing population of people over 60, such as Britain, is bound
to suffer in a comparison based on an aggregate measure of output. Third,
the table is sensitive to the estimated &quot;purchasing-power&quot; exchange
rates which are used to convert prices. Where countries are closely clustered
together, as they are at Britain's rank, changes in position mean little.
<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A far better measure of economic performance is growth in labour productivity--that
is, in output per worker. The ability of any economy to deliver long-term
improvements in pay and living standards boils down to this. Faster growth
in output per worker is the ultimate standard by which any economy should
be judged<BR>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In the 30 years to 1979, <FONT SIZE=-1>GDP</FONT> per worker grew much
more slowly in Britain than in most other industrial countries. Over the
period as a whole, Britain's productivity growth was only two-thirds the
average achieved by 12 comparable industrial countries, and in the 1970s
the gap widened appreciably. (Between 1973 and 1979, average productivity
growth in the 12 countries was 2.2% a year; in Britain, it was barely half
that, at 1.3% a year.) For three decades, in other words, Britain suffered
relative--and accelerating--economic decline. In the ten years after 1979,
in contrast, its productivity growth was slightly better than average (1.7%
against 1.6%). Instead of lagging behind almost everybody, Britain was
at last keeping pace. <BR>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="chart2.gif">Chart 2</A> on the next page shows this improvement
in <FONT SIZE=-1>GDP</FONT> per worker alongside two other measures: growth
in <FONT SIZE=-1>GDP</FONT> per person and growth in &quot;total factor
productivity&quot; (which measures how well the economy is using both labour
and capital). They tell a similar story of arrested decline--and, just
possibly, renaissance. Even more striking than these whole-economy measures
are the figures for productivity in manufacturing (see <A HREF="chart1.gif">chart
3</A>). Manufacturing output per worker grew more slowly in Britain between
1960 and 1973, and between 1973 and 1979, than in almost every comparable
country. In 1979-94, it went up faster than in all but one: Japan. <BR>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;These figures accord with the voluminous, albeit unsystematic, testimony
of factory-floor anecdote. Almost anybody who works in one will say that
Britain's factories and offices are much better run and very much more
productive than they were in the late 1970s<B>--</B>and many will say that
the change since then has been revolutionary rather than evolutionary.
Nonetheless, when the improvement in productivity first began to register
statistically in the mid-1980s, many dismissed the numbers as a mirage.
In particular, it was argued that just as a cricket team can raise its
batting average by fielding only its best few batsmen, so an economy can
increase its output per worker by forcing its least productive workers
on to the dole. And just as a cricket team scores fewer runs in total with
this strategy, so an economy is worse off if it does the same. It is obviously
better that relatively unproductive workers do something, however little
(and even if their small output drags down output per worker), than nothing
at all. <BR>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This argument is still advanced to belittle the Tories' success on productivity.
Though quite correct in principle, it is no longer at all plausible in
practice. Britain's improvement in productivity was sustained during the
fall in unemployment of the late 1980s, and beyond. Moreover, compared
with other European countries, Britain has since continued to combine good
growth in output per worker with relatively low unemployment. All this
implies that the anecdotes are right, and the improvement in productivity
of the Thatcher-Major years is real.</P>

<P><B>Causes and symptoms <BR>
</B>This is not to say it will continue indefinitely. How lasting an improvement
it proves to be, and what it will come to mean for future living standards,
will depend on exactly why productivity has increased. A first possibility
to consider is taxes. Tories, the &quot;party of low taxation&quot;, would
love to claim that steady progress in cutting public spending and taxes
had spurred enterprise and worked a supply side miracle, as they long argued
it would. Unfortunately, the numbers make this awkward. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;True, the government has reformed taxes in
a variety of ways that, it would argue, have improved incentives and promoted
effort: the cut in top rates of income tax from 83% to 60%, and then to
40%; the shift from direct taxes (notably income tax) to indirect ones
(notably value-added tax); and so on. These changes, especially the cut
in top rates, presumably helped. But the fact remains that the aggregate
burden of taxation, which is what matters most, has hardly changed. In
1979, the government collected 35.5% of national income in taxes; in 1995,
the proportion was actually 36%. (Public borrowing was also about the same
in both years.) <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As with productivity, this sort of comparison
understates the Tories' achievement somewhat. Until 1979, the trend of
taxation was relentlessly upward; if the trend estimated over the period
1965-79 had continued for the past 17 years, taxation would now stand at
41% of <FONT SIZE=-1>GDP</FONT>. Merely curbing this rise in taxes took
some doing--which is why complaints about the spending &quot;cuts&quot;
that made it possible have some substance. Nonetheless, the fact that taxes
failed to decline as the government had hoped means that the improvement
in productivity has to be accounted for in some other way. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;What else might explain? it Does it, for instance,
reflect a once-and-for-all improvement in working practices, or a persisting
change in the ability of businesses to adapt to new conditions? Perhaps
both, but the more it is the latter the more optimistic one is entitled
to be about the economy's prospects. It is too soon to say for certain,
but there are grounds for thinking that the second kind of change is a
good part of the story. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Odd as it will seem to those subscribing
to the orthodox account of Tory depredations, one of these grounds for
optimism is the progress that has been made in the quantity, if not the
quality, of education. For all the failings of British schools, especially
primary schools, education has improved in at least one measurable way
since the Conservatives took office--indeed, it has been transformed. In
1979 13% of recent school-leavers (that is, people aged 16-19, not in full-time
education) had no educational or vocational qualifications whatever. By
1995 that proportion had fallen to 8%. The proportion of people with a
first or higher degree more than doubled, from 4% to 10%. So did the proportion
of young people with some form of intermediate qualification, which went
up from 33% in 1984 to 52% last year. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Partly, again, this reflects demography.
Mainly, though, it reflects a big increase in the rate at which school-leavers
have enrolled in further education. The proportion of 16-year-olds in full-time
education has increased from less than half to more than three-quarters
in the past 17 years--a huge expansion. If you believe that a more educated
workforce is a more productive workforce (as New Labour certainly does),
you would certainly expect such an increase to be yielding an economic
benefit. <BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;However, the expansion of further education
is unlikely to be the main cause of better productivity. That is because,
of all the difficulties that have beset the British economy since 1945,
one towers above the rest, even above the question of skills: industrial
relations. In meeting this challenge, the Tories under Margaret Thatcher
were at their most radical. </P>

<P><BR>
</P>

