<html><head><title> All Tories now </title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top>
<h3> A survey of Britain's new politics</h>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<h1> Power and the people </h1>

<i>The most contentious issues for the next government will be constitutional ones </i>

<p>NEW LABOUR is avowedly the party of constitutional reform. Its proposals include referendums on devolution for Scotland and Wales, and on electoral reform; procedural changes for the House of Commons and more radical reform of the Lords; a freedom of information act; and a bill of rights (to be achieved by embodying the European Convention on Human Rights into British law). The Tories, keen for once to emphasise their conservatism, are happy to agree that Labour is radical on the constitution--recklessly so, in fact. The British constitution, in their view, has worked well for centuries&#160;.&#160;.&#160;.&#160;envy of the world&#160;.&#160;.&#160;.&#160;mother of parliaments. Labour's tampering threatens to disturb its delicate equilibrium. Leave well alone. 

<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One can only admire the Tories' nerve in adopting this position. It is no exaggeration to say that since 1979 they have radically recast Britain's constitution. The adoption of quasi-markets within the welfare state is, properly understood, a constitutional change: in the provision of essential public services, the line of accountability between state and citizen has been redrawn, and in some cases deleted. Privatising the utilities was a constitutional change: what was once a matter of public policy (miners' pay, the price of a phone call) no longer is-- or is no longer supposed to be. Reforms in the civil service, notably the delegation of executive power to quasi-independent "agencies", are another profound constitutional change. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Tories have emasculated the local tier of government, through rate-capping, through the introduction of the uniform business rate, through their reforms in health and education, through the introduction of compulsory competitive tendering for local services, and in other ways. Altogether, it is hardly going too far to say that the Tories have abolished local government. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And then, at the other extreme, there is Europe. The Tories signed the Single European Act and the Maastricht treaty, both of which fundamentally altered the constitution. In many areas of policy, the executive powers of European institutions now hold sway in Britain. The role of the British Parliament and executive in framing many of the new laws that affect British citizens is limited, obscure and, even within its narrow purview, ineffective. In 1979 Britain was ruled from London--to be precise, from Whitehall. Today, for good or ill, it is ruled from Brussels as well. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Tories, then, have been zealots for constitutional change. But they have evinced a marked reluctance to discuss or defend these reforms in constitutional terms. Instead they have justified them, by and large, as aspects of their pursuit of efficiency--meaning economic efficiency. That was the rationale for quasi-markets, for privatisation, for civil-service and local-government reform, even for European integration (on this view, the mere handmaiden of regional free trade). They have failed to address the constitutional issues. These are, first, the question of subsidiarity--how much power should there be at different levels of government? And second, the question of accountability--how should the people who come to exercise that power be made answerable to citizens<b>
<p>The centre holds and holds?
<br></b>Almost all of those who criticise the Tories for their constitutional changes complain of the reforms' relentless tendency towards centralisation, towards increasing the power of ministers at the expense of other seats of power. The charge is true, but only up to a point. A constitutional (as opposed to economic) defence of the Tory reforms could run as follows. In most cases the underlying goal was not to centralise political power but to disperse it so widely that it ceased to be political power at all. The goal, in other words, was to shrink the realm of politics. The principle of subsidiarity holds that decisions are best taken as near as possible to the people they will affect. But once you take this seriously, you see that many decisions can be pushed so far down that they fall outside the scope of politics altogether.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If parents have no choice but to send their child to the neighbourhood school run by the local authority, then how the children are taught, and many other aspects of what is correctly termed education "policy", are plainly political matters. If parents are free to send their child to any of a range of schools, each with control over staffing, resources and teaching methods, what is left for politics, local or otherwise, to do? Devise the national curriculum, perhaps; monitor and certify, no doubt. But the realm of politics has been diminished. Recourse to the market mechanism does not, in principle, centralise political power; in cases such as this, it begins to make it redundant.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most political commentators, unsurprisingly, are keen on politics. In their view, the more you have, the better. In the same way, accountability is something you can never have too much of. A healthy civil society is one that is perpetually engaged in collective debate to settle every question that matters--and this is obviously a political endeavour. Seen this way, the market mechanisms favoured by the Tories are at a great disadvantage: judged in constitutional terms, they have the lethal defect of being undemocratic. But people also need to ask how much politics they want.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a liberal society, it is surely a step forward in constitutional as well as in economic terms that a miner's pay, or the price of electricity, should be settled in a market, undemocratically. Might the same not also be true of nurses' pay, or teaching methods, or how often your dustbins are emptied? A society in which these are political questions, as opposed to matters of private contract, is not necessarily a healthier society. In at least some of the areas where the Tories have reduced the political accountability of decision-makers to citizens, therefore, might it not be a good thing? Perhaps, in politics as elsewhere, less can mean better.
<br><b>
<p>Fine in theory
<br></b>Unfortunately, the Tories are inhibited in mounting any such line of defence. This is partly because, in some areas, their desire to concentrate political power at the centre was so obvious that it would be futile to deny it. Margaret Thatcher put local authorities (which are mostly Labour-controlled) as second only to trade unions on her list of enemies. They were most definitely not "one of us"--and were dealt with accordingly. More generally, the Tories' trouble is that so few of their reforms, economic virtues notwithstanding, separated the respective realms of politics and the market in an appealing or credible way.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is apparent wherever you look. The privatised utilities were sold, by and large, as monopolies rather than as unbundled competing firms. As a result, they had to be regulated--and the regulator's task has been at least as politically sensitive as that of the departmental planners who previously oversaw the industries. In education and in health, the government's half-hearted recourse to quasi-markets has left ministers up to their elbows in decisions affecting the quality of service, the allocation of resources, levels of pay and all the rest. The work of the new "agencies" is regarded by nobody as lying outside politics--least of all by ministers. The separation of policy (ministers' responsibility) and operations (somebody else's) is hopelessly opaque. A businessman is made head of the prison service and then sacked for presuming to run it. The fiasco of the Child Support Agency is an embarrassment first and foremost to ministers: they are briefed in depth to answer questions on it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Partly, this inability to separate the spheres of state and market, of policy and operations, is due to ministers' own insistence on retaining power--for with power, contrary to rumour, comes responsibility. It is also due to the undoubted technical difficulty of creating quasi-markets and/or delegated agencies, reforms that go against the grain of British experience. If you believe that competition in the provision of public services is a good thing, you owe ministers some sympathy on that account. But it is lastly due--and here is the government's greatest difficulty--to the fact that Britain is, by inclination, an intensely political country with a strongly centralised political culture.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;People want to blame the government for everything: mad-cow disease, child-killing maniacs, dirty beaches, dwindling fish stocks, escaped prisoners (and false convictions), the death of the novel (only 4,639 new titles published in Britain last year), crowded roads, declining theatre attendances, our disappointing performance in Atlanta and the crisis in Burundi. The "Today" programme's first choice of interviewee on any of those topics (and a million others) would be a minister, who will be called to account for the government's mistakes and who will, in all likelihood, turn up and say something. Even if the government wanted to stand aside, desirable as it is in many cases that it should, people wouldn't let it. Far from being accountable for less, as critics usually charge, the government is held answerable, much as it ever was, for everything.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Proposals for further constitutional reform need to keep in mind, as the Tories' inadvertently revolutionary plans failed to, that national politics is Britain's favourite spectator sport. Labour's assurances on restoring the powers of local government (or, as for some reason Mr Blair prefers to call it, "local civic government") do indeed reflect this reality. For a start, Labour's leader appears to share the authoritarian tendencies of Margaret Thatcher: as far as possible, one imagines, he will want local government to do what he wants, not what local councillors want. Moreover, Mr Blair appears to understand that central government will be blamed for anything that goes wrong in local government.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is presumably why the provisional manifesto promises to end "crude" council-tax capping (but not council-tax capping that isn't crude). It explains why local authorities would be allowed to spend their capital receipts for council-house sales, but only under strict supervision as to timing and use. Compulsory tendering will go (a boon to public-sector unions), but councils will be watched to see that they achieve value for money. "It is not for central government to dictate every detail of local service provision," Labour says, "but it must establish the framework." Labour seems hardly more likely than another Tory administration to restore the role of local government.
<br><b>
<p>The realm of the impossible
<br></b>Britain's most pressing, and intractable, constitutional problem is Northern Ireland. Here, Labour and the Tories have come to an even closer meeting of minds. Labour's proto-manifesto says nothing on the subject except to reaffirm its commitment to the bipartisan approach of recent months. To those unfamiliar with Ulster's perpetual enmities, this detente may seem surprising--because the policy has hardly been a great success. And however much the government might deny it, one of the reasons why the policy has faltered is that the prime minister has had to rely on one of Ulster's contending sectarian factions for Parliamentary support. Even if that has not swayed his decisions, it has made it impossible for the government to play its chosen role of honest broker.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government, or its successor, needs to rethink its policy. The "peace process" was founded on the premise that the province's political parties (including Sinn Fein) could be gently guided to agree among themselves to a settlement--that way it would be, as it were, their own settlement. This was worth a try, but it now seems doubtful that such an approach can succeed. Ulster's political parties are too extremist and uncompromising--more so (one hopes) than most of the people they represent. At some point, the government will have to offer a constitutional settlement (of the kind anticipated in the agreement on the Anglo-Irish framework) directly to Northern Ireland's people, for their approval in a referendum, without the poisonous intermediation of the province's politicians.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On Scotland, in contrast, Labour and the Tories part company in the most dramatic way. Mr Blair's plans for Scottish devolution are much more radical than anything he proposes for local-government reform. And yet they betray a similar hesitation over the question of subsidiarity. The party proposes an elected assembly with severely limited tax-raising powers. The case for an elected body of some kind is very strong: opinion polls say that most Scots want it, and many areas of policy are already dealt with on an exclusively regional basis through the Scottish Office. But why limit the assembly's tax-raising powers? The answer is that Labour fears it will be blamed if Scotland's parliament votes to put taxes up sharply--and it is probably right. Yet the logic of devolution surely requires that Scotland's representatives vote the taxes that will pay for their spending. To separate the two threatens to make the Scottish parliament a mere pressure group for more spending at others' expense--call it the English-local-government model.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That in itself would increase friction within the union. To make matters worse, Labour has no answer to the West Lothian question: why should Scottish <font size=-1>MP</font>s be able to vote at Westminster on English domestic matters when English <font size=-1>MP</font>s cannot vote on Scottish ones? It is wrong to dismiss this as a constitutional nicety of no wider significance. Circumstances are easy to envisage in which Scottish <font size=-1>MP</font>s hold the balance of power in Westminster, and vote through controversial legislation which affects England and Wales, but not Scotland. This would be not so much a nicety as an outrage.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If Scottish devolution, much demanded by Scots, is to succeed, Labour will have to think harder about questions of constitutional justice. Any assembly should have matching powers to tax and spend; and the role of Scottish <font size=-1>MP</font>s at Westminster will have to be correspondingly curtailed. Finding a fair way to do that is easier said than done. Merely denying Scottish <font size=-1>MP</font>s the right to speak or vote on "English" matters could well cause deadlock, with the government secure in its overall majority yet unable to pass laws for England. A better solution, arguably, would simply be to reduce the number of Scottish <font size=-1>MP</font>s. At any rate, Labour must spell all this out before its ideas on devolution can be judged.
<p><b>Making the best of a unitary state</b>
<br>The principle of subsidiarity has much to commend it, within the United Kingdom as well as within Europe (of which more in a moment). Britain's polity would be a healthier one if decisions on collective spending and the means to pay for them were pushed to lower levels--provided that popular discussion and deliberation moved down at the same time.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the case of Scottish devolution, this further requirement poses no great difficulty: Scotland is already a distinct political and cultural entity within the United Kingdom. In the case of local government in the rest of the country, it is doubtful that this necessary supporting culture exists, or whether it ever will. It might be worth the effort to attempt to create it. One possibility, mooted by Labour but not examined in any detail, would be to let cities elect mayors with executive powers. Innovations of that kind might be more promising than attempting to restore, partially and grudgingly, the pre-Thatcher functions of local authorities.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Applying the principle of subsidiarity within Britain may be difficult. Applying the principle of accountability is both easier and more urgent.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In theory, Britain's constitution guarantees accountability through the concept of the sovereignty of Parliament. The government, meaning Parliament, faces few formal checks on its power. Unlike in most countries with written constitutions, for instance, the legislature and the judiciary are both joined to the executive: none provides a truly independent scrutiny of the others. No such scrutiny is needed, the theory goes, because political power in Britain is vested in the House of Commons--a directly elected, and hence directly accountable, body.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Arguably, this view once made sense. Today, it certainly does not. Over the years, the sovereignty of Parliament has been corrupted; it has become instead the sovereignty of cabinet, a profoundly undemocratic idea. Exercising immense powers of patronage and intimidation, ministers rule the House of Commons, and hence the country. Parliament no longer even makes a plausible pretence of curbing the executive. Partly thanks to party discipline, its debates are a pitiful charade, and its committees are for the most part ineffective. The Tories' reluctance to countenance reform is hard to understand: the case for change seems unanswerable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The crucial things are to strengthen the judiciary and the House of Commons at the expense of the prime minister and cabinet. Two of Labour's ideas, worthy of enthusiastic support, would do this. Incorporating the European Convention on Human Rights into British law would give judges a clearer role as scrutineers of the executive. And a freedom of information act would make it easier for the Commons, not to mention ordinary citizens, to keep an eye on the government. Labour also talks (vaguely, as yet) of further steps to reform the Commons. Such steps would be welcome.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If <font size=-1>MP</font>s are to be constitutionally effective rather than merely ornamental, their job must be made interesting and useful, not just something that the able and ambitious must endure until a ministerial post turns up. Serving as an <font size=-1>MP</font> should no longer be regarded as a part-time job. Reflecting that, <font size=-1>MP</font>s should be given more responsibility and more pay--and be forbidden to accept other employment. Every <font size=-1>MP</font> should have an office and adequate access to research staff. It should be possible for somebody to spend his or her entire political career as an <font size=-1>MP</font>, and yet be regarded as a great success. If Parliament could offer that, it would greatly reduce the power of prime-ministerial patronage. And there is plenty of useful work for a more professional cadre of <font size=-1>MP</font>s to do.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In enlarging the duties of Parliament, the role of committees is crucial. Their powers to scrutinise the executive should be broadened. Ministerial appointments to agencies and other quangos could be subject to confirmation by the relevant committee, for instance; and, once appointed, heads of such bodies could be required to present themselves regularly for questioning. Chairmen of committees should be paid extra. They and their fellow members should have their own lawyers to help them draft amendments to laws under scrutiny. Committees should be appointed by the whole house, and not by party whips. Reform of the Lords is less urgent, perhaps, than reform of the Commons, but there can be no serious objection to Labour's proposal to deny hereditary peers their right to sit and vote there: that right has no place in a liberal democracy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour's other big idea on the constitution is electoral reform. But the provisional manifesto is terse to the point of invisibility on the subject--"We will provide a referendum on voting reform" is its discussion of the matter in full. Mr Blair has said he is doubtful about the merits of proportional representation; expect him, and many of his Parliamentary colleagues, to become a lot more doubtful if they win a big majority in the general election. Certain forms of proportional representation do seem extremely attractive. But it would be churlish to criticise Labour too harshly for its equivocation on the subject. Their ideas about Scottish devolution need to be repaired, but otherwise their thinking on constitutional reform far surpasses that of the Tories, who show little sign of having thought about the matter at all.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?843260400,sur ">Search</a>
