<html><head><title>Back to the garage</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="soft2.gif"  alt="Software">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<h1>Back to the garage</h1>


<i>The best software revolutions start small</i>

<p>THE boffins in Switzerland who invented the World Wide Web in 1991 did not see fit to include such frivolities as clickable pictures or sound. It was a tool for scientists, who after all could read. Text was quite good enough, and would avoid wasting the Internet's scarce transmission capacity with graphics files simply for decoration.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It took a 23-year-old programmer at the University of Illinois called Marc Andreessen to cast a vote for the common man. In 1993 he developed Mosaic, a multimedia Web "browser" that made it easy to view documents on the Web and jump between them. It was the first piece of Internet software to recognise that the network's future lay not with scientists but with ordinary people, who liked their information dressed up in multimedia frills. A year later Mr Andreessen joined up with Jim Clark, a wealthy computer industry entrepreneur, to launch Netscape and jump-start the Internet software market. Netscape's sophisticated browser quickly came to dominate the market (it has a share of more than 80% today), and is now a de-facto standard.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As more and more companies, from banks to airlines, began to offer their products and services on the Web, the technology grew with the demand: documents began to look as good as paper, and then better, with animation and interactivity. Users began to realise that the Web could be a place to work, not just a way to distribute information. Already some investment firms let their customers manage their portfolios remotely via Web pages. Companies allow their employees to monitor their pensions the same way. In "intranets" within firms, Web browsers are being used to retrieve information from databases of all sorts, from customer records to inventories.

</p><p><b>Happy browsing</b>
<br>The attraction is simplicity. The language of the Web, known as <font size=-1>HTML</font>, is a "cross-platform" standard, a universal tongue, understood just as readily in the Windows and Macintosh worlds as by Unix workstations. The same is true of the Internet as a whole. Together, the network and its multimedia face have opened up a new way of computing, where the type of computer on your desk matters less than your connection to the Internet. In this world most information is stored and generated on powerful machines known as "servers" somewhere in the network. Your <font size=-1>PC</font>, running a browser, is simply a window on that world.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Netscape's browsers already run on most desktop computers. But similar browsers from other companies run on all sorts of other devices, from Philips video-games machines and Nokia's newest cellular telephones, to a "Network Computer" being developed by Oracle to sell at less than $500, and interactive television "set-top boxes". You might not want to run a spreadsheet on most of them, but people who need to run spreadsheets tend to have <font size=-1>PC</font>s already. These other machines have advantages the <font size=-1>PC</font> lacks. Some are cheap, some fit in a jacket pocket, and some play great games. No wonder computer visionaries such as George Gilder are prophesying the advent of a new computing world, less dominated by the <font size=-1>PC</font> or by a desktop computer of any kind: the Internet is not fussy about machinery.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A few years ago, when Federal Express wanted to give its customers the tools to track packages in real time, it had to develop software for their computers (in separate Windows and Macintosh versions), promote it, distribute disks, and arrange a network of dial-in numbers for customers to call. But when the Web came along, FedEx simply hitched the same database to a Web site, with nothing like the sort of effort it took to develop its own software. Now customers use whatever browser they have on whatever computer they are using to reach the Web site by whatever means they usually gain access to the Internet. No matter how they get there, the site looks and works the same: there is no new software to learn.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By moving to a cross-platform, open computing standard, FedEx was able to get out of the desktop software development business, the telecommunications business and the software distribution business, none of which it wanted to be in, to concentrate on what it does best: shipping packages (although it still has to offer the old proprietary software for customers who are not on the Internet). Customers now track more than 13,000 packages a day on the Web site.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To Netscape, this and similar stories from other companies looked like the emergence of a new platform. The further computing moved away from the <font size=-1>PC</font> and to the Web, the more Netscape's browser, not Microsoft's operating system, became the key link. Netscape claimed that Windows would eventually be reduced to an obscure bit of necessary plumbing in a <font size=-1>PC</font>, just as Windows subsumed <font size=-1>DOS</font>. Or, as Mr Andreessen once tauntingly predicted, the rise of the browser will turn Windows into "a partially debugged device driver", by implication downgrading Microsoft's beloved <font size=-1>PC</font> to the status of a printer or monitor.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This tapped into a discontent already brewing in the software world. Over the past decade or so, many companies have switched from mainframes and minicomputers to <font size=-1>PC</font>s, in the hope that putting computing power directly into the hands of users would somehow unleash their creativity and make them more productive. It probably helped, even though the gains are hard to measure. What is showing up very clearly, however, is an unexpected side-effect: <font size=-1>PC</font>s have made life a lot tougher for corporate systems managers.

</p><p><b>Control freaks</b>
<br>In the days of the mainframe, programs ran from a central computer in some glass-enclosed room. Users simply had "dumb terminals" on their desks. The centralised control this implied may now be out of fashion with the management gurus, but for the systems managers it was bliss. There was just one copy of each program and just one configuration, safely locked out of reach of meddlesome users. Technicians did not have to spend their weekends moving from desk to desk upgrading software or fixing problems. And the software was often simpler, too.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Today, entire consulting industries have grown up to tackle the complexities of huge "client-server" systems. Some managers reckon that moving from a mainframe system to <font size=-1>PC</font>s can require a doubling of the support staff; the costs can add up to $6,000-8,000 a year for each <font size=-1>PC</font>. "While decentralised client-server computing was supposed to lower <font size=-1>IT</font> costs, the opposite has happened," argues the International Centre for Information Technologies in Stockholm.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, <font size=-1>PC</font> users seem caught in a pincer movement of rising costs and falling rewards. Software companies make a good part of their money by coaxing users into buying new versions of their programs every other year or so, promising new features to those who upgrade and implicitly holding out the threat of incompatibility to those who do not. It is hard to say no. Yet each new version is bigger and uses up more computing power, eventually forcing the user to buy a new <font size=-1>PC</font> just to maintain performance at the same level.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since the mid-1980s, Intel has released five processing chips, each more powerful than its predecessor. Over the same period, Microsoft has released four progressively bigger upgrades to its operating system. Yet the average user, having invested, say, $10,000 in new hardware and software over the past decade, may wonder what he has to show for it. True, his word processor is easier to use, and the screen looks better, but it works no faster than it did at the start. The cost of replacing a "delete" key with a picture of a rubbish bin has been high.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As the saying goes in the industry, "Intel giveth, and Microsoft taketh away." This unholy alliance certainly helps the sales of those two companies, along with those of the rest of the computer industry; but with many users beginning to wonder whether <font size=-1>PC</font>s were really such a good investment after all, enthusiasm is growing for a move away from the desktop. That does not mean a return to the mainframe. What users have in mind instead is a half-way house in which information is held and often processed on large, shared machines, but viewed and used on personal ones, and accessed via an open network that encourages all the collaboration, communication and information-sharing that management theorists hold so dear. In a word, the Internet.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this is splendid in theory, but somewhat less magnificent in practice, for two reasons. The first is that, as anyone who has used the Internet can attest, tasks involving travel along a network tend to take longer than on your own desktop; that is the cost of a shared resource. Secondly, it is worth recalling why the <font size=-1>PC</font> became so popular in the first place: it allowed users to work out their own ways of doing things, rather than just choosing between options predetermined by someone else.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Conventional Web pages, convenient as they are, are essentially no more flexible than the old mainframe terminal screens. In the spring of 1995, however, Sun Microsystems, a workstation maker, came up with the missing link: a computer language called Java that was designed explicitly for networks. It is a way of writing small programs, each designed to do a single task, that reside in the network until needed. When you click on a Java-enabled Web page, one or many of these "applets" is downloaded to your machine, where it runs. It could be something as simple as an animation or as complicated as a mini-spreadsheet.

</p><p><b>Less palaver with Java</b>
<br>Whereas Web pages are static documents, Java applets are real programs that you can control like any other software. Once they are downloaded, they run locally on your <font size=-1>PC</font>, largely free of the network's delays. You request only the applets you need, which will be no bigger than they need to be to do their one job. When you are done with them, they can be disposed of, or your <font size=-1>PC</font> can store them to save the downloading next time.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Best of all, you may not even notice they are there: content and software can be seamlessly merged. When you click on an analyst's company report, it seems only natural that the company's share price and latest financial results should pop up in a chart that can be manipulated, or that news headlines on the firm should scroll underneath. These are Java applets, working automatically in the background. They point the way to the future of computing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Computer languages come and go without sparking revolutions. Java is different, because it is more than a language. It is also, in a strange way, itself a computer. The applets that zip down the line when you click on a Java-enabled page are not written in the usual sort of code that processor chips can understand. They have to be decoded by a special program on your computer, known as a "Java virtual machine" that translates them into instructions the computer can understand. To the Java applet, the sort of physical hardware it has landed in does not matter; it need talk only to the virtual machine.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This method has two main advantages. The first is protection from computer viruses: Java applets have no access to the computer itself, but can do only what the virtual machine lets them do. The second is that Java is an agnostic in the holy wars of the operating systems. Like the Web's <font size=-1>HTML</font>, Java is a cross-platform language; the same applet will work on any computer running a Java virtual machine. These programs are already part of the Netscape browser for the <font size=-1>PC</font>, Unix machines and the Macintosh, and are now being written for Oracle's Network Computer and other similar machines.
</p><p><b>All you need is an idea</b>
<br>For the software industry, the arrival of the Internet was the blinding flash of an <font size=-1>H</font>-bomb. Java is the shock wave that follows, toppling buildings and flattening trees. The language has suddenly opened the industry wide for start-up software companies again (see <a href="csu341.gif">chart</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a market dominated by Microsoft, small firms found the barriers had been raised too high. They could not afford the huge teams needed to write massive programs. They did not have the marketing clout to compete with Microsoft's brand, nor the distribution clout to win scarce shelf-space in the shops. If they chose to develop software for any computer other than the <font size=-1>PC</font>, perhaps to avoid competing head-on with Microsoft, they were stuck with a small and probably shrinking market. And even if they did find a market, they quickly had to move into the cycle of perpetual upgrades to keep making money.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Java, and Internet software like it, promises to lower the barriers again. Because it is designed for small programs meant for specific tasks, a single person can develop a useful applet in a few weeks. Since Java applets typically live in the network, to be downloaded on demand, distribution or shelf-space is no problem. And the emerging technologies for Internet commerce suggest a whole new set of ways of selling software, from pay-per-use to pass-along revenues from information services firms which might, for example, include Java portfolio-management software with share prices.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;James Breyer, a venture capitalist with Silicon Valley's Accel Partners, reckons that 90% of the business plans that cross his desk these days are Internet-related; 90% of those are focused on Java. With Java-enabled Netscape browsers already sitting on millions of desktops, the market for Java software is huge, and not just for new companies. Micromuse, a British software firm, is developing its next-generation network-management tools in Java. Applix and MarketVision, two firms that make financial software for the zoo of workstations that populate trading floors, are switching to Java: it is the easiest way for them to make their offerings accessible to the greatest range of computers without the cost of multiple teams of programmers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite the enthusiasm, Java is no instant panacea. For a start, some technical hitches remain to be resolved. Before most software is shipped, it is compiled into a code that a processor chip can understand. Java, however, is translated line-by-line by the virtual machine as it arrives. That means it can be as much as ten times slower than conventional software. Several companies are developing "just-in-time compilers" that can shrink the difference to a factor of two or less, but Java will never be the fastest language around.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Java is also still incomplete. To put together a Java application that has all the bells and whistles of a full-featured Windows program, you would have to cheat by using part of Microsoft's operating system. This would not work on other computers, wiping out much of Java's advantage. Plenty of companies are working on Java versions of these gadgets on various computers, but Java's cross-platform strength may become a liability if the software is reduced to the capabilities of the least powerful device it might run on (a cellular telephone?).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Still, the enthusiasm for the language suggests that, one way or another, most of these problems will be solved. Java has the hearts and minds of thousands of developers, just as the <font size=-1>PC</font> did 15 years ago. Even Microsoft cannot resist this tide. It has announced that it will build a Java virtual machine into the next versions of Windows, and is subsuming its own prize languages and software technology into a package, called ActiveX, that is built around a Java core. Apple and its partners are doing the same with the Mac operating system.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Silicon Valley and software hotspots around the world, the Internet, the Web and Java have lit a fire that is burning on pure geek energy. "We've never seen anything like this," marvels Mr Breyer. Everyone, it seems, has an idea, and starting a company these days requires little more than that. Bill Gross, a software entrepreneur, set up the Idealab early this year when he realised that he and his friends had some 20 ideas between them, each of them good enough to support a stand-alone firm. He has spun out three of them so far. Charles Cohn gave up a high-powered job as a partner at McKinsey, a consultancy, to head CitySearch, one of the new companies. He is sleeping on the floor of a shared house and has not been paid in seven months. He could not be happier. "It's really exciting. All the big franchises and fortunes are up for grabs again," he says.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These adrenaline-fired young entrepreneurs are the foundation of a new industry, just as Steve Jobs, Bill Gates and their friends were in the late 1970s. But first they must work out how to make it pay.


