<html><head><title>Teatime</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Teatime</h1>

<p><p>FOR a glimpse of the new software industry, turn to a rosy-cheeked 28-year-old in a rented San Francisco office, wearing a Toy Story <font size=-1>T</font>-shirt. This is Karl Jacob, the chief executive of Dimension <font size=-1>X</font>, a thoroughly modern software company, right down to its <i>Zeitgeist</i>-friendly name.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dimension <font size=-1>X</font> is an archetypal Java start-up. Just 15 months old, it has already grown from the original seven people to 28 (average age: about 25), and is now looking for bigger office space, perhaps a few dozen blocks across San Francisco to SoMa, where dozens of similar young software and "new-media" firms have colonised the lofts of an old industrial district. The firm makes Java animation tools for companies designing Web sites and entertainment software. Like others in the Java league, Dimension <font size=-1>X</font>'s first order of business was to find a caffeine beverage to name its products after. Symantec had taken "Caf&eacute;", Borland "Latte", Applix "Espresso", Natural Intelligence "Roaster", and Microsoft and Cadis had played the even more recondite island-near-Java card with "Jakarta" and "Krakatoa", respectively. Dimension <font size=-1>X</font> was left with "Tea", which it reverse-engineered to stand for The Easy Animator.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Like many young software firms, Dimension <font size=-1>X</font> started off by consulting for other companies to help pay the bills. While it designed custom-made Java Web sites for its clients, it was also building its own, stand-alone, tools. Mr Jacob funded the early days by tracking down old friends from college, of the sort that had once said over a beer, "If you ever do anything interesting, give me a call." They did not know much about computers, much less the Internet, but they knew Mr Jacob, and that was enough.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When the time came for a second round of financing, Mr Jacob wanted more than money. He looked for people who had invested in similar Internet ventures before, and could also bring contacts and advice. Since the next step for this sort of firm is a public offering, which in the current Internet frenzy might value the firm at hundreds of millions of dollars, Mr Jacob knew he needed to bolster his business team too. He thought he was a pretty well-qualified chief executive, having started his management career in the hardest of all jobs, running his fraternity house at university. And the finance director, he notes with pride, "is in his 30s". But he is now adding more grown-ups, including a marketing person who has actually worked in a big computer company.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a crowded space with more computers than windows, Mr Jacob counts the reasons why this is such a good time to be a young software company. The first advantage, not to put too fine a point on it, is "the hype". Java is the hottest thing in the software industry right now, and a sure way for a start-up to get money and attention. Second, software houses are happily riding the wave of innovation that the Internet has set off. Every day brings new Java tools and opportunities, making Dimension <font size=-1>X</font>'s job easier and the company's potential market bigger.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The final advantage is generational: a feeling for what tomorrow's media consumers are going to want. Today's software is mostly worthy, useful stuff: spreadsheets and the like. But tomorrow's software will increasingly be an integral part of the media stream: less balance book, more "Beavis and Butthead". The point is not to replicate television on a computer, but to add a computer's responsiveness to media of all sorts. "People can't stand being in a room with a 15-year-old and a <font size=-1>TV</font>," says Mr Jacob. "It's click, click, click. But they don't want to click faster, they want to control the flow." What those 15-year-olds want is interactivity--just what the Web and Java do best.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dimension <font size=-1>X</font>'s twentysomethings do not watch much <font size=-1>TV</font> these days, Mr Jacob says. Instead, they have "bookmarks"--pointers to dozens of favourite Web sites. If short attention spans and an insatiable desire to click on things are the lasting cultural imprint of the 1990s, Dimension <font size=-1>X</font> and the hundreds of software start-ups like it will be on to a very good thing.


</td></tr></table>
