<html><head><title>Doomonomics</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="soft6.gif"  alt="Software">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<h1>Doomonomics</h1>


<i>Software is stretching traditional economics

</i><p>WHAT does a chainsaw-toting marine with a taste for blood have to do with the economics of business? Perhaps more than you think. The tale of how "Doom", a drippingly gory computer game, took its creators from obscurity to riches in just four years holds a lesson of striking relevance to tomorrow's information economy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In early 1991, three computer-game designers left their jobs at a middle-tier games company and set up shop as id Software in a small office next to a freeway exit in Mesquite, Texas. They had just released a game, "Commander Keen: Invasion of the Vorticons", into the so-called "shareware" market, and wanted to develop other games on their own. Shareware games operate on the free-sample principle. The first few levels of the game can be downloaded from the Internet and played without charge, as a taster. But once hooked, users have to pay extra to get the more difficult levels so they can have even more fun.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Id did modestly well until 1992, when it wrote Wolfenstein 3-<font size=-1>D</font>, a fairly standard blow-away-the-Nazis game souped up with a three-dimensional interface. Millions downloaded the free version, and 250,000 paid for the fancier edition. In late 1993 came Doom, with more gore, lots of demons to kill, and an even better 3-<font size=-1>D</font> interface. It became a global phenomenon, with an estimated 15m people downloading the free game. By now id had become famous, and Doom a recognised addiction. In late 1994 the company released Doom II through regular stores. It has already sold 1.6m copies. Id's founders now drive Ferraris.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Id is not the first company to make a fortune by giving away free samples of its products. But, by harnessing the economics of the software world, it was able to spend less and make more than any company in a traditional industry could hope to. The advantage derives from a basic characteristic of software (and indeed any sort of digital information): making perfect copies and distributing them costs virtually nothing. When it released Doom on the Internet and other computer networks, id let the marketplace do its distribution, marketing, even advertising for it. Its only costs were to write the program in the first place, and to man the telephones to take credit-card numbers when people called to pay for the full version.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Netscape, the leading Internet software company, was sufficiently impressed to adopt the same model to make its mark. It put its browser on the Internet, free to anyone who wanted it, and encouraged others to distribute it widely. Once it dominated the market, it started to charge for the browser and related software. Revenues in its first full year of operation ran to over $80m. Most other Internet companies are following in its path, giving away software to build market share and brand, and then finding some way to make money later.
</p><p><b>The industrial age ends here</b></b>
<br>Id's strange business plan encapsulates the real software revolution: its stretching of a central principle of traditional economics, the law of diminishing returns. This says that, as production expands, every individual producer will eventually find that his costs per unit start to rise. This may happen for a variety of reasons: what matters is that, beyond a certain point, size breeds inefficiency. The result is profound: firms stop growing, and competition can flourish.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Production of software does not appear to obey this rule--or, at any rate, not in a straightforward way. Once a program has been written, it costs next to nothing to manufacture and market. That is why software companies can choose to sell their products very cheaply or indeed give them away. As Doom proved, once market share has been gained, it becomes easier to sell follow-on products at higher prices. Microsoft and others recognised this years ago by offering "competitive upgrades": owners of competing software can buy the Microsoft version at a huge discount. Since each copy costs Microsoft only a tiny fraction of even the discounted price, each sale generates revenue it would not otherwise have had, and produces a new customer who might be persuaded to buy the next upgrade at the full price.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This stretching of the law of diminishing returns has other implications too. In the mid-1980s, Brian Arthur, a Stanford economist, noticed three common factors in the booming computer industry of Silicon Valley. First, software, in common with other high-technology products such as pharmaceuticals, has very high development costs, but very low production costs. Second, networks of users want compatible software. And third, customers, once they have chosen a program, tend to "groove in"; learning to use software takes time, and information is often saved in proprietary file formats, so switching programs is painful.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this seemed to Mr Arthur to add up to a different economic model: one of increasing returns. Simply stated, this describes the tendency of market leaders to get even further ahead. The cost of developing a program is the same whether a company sells one copy or 10m. Thus, while the market leader and the followers have the same costs, the leader makes more money. The winning firm can invest that money in developing new products, lengthening its lead. Network effects and customer groove-in further strengthen its hold on the market.

</p><p><b>Winner takes all</b>
<br>Increasing returns is not a new idea. However, Mr Arthur argues that the development of high-technology industry lends it an altogether new significance. This is a controversial position, and for good reasons: an economy ruled by increasing returns is a scary thing to contemplate. Free markets work well because they tend to reach equilibrium, with many companies competing and no one firm dominating for too long. In the world of increasing returns, this equilibrium would seem to break down: the big tend to get bigger without limit. Monopoly power becomes pervasive, and the need for vigorous regulation by government correspondingly great. Indeed, Mr Arthur himself argued in a brief submitted by a group of software companies to America's Justice Department that the effects of increasing returns gave Microsoft unfair monopoly powers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Justice Department--wisely--chose not to prosecute. Software economics is not as threatening as it seems. To understand why, consider it in the traditional two parts: supply and demand. Increasing returns primarily influence the supply side: more market share leads to more profit, which leads to more new products, and so on. Network effects influence demand: the more customers you have, the more you get.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But both have their limitations. On the supply side, the Internet's new economics of production and distribution lower the cost for everyone, and languages like Java will lead to a proliferation of small programs that will be relatively cheap to develop. This will reduce the cost of entering the software market; technological ingenuity and a spirit of innovation will matter more than marketing clout, manpower and other expensive resources. The smaller the initial cost, the smaller the financial advantages of increasing returns.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Increasing returns eventually run out of steam, too. As the previous article argued, Microsoft is reaching saturation in its biggest markets. Climbing from a market share of 98% to 99%--converting the most tenacious hold-outs--costs more than simply riding the rising tide between, say, a share of 60% and 70%. All software products will eventually reach such limits. Diminishing returns still kick in, just later than they might in other industries.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the demand side, network effects also have limits--most obviously because not all software is used by people on networks. Games and personal organisers, for example, are generally a matter of personal choice. Where networks are involved, they may be mostly local rather than global ones. One company may settle on Microsoft's Excel as its spreadsheet throughout the firm, but another will choose Lotus <font size=-1>1-2-3</font>. Since spreadsheet files are rarely exchanged between firms, global standards are not an issue. Indeed, Lotus <font size=-1>1-2-3</font> once did have a dominant market share, and lost it to Excel, despite having the force of increasing returns on its side. The same happened to WordPerfect's word processor.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Furthermore, network effects hold only until a new technology takes over, changing the entire market. In a world of e-mail and fax, it no longer matters much who controls the telex market. Likewise, American Express's travellers'-cheque network does not count for much when tourists discover that their regular bank cards work around the world. Because the Internet allows technology to proliferate so quickly, these shifts will occur more frequently, knocking incumbents off their network-effect perches.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These factors limit the effect of increasing returns, but do not render them illusory. Costs are lower on the Internet, but not zero; and the Internet, which is nothing but a big computer network, tends to amplify network effects. The more computers are connected, the more their software must work together, and the more software works together, the greater the need for a single standard. In the real world, a telephone need only connect to a standard outlet: any of them will do. On the Internet, "telephones" are intelligent programs that will work only with compatible software; communication is possible only among those that obey the same protocols. Hence the tendency for a market leader to emerge and dominate, at least until the next technology--videophones, say--takes over.
</p><p><b>The software economy</b></b>
<br>The economic implications of the digital revolution extend far beyond the software industry. Any information-based industry will be subject to the same forces as it automates and moves on-line. Banking, for example, has traditionally been a diminishing-returns business. But as banking moves on-line, the work of processing customers' business is done by cheap computers, not expensive staff. The bank that has the greatest reach and can spread its fixed costs over the largest number of customers will be able to offer the best rates and deals, thereby attracting even more customers. Enter increasing returns.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The same can be said for all sorts of service industries, from processing insurance-claims forms to managing inventories. Whenever computers and networks can greatly diminish variable costs, volume suddenly becomes all-important: the more the better. What worked for Doom can work for Deutsche Telekom. "Everything's going software," says Mr Arthur, with a gleam in his eye.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832978800,sur">Search</a>
