<html><head><title>Dangerous deriving?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><!img src="images/ib3.gif"  alt="Illustration">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Dangerous deriving?</h1>

<br><p>WILLIAM MCDONOUGH, the president of the ederal Reserve Bank of New York, has dubbed it "derivatives angst": the nagging feeling that sooner or later a transaction involving some swap or option will go wrong, causing panic in the banking system.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Concern that derivatives may pose a threat to banks has been fuelled by recent derivatives-related disasters at big firms such as Japan's Kashima Oil and Germany's Metallgesellschaft; by a messy legal battle between Procter &amp; Gamble and Bankers Trust, an American bank accused of selling its client dud interest-rate swaps; and by the huge losses on Nikkei and Japanese government-bond futures that sank Britain's Barings. The main culprit was often not derivatives but lax internal controls or a failure to price risk properly; yet the impression that derivatives are dangerous has stuck. Do they really pose a new and particularly pernicious form of systemic risk?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In principle, swaps, options and the like actually help to reduce the chance of a systemic crisis by providing a cheap and efficient mechanism for shifting risk from those who do not want it to those who do. As Martin Taylor, the boss of Barclays Bank, puts it, "Risk, like energy, is neither created nor destroyed, merely passed around." If it ends up in the hands of those who know what to do with it, the system will emerge stronger as a result.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, banks are not putting as much money at risk in derivatives as hysterical commentators sometimes suggest. When a bank makes a loan, it runs a big credit risk. If the borrower defaults, in some cases it can lose all of its money. But derivatives contracts are different. The size of a contract, or its "notional" value, is simply a reference point for calculating how much is actually owed. For instance, an interest-rate swap may have a notional value of $40m, but the cost of replacing it if one party defaults will reflect only the movement in interest rates since the contract was drawn up.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Often, this is a small fraction of the notional value. According to the Bank for International Settlements, the cost of replacing all of the over-the-counter (<font size=-1>OTC</font>) derivatives contracts (ie, those not traded on an exchange) outstanding at the end of March 1995 was $1.7 trillion, or just 4% of their notional value. A recent study for the New York Fed shows that--except for J.P. Morgan and Bankers Trust--most banks' credit risk from derivatives is tiny compared with that from lending (see <a href="images/csu120.gif">chart</a>). So if they are going to go bust, it will probably still be in the old-fashioned way.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The outcome of the Barings affair has also confounded Cassandras who had predicted that the collapse of a big trader would badly hit both the derivatives exchanges involved and the underlying market (in this case, Japan's stockmarket). In the event, both the Singapore International Monetary Exchange and the Osaka Securities Exchange coped with the shock; and when the Japanese market opened on the Monday after Barings closed, the Nikkei average fell just 4% before bouncing back the next day.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some regulators worry that derivatives make it easier for banks to "leverage" themselves because the downpayment for a contract is much smaller than the amount of money it puts at risk. But there are plenty of other ways in which banks can take huge bets on markets. As for worries about derivatives' complexity, the recent disasters mostly involved relatively simple contracts. The true cause of the fiascos was not complexity but greed, hubris or mismanagement--and sometimes all three.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another much-cited cause for concern is the biggest banks' domination of their industry's derivatives business. According to the same Fed study, at the end of 1994 the seven largest bank derivative dealers accounted for more than 90% of all contracts held by American banks. But by and large these firms have also invested more heavily in risk-management systems than smaller banks, and have good credit ratings. A more fragmented market would not necessarily lessen the risk of a systemic crisis; it might even increase it by bringing in many less experienced players.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The lack of widely available information about some areas of the <font size=-1>OTC</font> derivatives business is worrying. But at last banks everywhere seem to be recognising that it is in everybody's best interest to know as much as possible about their counterparties, and their counterparties' counterparties. In the past couple of years a stream of reports from industry groups and regulatory bodies have recommended changes in disclosure and accounting policies to clear away much of the statistical fog.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This does not mean that regulators can afford to relax. Banks' derivatives activities need no less attention (but no more either) than the other parts of their business. The fact that they have become far bigger forces in derivatives than, say, securities houses, is striking. One possible explanation for this comes from a report on derivatives published in 1994 by America's General Accounting Office, a congressional watchdog. This hints that banks may run bigger risks (relative to their capital) because they have a government safety net to fall back on. If so, the real problem is not derivatives, but governments' willingness to underwrite too much risk. Time, perhaps, for some taxpayer angst?


</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?830559600,sur">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="ibsu4.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
