HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 01:32:14 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:13 GMT
Content-length: 16135
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>A financial horror story</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="images/ib4.gif"  alt="Illustration">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<h1>A financial horror story</h1>

<p><b></b></p>
<i>How safety nets create banking zombies</i>

<p>WHY is the banking system so fragile? The answer seems obvious. On the deposit-taking side of their business, banks are vulnerable to contagious runs by uninformed and flighty customers; on the payments side, they can easily become the innocent victims of someone else's problems. End of story. Or is it? According to some economists, leaving the government's safety net off the list of causes of instability in banking is like leaving the Prince of Denmark out of "Hamlet". The net's operation, they say, has created a perverse set of incentives in banking that is contributing to the rising cost of bank failures.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The debate about the safety net is liveliest in America, which has long relied on deposit insurance to prevent systemic problems in its atomised banking system (at the last count it still had over 10,000 banks). The Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (<font size=-1>FDIC</font>), which manages the bank insurance fund, and the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corporation (<font size=-1>FSLIC</font>), which manages the <font size=-1>S&L</font>s' one, were both set up in 1934, after the worst period of instability in American banking history. The aim was to reassure worried depositors that even if their bank ran into trouble, their money was safe.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other countries with more concentrated banking systems have largely relied on a lender of last resort to deal with troubled banks. Although many of them have set up their own insurance schemes, these have been intended mainly to protect depositors, not to prop up the system. Most of these schemes offer less generous coverage than America's 100% of deposits up to $100,000 (see <a href="images/tsu258.gif">table</a>), and come in 57 different varieties. Britain's, for instance, is statutory and, in effect, compulsory; Germany's is informal and voluntary. America's scheme is administered by the government, whereas those in Germany and France are privately run. Most rely on contributions from the banks, with governments chipping in once a fund has been exhausted.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until the 1980s, government insurance of deposits in America seemed to be that rare thing, an economic policy that worked as intended. In the 1920s the country lost roughly 6,000 of its 30,000 banks, and thousands more between 1930 and 1933, amid numerous runs. But between the establishment of the <font size=-1>FDIC</font> and the early 1980s, on average only about 15 commercial banks a year failed. Much the same was true for <font size=-1>S&L</font>s. Yet by the end of 1991, 1,000 banks were on the <font size=-1>FDIC</font>'s problem list; and by 1992 almost half the 4,000 thrifts that had been around at the start of the 1980s had disappeared. <font size=-1>FSLIC</font> went bankrupt, requiring a $150 billion government bailout.
</p><p><b>Betting the bank</b></b>
<br>What went wrong? Part of the blame has been laid on rising interest rates, incompetent management and lax oversight. But the main lesson of the thrift crisis in particular is the "moral hazard" created by comprehensive deposit insurance. Knowing that their money was safe, the thrifts' small depositors had no incentive to monitor the risks these institutions were taking. At the same time, stiffer competition encouraged thrifts to take bigger risks with depositors' money, safe in the knowledge that if the worst came to the worst, the government would protect depositors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A paper by Arthur Rolnick of the Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis*<font size=1>(1)&#160; </font> provides a neat illustration of the problem. Assume, he says, that a man who has $200,000 in cash uses $100,000 of it to open a bank, which becomes a member of the <font size=-1>FDIC</font>. Assume, too, that he offers a rate of interest slightly above his competitors' and attracts $900,000 of deposits. The bank now has $1m of reserves (his $100,000 of equity plus $900,000 of deposits). To put the bank's $1m to work, he goes to Las Vegas, finds a casino with a roulette wheel and bets the entire amount on black. At the same time, he bets his remaining cash of $100,000 on the only other colour, red.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;From the bank's point of view, this is an extremely risky investment, but to the shareholder it looks perfectly safe. If the red comes up, the bank goes bust, making its stock worthless. But the shareholder's winning private bet on red takes his cash to $200,000, back where he started before he opened the bank. If the black comes up, he will have lost his $100,000 bet, but the rise in the value of his bank stock will more than compensate for that. As for the bank's small depositors, they do not care what the bank does because their money, including the interest on it, is protected by the <font size=-1>FDIC</font>. This example shows that, provided shareholders can either hedge the risk of their investment in a bank, or are relaxed about it because it represents only a small fraction of their overall portfolio, they will want the bank to pursue the riskiest strategy possible.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But is this what happens in real life? The parallel depends on the financial health of a bank. In good times, its managers are unlikely to take huge risks with depositors' and shareholders' money, not least because they have their jobs and reputations to protect. But their attitude could change if the bank is close to insolvency. By raising rates to attract new deposits and then betting everything on a few risky investments, they can try to turn it around. This "gambling for resurrection", in economists' parlance, is what happened at many troubled thrifts, which often tried to avoid liquidation by spending billions of dollars on risky junk bonds, or investing in shopping centres in the middle of the desert. Some banks also took reckless gambles, only to end up in the arms of the insurance fund.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Surely, you might think, big, uninsured depositors at a bank or thrift would put a stop to this? Not necessarily. For a start, governments often bail out all the depositors of big banks that run into trouble. When Continental Illinois became insolvent in 1984, the <font size=-1>FDIC</font> announced that it would protect all depositors, not just small ones. The rescue of France's Cr&eacutedit Lyonnais, state support for big banks in Sweden, Finland and Norway, and Latin American governments' efforts to protect their banking flagships all bear witness to a "too big to fail" policy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even big depositors in smaller banks have little incentive to keep an eagle eye on their bankers. To see why, consider the ways in which governments deal with the corpse of a bank that has gone bust. These include:
<ul>
<font size=-1><li></font>Burial (or liquidation). This involves paying off a bank's insured depositors and then selling its assets to help reimburse any uninsured creditors, including the deposit insurer itself. <font size=-1>BCCI</font> was laid to rest in this way.
<font size=-1><li></font>Reincarnation (or merger). If there is still some value in a deceased bank's franchise--its customer base, its labour force, its branch network--another bank might be willing to buy it and to take over its liabilities, possibly with some financial help from the deposit insurer. An example of a bank reborn is Barings, which was bought by <font size=-1>ING</font> of the Netherlands in March 1995.
<font size=-1><li></font>Resuscitation (or state guarantee). A bank may be revived either by providing it with a state guarantee of its borrowings, or by stripping some of the worst loans off its balance sheet and placing them in a state-financed "bad" bank. Both France and Sweden have used this method.
<font size=-1><li></font>Divine intervention (or nationalisation). This is the most extreme solution, reserved for occasions when a government fears that the collapse of a bank could trigger a systemic crisis. The Norwegian state took over some of the country's biggest banks in the early 1990s because it feared a run on them.
</ul>
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When a bank is "buried", its uninsured depositors are unlikely to get much, if any, of their money back. In <font size=-1>BCCI</font>'s case, for example, the British government steadfastly refused to pay out more than the official limit. But under the other methods, both big and small deposits are usually fully protected. So the prospect of lots of burials would provide a strong incentive for big depositors either to stop their banks from taking big risks or to pull their money out fast if they do. Unfortunately, burials are rare. In a study*<font size=1>(2)&#160; </font>of 120 bank failures in 24 countries, mainly between the early 1980s and early 1990s, Charles Goodhart and Dirk Schoenmaker of the London School of Economics found that two out of three failed banks were bailed out.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This highlights another problem. Regulators routinely tell banks that if they become insolvent, they will be dealt with harshly. But when banks, especially large ones, get into trouble, the same regulators often work hard to keep them afloat. This "regulatory forbearance" undermines the credibility of the threat.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why do regulators forbear? They may be worried that closing one bank could trigger a run on others, or they may be under pressure from politicians to show leniency. Whatever the reason, the cost of procrastination can be high, as America's thrift crisis showed. When rising interest rates tipped many thrifts into insolvency in 1982, regulators tried to sweep the problem under the carpet by altering the accounting rules they applied to the industry. They knew that the alternative--closing the thrifts down, at an estimated cost of $20 billion--would bankrupt the <font size=-1>FSLIC</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The regulators were encouraged in their efforts by national and state politicians who lobbied on the thrifts' behalf. Thus they helped keep alive what Ed Kane, a professor at Boston College, calls "zombie" <font size=-1>S&L</font>s--living-dead institutions that distorted the rest of the market by offering higher interest rates and slashing loan prices in a gamble for resurrection. This forced healthier thrifts to follow suit, turning them into zombies too. In the end the industry had to be bailed out anyway, by which time the price tag had risen to an exceedingly painful $150 billion.
</p><p><b>Cheques, but few balances</b></b>
<br>In their defence, regulators argue that sometimes forbearance is essential to avert a run on a bank. The same argument is often used to justify the intervention of a lender of last resort to prop up an ailing bank. Take America's Continental Illinois, mentioned earlier in this article. When, in 1984, it suffered a disastrous run on its interbank deposits, nearly 1,000 other banks had money in its accounts. Without government support, a systemic crisis might have erupted. But some academics have since questioned the case for a rescue.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;George Kaufman, a professor at Loyola University in Chicago, has claimed that before the bailout, regulators were assuming that the recovery rate on Continental's assets would be around 97%--a level at which only two creditor banks would have lost between half and all of their capital. In the event, the recovery rate was a little above 95%, close to the original estimate. Yet when the crisis occurred, the size of the bank's losses and the time it would take to recover its assets were both unclear. This uncertainty could have triggered a much wider run if the Federal Reserve had not provided the bank with emergency loans. The Bank of England also invoked the threat of a widespread run to justify a &#163;240m ($360m) rescue plan in 1991 for several small British banks that had got into trouble after lending heavily to the property sector.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some scholars, including Mr Kaufman, argue that bank runs are not as threatening as they seem because they generally involve a flight to quality, with depositors pulling their money out of sick banks and redepositing it with healthy ones. This means bad banks close faster. But what if fleeing depositors simply stick their cash under mattresses instead of putting it into another bank? In such cases, the academics say, governments should pump money into the banking system as a whole to offset the effects of a monetary contraction.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Their case for restraint at first sight seems compelling, but it takes no account of the other economic costs of bank runs. They can destroy long-standing relationships between banks and their customers, who have to spend time and money finding new sources of finance. Moreover, those banks that survive may be reluctant to take risks with new borrowers. It is these side-effects--call the problem "systemic mess"--that make bank failures so damaging to an economy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;None of this is an excuse for lenders of last resort to hand ailing banks a blank cheque, however. More than a century ago, in his book "Lombard Street", Walter Bagehot, a former editor of this newspaper, provided central bankers with a classic guide to handling the problem. They should, he wrote, lend only to banks that are solvent but illiquid, and then only at a penal rate. He also said that lenders of last resort should make their intentions clear in advance to discourage banks from taking excessive risks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A handful of central bankers have heeded this advice, including Eddie George, the governor of the Bank of England. He has publicly stated several times that the Bank will prop up institutions only if their failure poses a systemic risk, and that any support given would be on particularly onerous terms. The collapse of <font size=-1>BCCI</font> and, in particular, Barings provided proof that the Bank means what it says. Most other central banks have left their intentions unspoken--a policy known as "constructive ambiguity". Yet their actions have often been far from ambiguous. Time and again, they have leapt to the aid of big banks, reinforcing the impression that, solvent or not, some of them are "too big to fail". In many cases, they have been unwilling to let even small banks collapse.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The trouble is that by being too generous with their support, most lenders of last resort have eroded the penalties for excessive risk-taking in banking. Japan is one of the countries that has discovered just how dangerous and expensive it can be to ignore Bagehot's advice.

<br><hr><br><font size=-1>*(1) "Market Discipline as a Regulator of Bank Risk", by Arthur Rolnick. In "Safeguarding the Banking System in an Environment of Financial Cycles". Federal Reserve Bank of Boston, 1993.


<br><br>*(2)  "The Central Bank and the Financial System", by C.A.E. Goodhart. MacMillan, 1995.</font>



