<html><head><title>Safe banking</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="images/ib6.gif"  alt="Illustration">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<h1>Safe banking</h1>

<p><b></b></p>
<i>Like safe sex, safe banking requires effective precautions</i>

<p>THERE is a simple solution to the problem of moral hazard. The bosses of Japanese banks that fail could be made to fall on their swords. American bankers could be tossed from the top of the Empire State building, French ones from the Eiffel Tower. That would make bankers much more cautious in future, and banks much less fragile. But leaving aside the humanitarian objections, there is another snag: lending would dry up. Companies and individuals would find it far harder to get credit, and society as a whole would be worse off.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Striking the right balance between efficiency and financial stability is a devilishly difficult task, as America's <font size=-1>S&L</font>s and Japan's <i>jusen</i> have demonstrated. Academics, consultants and regulators are still trying to come up with ways of avoiding the pitfalls. One school of thought argues that the present system of regulation can be modified in ways that will help to reduce, though not eliminate, moral hazard. Another argues that more far-reaching changes are needed in the structure of the safety net that underpins most of the world's banks. This article considers the regulators' responses to the increasing complexity of banking risks. The next looks at some of the radical suggestions for reforming the structure of the banking system to make it safer.
</p><p><b>Tightening the screws</b></b>
<br>An obvious answer to the problem of moral hazard is to tighten regulation dramatically, while retaining comprehensive deposit insurance. But there are several problems with this approach. For a start, it probably would not work, because banks are past masters at finding loopholes in laws. Worse, an attempt to turn the screws might simply drive business to more lightly regulated offshore havens. It would certainly impose an even heftier burden on banks, which would pass it on to their customers. A study by the London Business School last year found that the annual direct cost of financing regulators' activities in Britain was almost &#163;90m ($140m); in America, it was $795m. On top of this, banks also have to foot the bill for the paperwork that regulators demand. The American Bankers Association has estimated the cost of this to its members at $14 billion a year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So rather than introducing new restrictions, some governments are looking for other ways of getting banks to behave more prudently. One option is to give all depositors a greater incentive to monitor their banks by limiting government insurance to a fixed percentage of deposits--a system known as "co-insurance". Under such a scheme, which is currently used in Britain, all depositors have a strong incentive to watch the activities of their banks carefully. At the same time, there is less of an incentive for regulators fully to protect depositors when a bank does go bust.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another way of encouraging banks to be cautious is to tie their deposit-insurance premiums to the riskiness of their portfolios (at present, most premiums are calculated as a straight percentage of a bank's assets). This amounts to charging banks for the risks that they are asking taxpayers to bear. America's <font size=-1>FDIC</font> is in the van: since 1993, it has based its premiums on banks' capital-to-assets ratios and the results of bank examinations. But assessing the exact riskiness of a bank's portfolio is tricky.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Regulators, too, are trying something different. Their idea is to create rules that encourage banks to behave as they would if there were no safety net--a strategy that Tommaso Padoa-Schioppa, the chairman of the Basle Committee on Banking Supervision, has dubbed "market-friendly" regulation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Padoa-Schioppa argues that the original Basle capital ratios on credit risk were a move away from credit ceilings and other administrative measures, and a first step towards market friendliness. But they failed to recognise that some risks cancel each other out; banks must still put capital against them. They also failed to distinguish between different categories of credit risk: for example, loans to a blue-chip corporate giant and a tiny high-tech start-up both carry a risk-weighting of 100%. And so the list of gripes goes on.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the rules covering market risk--the threat of losses on securities because of price movement--the Basle committee has taken a new step. Instead of stipulating a framework of detailed capital ratios for everyone, it has given banks a choice. Either they can use their own financial models to calculate how much capital to hold against their risks (although the result is subject to a multiplier laid down by the committee), or they can use the regulators' standard formula. Each bank must calculate a "value at risk" for itself: the maximum amount that it might expect to lose by holding a particular position for a certain period. If all goes according to plan, this new way of measuring market risk will be implemented by the end of 1997.
</p><p><b>Do-it-yourself regulation</b></b>
<br>The advantage of this method is that it should minimise the distortion of banks' activities caused by rigid capital rules. At the same time it is intended to encourage banks to improve their risk management, because the best risk managers should face relatively low capital charges. In the same spirit, America's Federal Reserve has floated another idea for calculating capital requirements for market risk, called "pre-commitment". This would allow banks to decide for themselves what their likely maximum loss will be on a trading portfolio over a certain period and to set capital aside against this. If the actual losses exceed the limits the banks have set, regulators can "fine" them by, say, imposing extra capital charges.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This carrot-and-stick strategy is based on the realisation that regulators will find it hard to judge which risk-management models will work. Under pre-commitment, they need not bother with such assessments. The problem is that such penalties may not always be an effective deterrent to excessive risk-taking. If a bank has run up far bigger losses than expected on its trading portfolio, a hefty fine might push it into bankruptcy, so regulators might think twice before imposing one.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is another snag with both the model and the pre-commitment approaches. Neither provides a direct answer to the problem of sloppy internal controls. Yet it was these that caused both the Barings and Daiwa Bank crises. Regulators are trying to give banks an incentive to sharpen up here, too. Some are adding a new form of oversight, which America's Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (<font size=-1>OCC</font>) calls "supervision by risk". Eugene Ludwig, the agency's boss, talks about developing "a risk vocabulary for banks" on the basis of the new method that the <font size=-1>OCC</font> began using this year. The idea is for watchdogs to rate banks' internal processes as well as their finances. To do this they must assess, among other things, how much directors know about a bank's risk-management strategy and how independent its internal audit teams are.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But without the powers and resources of a secret police force, regulators will find it hard to monitor banks' affairs so intimately. Better, some say, to rely even more on market forces by making banks issue some form of subordinated debt, if they have not already done so. The idea behind this is simple. Because holders of this debt know that, if a bank fails, their claims will be the last to be honoured (hence the term "subordinated"), they should have a big incentive to monitor banks closely.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But even subordinated debt might not change banks' behaviour if the debtholders believe that governments will tend to rescue troubled banks. Could something be done to cure this habit, too? George Kaufman of Loyola University in Chicago and George Benston of Emory University in Atlanta think so. They are the brains behind a scheme called Structured Early Intervention and Resolution (<font size=-1>SEIR</font>), which tries to mimic what would happen to banks in the absence of deposit insurance by creating a sort of bankruptcy code. Typically, shareholders of an ordinary company whose equity has shrunk dramatically are asked by creditors to recapitalise the firm. If they do not, the creditors may force it into bankruptcy. Yet troubled banks rarely face such ultimatums because their depositors know that the government will rescue them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>SEIR</font> changes this by forcing banks to hold plenty of capital, and by prescribing a series of progressively tougher actions that regulators must take each time a bank's capital-to-assets ratio falls below certain pre-determined levels. When the bank's net worth has reached a pre-set low point, but before it goes into the red, the regulators are meant to shut it down. This system has three big advantages over the status quo. The first is that the sanctions make it far harder for banks to gamble with depositors' cash as their fortunes decline. The second is that at the point when banks are shut, they should still have enough money in their coffers to pay depositors. Lastly, at least in principle, under such a system no bank should be too big to fail.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Japanese and other taxpayers might be delighted at the chance to tie their regulators' hands. But will <font size=-1>SEIR</font> work in practice? America has had its own version, known as "prompt corrective action", since 1991 (see <a href="images/tsu142.gif">table</a>). Among other things, this forbids weak banks from accepting brokered deposits--large sums of money broken up into small amounts so that they qualify for deposit insurance--and restricts the interest rates they can offer. But there have been few big-bank failures in recent years, so the system has not yet been fully tested. Moreover, Messrs Kaufman and Benston complain that the American system has watered down their proposals by, for example, including a get-out clause enabling regulators to offer banks special help in some circumstances.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Market-friendly regulation, supervision by risk and prompt corrective action all seem like perfectly good ideas. But there is no guarantee that they will work, or that the proliferation of rules they imply will be cost-effective. One thing is certain, however. None of them will do any good unless banks are forced to provide more information about their business more quickly. At least one country, New Zealand, is relying on greater disclosure as a substitute for much of the traditional paraphernalia of supervision (see <a href="ibsu8.html">page</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some officials are beginning to suggest that the present system may need to be adapted in more radical ways. In a speech to the World Economic Forum in Davos in February, Thomas Hoenig, the president of the Federal Reserve Board of Kansas City, said that regulators would find it increasingly hard to keep up with large global banks dealing in complex financial instruments. To do so effectively, he said, they would need to know "as much about a bank, its model and control procedures as the rocket scientists who built the model and the management who designed the risk-management strategy." Given these difficulties, Mr Hoenig suggested that it might be time to remove the safety net from such banks altogether. That is just what many financial economists have been saying for some time.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?830559600,sur">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="ibsu8.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
