<html><head><title>A standard dose</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="images/ib8.gif"  alt="Illustration">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<h1>A standard dose</h1>

<p><b></b></p>
<i>Cross-border prescriptions for banking systems can sometimes do more harm than good</i>

<p>AS MEDICAL science progresses in parallel with the appearance of each new disease, so progress on international co-operation in banking is often linked to crises. The Basle Committee on Banking Supervision, founded in the aftermath of the Herstatt affair in 1974, has gradually developed a global framework for dealing with the industry's problems. Many of its achievements are impressive. But occasionally the rich world's central bankers have allowed politics to get in the way of prudence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The original agreement drawn up in 1975 on supervising international banks, known as the Concordat, has been revised twice since then: in 1983, following the collapse of Italy's Banco Ambrosiano, and again in 1992 following the <font size=-1>BCCI</font> affair. Its minimum standards now require, among other things, that all international banks must be supervised on a consolidated basis (ie, looking at their entire business worldwide) by a capable authority from the country in which they have their head office. At the same time, if other countries in which the bank has branches do not think that the "home-country" supervisor is doing a good job, they can restrict the bank's activities there.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;International co-operation has not always gone smoothly. Witness the decision last October by Daiwa Bank's American hosts to make it sell its local operations for failing to inform the Federal Reserve immediately after it found one of the traders in its New York office hiding trading losses of $1.1 billion. The Barings affair, in which a gaggle of regulators in Britain, Japan and Singapore failed to spot what a rogue trader was up to, also showed up gaping holes in the system.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But at least the committee provides a forum in which such problems can be tackled. At the same time, it is valiantly trying to harmonise some of the prudential rules that govern countries' banks. Why bother? After all, domestic lenders of last resort should be able to deal with most banking crises except, say, Herstatt risk. The answer is that, in the absence of harmonisation, countries that tried to tighten their rules unilaterally could find that their entire banking industry had decamped to other, more relaxed regimes, making the system as a whole more fragile.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The trouble with the Basle approach is that any deal requires a lot of political horse-trading. Often, the separate aims of ensuring the system's stability and creating a level playing field between banks from different countries are mixed up. Consider the original Basle capital-adequacy agreement that covers banks' credit risk. Its main backers were American and European banks, which saw it as an ideal way to rein in the lending of Japanese rivals they considered undercapitalised. Smaller countries went along with this, fearing that otherwise their banks would find themselves shut out of several of the world's main financial markets.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The European Union's Capital Adequacy Directive (<font size=-1>CAD</font>), which came into effect in January, is another example of a harmonised rule that puts level playing fields before level-headedness. In a recent paper*, Harald Benink of the University of Limburg and David Llewellyn of Loughborough University argue that the directive is flawed because it applies the same capital standards for market risk--the chance that the price of a security will fall--to banks with securities operations and to ordinary securities firms. Yet securities firms are less risky beasts than banks: they have highly liquid portfolios, unlike banks' illiquid loan books, and are not directly linked to the payments system. By failing to insist on higher capital standards for banks, Messrs Benink and Llewellyn argue, the new European rules may have increased risk in the system.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;None of this undermines the case for closer international co-operation among the world's financial regulators, though it does argue for caution in rule-making. One of the most useful things that the Basle committee does is to collate and publish figures on activity in areas such as derivatives. Together with a group of securities regulators, it has also issued joint proposals aimed at improving the quality of the information that banks and securities houses report about their trading activities.
</p><p><b>Three into one</b></b>
<br>Banking watchdogs have also been working with securities and insurance regulators on the risks posed by the growth of financial conglomerates. In Japan, and to a lesser extent in America, rules and regulations restrict the number of hybrids that can combine securities, banking and insurance (or indeed any two of these) under one corporate roof. But in Europe they are all the rage. In two of the most notable deals concluded last year, Barings was bought by <font size=-1>ING</font> (itself the product of a merger between a Dutch bank and an insurer), and Swiss Bank Corporation gobbled up S.G. Warburg, another British merchant bank.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Countries such as Switzerland, the Netherlands and Germany, whose banking groups have fingers in many pies, have largely managed to avoid banking hiccups. This suggests that diversified financial groups are in fact more stable than narrowly focused ones. But a preliminary report published by a joint group of banking, insurance and securities supervisors last July noted that the growth of such conglomerates also makes it harder for outsiders to get an overall view of the risks that they are running. And it pointed out that problems in one part of a group could quickly spread to other areas, as happened at Barings.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One way of dealing with this blurring of boundaries between different businesses might be to switch from regulation by institution, the most common form now, to regulation by function; in other words, let banking watchdogs supervise the banking operations of all financial firms, insurance regulators the insurance operations and so on. This would ensure a consistent approach to regulation across the industry, but it might cause problems too, because no single body would be able to take an overall view of a group.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some academics have even suggested a variation on this theme that would split supervision between two bodies: one responsible for ensuring systemic stability across the financial industry, and another responsible for consumer-protection issues. Such novel schemes would probably be better than the status quo, but they would not be foolproof. Besides, fiddling with the regulatory system will do nothing to tackle the underlying cause of financial instability: governments themselves.

<br><hr><br>
<font size=-1>* "Systemic Stability and Competitive Neutrality Issues", by Harald Benink and David Llewellyn. <i>Journal of Financial Services Research</i>, Vol 9, No 3/4, December 1995.</font>



