<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width="271" height="24" alt="Politics this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>The enemy within
</h2>In his state-of-the-union message to Congress, President Clinton said <b>America's greatest enemy </b>was "inaction", and accordingly called for action to balance the budget (spending will rise only slightly, to $1.69 trillion for fiscal 1998), reform campaign finance and welfare, and improve schools.
<p>More than a year after his acquittal in a criminal trial, a jury in a civil trial found <b>O.J. Simpson</b> responsible for the deaths of his ex-wife, Nicole Brown Simpson, and her friend, Ronald Goldman. He must pay $8.5m in compensatory damages; punitive damages, expected to be "gigantic", were yet to be assessed.
<p>In <b>Ecuador</b>, unions launched a general strike against President Abdala Bucaram's austerity policies, and demanded his resignation.
<p>Several days' fighting between <b>Colombian government troops </b>and <font size=-1>FARC</font> guerrillas only 50km from Bogota left at least 15 dead on each side.
<p>A new twist to <b>Mexico's</b> <b>soap opera</b>. The plot so far: (1) Raul Salinas, brother of ex-President Carlos, is accused of murdering a top politician in 1994. (2) A "psychic" helps police unearth the corpse on a ranch of Raul's; (3) it is the wrong man. (4) The main investigator is sacked, along with his boss, the (non-ruling-party) attorney-general.
<p>(5) The psychic is arrested and accused of planting the stiff. This week: the ex-investigator is accused of paying her to do so. Nonsense, he says; electoral flam, says his ex-boss.
<p>President Alberto Fujimori of <b>Peru</b> talked to Japan's prime minister in Toronto about the Lima hostages. He is trying to get talks moving with the Tupac Amaru guerrillas, but will not consider releasing their imprisoned comrades.
<p><h2>Israel in mourning
</h2>A day of national mourning was proclaimed in <b>Israel</b> after 73 soldiers and airmen were killed when two helicopters carrying troops into Lebanon collided. 
<p>Rebels in <b>Zaire</b> moved into the southern province of Shaba. A promised government counter-offensive failed to materialise.
<p>The<b> </b><font size=-1>UN</font> pulled out of the western region of Rwanda after four <b>human-rights monitors </b>were shot dead.
<p>At least 38 people were murdered in <b>Algeria</b>, bringing the number killed in political violence to over 300 since Ramadan began on January 10th.
<p><h2>Pressed rulers
</h2>Bulgaria's ruling Socialist Party caved in to demands for an <b>early election</b>, to be held in mid-April, after a month of protests and strikes.
<p>Serbia's president, <b>Slob</b><b>o</b><b>dan Milos</b><b>evic</b>, appeared to concede that the opposition had won elections to the councils of Serbia's biggest towns.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>Rioting in <b>Albania</b> intensified in the unrest over collapsed pyramid schemes.
<p>Sweden's minority Social Democratic government said it would start shutting down <b>nuclear power plants</b>. 
<p>Switzerland's three biggest banks set up a SFr100m ($70m) fund to compensate <b>Holocaust victims</b> who deposited money in the country. America, Britain and France froze $68m-worth of gold stolen by the Nazis from European countries.
<p>France's president, Jacques Chirac, met his Russian counterpart, Boris Yeltsin, for a three-hour discussion about the <b>enlargement of NATO</b>. Mr Chirac then proposed a five-nation summit on European security in Paris.
<p><b>German unemployment </b> rose in January to 4.7m, the highest figure since Hitler took power in 1933. This represents about 12% of the workforce (11% in the west, 19% in the east).
<p>(See <a href="ww1.gif">chart</a>)<br><b>Luxembourgers </b>were richer than Americans in 1995. The <font size=-1>EU</font> members poorer than the Union average were Finns, Britons, Irish, Spaniards, Portuguese and Greeks.
<p>Marek Belka, an economist of liberal views and no party affiliation, replaced the irascible Grzegorz Kolodko as <b>Poland's finance minister</b>. He promised to overhaul the social-security system.
<p>Eurostat, the <font size=-1>EU</font>'s statistical service, ruled in favour of accounting tricks adopted by Italy, France, Belgium, Spain and others, making it easier for them to qualify for <b>Europe's single currency </b>in 1999. Separate reports that Italy may be kept out of the first wave of entrants produced an angry response from Romano Prodi, Italy's prime minister, who insisted Italy would be in at the start.
<p><h2>Sharif's mandate
</h2>Nawaz Sharif's Muslim League had <b>an easy victory in Pakistan</b>'s general election, winning at least 134 seats in the 217-seat parliament, and crushing the party of Benazir Bhutto, the former prime minister.
<p>Tensions between <b>Christians and Muslims </b>grew in the Philippines after a Roman Catholic bishop, Benjamin de Jesus, was shot dead in Jolo, a Muslim-dominated town in the south.
<p>The United States is considering reducing the number of its <b>troops in Asia</b>,<b> </b>at present 100,000, according to a report in Washington.
<p>Britain said it will grant citizenship to Indians, Pakistanis and other <b>minorities in Hong Kong</b> when the colony reverts to China in July. China has refused them Chinese citizenship.
<p><b>Australia </b>plans a "people's convention" to consider whether the country should become a republic, replacing Queen Elizabeth with an Australian head of state. Opinion polls suggest about half of voters want a republic.
<p>

</td></tr></table></center>
