<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Leading the pack
</h2>(See <a href="bw1.gif">chart</a>)<br><b>Morgan Stanley</b>, one of America's leading investment banks,<b> </b>and <b>Dean Witter</b>,<b> </b>a retail broker whose Discover credit card is America's third most common, are merging to create a firm with a market value of $23 billion. The new financial giant will have assets under management of more than $270 billion.
<p><b>Nippon Credit</b>, one of Japan's top 20 banks, denied that it was close to bankruptcy. But its soothing words failed to arrest a sharp fall in its share price.
<p>An offer last week by <b>Abbey National</b>, Britain's fifth-largest bank, for <b>Scottish Amicable</b> brought out other suitors interested in the mutual life insurer, which has plans to demutualise. The <b>Prudential</b>, Britain's biggest life insurer, topped the Abbey's offer by offering &#163;1.9 billion ($3 billion) for the group.
<p><b>Alan Bond</b>, already in prison, was given a four-year sentence in Perth for his part in Australia's biggest corporate fraud. He pleaded guilty to charges related to a A$1 billion ($770m) unsecured loan from Bell Resources to prop up Bond Corp.
<p><b>Gold</b> prices, depressed by worries that European central banks will sell more gold to ensure governments meet criteria for economic and monetary union, recovered a little after Eurostat, a statistical agency, said that governments could not use proceeds from gold sales for that purpose--although they could be used to pay down public debt.
<p><h2>Unravelled
</h2>Britain's <b>Cable & Wireless</b> is pulling out of its joint alliance with <b>Veba </b>and <b>RWE</b>, two German utilities. The alliance was formed to challenge Deutsche Telekom after the telecoms industry is liberalised next year. Veba has made an offer to <font size=-1>C&W</font> for its 45% stake in Vebacom and hopes to find another international telecoms partner. <font size=-1>C&W</font> may have a bigger tie-up in mind. 
<p><b>Sotheby's</b>, the world's biggest firm of auctioneers, suspended senior members of staff following allegations in a <font size=-1>TV</font> documentary that it had systematically smuggled art treasures into Britain.
<p>The outlook for <b>digital broadcasting in Britain </b>improved after British Digital Broadcasting, a consortium made up of <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> and Britain's two biggest independent television companies, Carlton and Granada, bid for a licence to provide terrestrial digital-<font size=-1>TV</font> channels.<b> </b>Separately, <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> will launch 200 channels of digital satellite <font size=-1>TV</font> in the autumn. <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> also said it might pull out of a digital-<font size=-1>TV</font> deal with Kirch in Germany.

<p>French water and media conglomerate <b>G&eacute;n&eacute;rale des Eaux </b>plans to sell its 19.3% stake in pay-<font size=-1>TV</font> group <b>Canal Plus </b>to Havas, another media giant.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>Canada made some moves to liberalise its <b>telecoms </b>industry as the World Trade Organisation continued to argue about how to reach a telecoms pact by a deadline of February 15th. 
<p><h2>Diced Apple
</h2>Faced with steeply falling revenues and rising losses, <b>Apple Computer</b> is restructuring, again. It will consolidate sales, marketing and research units into fewer groups to save money; job cuts will be announced later. Both co-founders are now back at Apple part-time: first Steve Jobs, now Steve Wozniak.
<p>America's <b>Goodyear Tire & Rubber</b>, the world's third-largest tyre maker, and Japan's <b>Sumitomo Rubber</b>, the fifth-largest, have agreed to make car tyres for each other in Asia and North America, beginning later this year. Up to 2m tyres per year will be produced up to the end of 2000.
<p><b>Sony</b> of Japan said group net profit nearly doubled in the third quarter and predicted record profits for the year ending March 31st. Sales of PlayStation, its video-game player, boosted operating income in its electronics unit. A weaker yen also helped.
<p>Japan and the European Union settled their long-standing row over discriminatory Japanese taxes on European spirits. <b>Taxes on whisky </b>and cognac will be 3% higher than Japan's home-grown <i>shochu</i> (the current gap is 500%); the 140% penalty on vodka and gin will disappear altogether.
<p><b>PepsiCo</b> slumped after big losses in its international soft-drinks operations. Strong competition from Coca-Cola reduced Pepsi's net profit of $181m in the fourth quarter of 1995 to $28m in the fourth quarter of 1996.
<p>Patricia Reggiani, ex-wife of <b>Maurizio Gucci</b>, a grandson of the founder of the Gucci fashion empire, was charged with his murder. Gucci was shot dead outside his office in Milan in 1995.
<p>Shares in Dixons, a big British electrical retailer, fell after <b>Sir Stanley Kalms</b>, the firm's chairman, sold 1.1m shares for &#163;5.7m ($9.2m) days after criticising a broker who had advised clients to sell.
<p><h2>Getting fit
</h2>(See <a href="bw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>Germany's <b>Lufthansa</b>, which is to be fully privatised later this year, is putting all its passenger services into a single profit centre with its own divisional management board. One in ten management jobs will go. Unions called this a "declaration of war", but the carrier's share price rose 5.6% on the news.
<p><b>Air France</b> and <b>Alitalia</b> are henceforth to share codes and bookings and generally explore "all possible synergies" between the two airlines.
<p>The Netherlands' <b>KLM</b> increased revenues in its third quarter but slipped into a net loss of 7m guilders ($4m) compared with a profit of 102m guilders a year earlier as fuel costs soared.
<p>

</td></tr></table></center>
