<html><head><title>A travesty of justice</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>

<h1 align=left>A travesty of justice</h1>


<p><b>Why the second O.J.Simpson trial was not much better than the first</b><p>
AFTER the first triumphant volley of shouts from white onlookers, America has reacted in rather subdued fashion to the second Simpson verdict. Well it might. The second trial, which found the former football star "liable for the deaths" of his ex-wife, Nicole, and her friend Ron Goldman, was less about justice than about revenge. Because the first trial had produced a result that seemed to many ridiculous, the families of the victims tried it again another way. The result, from their point of view, was satisfactory; it has staunched their grief and made their lives more bearable. But was this second process any more just?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Simpson's first trial, on criminal charges, was a farce. The judge barely controlled his courtroom; examination and cross-examination rolled on interminably; witnesses played to the cameras; incriminating evidence, such as the car chase after the murder, was not admitted. Most notably, the judge allowed the defence to skew the case at issue from one of murder to one of racist conspiracy by the police; at which the jury, which was mostly black, decided to acquit Mr Simpson. Their decision was defensible; doubts had been introduced about the trustworthiness of the evidence, and criminal trials do not allow equivocation. Nonetheless, they delivered their verdict so quickly--after mere hours of deliberation--that it seemed to many that the verdict had nothing to do with justice, and everything to do with race.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On its face, the second trial was much more efficient (see <a href="am3224.html">page)</a>. As a civil process, its aims were more modest: to establish responsibility for the deaths and to set damages. It was conducted, by Hiroshi Fujisaki, with almost brutal dispatch. Cameras were banned. Mr Simpson was made to take the stand (where he did himself no good). The judge refused, from the start, to allow racist conspiracy theories to be aired in court, and so gave greater credence to bits of evidence--such as blood samples--that had been disputed in the previous trial. Yet since all this was so, and since the jury this time contained only one black, the verdict was not much in doubt at any point; this was the trial that would find Mr Simpson guilty. And the result is bizarre in the extreme: a man who is held to have killed two people is allowed to remain free.
<br></p><p><b><b>Keeping jeopardy single</b>
</b><br>America's constitution forbids double jeopardy: a man may not be tried twice for the same offence. Yet lawyers resist the notion of double jeopardy in the Simpson case. After all, they say, the first trial was criminal: the charge was murder, and Mr Simpson stood to lose his liberty and possibly his life. The second was civil: different charges, and only money, not freedom, at stake. Doubtless this makes a world of difference to lawyers, the main beneficiaries from any duplication of trials. But it is an unconvincing distinction. Mr Simpson was indeed on trial for the same offence, though dressed up in different words. The actions under discussion (knifing, near-decapitation) were the same; the evidence produced against him (clothing, blood) was largely the same. Indeed, where is the difference, except in the labelling and the penalties? 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is not the first such double-trial to have happened in America. The policemen who beat Rodney King, a black motorist, were also tried twice (the first time for beating, the second time for "depriving" Mr King of his civil rights), until the "right" verdict was reached, the one that found them guilty. It is becoming something of a habit, especially in trials that are hugely controversial and where race is a factor. The second trial may indeed seem an "improvement" on the first: more soberly conducted, in a less explosive atmosphere. But it is hard to believe that when trials are held again in a different place, with a differently balanced jury, the intent is to establish justice. Whatever the truth, such a process is inherently unjust. The intent, surely, is to correct the mess that was made the first time. Yet to avoid a mess the first time would be much the better--and more just--course.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
