<html><head><title>If at first you don't succeed . . .</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>The Simpson verdict
<h1>If at first you don't succeed . . .</h1>

</b></p><font size=1>LOS ANGELES
</font><p>TWO and a half years after they were butchered, Ron Goldman and Nicole Brown Simpson may finally be allowed to rest. On the evening of February 4th, seconds after Bill Clinton finished his state-of-the-union message, the jury in O.J. Simpson's civil trial pronounced its verdict, ruling that Mr Simpson was liable for the deaths of both victims, and awarding the Goldman family $8.5m in compensation. The jury's verdicts were unanimous throughout; asked, during jury polling, if he agreed with his fellow jurors, one man almost yelled his response, giving a hint of the strength of the jury's feelings. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The result gripped America to such an extent that the president's address was downgraded to second place by most news programmes. Some channels split their screens so that you could watch both events at once; others ignored Mr Clinton to focus on the closing act of the Simpson saga.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The result of the world's most highly-publicised trial was made public by a kind of semaphore, thanks to the aversion to the media felt by the judge, Hiroshi Fujisaki. The court's proceedings were broadcast to a handful of journalists stationed in a prefabricated hut close to the courtroom. The journalists then held up pieces of paper inscribed with the jury's answers to a series of questions--a "Y" for yes in every case. The Goldmans emerged to loud cheers from the huge crowd around the courtroom, Mr Simpson to boos and cries of "killer". Mr Simpson, looking stoical despite it all, stopped off to buy ice cream on his way home.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The dominant feeling in Los Angeles seemed to be that the verdict was correct, although there were still divisions along racial lines. A <i>Los Angeles Times </i>poll conducted between January 29th and February 2nd found that 71% of whites thought that Mr Simpson was guilty of the killings, whereas only 10% of blacks thought so. The police chief, Willie Williams, reported a quieter night than usual after the verdict--everyone was glued to the television--but said that the police would be on full alert until at least the weekend. Daryl Gates, Mr Williams's predecessor, said what, for legal reasons, Mr Williams could not say: that the verdict was a vindication of the <font size=-1>LAPD</font>, which had come under suspicion of racism and planting evidence during the criminal trial.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The speed with which the verdict was produced was something of a surprise--though not as much of a surprise as the three-hour verdict in the first trial. The jury had had to go back to square one on January 31st when a juror was dismissed for failing to declare that her daughter worked for the city's prosecution department and a substitute had to be installed. The jury had asked for several pieces of lengthy testimony to be read back to them earlier on the 4th, suggesting that they were still deep in deliberation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why was Mr Simpson subjected to a second trial? And why did the second jury produce such a dramatically different verdict from the first? The "double jeopardy" clause of the American constitution protects people from being tried twice for the same crime; but the civil courts give plaintiffs another avenue of attack, provided they put a new gloss on the charges. The rules of civil courts are more plaintiff-friendly than the rules of criminal courts: the prosecution has to prove its case "on the balance of the evidence" rather than "beyond reasonable doubt", and a conviction requires a two-thirds majority rather than a unanimous verdict. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Two other things may have tipped the balance against Mr Simpson. The first was that the trial took place in predominantly-white Santa Monica, the nearest court house to the scene of the crime, rather than in minority-dominated downtown. This meant that there was only one black on the original jury. The second was that Mr Simpson could not refuse to take the witness stand, as he had in the criminal trial; instead he made a botched attempt to pitch his personal charisma against solid evidence about his penchant for beating his wife and wearing Bruno Magli shoes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This verdict is not the end of the matter. The $8.5m is intended only to compensate the Goldman family for their loss. (The Browns refused to file for compensation because it would have involved the Simpson children testifying against their father.) The court reassembled on February 6th to consider the separate question of punitive damages, which could be even higher. Mr Simpson will try to protect as much of his wealth as possible, taking advantage of the fact that America's laws are notoriously generous to debtors and the courts have limited access to pension funds; and Fred Goldman, who is nothing if not tenacious, will have to harry him for his money in other courts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Simpson will be in court for other reasons, too. He faces a renewed battle for the custody of his two young children, which was restored to him late last year. He is also highly likely to appeal against the verdict, though he may find it difficult to come up with the $1m or so another case will cost. He can point out that the jury that delivered the verdict in this most race-charged of trials did not contain a single African-American. He can point out that the jury delivered its verdict with such passion that it seemed biased. Above all, he can point out that the judge refused to allow "far-fetched hypothesising" about the police and racist conspiracies, thereby ruling out of court the essence of the defence case in the criminal trial.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whether or not Mr Simpson appeals, the sorry affair will continue to raise some troubling questions about race and justice in America. A black hero who was found not guilty by a mostly black jury has now been found "responsible" by a mostly white jury. On the other hand, a man who has been found responsible for butchering two people is being allowed to enjoy his freedom, if not his fortune. Justice this is not, either for Mr Simpson or the dead victims.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?855363600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
