<html><head><title>Al, Viktor and the Moscowrena</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>
<b>LEXINGTON</B>
<h1>Al, Viktor and the Moscowrena</h1>

AL GORE'S Macarena joke, like the hair on the top of the vice-president's head, is wearing a bit thin. Audience after audience has seen him offer to do his Macarena demonstration and then, after a moment's motionless silence, ask if they want to see it again. It is the famously wooden Mr Gore's way of saying he is quite a fun fellow, really.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is not the only dance he has been working on. Since 1993 he has been practising a routine with an equally wooden partner, Russia's prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin. Officials call the half-yearly sessions (which alternate between America and Russia) the Gore-Chernomyrdin Commission, <font size=-1>GCC</font> for short, but we prefer to call them the Moscowrena. It is a delicate dance of small, often almost imperceptible steps, which are nevertheless designed to contribute to an impression of great move ment. Remarkably, this is turning into a hot number.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This week, Messrs Gore and Chernomyrdin began their eighth session, three days of talks in Washington to be followed by a joint trip to Chicago to hobnob with businessmen. What began at the behest of Presidents Clinton and Yeltsin at their Vancouver summit four years ago as an effort to enhance co-operation in space and energy has mushroomed into a process with multiple committees, sub-committees and working groups. Much of its work is on what Mr Gore described last year as "highly complex, painstaking and technical questions"--in other words, the sort of things the vice-president really enjoys. It is often tedious stuff, but important for the development of Russia's democracy, its market economy and its relations with America. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And the process works. It has been getting things done, with some 150 agreements hammered out so far. A few of these are eye-catching, such as the "megatons-to-megawatts" agreement to take weapons-grade plutonium out of Russian warheads, blend it down and send it to America to be made into reactor fuel. There is the agreement to use once-secret satellite data for environmental research, and the health-care co-operation that has contributed to a 60% drop in diphtheria cases in Russia. Collaboration on a space station (though threatened by delays on the Russian side) also occasionally makes headlines. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But much of the work involves nuts-and-bolts labour on things such as intellectual-property rights and bilateral investment rules. Subjects for co-operation range from timber stewardship in Russia's Far East to ways of promoting small businesses and providing Russian farmers with information on market conditions. A typical example of business is: "Transmittal memorandum for the final report of the <font size=-1>US</font>-Russia commercial tax dialogue"--not exactly thrilling, but essential for integrating the new Russia into the modern world.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of late, the process has taken on added significance. Not only is this week's session a chance for the two recently re-elected governments to map out a shared agenda. With Mr Yeltsin often confined to bed, leaving greater day-to-day power to his prime minister, the Gore-Chernomyrdin dialogue also brings a "meta-benefit", as they babble in the White House. It becomes an important channel for discussing so-called "off-line issues", especially security matters. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Thus, this week the vice-president and the prime minister were asked to prepare the agenda for the presidential summit planned, Mr Yeltsin's health permitting, for March (Mr Clinton's letter of invitation for Mr Yeltsin was delivered by Mr Gore to Mr Chernomyrdin at a security summit in Lisbon last December). The two men were also due to discuss strategic nuclear weapons reductions. Not least, they were to work on the delicate matter of <font size=-1>NATO</font> expansion into Central Europe, an idea Russia hates but which the western allies are committed to. Shortly before he ar rived in Washington Mr Chernomyrdin was busy huffing and puffing about <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s plans, telling the <i>Washington Post </i>that "developments in Russia could take an ominous turn" and calling hopefully for the conversion of <font size=-1>NATO</font> into a political rather than a military alliance. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This complicates the Gore-Chernomyrdin footwork, and raises a question: is too much now expected of their dance? The strength of their effort has so far been in technical projects and in building trust. It would be a pity if this useful business were jeopardised by their involvement in contentious issues such as <font size=-1>NATO</font> enlargement. The Number Twos have shown that they can do valuable work, but perhaps for the sake of their worthy endeavours there are some subjects that ought to be left to their bosses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Both Mr Gore and Mr Chernomyrdin, of course, aspire to being Number One eventually. They may therefore be tempted to exploit their networking as a rehearsal for greater diplomacy ahead, a preparation of their future special relationship. They might be flattered into thinking it a good idea to add a novel element--a dash of excitement--into their routine. They are in danger of forgetting the virtues (for the Gore-Chernomyrdin process) of dullness.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is understandable. In Mr Chernomyrdin's case, dullness has already drastically dimmed his prospects of one day winning Russia's presidency. The former bureaucrat-boss of the Soviet gas industry may be superbly connected and (some believe) obscenely rich, but he utterly lacks the popular touch. His support has sunk to about 10% in the polls, where he is outclassed by the populist flair of Alexander Lebed (see <a href="eu6356.html">page</a>). The lively Mr Lebed mocks the prime minister for being "so inarticulate he needs a translator from Russian into Russian". 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Gore, with his presence at a much-mocked fund-raising meeting at a Buddhist temple in California, has had a recent embarrassment of his own. He too is charismatically challenged, vulnerable to the emergence of a rival with star quality. The opportunity for some high-profile diplomacy through the Gore-Chernomyrdin process is oh-so tempting. But it is risky. The charm of the Moscowrena has been in its plodding pragmatism. 
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
