<html><head><title>All change, or no change, in Pakistan?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/as.gif" width="67" height="26" alt="Asia" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>All change, or no change, in Pakistan?</h1>

<font size=1>ISLAMABAD
</font><p>MOST pundits had reckoned that the Pakistan Muslim League, led by Nawaz Sharif, would win the general election on February 3rd. But almost nobody had reckoned on the landslide that has left Mr Sharif's party controlling almost two-thirds of the seats in the 217-member National Assembly, while reducing the Pakistan People's Party, led by Benazir Bhutto, to just 19 seats--down from 86 at the previous election.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Last November, Miss Bhutto was sacked as prime minister, by order of the president. She had predicted that the subsequent election would be rigged against her and threatened not to accept the results. But, in the aftermath of defeat, Miss Bhutto took a more conciliatory line and said she would accept a role as leader of the parliamentary opposition. Miss Bhutto may have been chastened by the scale of her defeat, and will certainly be aware that international observers have not supported her charges of widespread electoral fraud. But the former prime minister also seems to be trying to be statesmanlike. She told a post-election press conference that opposition parties in Pakistan had fallen into the habit of using extra-parliamentary agitation to get their way. "Somebody has to take a decision to break this circle," she said. "I am breaking this circle." 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This will be the second time Mr Sharif has served as prime minister. His first term in office ended in 1993, when he was dismissed from power by the then president, Ghulam Ishaq Khan. Mr Sharif is sometimes called the "businessman prime minister", to distinguish him from Pakistan's traditional rulers, who have usually been large landowners. His family own the Ittefaq group, one of the country's largest industrial empires with stakes in steel, sugar and textiles.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Sharif's rise to power was at first nurtured by the powerful military establishment. His first political job was as finance minister in the province of Punjab, a job he took in 1981 during the dictatorship of General Zia ul Haq. Next he had two spells as chief minister of Punjab (in 1985 and 1988), also under the watchful eyes of the generals. After Miss Bhutto was sacked as prime minister for the first time in 1990, Mr Sharif took over. At the time, he was widely seen as the establishment's man. But in 1993 he too was sacked, amid accusations of corruption. This clash with the powers-that-be helped to change his image. He now has some populist, anti-establishment credentials. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Will the second incarnation of Nawaz Sharif be any different from the first? The early signs are mildly encouraging. Mr Sharif has promised not to victimise the opposition--an unusually generous declaration for a Pakistani politician. He has also promised economic reforms. His victory has been widely welcomed by businessmen. Share prices rose by 7% in the two days before and after the election.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet Mr Sharif will have difficulty satisfying the hopes of businessmen. Pakistan is in the midst of a demanding <font size=-1>IMF</font>-imposed fiscal diet. The new government will have to cut spending to keep its deficit down. So tax breaks for business (one of the hallmarks of Mr Sharif's previous tenure) will be out this year. He hopes in due course to reduce tax rates in order to lure more taxpayers into the net and raise revenues. Unfortunately, tax evasion is so rampant--in a population of 127m, only about 1m pay income tax--that simply lowering rates may not be enough to break the habit.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The caretaker administration that is about to hand over power to Mr Sharif claims to have laid the basis for further privatisation. The hope is that once public-sector enterprises are privatised, the government will have enough money to pay off some of its debt, so that debt servicing, which is expected to eat up more than 36% of this year's budget spending, will become less of a burden. The idea makes sense, but foreign investors will be wary of a country where political uncertainty has been a perpetual problem.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That uncertainty will not go away. Mr Sharif faces a tricky situation in the economically powerful province of Sindh, where a restive ethnic party, the Mohajir Qaumi Movement, has gained enough seats to look for a role in government. He will also be working alongside President Farooq Leghari, who dismissed Miss Bhutto. The president's position has been strengthened by a Supreme Court verdict on January 29th, which upheld his decision to sack the Bhutto government. It is conceivable that future dis missal orders will be defended on the strength of that verdict.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A low turnout (below 38%) on election day has also weakened Mr Sharif's claim to a popular mandate. He has also, in earlier days, faced the sort of corruption accusations that haunted Miss Bhutto. Like many charges laid against the high and mighty in Pakistan, the accusations against Mr Sharif were never proven. But he will need to be wary of giving critics fresh ammunition for charges of wrongdoing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, Mr Sharif also has some things going for him. Miss Bhutto's apparent decision not to boycott the new parliament is helpful. If he is bold, and if he could win the support of enough independents to give him a two-thirds majority in parliament, Mr Sharif could repeal the dreaded eighth amendment to the constitution, which has allowed Pakistan's presidents to sack three prime ministers since 1990. That would remove a Sword of Damocles that hangs over--and sometimes chops off--the head of every elected government. The abolition of those presidential powers would also blunt the force of the recently created Council for Defence and National Security, headed by the president, which has given a formal political role to the country's most senior generals, for the first time since martial law was lifted. It is more likely, however, that Mr Sharif will want to conciliate the generals than to confront them.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
