<html><head><title>A relic of empire</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/ir.gif" width="224" height="26" alt="International" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>The Caribbean
<h1>A relic of empire</h1>

</b></p><font size=1>PORT OF SPAIN, TRINIDAD
</font><p>THE British Empire has taken its time dying. A generation or more after independence, 11 ex-British Caribbean coun tries still allow legal appeals to the "judicial committee" of Britain's Privy Council in London. They are not alone: among others, Mauritius and even New Zealand still do it. But now they have agreed to set up a Caribbean Court of Appeal, which will start work as soon as three of the 11 have passed the necessary constitutional amendments, maybe by the end of this year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Privy Council itself is an arcane bit of British flummery. But its judicial committee is for real, serving as a final court of appeal for remaining British colonies and some ex-colonies. The judges are usually British "law lords"--the top level--though a qualified judge from one of the countries concerned (there are three such judges in the Caribbean) may be asked to join them. Appeals are normally heard by five judges, who look not only at the laws of the relevant country but at precedents and opinion from other jurisdictions. In roughly one case in three, they overturn the decision of the local court. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the Caribbean, the judicial committee rules on the interpretation of national constitutions as well as on civil and criminal cases. Why did Caribbean countries not set up their own supreme courts--or a joint one--years ago? One reason is that a link to a wider legal system is an asset. In a small island where everyone went to school with someone's cousin, it can be useful to refer decisions to outsiders. The Privy Council's services also come free (though not so the British lawyers who appear before it, or the cost of taking Caribbean ones to London).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why change? Plain national pride is one reason, but not the main one. The Privy Council has made itself unpopular by protecting convicted murderers. In 1993, it ruled that it would be "inhuman and degrading" to hang two Jamaicans who had spent 14 years on death row. At the time, it was thought to have fixed a five-year limit to the time from sentence to execution. Later decisions have lessened the permitted interval (to two years, as Caribbean lawyers read them; London ones are less sure just how far). 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Jamaica, with only 2.5m people, had almost 1,000 murders last year. Murder is far less common elsewhere, but Caribbean politicians and voters are worried. There is a feeling that hanging would help--and that judges in Britain, which has far fewer murders and gave up hanging 30 years ago, are ill-placed to make rules on this issue for the Caribbean. The same goes for some other issues. Constitutional decisions, however based in law, are in practice political. Should they not be made on the spot? Granted, they then risk being politicised. The answer could be a joint supreme court. True, Caribbean societies are by no means all alike. Nor are they all united in brotherly love: local rivalries have been one reason that there is no joint court already, some countries preferring to have their controversial cases decided by far-off Britons than by their neighbours. Even "far off" is a vague term: from Belize, it can take longer to fly to Trinidad than to Britain. Even so, the feeling has grown that Caribbean judges will understand Caribbean issues better than ones in London.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet might the change bring worse law? It need not. Even those who prefer the current system accept that there are fine lawyers in the Caribbean, even if (as elsewhere) the best are not all judges. Solid guarantees of independence, and good pay, will be needed to attract the ablest to a new court. If, as some lawyers feel, an outside view would still be useful, the court--whose members will probably be picked by a regional body, not named by individual governments--could include a non-Caribbean judge. As for communications, the region's geography is what it is. But information technology makes it, in principle, almost as easy to refer to worldwide case law from St Lucia as from London. Fears of worse law look ill-founded.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So, though, do hopes of speedier law. Caribbean law is slow, even by lawyers' standards: Trinidad's chief justice, taking office in 1995, called it "not unusual" for criminal cases to take four years to pass through the magistrates' courts, or eight to the next level above. Then there may be a local appeal. Appeal to the Privy Council is merely the icing on a long-baked cake. Civil cases can take just as long. Trinidad's appeal court has got moving: last year it dealt with five times as many cases as in 1993. And a regional conference on legal delays was held in the Bahamas last month. But few expect any great acceleration of justice, Privy Council or no Privy Council.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
