<html><head><title>The emperor's new health</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/eu.gif" width="105" height="26" alt="Europe" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Russia
<h1>The emperor's new health</h1>

</b></p><font size=1>MOSCOW
</font><p>PEOPLE and politicians alike in Russia understand that a charade is being played out around President Boris Yeltsin. Statements about his health and his capacity to work bear no necessary relation to the truth. All one can be sure of is that he is an elderly man who has been desperately ill, who has had a big heart operation, and who is having trouble recovering. Probably, he can either work hard, or live longer, but not both.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The calculations are such, however, that few Russian politicians want to hasten Mr Yeltsin's exit. The main exception among them is Alexander Lebed, an ex-general who thinks he would win a snap election; and it is the fear that Mr Lebed is right that encourages others to cosset Mr Yeltsin nervously. If few privately expect the president to last the year, they will help him through as much of it as possible.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The contingency plans being hatched for a post-Yeltsin era fall into two main groups. One group presumes that the current constitution would prevail: the president would step down, the country would be run for up to three months by the prime minister (currently Viktor Chernomyrdin) and a fresh election would be held. A second group of plans assumes the constitution could be changed or flouted. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Lebed is the champion of the constitutional route. Sacked in October from his briefly held job as Mr Yeltsin's security adviser, he has been looking for friends and money, accepting invitations to travel abroad, and putting together a political party of sorts. He has stayed in the public eye. Opinion polls still rank him Russia's most trusted politician. His search for friends has yielded a mixed bunch. He remains thick with Alexander Korzhakov, Mr Yeltsin's sinister former bodyguard, whose expertise in bugs and slush-funds may still have its uses. He has also formed a mutual appreciation society with Alexander Lukashenka, Belarus's near-dictator.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Lebed's political party, the National Republican Party, is due for its first congress next month. Its main ingredient will be a movement of uncertain size called Honour and Motherland, made up of soldiers loyal from Mr Lebed's army days. It will have links with the Congress of Russian Communities, a party that backed Mr Lebed in the past; with Svyatoslav Fedorov, a businessman who took 1% of the vote in the first round of last year's presidential election (when Mr Lebed took 15%); and with the Democratic Party of Sergei Glaziev, a reformer-turned-nationalist who might run President Lebed's economic policy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Lebed has said he could foresee a tactical alliance with Grigory Yavlinsky, Russia's leading social democrat. But his biggest prize, which he is stalking with care, would be the Communist vote. To that end he has been matching criticism of the Communists' leader, Gennady Zyuganov, with expressions of sympathy and admiration for the party's rank and file. Current gossip does not credit Mr Lebed with much money. But if he looks like a winner when a presidential election approaches, he will doubtless raise quickly enough the $50m or so needed to run a national campaign.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The "stop Lebed" camp has only one plausible candidate for election: Yuri Luzhkov, mayor of Moscow, a neo-Victorian mixture of reformer, paternalist and nationalist. He took 90% of the vote in Moscow in last year's mayoral election. He has forged alliances with the governors of a dozen of Russia's richer cities and regions, including Vladimir Yakovlev of St Petersburg and Boris Nemtsov of Nizhny Novgorod. He has started to speak out louder on national issues, taking up Russia's claim to the Ukrainian port of Sebastopol as his personal cause. He may well have his eye on the chair of the Federation Council, the upper house of parliament. By raising that job's profile, he would be able to project himself as a national figure while still hanging on to his Moscow fief.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is not much comfort in this for Mr Chernomyrdin. Once considered a natural successor to Mr Yeltsin, he has come to look like one of yesterday's men. He may have lost a few more votes last week with his smiling admission on television that he was fresh back from a hunting trip on which, with an entourage of helicopters, bulldozers and bodyguards, he had bagged a mother bear and two cubs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Still, he is a safe pair of hands. Were Mr Yeltsin to step down, and were Mr Chernomyrdin to step in, there might be moves in the Duma to extend his tenure beyond three months--perhaps to 18 months, or for the balance of the presidential term. 
<br></p><p><b><b>Odd ways out?</b>
</b><br>Any device expressly designed to deny Mr Lebed power would, however, make a lot of Russians angry. Some 11m voted for him in 1996. His ending of the Chechen war, and disenchantment with Mr Yeltsin, have probably brought him many more fans. The army adores him. If an election did not bring him to power, a putsch might do so instead. For that reason, another way of settling the succession to Mr Yeltsin might be to install a "state council", seats on which would be given to the half-dozen or so politicians too popular and powerful to be refused them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A final variant, floated seriously by one or two commentators, has been the re instatement of a tsar as "constitutional monarch". Plenty of Romanovs are available. But why turn to them? Though no one has said as much, the best man for the job would surely be Mr Yeltsin himself. After all, he is practically doing it already.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
