</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Spend, spend</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>The national lottery
<h1>Spend, spend</h1>

</b></p>GAMBLING mania got a new lease of life on February 5th, when the national lottery held its first mid-week draw. Camelot, which runs the business for the government, expects overall sales of lottery tickets to increase by up to 20% as a result of the new Wednesday ("Wins-day") event, lifting total revenues in 1997 above last year's &#163;5.2 billion, and raising more money for "good causes". Already, the lottery has far exceeded expectations at its launch in November 1994. As well as creating (so far) almost 600 millionaires, the lottery is having a perceptible effect on the economy and, increasingly, on the election campaign.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The amount of money that the British spend on gambling has climbed. After rising to 1% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> in the early 1970s, the proportion of national income gambled each year fell steadily to less than 0.6% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> in 1993. Two years later, total spending on gambling had increased again to nearly 1% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>. Although it edged down in 1996, the sums gambled remained much higher than before the lottery. The lottery has hurt other gambling much less than had been thought, although the soccer pools, in particular, have lost some business.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;According to David Mackie, an economist at J.P. Morgan, an investment bank, the main losers from extra gambling were recreation and entertainment, which fell by 2.9% in 1995, confectionary (down 3.7%), and newspapers and books (down 3.2%); all this in a year when total consumption grew by 1.9%. The switch had a once-and-for-all effect on retail sales, depressing them by around 1% in 1995. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Because lottery spending displaces other purchases, talk of the lottery spurring employment should be taken about as seriously as Mystic Meg's predictions of the winning numbers. A study for Camelot by the Henley Centre, an economic forecasting firm, found that by 1999 the lottery will have created, or preserved, some 109,000 jobs that otherwise would not have existed. But these are likely to be more or less cancelled out by job losses in firms that earn less than they would have done if there were no lottery.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many expected the lottery to deal a severe blow to charities. It was feared that people would regard buying a lottery ticket as all the giving they need do, since 6% of the price of a ticket goes to charity. On February 2nd Barclays Bank reported that individual charitable donations have fallen since the launch of the lottery. However, the total income of charities--which includes government payments and business revenues--has continued to grow since 1994.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the lottery is channelling money from the regions to London, which gets a disproportionately large slice of the 28% of each lottery ticket that goes to fund "good causes". And there is a similar shift from poor areas to richer ones, says Luke Fitzherbert, author of the forthcoming "1997 National Lottery Year Book". This is on top of another bias to the rich: although weekly spending on the lottery by poorer households tends to be less than by richer ones, it accounts for a larger slice of their income.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Any qualms politicians may have about such a regressive, albeit voluntary, method of raising money have been forgotten in the rush to spend the cash. Or, at least, to promise to spend it. Of the &#163;3 billion raised (and, mostly, allocated) for good causes, only &#163;595m has left the Treasury's bank account, where it earns interest for the government.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Office for National Statistics insists that lottery spending is treated as public spending, but the government refuses to include it in its target for cutting public spending as a proportion of <font size=-1>GDP</font>. Thus, promising to spend lottery cash offers a simple way for politicians to evade their self-imposed tax-and-spend strictures. The Tories have already pledged lottery cash to improve British sport and film-making, and Labour has promised to use the money for, among other things, the arts, information-technology training for teachers and an energy-efficiency programme. So much for the government's promise that lottery money would not be used as a substitute for public spending.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
