<html><head><title>Political football</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<h1>Political football</h1>

JOHN MAJOR and Tony Blair, along with much of the British public, this week showed themselves to be card-carrying Eurosceptics, at least when it comes to soccer. On February 1st came news that <font size=-1>UEFA</font>, the body which runs European soccer, had backed Germany's bid to host the World Cup in 2006. This seemed to kill a rival bid from England, and sent the tabloid press into a frenzy of Europe-bashing, with particular refer ence to Germany. Since a general election is imminent, the politicians lost no time. "We must halt this outrage," thundered Mr Major in an article in the <i>Sun</i>. Alongside was a piece by Mr Blair: a "cosy stitch-up", he fumed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Football Association (<font size=-1>FA</font>), which runs the game in England, decided to apply for the 2006 World Cup after it hosted last summer's Euro 96 tournament. That event went surprisingly well. England reached the semi-finals, losing on penalties to Germany. And the English fans, noted for their brutality, rioted just once.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>FA</font> said that it had not realised that <font size=-1>UEFA</font> was backing Germany (which had tabled its bid years ago) until a fax to that effect arrived on January 31st. <font size=-1>UEFA</font> claims that an <font size=-1>FA</font> representative at tended the meetings when the choice was made--although, oddly, the deci sion had not been re corded in the minutes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Bids for the 2006 tournament do not have to be submitted to <font size=-1>FIFA</font>, soccer's worldwide governing body, until September 1999. So what was <font size=-1>UEFA</font> doing making its mind up this early? The official explanation is that, by backing one country early, <font size=-1>UEFA</font> would avoid a costly and embarrassing bid ding-war between regional neighbours, of the kind that took place between Japan and South Korea for the 2002 World Cup. Between them, those countries are said to have spent well over $100m on the bidding before <font size=-1>FIFA</font> decided that the two should co-host the event.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More cynical observers link Germany's good fortune to murky machinations designed to help Lennart Johansson, a Swede who runs <font size=-1>UEFA</font>, become boss of <font size=-1>FIFA</font>. Rumour has it that Mr Johansson persuaded his colleagues at <font size=-1>UEFA</font>, who had doubted the ability of English fans to behave themselves, to let England host Euro 96. But this was supposedly on the understanding that the <font size=-1>FA</font> would in turn agree to support Germany's bid for the World Cup in 2006.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>FA</font>, this rumour has it, broke the gentle men's agreement when it realised that <font size=-1>FIFA</font> may start to rotate the World Cup among four geo graphical areas. This could mean that, if Germany gets the tournament in 2006, football might not come home again to England, where modern soccer was invented, before 2022.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
