<html><head><title>Down the tube</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>London Underground
<h1>Down the tube</h1>

</b></p>WHEN John Major singled out London Underground as a candidate for privatisation at last year's Tory party conference, it was inevitable that the idea would become the subject of election knockabout. The fun and games began last week with the leak of confidential cabinet documents warning that a rushed sale might raise only &#163;600m compared with a capital asset value estimated at &#163;13 billion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour was quick to denounce the planned sell-off as political larceny. It claimed that privatisation would do nothing to improve the lot of the system's long-suffering customers, some 1.6m of them each day. A new Labour government, said Tony Blair on February 4th, would keep the Underground in public control. Two days later the government took fright, shelving plans to announce the sale.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Behind the shouting is a recognition by both parties that something has to change. Decades of under-investment have left the tube with much signalling, track and rolling stock dating back to the 1930s. The result has been a growing incidence of equipment failures. Two months ago, a faulty control valve in a 91-year-old power station trapped more than 20,000 people for up to two hours. It was the tube's third big power failure in the past three years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;London Transport, the state-owned company which manages the under ground, now says that at least &#163;1.2 billion is needed to modernise the tube and make up for past neglect. But how can this best be done? The record of public ownership hardly inspires confidence. Successive governments have constantly changed their minds about how much new investment to put into the system. The Tories have been especially erratic over the past few years (see <a href="br2.gif">chart</a>), making long-range planning impossible. Industrial relations have also been fraught, with drivers frequently threatening to strike. After a critical report by the Monopolies and Mergers Commission (<font size=-1>MMC</font>) in 1991, investment rose sharply, but it has now once again been cut. The position has been aggravated by a &#163;300m cost over-run on the new Jubilee line extension. This will mean even less money to maintain and upgrade the tube's existing network over the next two years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For all its problems, the tube is hardly a basket-case. Carrying 780m passengers a year, it has an annual turnover of &#163;770m. Its passenger numbers are projected to grow by 20% by 2010. Fares already cover the costs of operation and maintenance. But there is little leeway. Fares in London are 20% more expensive than in Paris and Berlin, 30% more than in Toronto and 36% more than in Sydney and Amsterdam. Since the 1991 <font size=-1>MMC</font> report, performance has improved and a workforce of 22,000 has been reduced by a quarter. A study of the five biggest underground systems in the world in 1995 found that the London tube compared well in operating costs with the other systems.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Privatisation is certainly worth thinking about. Unfortunately, thinking is something the government has little time for at the moment. How would it be done? A rushed sale would almost certainly mean that the system would have to be sold at a substantial discount to its potential value. Three approaches are currently under consideration. A single complete sale to a private bidder; selling individual lines to different bidders; and splitting ownership of the track from its operation, which would then be franchised to different private companies. The last option, similar to the way British Rail was privatised, is the front runner, and probably makes the most sense. But such a privatisation will be complicated.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A franchised tube would require strict regulation to ensure that the public interest was safeguarded. Prices and conditions would have to be negotiated for the franchisees. New ticketing systems would have to be installed. The government has barely begun to examine such issues.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour's alternative looks equally half-baked. The notion that large amounts of private capital can be attracted to publicly-owned, inherently loss-making urban transport systems is either naive or dishonest. The private finance initiative, as the current government has found with the much-delayed new rolling stock on the Northern Line, cannot be relied on to fill the gap left by a lack of public investment. A publicly-owned underground requires long-term, consistent government funding. If Labour is either unwilling or unable to meet that commitment, it too may have to consider some form of privatisation.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
