<html><head><title>Shared misery</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<h1>Shared misery</h1>

GORDON BROWN, the shadow chancellor of the exchequer, turned down a likely pay rise this week. On February 4th he announced that the pay of ministers, <font size=-1>MP</font>s, senior civil servants, judges and military top brass would be frozen during the first year of a Labour government. Currently, the prime minister's salary is planned to rise next year by &#163;41,000, to &#163;143,000, and a cabinet minister's (ie, Mr Brown's if Labour wins) by &#163;16,000, to &#163;103,000. This pledge pre-empted the cabinet's response on February 6th to new recommendations by the Senior Salaries Review Body.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Brown hopes that his pay freeze will embarrass the Tories now, and help him to control public pay later if Labour wins power. The Tories have frozen the public-sector pay bill in recent years, and pressure for big increases has been building. Public-sector unions deny that they expect generosity from a Labour government, but they may change their minds once victory is secured. Mr Brown hopes to lower expectations and to curb resentment over small pay settlements by showing that the whole public sector, from top to bottom, is in the same position.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;An admirable sentiment, no doubt, but the fact is that the case for a sharp increase in pay at the top is much stronger than the case for an across-the-board rise. As our (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>) chart shows, pay in the public sector as a whole has increased since 1979 by about as much as pay in the private sector. And in four of the past six years it has grown faster, according to Chris Trinder, an economist at <font size=-1>CIPFA</font> (a body for public-sector financial professionals).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The pay of a backbench <font size=-1>MP</font> has risen by slightly less than the public-or private-sector averages, and that of a high-court judge by a little more. The pay for top civil servants has mostly risen by less than the average, except in a few cases. Most striking of all, the salary of the prime minister has increased by much less than the average. You could argue that the supply of would-be prime ministers greatly exceeds the number of available posts, in which case the pay for that job could stand to fall a good deal further, relatively speaking. But this may be less true of top civil servants. The public sector needs to have able people in charge. If Mr Brown starts a new exodus to the private sector, he might come to regret it.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
