<html><head><title>Covering up</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Accountability
<h1>Covering up</h1>

</b></p>"THE adjudication officer has de cided you are not entitled to a payment. This is for the following reason. The adjudication officer has decided that we cannot pay you." This is what the government's benefits agency told an aggrieved claimant recently, according to "Short Changed", a report by the National Association of Citizens' Advice Bureaux on how the agency is coping (or failing to cope) with cuts in its budget. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If you encounter such boneheadedness, who are you supposed to complain to? Who is to be held accountable? If an <font size=-1>MP</font> wanted to find out, he would be expected to write to the chief executive of the agency, who would in turn reply. The chief executive could even be summoned to answer questions before a parliamentary select committee. However, and this is the point, he would not give evidence on his own account, but under the instructions of his minister. Suppose the chief executive thought the problem was lack of staff: his minister could forbid him to say so. The minister could even tell him to refuse to answer the committee's questions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Things will improve if a Commons debate on February 12th backs a parliamentary resolution designed to provide more accountability. It has been negotiated by Roger Freeman, the public services minister, and the Commons select committee on public service. The latest draft says that "ministers should require civil servants who give evidence before select committees on their behalf and under their directions to be as helpful as possible in providing full and accurate information."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The good news is that a minister who ordered civil servants to conceal embarrassing facts would be directly contravening a requirement of Parliament, a grave offence. The bad news is that the resolution still requires civil servants to give evidence under ministerial direction, rather than to tell the truth as they see it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Liberal Democrat <font size=-1>MP</font>s have argued for going further. They want to make agency chiefs directly answerable to Parliament. Giles Radice, the Labour chairman of the committee, sympathises, but is willing to accept a fudge. And a fudge is the best the government will offer. Mr Freeman be lieves that if agency chiefs were to give evidence in their own name, ministers would come to appoint only political trustees--people who could be relied on to hide the inadequacies of their political masters without being explicitly told to. Privately, agency chiefs respond to this argument scathingly. In public, they toe the line.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?855363600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
