<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><p align=center>
<table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</p></center>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width="231" height="24" alt="Britain in Brief" border=0></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<p><b>Entry stamp</b> &nbsp; The government, in an abrupt <font size=-1>U</font>-turn, agreed to grant British passports to 8,000 non-Chinese citi zens of Hong Kong. These residents, mainly ethnic Indians and Pakistanis, were in danger of becoming stateless after China said they were not entitled to citizenship.
<p><br><b>Sacked</b> &nbsp; Sir George Gardiner, the Eurosceptic Tory <font size=-1>MP</font> who was dropped as Conservative candidate for Reigate after repeated attacks on the prime minister, decided to sue the local party for reinstatement.
<p><br><b>Gunned down</b> &nbsp; The government was defeated in the Lords on three different amendments to the Firearms Bill, which would ban most handguns. Peers voted to compensate dealers hit by the ban, to create a police register of legally-held firearms and to allow gun-owners to keep certain parts of their weapons at home rather than at secure clubs.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><br><b>Heads must roll</b> &nbsp; Chris Woodhead, the government's chief schools inspector, said in his annual report that there were 3,000 incompetent headteachers in England's schools.
<p><br><b>Dated</b> &nbsp; The government set February 27th as the date for the Wirral South by-election. Labour is hoping to overturn the Conservative's 8,183-vote majority in the seat as a boost to its general election campaign.
<p><br><b>Last wish</b> &nbsp; The Court of Appeal ruled that Diane Blood, a young widow, had the right to have a child from the frozen sperm of her late husband even though he had not given his express consent before his death.
<p><br><b>Back in business</b> &nbsp; Manufacturing output rose by 0.2% in December, an increase of 1.4% on a year ago, after a disappointing showing in November. The figures were better than expected.
<p><br><b>No relief</b> &nbsp; North Wiltshire council employees, who had been sent to a meditation course to reduce stress at work, complained that the hassle of getting there, the hard seats and the lack of biscuits left them worse off than before.

</td></tr></table></center>
