<html><head><title>Webbed flight</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Webbed flight</h1>

<font size=1>TOKYO</font><p>AS THE skies across the Pacific grow thick with airlines vying to carry Japan's well-heeled travellers, the need to trim costs--without customers noticing--is becoming the hottest topic on the tarmac. Japan Airlines (<font size=-1>JAL</font>)--the <i>grande </i><i>dame</i> of Asian airlines--has had more to trim than most. Since early 1994, <font size=-1>JAL</font> has axed a surprising &#165;100 billion ($820m) a year off its fixed expenses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One result is that savings are becoming harder to find. But <font size=-1>JAL</font>'s procurement department has had a good idea. Since February 1st the airline has been using the Internet to track down cheaper suppliers abroad.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The initial target is the &#165;6 billion a year that the airline spends on in-flight consumables--such things as waste bags, plastic cups and head-rest covers that are used once during a flight and then discarded on landing. The airline buys 17m paper towels a year, 8m plastic cups, another 8m paper napkins and more than 2m airsick bags. Such items cannot be bought off-the-shelf at a local supermarket. All have to be made to the carrier's own specification and come complete with its corporate logo.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All told, <font size=-1>JAL</font> buys some 1,200 different items from a host of high-price suppliers located in Tokyo and Yokohama, close to <font size=-1>JAL</font>'s operational centre at Haneda airport. But there is no reason why many of these goods could not be bought from foreign suppliers at <font size=-1>JAL</font>'s destinations abroad. At present, all in-flight consumables for the airline's return flights from overseas have to be carted expensively on its outbound flights. <font size=-1>JAL</font> has 72 flights a day to Hawaii alone, each loaded with objects that could be made in Honolulu.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By adding a special procurement section to the company's web-site on the Internet (<a href="http://www.jal.co.jp">http://www.jal.co.jp</a>), the airline now hopes to attract the attention of more competitive suppliers elsewhere in the world. The procurement department's web-page list items--along with full specifications, photographs and engi neering drawings--that it wants foreign suppliers to bid on. The web-site even provides on-screen application forms so that would-be suppliers can submit their quotes electronically. Initially, 15 of the carrier's most urgently needed items are being put up for Internet tender. More will be added each month.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Japan, <font size=-1>JAL</font>'s home page is the second busiest web-site on the Internet, with more than 60,000 separate requests for information a day. (<i>Asahi Shimbun</i>, one of Japan's largest daily newspapers, gets 70,000 requests a day.) Through it, customers can reserve seats on domestic flights, check arrival times and even buy goods from the airline's mail-order catalogue. The next job is to put <font size=-1>JAL</font>'s ticketless travel service--which accounted for 10% of domestic sales last year--on the Internet as well. The cost of selling tickets could eventually fall by 70% or more.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Meanwhile, <font size=-1>JAL</font>'s domestic suppliers face a nasty shock. <font size=-1>JAL</font> will be delighted if foreign firms find they can undercut Japanese suppliers who provide the kit for the airline's outbound flights as well. The carrier is betting that fear of losing some of their domestic contracts will work wonders with local suppliers. Suddenly, a wholesale lowering of <font size=-1>JAL</font>'s in-flight costs is in the air.
<br>
<br>
