<html><head><title>Crosswired</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Crosswired</h1>

TOGETHER, Louis Rossetto and Jane Metcalfe represent the closest thing the young Internet publishing industry has to a Citizen Kane. Five years ago they launched <i>Wired</i>, which has evolved from the hip bible of the Internet generation to an advertisement-packed lifestyle magazine for the pretentious technophile. On-line, their HotWired network proffers everything from politics to cocktail recipes. Off-line, they run a book publisher and are dabbling in television. The couple even named their first son, born on January 28th, Orson. No wonder that the fortunes of their Wired Ventures are so keenly watched: as it goes, so may go the entire "new media" industry.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Bad news, then, from this digital San Simeon. Wired Ventures an nounced on February 4th that it is closing its British edition after two money-losing years. Wired had hoped to raise up to $75m in a stockmarket offering last year, which would have supported the British version, and allowed it to launch four other regional editions and bankroll other ventures.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the market rejected its offers (the first valuing the firm at $447m; the second at a more humble $293m) as too dear, especially for a company that is at least half a traditional paper-and-ink pub lisher with correspondingly modest growth prospects. A subsequent round of private investments raised a mere $21.5m, and Wired's atttempt to find a partner for the British <i>Wired </i>(approaching, among others, <i>The Economist</i>) ultimately failed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Disappointing as the setback is, it hardly points to the coming death of new media. Wired's big problem is not that many of its ventures are losing money. Most new magazines lose money for a few years, and the Internet publishing market is still in its infancy. Rather, it has found it impossible to raise money as quickly as the market opportunity and the strength of its competition require. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Two other big on-line publishers are Microsoft (in the form of both the software firm's own <font size=-1>MSN</font> network and its <font size=-1>MSNBC</font> joint venture with <font size=-1>NBC</font>, the television network) and <font size=-1>C/NET</font>, a start-up much like Wired itself. Microsoft has $9 billion in cash, a sizeable fraction of which it is willing to blow on Internet media ventures in the hope of getting one right. <font size=-1>C/NET</font>, which is more of a pure on-line publisher than Wired, had the good fortune to catch the tail end of a bull market for Internet offerings in early 1996; the firm, whose revenues are about one-third of Wired's, is now valued at nearly $370m, despite losing more than $16m last year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By contrast, Wired must live on the modest amount it has already raised and any earnings it can muster. Mr Rossetto says that he is not looking for more investors, and is instead counting on <i>Wired</i> to become profitable this year and start pumping out enough cash to support HotWired (which was losing more than $3m a quarter when Wired last disclosed its finances). This rules out more traditional magazines and regional editions: paper and ink are more expensive than electronic digits. But Mr Rossetto says that Wired's growth plans for HotWired are unchanged. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even so, Microsoft will probably spend up to ten times as much on-line as Wired over the next three years. Up to now, Wired's on-line efforts have been creative, if uneven. Who knows what it might have done if it had caught the market in better mood?
<br>
<br>
