<html><head><title>Rambo Rambus</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width="371" height="26" alt="Science and Technology" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Rambo Rambus</h1>

<p><b>If computers are to continue to think faster, their memories must get better. Whoever designs that better memory should make a lot of money</b></p>
<br>A COMPUTER, like a convoy, must run at the speed of its slowest component. In the case of personal computers (<font size=-1>PC</font>s) that component was, until a few years ago, the part that does the number-crunching upon which a <font size=-1>PC</font> relies to perform its miracles--its microprocessor. Recently, though, the slowcoach microprocessor has not only caught up, it is threatening to steam out of sight. Chips such as Intel's Pentium Pro and Motorola's Power<font size=-1>PC</font> now run so fast that everything else has to struggle to stay abreast of them. And when the Pentium's successor, the <font size=-1>P7</font>, is introduced in a year's time, the situation will be even worse.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The new laggards are what were once among the swiftest parts of a <font size=-1>PC</font>--the <font size=-1>DRAM</font> (dynamic random-access memory) chips that store instructions and data temporarily while calculations are under way in the microprocessor. The problem is not the chips' capacity, which has grown enor mously, but the speed at which information can be stored and retrieved from them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>DRAM</font>s use a design that can trace its origins back to what is, by computing standards, the pre-Cambrian: the first such chips were turned out by Intel in 1971. Then, they had but a single kilobit of memory--being able to store a mere 1,024 of the binary digits ("bits") that are the currency in which computing is carried out. Now they can hold as much as 64 megabits--over 65,000 times as much.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If Intel has its way, however, that will be the end of the line for the traditional <font size=-1>DRAM</font>. The company, which dropped out of the <font size=-1>DRAM</font> business in the mid-1980s to concentrate on its microprocessors, is planning to team up with Rambus, a small chip shop based in Mountain View, California. Together, they hope to shake up the computer-memory industry. For Rambus has redesigned a critical part of the <font size=-1>DRAM</font>--the way it talks to the outside world. And from 1999 onwards, Intel's microprocessors will be configured to work solely with a derivative of Rambus's radical makeover.
<br></p><p><b><b>Don't miss the bus</b>
</b><br>The trouble with the current <font size=-1>DRAM</font> is that a simple design has become too compli cated. Its great attraction is that, unlike other types of memory device, such as the lightning-fast but hugely expensive static-<font size=-1>RAM</font>, dynamic-<font size=-1>RAM</font> uses only one tiny transistor per memory cell. As each of those cells stores one bit, it requires a mere 65m or so of them for its latest incarnation. Non-<font size=-1>DRAM</font> memories of similar capacity would require hundreds of millions of transistors. That makes <font size=-1>DRAM</font>s cheap to produce.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But with more than 65m cells on a chip, the channels needed to store or retrieve a piece of data have become a rats' nest of connections--creating all manner of interference, timing and noise problems. This "signal skew" is now the bane of those <font size=-1>DRAM</font> designers who are seeking ever higher retrieval speeds, because it limits the volume of data that can be shuffled in and out of the chip.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The amount of data being moved around this way is usually measured in "bytes". Eight bits make a byte--a computing "word" that is big enough to store a single letter of the alphabet. To transmit more data in a given amount of time, a channel can be made bigger--so that more bytes of data are sent simultaneously ("wider words" in geek-speak). Or each word can be sent through it in quicker succession ("faster clocking").
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In trying to make their <font size=-1>DRAM</font>s slicker, chip designers have tended to favour the wider-word approach, increasing the traditional word size from one byte to as much as eight bytes. The Rambus chip takes a different approach. Its designers have changed the chip's layout in order to solve the signal-skew problem. They have re placed the tangled web of signalling lines by a simpler arrangement known as a "bus" in which all the leads are parallel, the same length and short. Then, having simplified the wiring, they have been able to go for faster clocking, rather than wider words.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So, instead of sesquipedalian eight-byte words, terse, single-byte monosyllables are the order of the day. But they are squirted along at the rate of 600m a second. And Geoff Tate, Rambus's boss, reckons this number will grow by 200m a year for the foreseeable future as computers' internal clocks (which control it) are made to tick faster. Also, the rate at which data are moved in and out of a Rambus chip can be doubled by adding a second bus to the arrangement. This will allow the Rambus design to meet Intel's target of shifting 1,600 megabytes of data a second by 1999.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Intel has opted for the Rambus architecture because it has been proved in practice. Early versions of Rambus <font size=-1>DRAM</font>s are already used in such advanced computers as the Silicon Graphics Indigo2 workstation and the Nintendo 64 video-game player, both of which need to process realistic <font size=-1>3-D</font> graphics at high speed. Indeed, some $400m-worth of these first-generation Rambus chips have already been shipped by licence-holding manufacturers such as <font size=-1>NEC</font> and Toshiba in Japan.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The desire to bring such graphic capability to general-purpose <font size=-1>PC</font>s is the main reason for Intel's decision to abandon traditional <font size=-1>DRAM</font>s. The mere act of "refreshing" a <font size=-1>PC</font>'s screen when it is running software with lots of <font size=-1>3-D</font> graphics can require crunching up to 500 megabytes of data a second. This means that a third of Intel's performance target will be needed just to run the screen. And that is before <font size=-1>PC</font>s start being equipped to play digital-video-discs--the much-vaunted replacements for the <font size=-1>CD</font>-<font size=-1>ROM</font>. Decompressing and presenting the two and a half hours of full-motion video that these new discs can carry will put an even greater strain on a <font size=-1>PC</font>'s short-term memory.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By anointing the Rambus design, Intel has caused consternation among traditional memory-chip makers. They have been trying to hammer out a new <font size=-1>DRAM</font> standard known as SyncLink. This aims to hit Intel's target with a design that allows a microprocessor to talk to the memory cells by means of two specially tuned buses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now, though, they have been out flanked. Intel has decided it prefers Rambus's real design to SyncLink's "paper chip". So, since Intel's microprocessors are used in over 90% of the <font size=-1>PC</font>s sold around the world, <font size=-1>DRAM</font> makers everywhere will have to take out Rambus licences if they want to stay in the business.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All of which should please Rambus's founders. Even with a royalty of as little as 1.5% of the value of each chip made by its licence holders, the company is going to be coining it. Some 2.5 billion <font size=-1>DRAM</font>s were sold last year at an average price of $6 apiece. Within a few years, Rambus could be collecting $100m-150m a year in royalties just for coming up with the right <font size=-1>DRAM</font> architecture at the right time.<b> </b>In the computing industry even seven-stone weak lings can become superheroes overnight.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
