<html><head><title>Don't be salesmen</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>

<h1 align=center>Don't be salesmen</h1>


THERE are a lot of things, these days, which ministers and bureaucrats should not be doing. Printing money to finance reckless borrowing. Raising taxes so high as to discourage work and enterprise. Impeding flows of trade and investment. Introducing or preserving regulations that impose high costs on business and distort economic decisions. Nationalising companies, or thwarting the privatisation of existing state-owned firms. Protecting monopolies and cartels. Intervening in the economy to "pick winners" in new industries or protect "lame ducks" in old ones. For those who accept such self-denying ordinances, politics and economic policy-making are much less fun than in the 1960s or 1970s. But at least one thing is still allowed: ministers and officials can fly off on trips promoting exports and tempting foreign companies to invest in their countries. Pushing for more trade, more jobs, more investment: what could be wrong with that?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sorry to be a party-pooper, but quite a lot--both in practice and in principle. In practice, the things that governments do to promote exports are becoming controversial. William Daley, the new head of America's Commerce Department (see <a href="am3212.html"> page</a>), has suspended his department's export-promotion effort while investigations take place into allegations that political donations have bought access to help and to trade missions. Separately, Britain's main political parties have been arguing about whether public money should be used to buy a new royal yacht, whose main use would be, or could be, export promotion. Meanwhile, questions of whether China should be criticised for civil-liberties infringements in Hong Kong have become entangled in European governments' desire to secure contracts for their firms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such controversies are unlikely to end the fashion. Governments want to do something to help their economies grow, and many believe, with Bill Clinton, that "geo-economics" has replaced geo-politics as their main concern. Our article on <a href="sf0823.html">page</a> describes the various methods governments are using, and quotes these war-weary words of Jeffrey Garten, under-secretary of commerce during Mr Clinton's first term: "In the best of worlds, governments ought to get out of this business altogether. But the marketplace is corrupted by the presence of government. So do you sit on the side and pontificate about Adam Smith, or do you enter the fray?"
<br></p><p><b><b>What not to do</b>
</b><br>This sounds convincing. Like most arguments for government intervention, it contains an element of truth. The trouble is that on the basis of that element a mountain of self-serving or plain bad practice has been built.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The reason why government export promotion is wrong in principle begins with a simple observation: everything has a price. Whenever a minister jets off to Indonesia, or China, or Saudi Arabia to secure a contract for a private firm, the question that should be asked, but almost never is, is what price the minister is paying. It is in the minister's interest only to emphasise the benefit of his venture, usually in terms of jobs created or income earned. But buyers of exports are rarely fools, swayed merely by a minister's flattery. They extract a price. After all, as Mr Garten suggests, there are plenty of other minister-salesmen clamouring for the buyer's attention.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The easiest case is where an export-promoting government offers a subsidy: cash to cover a discount, say, or a generous export-credit deal, or aid to the buyer linked formally or informally to the purchase. Most rich-country politicians now accept that domestic subsidies do not make sense. Yet they continue to claim that exports are different. So taxpayers are, in effect, subsidising exporters to produce goods, while paying foreigners to take them away. Only in truly remarkable instances could taxpayers be better off as a result. In most cases, regardless of whether other governments wish to waste cash in this way, they are worse off. So is the economy, for such subsidies divert resources towards industries that benefit from them and away from those, serving mainly the domestic market, that do not. There are two other beneficiaries: the bribed buyer; and the minister, pointing proudly at all those jobs and exports.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Are not exports the modern holy grail, proof of a country's competitiveness? This is just a new form of the oldest mercantilist myth. There is nothing magic about exports; they are simply a necessary means to pay for imports. Look at France, which is running a $24 billion annual trade surplus and thus has exports galore. But it also has unemployment galore, and problems galore, none of which will be solved by more exports. It is safe to predict, however, that right now, somewhere in Paris, someone is planning the next trade-promotion trip for President Chirac or one of his ministers, and working out ways to bribe the lucky hosts to buy more Airbuses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The more complicated case, but also now the most common and the most insidious, is where the price is non-financial. China is the best illustration, but is only one of many. Officials, ministers, chancellors, presidents are flocking to the Middle Kingdom to press the flesh, drink the rice-wine and sign the export contracts. From time to time, however, China's dictators do something outrageous: they massacre some people, lock others up, grab a reef, fire missiles near Taiwan, restrict Hong Kong's liberties. The export-salesmen insist that foreign-policy considerations such as these can be separated from the trade missions. The Chinese know better. This export zeal provides them with a perfect pressure point, as well as with a way to divide one western ally from another.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What, then, can governments do? One sort of export promotion does no particular harm and (depending on the cost) may even do some good. That is general marketing of a country, carefully insulated from particular contracts and particular companies, in a way analogous to the work done by an industry association for its members: drum-beating, information-gathering, information-disseminating. Beyond that, there are two other legitimate roles for governments.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One is that for some longer-term export contracts, as for inward investments, reassurances about the stability of regulatory and macroeconomic policy can be important. This is no truer of a foreign buyer than a domestic one, but the foreigner may have less information or understanding of policy trends than the resident does. Even more important, of course, is actually maintaining that stability. The other legitimate role is that in the defence business governments do typically have to deal with governments. There, if you want to be in the business, you have to get into the fray.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most export-salesmanship, especially that by politicians, does not fall into these categories, however. Any benefits obtained from it come at a price. And that price, whether in economic or in diplomatic terms, is not worth paying.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
