<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width="271" height="24" alt="Politics this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Boss of Chechnya
</h2><b>Aslan Maskhadov</b>,<b> </b>Chechnya's guerrilla leader who made peace with Russia last year, easily won an election for the presidency of the rebel republic. 
<p><b>Boris Yeltsin </b>made a brief, but pre-recorded, appearance on television and subsequently tottered into the Kremlin. But doubts continued about his chances of a full recovery from his heart operation and pneumonia as more meetings with foreign leaders were put off.
<p>Discord grew in the German government over plans unveiled by Theo Waigel, the finance minister, to revamp the <b>tax system</b>. The top rate of income tax would fall from 53% to 39%, the bottom rate from 26% to 15%. The labour minister, Norbert Bl&uuml;m, complained that Mr Waigel's plan threatened his own proposed reform of pensions. 
<p>A former French minister, <b>Maur</b><b>ice Pap</b><b>on</b>,<b> </b>now 86, was sent for trial, accused of sending Jews to death camps under France's Vichy government in the second world war.
<p><b>Switzerland's ambassador </b> to the United States, Carlo Jagmetti, resigned. A leaked document revealed that he had urged his government to "wage war" against Jewish groups pressing Switzerland to make immediate amends for not returning assets confiscated by Nazis and held in Swiss banks.
<p><b>Bulgaria's new president</b>, Petar Stoyanov, appealed for western help, saying his country was in dire financial straits. He asked a Socialist, Nikolai Dobrev,<b> </b>to form a caretaker government--and then urged him to agree to hold new elections.
<p>Albania's president, Sali Berisha, said his government would compensate his compatriots--thought to number more than a third of the population--who have lost their savings in collapsing <b>"pyramid" schemes</b>. Western bankers said Albania could not afford to pay.
<p>Latvia's president, Guntis Ulmanis, asked a former prime minister, <b>And</b><b>ris Skele</b>,<b> </b>a non-party businessman, to form another government--a week after he had resigned.
<p><h2>Avoiding that issue
</h2>President Clinton, at a press conference, promised that next week's <b>budget </b>would spend more on education and on a programme to detect outbreaks of food-borne illnesses. His audience only wanted to know about campaign fund-raising scandals.
<p>New York health officials reported that <b>deaths from AIDS</b><b> </b>in the city dropped by 30% last year, the first fall since the disease was recognised as an epidemic in 1981. The rate of new <font size=-1>AIDS</font> cases in the city remained unchanged. 
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>A study by the University of Michigan found that Gary, Indiana, is the <b>most segregated city</b> in the United States. Detroit was second. The least segregated city was Jacksonville, North Carolina. 
<p>In <b>Brazil</b>, the lower house of Congress backed a constitutional change that would allow President Fernando Henrique Cardoso to seek re-election in 1998.
<p><b>Colombia's</b> <b>feminists </b>were up in arms, after the Constitutional Court rejected a challenge to the penal code's total ban on abortion. Even after rape, the court decided, by six votes to three, abortion violates the fundamental rights of the unborn child--and the mother. Penalty: up to three years in prison.
<p><h2>Cry guilty
</h2>In South Africa, five former policemen confessed that they killed <b>Steve Biko</b>, a black activist, in 1977 and applied for amnesty--a breakthrough for the Truth and Reconciliation Commission. In the first meeting of its kind, the <b>Commonwealth </b>is bringing together African rulers and leaders of opposition parties later this month in Botswana to discuss governance in Africa.
<p>The United Nations said that <b>Burundi's army </b>had killed more than 1,000 people since the start of December.
<p>Algeria's President Liamine Zeroual blamed the current wave of <b>terror bombings and massacres</b> on foreign conspirators. The Islamic Salvation Front's leaders<b> </b>in<b> </b>exile called for a government of national unity. A peace rally in Algiers was broken up by security forces. Abdelhaq Benhamouda, secretary-general of Algeria's largest union and a close ally of Mr Zerou<b></b> al's, was murdered.
<p>Three <b>Israeli soldiers </b>were killed by a Hizbollah mine inside south Lebanon.
<p><h2>Weighing the odds
</h2>As <b>Pakistan </b>prepared to go to the polls on February 3rd, an opinion poll gave the party of Benazir Bhutto 20% of the vote, and that of her main rival, Nawaz Sharif, 40%. The Supreme Court rejected an appeal by Miss Bhutto to restore her government, dismissed by the president in November for corruption and misrule.
<p>Assets of Tang Liang Hong, an opposition candidate in <b>Singapore</b>'s recent general election, were frozen after government officials raided his home and office. Mr Tang, a lawyer, is in dispute with ministers over remarks said to have been made during the election campaign.
<p>A fire in a <b>Hong Kong </b>nightclub which killed 17 people was blamed on a gang war.
<p>The Chinese president, Jiang Zemin, launched a new campaign against <b>corruption in China</b>,<b> </b>saying that members of the Communist Party were forgetting its socialist traditions of struggle and frugality. In 1996, 116,000 people were punished for graft, 14% more than the previous year.
<p>

</td></tr></table></center>
