<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Indomitable dollar
</h2>(See <a href="bw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>The <b>dollar</b> continued its rise against a weakened yen, pushing up towards &#165;125. Japanese retail sales slipped by 0.4% in 1996, to &#165;23 trillion ($211 billion), the fifth year of decline. December was a bad month for department stores and supermarkets; sales fell 2.1% from a year earlier.
<p><h2>Bad business
</h2>The founder of <b>Hanbo Steel</b> was hauled from hospital to answer questions following the collapse of the company and other parts of the Hanbo Group, a conglomorate with debts of 5 trillion won ($5.8 billion). Five of the South Korean firm's banks are under investigation; President Kim Young Sam ordered an inquiry into allegations that some of his aides organised loans to Hanbo. The government is pouring 6 trillion won into the money market to avert a credit crunch. 
<p><b>Hilton Hotels</b> launched a $6.5 billion hostile takeover bid for <b>ITT</b>, its main rival in the hotels and casino businesses; with an assumption of debt, the offer was worth $10.5 billion. A successful bid would create the world's largest hotel and gambling giant.
<p>Shares in <b>IBM</b>, depressed by recent fourth-quarter results, jumped after the computer maker announced its first stock split for 17 years, halving the unwieldy $150-or-so share price.
<p>The proposed $20 billion merger between <b>BT and MCI </b>is under scrutiny on both sides of the Atlantic. Competing long-distance telephone companies have demanded that regulators in the United States and at the European Commission impose conditions. The commission said it is likely to investigate the deal.
<p>The European Commission proposed legislation to close a loophole whereby <b>"callback"</b> <b>services </b>in Europe run by foreign telecoms companies pay no value-added tax. European-run services are subject to 15-25% <font size=-1>VAT</font>.
<p>Eager to breathe life into the moribund privatisation of <b>Stet</b>, the Italian government announced the shake-up of top management at the telecoms giant and the merger of its main operating unit, Telecom Italia, with the holding company. Opposition politicians claimed the appointments were political.
<p>While the Italian government urged Stet to find an international partner, its Spanish counterpart, <b>Telefonica de Espa&ntilde;a</b>, prepares to name one. The choice, likely to be <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, <font size=-1>MCI</font> or <font size=-1>GTE</font>, will be made in the next few weeks to help the company expand in Latin America.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>America Online</b> offered to reimburse clients and limit membership after more class-action lawsuits by customers who are irritated by the online service's swamped networks. <font size=-1>AOL</font>'s switch to unlimited-use fees in December has backfired because its users refuse to log off.
<p>New drugs and strong domestic sales gave most <b>American drug companies </b>double-digit profit growth in 1996, galloping past the corporate average. The tighter rein on drug costs that the huge managed-care companies were expected to bring didn't happen. Drug prices rose 5% last year and sales volume also increased. In Britain, Zeneca said pre-tax profits this year would rise 14% to about &#163;1 billion ($1.6 billion).
<p>Shares in <b>J. Sainsbury</b> slumped after the supermarket chain, long Britain's biggest until Tesco tried harder, gave a warning that profits this year will be 10% lower than last year. 
<p><b>Michael Grade </b>resigned as chief executive of Britain's Channel 4 television station to become fully involved in the family firm, First Leisure, where he takes over as executive chairman. He plans to add film distribution to the company's interests in among other things, Blackpool Tower and bingo halls.
<p><b>Suez</b> completed a FFr3 billion ($540m) sale of property loans to Goldman Sachs, an investment bank, and announced it had returned to profit. The huge French holding company, after restructuring, made a FFr800m net profit in 1996 compared with a FFr3.9 billion loss in 1995.
<p><h2>Cash cars
</h2>The president of Toyota said his company might not make <b>new investments in Britain</b> if the country stays out of <font size=-1>EMU</font>. He said Toyota, one of Britain's largest foreign investors, might prefer continental Europe instead.
<p>(See <a href="bw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>Recent strikes that plagued General Motors, the biggest of <b>America's big three </b>car makers, caused net profits to plunge last year. But the cash-rich company approved a cautious $2.5 billion share buyback. Ford rallied domestically but suffered larger losses in Europe and Latin America. Earnings leapt at Chrysler, the smallest and fastest growing of the three (it reported last week).
<p>Soren Gyll quit suddenly as head of <b>Volvo</b>, Sweden's biggest car maker. He is replaced by Leif Johansson, chief executive of Electrolux, part of Sweden's Wallenberg empire. He said he would consider alliances with other car makers but ruled out another merger attempt such as the one with Renault which failed.
<p><b>Rover</b> sold more cars abroad than in Britain for the first time. Now owned by Germany's <font size=-1>BMW</font>, Rover produced 507,000 cars last year, over 500,000 for the first time since 1988; 54% of them were exported.
<p>

</td></tr></table></center>
