<html><head><title>Thoroughly modern mercantilists</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif" width="374" height="26" alt="Special feature">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Thoroughly modern mercantilists</h1>

<p><b>President Charles de Gaulle of France once refused to meet a Japanese prime minister, dismissing him as a "transistor salesman". Now, presidents of all stripes are making exports a central part of their foreign policies</b></p> 
<br>BILL CLINTON puts in a word with the Saudi princes, and snatches an order for Boeing from under the nose of Europe's Airbus. Helmut Kohl flies to Beijing, becomes the first western leader to inspect troops since the Tiananmen Square massacre and departs with a stack of Sino-German trade deals; other westerners fume--outwardly about human rights, inwardly about lost business. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How times have changed since de Gaulle's disdain. Now, the French prime minister goes to Tokyo to sell helicopters. No political leader thinks twice about doubling up as a commercial traveller. And nowhere has this transformation been so swift as in the United States.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;America's government used to be a lonely standard-bearer for free trade, trying to stick to the belief that governments should not intervene to boost exports. That is changing. Campaigning on the slogan that "it's the economy, stupid", Bill Clinton promised, in 1992, to focus America's foreign policy on its trading interests. In his first term he appointed as commerce secretary Ron Brown, an energetic and powerful friend who had helped organise Mr Clinton's winning campaign. Mr Brown raised the status of the Commerce Department within the administration, leading a series of high-profile trade missions abroad.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, it is a backhanded testimony to trade's political significance that America and Britain are now both passing through political awkwardnesses connected with it. In Britain, the government has stirred up a parliamentary squall by promising to spend &#163;60m ($97m) on a new yacht for the royal family, arguing that a gracious chat with Her Majesty will so impress "foreign potentates" that business will flow to British companies wherever <i>HMS Buybritish </i> docks. In America, Mr Brown, who remained as commerce secretary until his death in an air crash in 1996, has been accused of allotting places on export-promotion trips to firms which had donated money to the Democratic Party. William Daley, his successor-designate, has suspended all such trips for 30 days while corruption-proof guidelines are drawn up.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such scandals may smudge the image of the politician-salesman, but they do not alter the broader picture: in the past few years of free-market liberalism, politicians' enthusiasm for promoting national exports has been growing. As Clintonites put it, cold-war geopolitics has been replaced by "geo-economics", a theory which holds that trade security matters as much as military security.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Leaving aside the question of whether this shift in policies is justified (for which, see <a href="ld4529.html">cover leader</a>), these three pages ask: how in fact do governments promote exports? And are their policies changing? 
<br></p><p><b><b>Ask what your country can do for you</b>
</b><br>In principle, governments have four main methods at their disposal. The simplest is to <b>subsidise exporters.</b> The crudest such measures--direct subsidies of exports--are outlawed under the rules of the World Trade Organisation (<font size=-1>WTO</font>), which nearly all trading nations have promised to abide by. <font size=-1>WTO</font> members whose industries are damaged by others' industrial subsidies (even if these are not related to exports) can also bring a case before the trade club's dispute-settlement system: the result may be an end to the subsidy or compensation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even so, governments can still find channels down which to pump money for exporters (see <a href="sf1.gif"> chart</a>). They can, for example, <b>subsidise research and development</b>. Under <font size=-1>WTO</font> rules, governments may pay up to 75% of a firm's industrial-research costs, or half the cost of product development. There is a respectable economic argument for this: a firm undertaking research may not secure all the benefits from it; these can accrue to everyone, in the form of better-educated scientists, say. Governments have an interest in encouraging this. The trouble is that in practice they are poor at picking good research projects; markets are rather better.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Governments can also offer <b>"tied aid", </b> in which the recipient promises to buy goods from companies in the donor country. This is often given for foreign-policy as much for commercial reasons, and might be categorised as "aid" not "trade". One of the most spectacular recent examples of an export-promotion deal blowing up in the promoter's face occurred when the British government muddled trade and aid when dealing with Malaysia over a large arms contract (see <a href="sf0822.html"> page</a>). In December last year the <font size=-1>OECD</font> adopted new guidelines on tied aid, aimed at ensuring that it is given only to projects that cannot be commercially financed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Or governments can finance exports through <b>"export credit guarantees", which insure exporters against the risk of default by their customers. In the past, governments have used these to subsidise exporters by guaranteeing loans at below-market interest rates.</b> As with tied aid, <font size=-1>OECD</font> countries have signed a self-denying ordinance, intended to eliminate such beggar-my-neighbour subsidies on credits of two years or more. Many European governments have also increased private-sector involvement in their short-term export-credit operations, bringing market discipline to bear on them. By and large, governments have been using these various ways of subsidising exporters rather less enthusiastically than in the past.
<br></p><p><b><b>America's</b> <b>commerce conversion</b>
</b><br>That is also true of the second broad way in which governments can boost exports: manipulating the <b>exchange rate</b>. By devaluing, a government makes exports cheaper in foreign-currency terms. This helps exporters in the short run, but not in the long. Devaluation raises import prices, and, if workers maintain the purchasing power of their wages, labour costs rise, too. Eventually much, if not all, of the initial gain is inflated away.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That leaves the third and fourth means of help, where renewed government trade activism is concentrated. The third is simple <b>information-gathering</b>. Commerce departments and trade ministries spend lots of time and trouble gathering business information of every sort on foreign markets. Companies could do this for themselves singly (if big enough) or collectively--and many do. But firms, especially small ones, also get a sort of free ride from embassies set up for other reasons. Diplomats spend much of their time gathering information about local markets, showing the flag at trade fairs and arranging business meetings. These are skills at which the Americans and British are said to be conspicuously good--the Germans less so. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This overlaps with the last area, which might be called <b>trade boosterism</b> and is exemplified by the high-profile missions which were Mr Brown's trademark. European politicians and diplomats have long acted as export boosters. Asian tigers, too, are making big efforts. The (South) Korean Trade-Investment Promotion Agency has a network of offices round the world. The Hong Kong Trade and Development Council, which stages some 350 events a year around the world, is unusual in that it recoups 70% of its HK$1 billion ($130m) budget by charging participants fees. Assuming businesses pay only for services they find useful, the <font size=-1>HKTDC</font> probably does a better job than most of its counterparts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Japan is an exception to the rule. Having being bullied for decades by the Ministry of International Trade and Industry (<font size=-1>MITI</font>) to "export or die", big Japanese manufacturers need no encouragement, financial or otherwise. Now, <font size=-1>MITI</font> has become a shadow of its former self and <font size=-1>JETRO</font>, the Japan External Trade Organisation, has reinvented itself as a sort of ministry of imports. Fear of trade friction with America has been the main reason for this change.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;America's conversion to export activism has been as striking as Japan's retreat from it. With Jeffrey Garten, an undersecretary in his department until 1995, Mr Brown concentrated his efforts on the most populous emerging markets, such as China, India, Indonesia and Brazil, where demand was strongest for big-ticket projects such as power stations, transport systems and telecommunications networks. Besides leading trade missions abroad, Mr Brown organised a "war room" in the Commerce Department, to track the 100-odd biggest contracts overseas and plan government support for American competitors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Brown also co-ordinated the export-boosting efforts of the 19 disparate government agencies with new vigour. In fact, as officials admit, this followed on from a law signed by George Bush in 1992, which beefed up a little-known entity called the Trade Promotion Co-operation Council (<font size=-1>TPCC</font>) and required it to liaise between the agencies seeking to help exporters.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet America's export-promotion strategy remains confused. The Commerce Department offers exporters advice; the Export-Import Bank offers them finance. But so do, say, the Agriculture or Energy Departments to firms on their turf. Now, other bits of government are vying to boost exports, notably the Pentagon and the overseas aid agency (of all things).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The departments are sometimes at loggerheads. Ex-Im Bank, for example, has refused recently to help firms exporting to Haiti, arguing that the country is too risky. The Overseas Private Insurance Corporation (<font size=-1>OPIC</font>), on the other hand, is more sensitive to the State Department's interest in Haiti's stability: it is open for business there. Over China, the two agencies reverse roles. Ex-Im Bank is bullish and happy to underwrite trade there. <font size=-1>OPIC</font>, influenced by touchy diplomatic relations with the Chinese, refuses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Worse, the allocation of export-boosting cash makes no sense. Roughly two-thirds of it goes on promoting food exports, reflecting the food lobby's clout, rather than its needs. At one point, California's raisin growers secured $4m to advertise their raisins in Japan--a sum which exceeded the Commerce Department's entire Japan budget. Because the <font size=-1>TPCC</font><b> </b>has to produce an annual report on export promotion, such misallocation is at least clearer than before and is becoming less extreme. Even so, money is being shifted from the food lobby to other industries only slowly.
<br></p><p><b><b>So why do it?</b>
</b><br>It may seem odd that governments should be putting so much effort into promoting exports just when they are cutting back on other forms of interference in trade, such as tariffs, under the auspices of the <font size=-1>WTO</font>. One plausible explanation is that most of their energy goes into helping small firms, which cannot afford to set up their own offices overseas. America's Commerce Department, for instance, reckons that 90% of its work is on behalf of small companies. But how successful is it? Laura Tyson, until recently head of America's National Economic Council, admits there has been only a slight increase in small firms' share of American exports, though increasing that share was one of the administration's aims.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A second explanation is that, especially when big infrastructure contracts are at stake in emerging markets, governments are afraid to abandon their national companies because other governments are committed to backing their own champions. At the same time, the purchaser itself is usually a government, or state-owned company. Winning a contract is harder without the personal endorsement of a minister.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other governments' support for their national firms was a prime reason why the United States joined battle so fiercely. "In the best of worlds," says Mr Garten, now the dean of Yale School of Management, "governments ought to get out of this business altogether. But the marketplace is corrupted by the presence of government. So do you sit on the side and pontificate about Adam Smith, or do you enter the fray?"
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Will governments ever get out of the export-promotion business? When pigs fly, perhaps. Clearer government-procurement procedures, especially in developing countries, are achievable, though <font size=-1>WTO</font> talks on the matter (long an American priority) are still some way off. An <font size=-1>OECD</font> agreement to clamp down on bribe-paying (ditto) might make a difference--if anyone takes any notice. And even then such things might not be enough. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Governments love to think, usually mistakenly, that their economies will be better off if they help things along than if they leave well alone. Now that they are renouncing some forms of support for their industries against international competition, they have eagerly embraced another. The temptation to meddle seems always be too great to resist.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
