<html><head><title>Uncommercial travellers</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif" width="374" height="26" alt="Special feature">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Uncommercial travellers</h1>

TRADE promoters yell "Buy our goods!" But if you are in the trade diplomats' bazaar, you are just as likely to hear another hawker's cry: "Buy our workers!" As governments compete to sell exports, so they fight to persuade foreign companies to set up factories back home.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some make better salesmen than others. The French have an urbane roving ambassador who lives up to his country's best traditions by wining and dining foreign investors, and by extolling <i>la France</i>. The British, says one rival, are "very good, very organised". But beneath the patter the pitches are much the same. The locals are friendly and have just the skills you need; the country is beautiful--and the government is very, very generous.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Governments are keen to attract foreign direct investment for much the same reason that they strive to win juicy export contracts: they can point to jobs created at home (and, by implication, not "lost" to foreigners). Politicians usually expect foreign-owned factories to export their wares to neighbouring countries. And like export-promotion schemes, foreign-investment subsidies have the advantage of supporting industry without protection against imports--although, like export subsidies, <font size=-1>FDI</font> subsidies distort world trade away from the pattern that would have prevailed but for the sweeteners.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are two differences, however. First, governments see foreign investment as a way of reviving economically deprived regions, hence can argue they are not providing unfair subsidies, just (say) bringing the roads and telephones of a poor region up to scratch. Second, they can offer fat bribes to foreign investors--in the form of tax breaks, grants and so forth--that would be illegal, or at least well hidden, in trade deals.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And what bribes. The cost to taxpayers of snaring foreign investment can be up to $250,000 per job, especially if there is a bidding war (see <a href="sf2.gif"> table</a>). There are two lots of winners from this: the lucky workers with subsidised employment; and the shareholders of foreign companies. The best outcome for shareholders (and the worst for taxpayers) is that they end up getting paid to pitch camp where they would have done anyway, so their hosts' largesse is pure gain.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Too bad for taxpayers, and for workers in countries whose pockets are not deep enough to compete in auctions for foreign investment. Some developing countries complain that, while rich-country governments are keen to see foreign investors given greater protection against interference from host governments (an <font size=-1>OECD</font> agreement on this is due to be completed by May), they are less eager to call a halt to <font size=-1>FDI</font> auctions.
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?854758800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
