<html><head><title>The new Daley machine</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>
<b>LEXINGTON</B>
<h1>The new Daley machine</h1>

THINK of the name Daley, and you think of machines. Richard J. Daley, the mayor of Chicago from 1955 to 1976, was a master of machine politics. His son, Richard M. Daley, Chicago's mayor since 1989, has covered the old machinery with the trappings of modern management. But now another member of the Daley family--William, son of the former mayor, brother of the current one--is to be in charge of a formidable chunk of Washington machinery known as the Commerce Department.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On January 30th the Senate looked set to confirm Mr Daley's nomination as the new commerce secretary. After a dramatic start (when, under the bright lights at the press conference where President Clinton announced his new appointments, the 48-year-old Mr Daley fainted and tumbled into the arms of <font size=-1>CNN</font>'s Wolf Blitzer), the confirmation process has gone smoothly. This is surprising, given the controversies engulfing the Commerce Department and in view of Mr Daley's own background, which would seem just the sort to inspire despair that anything much will change.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Take the controversies first. The Commerce Department has been at the top of the list of government agencies that Republicans would like to eliminate. Its defenders argue that it is a vital champion of American business, helping firms compete on an equal footing in the global marketplace; $250m-worth of export promotion over the past four years resulted in over $40 billion in overseas sales, according to Mr Daley at his confirmation hearing on January 22nd. The department's critics are wary of such claims, seeing the place as a wasteful dispenser of corporate welfare (notably through its Advanced Technology Programme, which doles out aid to some of the country's largest companies) and a bureaucratic amalgam of functions--from the Census Bureau to the Patent and Trademark Office and the National Weather Service--that do not obviously belong together. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Republican zeal for dismantling the department has diminished somewhat. The main campaigner in the House of Representatives, Dick Chrysler, lost his seat in the November elections. But reasons for wariness about its activities have grown. Not only has it continued to be a dumping ground for political operatives, but it has aroused suspicions of being abused as a machine for processing influence and business connections into political cash.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Critics have long suspected that many of the coveted places on trade missions under Mr Clinton's first commerce secretary, Ron Brown, went to donors to the Democratic Party. Fresh concerns over influence-peddling have come with the revelations of the dubious fund-raising activities of John Huang, a political appointee at the Commerce Department who moved to the Democratic National Committee (<font size=-1>DNC</font>) and is the man at the centre of the Democrats' Asian-money scandal. The relationship between the Commerce Department and the <font size=-1>DNC</font> has had a troublingly incestuous appearance.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Which is why Mr Daley's background should raise eyebrows: it is the identikit lawyer/business-lobbyist/party-fundraiser profile of his predecessors. Ron Brown was a super-lobbyist with the Washington law firm of Patton, Boggs & Blow and a successful chairman of the <font size=-1>DNC</font>. Mickey Kantor, who took over after Brown's death, is another lawyer-apparatchik; he chaired Mr Clinton's 1992 presidential campaign. And now there is Mr Daley, high-earning lobbyist with the Chicago law firm of Mayer, Brown & Platt, member of Chicago's political dynasty, head of Mr Clinton's successful Illinois campaign in 1992, fundraiser for the 1996 Democratic Convention in Chicago. Passed over four years ago for the job of transport secretary, he is at last getting his reward with a cabinet post. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is of course entirely appropriate that a commerce secretary should be experienced in the world of business (Mr Daley's corporate clients have included some of the best-known American and foreign companies) and familiar with the ways of Washington (he was a frequent lobbyist with his Chicago friend, Dan Rostenkowski, the disgraced former chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee). Mr Daley is also highly competent. Those who have worked with him describe him as focused, bright and personable. Brought into the White House in 1993 to run the flagging campaign for the North American Free-Trade Agreement, he added order and a sense of mission that helped win the day.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His skills have been on display during his confirmation process. To pre-empt Republican objections, he pledged to cut the department's 256 slots for political appointees by 100. He also promised to suspend all trade missions abroad for a month while he reviews procedures. That came close to an admission of past abuses. "There is no place for politics at the Department of Commerce," he assured senators.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Not everyone was impressed. Sam Brownback, a newly elected senator from Kansas, voted against Mr Daley's confirmation in committee on Wednesday. He was underwhelmed by the secretary-designate's promises (for example, some 50 political slots are currently vacant at the department, so the Daley cuts are only half as big as they sound) and unconvinced about his commitment to reform. Once confirmed, Mr Daley can expect intense scrutiny of his department--as well as a renewed push for its dismantling--from Mr Brownback and like-minded Republicans.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If he really wanted the Commerce Department to be above politics, Mr Clinton might have chosen it--rather than the Defence Department--as the place to have a Republican at the helm. Last December, in an interview with the <i>Los Angeles Times</i>, Mr Clinton said of Taiwanese-Americans such as Mr Huang, "The culture out of which they come doesn't draw the same bright lines between politics, government and business that we do." In appointing Mr Daley to Commerce, the president has hardly drawn a bright line himself. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
