<html><head><title>Big winners, big losers</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/as.gif" width="67" height="26" alt="Asia" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Australia
<h1>Big winners, big losers</h1>

</b></p><font size=1>SYDNEY
</font><p>THE prime minister has denounced them. So has the premier of New South Wales. Even Rupert Murdoch, bearer of breasts and bottoms in his newspapers, is agin them. They are breeding across Australia the way rabbits used to and, say their critics, are causing similar havoc. Adelaide's grand colonial railway station has been taken over by one. Melbourne has one of the biggest in the world. Even Alice Springs has one.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the past few years, the number of casinos in Australia has almost doubled. In 1992 there were eight; by 1995 there were 14. The mania for building them, from Perth to Queensland, has fed a gambling culture inherent in Australia from colonial times. For years, much gambling flourished illegally, particularly in New South Wales, the most populous state, where it was a source of police corruption.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The culture has changed dramatically since Australia's two biggest cities opened their first legal casinos, Melbourne in 1992 and Sydney two years later. Licensed under strict controls, these are no ordinary casinos, neither discreet like those in London nor glitzy like those in Las Vegas. They are mega-buildings, occupying prime sites of the sort once reserved for cathedrals and town halls.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Sydney Harbour Casino is by one of the world's most magnificent harbours, where acres of old warehouses have been bulldozed to make way for a complex that will eventually include flats, a hotel and two theatres. The Crown Casino in Melbourne, nearing completion, is even more grandiose. Built across a freeway by the Yarra River, it comes with 25 restaurants, 40 bars and three nightclubs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Sydney casino's fortunes received a boost on January 13th when Kerry Packer, an Australian tycoon, announced an offer to take over its management, and a fifth of its ownership, from Showboat, an American casino operator. He had sought the casino licence, but was outbid by the American company. Mr Packer is not only Australia's richest man; he is also its most redoubtable gambler. Winning streaks apparently gained him $9m in Las Vegas in 1994 and another $20m a year later. After such successes, he happily dispenses tips of $25,000 to dealers. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As part-owner--assuming the authorities give their approval--Mr Packer would be banned from playing in his own casino. That is unlikely to trouble him. Through his media company, Publishing and Broadcasting, he will be investing in one of Australia's biggest and fastest growing industries. Turnover from all forms of gambling in 1985 was A$61 billion ($47 billion), A$4,800 for every Australian. New South Wales, Mr Packer's home state, accounted for 43% of this. Mr Packer is also an investor in the Melbourne casino.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Gambling breeds losers as well as winners. One of the first signs greeting visitors to the Sydney Harbour Casino offers a hotline telephone number for "problem gamblers". Addicts can register with security guards and have themselves excluded. In the casino's first 15 months of operation, nine customers received medical counselling after threatening to commit suicide. Bob Carr, the Labor premier of New South Wales, who took office after the Sydney licence had been awarded, has described casinos as "the scourge of our society".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No such inhibitions cramp Jeff Kennett, his Liberal counterpart in Victoria. Mr Kennett has dismissed a political storm over the awarding of the Crown Casino licence to companies with close links to the state's ruling Liberal Party. He maintains that all proprieties were respected.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Politicians of all persuasions are mostly turning a blind eye to the social impact of gambling. In an era of smaller government and shrinking public revenue, the casinos and other forms of legalised gambling are a new source of money and jobs. Victoria now receives 14% of its state revenue from gambling taxes and licence fees, and hopes gambling will draw rich Asian tourists. New South Wales gets 12%. Jobs in the casino industry rose by 72% between 1992 and 1995, compared with only 5% in the Australian workforce as a whole. However, opponents of gambling take comfort from reports that casino profits are falling amid signs that the industry has reached saturation point. Its luck may be running out.
<br>
<br>
