<html><head><title>Be fruitful</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/ir.gif" width="224" height="26" alt="International" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Rwanda
<h1>Be fruitful</h1>

</b></p><font size=1>KIGALI
</font><p>THE maternity wards are packed. So are the churches, where dozens of young couples get married every Saturday amid soon-to-be grandparents shouting instructions from the pews to be fruitful and multiply. One popular <font size=-1>T</font>-shirt proclaims: "Let's Make Babies". 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though the slogan is not government policy, breeding has unofficially become a public duty, especially among the Tutsi minority, who lost maybe 750,000 of their kin in the genocide of 1994. "Too many people died. We want to repopulate," says 30-year-old Katherine Uwera, who lost most of her extended family in the killings. She has two toddlers at home, a baby strapped on her back, and plans for another soon.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Demographically, Rwanda has undergone some erratic developments recently. After the massacres, over 2m Hutus fled into neighbouring countries and around 1m Tutsis--former refugees who fled in the past three decades, and their descendants--flooded in, herding 1m cows with them. The Tutsi rebels who fought their way to power are leading the baby boom by example: nearly every army officer you meet has another child on the way.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Meanwhile, 1.2m of the Hutus who fled in 1994 to Zaire and Tanzania have come back, with large numbers of new-born children. For two years, the refugees enjoyed internationally provided health care. Though often described as squalid, the camps had birth rates far exceeding the death rates. No one knows for sure how many Hutu refugees are still in Zaire. Will they stay there, or make the trek home and, no doubt, multiply enthusiastically too?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One doctor has coined the term "revenge fertility" to describe what he believes is ethnic competition to procreate. Now that so many have returned, he says, "We're back at square one. Population pressure is worse than it was before."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is saying something. The former president, Juvenal Habyarimana, whose death when his plane was shot down in April 1994 gave the signal for the genocide, used to pour water into a full glass to demonstrate what would happen if Tutsi refugees came home. Rwanda, he said, was full. It is the most densely populated country in mainland Africa, with at least 7.2m people, most of them dependent on small farms, crammed into a space about the size of Sicily, or Maryland. In 1991, fertility ran at about seven children per woman, and the population, growing at 3.5% a year, was expected to reach 25m by the year 2030. Habyarimana set up a National Population Office. It was resented and ignored; the Catholic church had more influence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Tutsis now in power long since dismissed Habyarimana's population arguments as politically inspired nonsense. "For most of the people it doesn't make sense to talk about family planning after genocide," says Maurice Bucago, the government's population expert. "They expect us to tell them to have babies. We have to be realistic." In fact, they need little telling. Contraception was never widespread; perhaps one couple in eight used it before the genocide. Now hardly anybody does.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government is planning a "villagisation" programme to bring everyone in from their present scattered homes and plots and collect them in villages, where they can be given health and education services (and better controlled). Whether that will, in time, lead to wider use of birth control remains to be seen.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The one force today against a population explosion is--not by coincidence--the worst: <font size=-1>AIDS</font>. Before 1994, it was reckoned that up to a quarter of adults in the capital, Kigali, were infected with <font size=-1>HIV</font>. In the countryside, where most Rwandans live, the rate was under 4%. Now researchers expect infection to jump. Many of the newly returned Hutu refugees are carrying the virus, which is thought to have spread wildly in the camps. And more and more people now live in towns--Kigali's pre-1994 population of 300,000 may have nearly doubled--where <font size=-1>AIDS</font> spreads more rapidly. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Genocide was not a reaction to over-population; its roots were political. But over-exuberant procreation will only increase the fears and ethnic rivalry that the politicians were able to exploit. 
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?854758800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
