<html><head><title>Russia's surly answer to NATO</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/eu.gif" width="105" height="26" alt="Europe" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Russia's surly answer to NATO</h1>

<font size=1>MOSCOW
</font><p><p><b>Russia was never expected to welcome NATO's eastward expansion (see <a href="eu1.gif">map</a>). But what it proposes to do about it is still uncertain</b></p>
<br>CONFRONTED with <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s arguments for edging eastward, Russia has decided to affect deafness--but not blindness. It sees that the expansion will probably occur. Parliament, government, the armed forces and the press are preoccupied with deciding how to respond. But so far they have sounded unreceptive, to say the least, to western suggestions for building new <font size=-1>NATO</font>-Russia relations.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hostility towards a bigger, nearer <font size=-1>NATO</font> is almost universal. A group of admirals and generals published a letter in January calling on Boris Yeltsin to point nuclear missiles at the capital cities of <font size=-1>NATO</font> members. Anatoly Chubais, Mr Yeltsin's liberal-minded chief of staff, called the expansion of <font size=-1>NATO</font> "one of the worst ideas advanced by the West in recent years". Even Mikhail Gorbachev has found himself in tune for once with his country's mood. An expansion of <font size=-1>NATO</font>, he said, would mean that "the West's most hawkish, conservative and aggressive (and also most ignorant) circles have gained the upper hand".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until and unless Mr Yeltsin--who appeared on television on January 28th for the first time in three weeks--is fit for work, the man to listen to most closely amid the hubbub of Russian voices will be Yevgeny Primakov, the foreign minister. Characteristically, Mr Primakov has maintained a baleful calm. When <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s secretary-general, Javier Solana, came calling last week, Mr Primakov insisted on a formal, private meeting. He offered nothing that could have been construed as acquiescence, or as a threat. Russia's official position remained that <font size=-1>NATO</font> should offer a legally binding mechanism giving Russia a say equal to that of any <font size=-1>NATO</font> member (and thus, in effect, a veto) on anything affecting Russia's vital interests. That would include, above all, any expansion of <font size=-1>NATO</font> eastward.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>NATO</font> has proposed to Russia merely a declarative "charter". Possibly, therefore, no deal between Russia and <font size=-1>NATO</font> will be done before the <font size=-1>NATO</font> summit, set for July, at which invitations to one or more would-be entrants may be issued. Some Moscow commentators have foreseen humiliating consequences for Russia. A deal struck later, with an enlarged <font size=-1>NATO</font>, would need the blessing of <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s new members, too. Former Soviet vassal-states would thus have a whip-hand over Russia.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Primakov seems less worried. His main rule of diplomacy seems to be: better a long argument than a quick compromise. Better, in other words, for a weak Russia to keep alive all the disagreements and claims it can, until the time when it is a stronger country and better able to have its way. To withhold consent of any sort to <font size=-1>NATO</font> expansion, and so to have in place a bone of contention with the West for years to come, would be very much Mr Primakov's style.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Duma, the lower house of Russia's parliament, has taken a lead in linking <font size=-1>NATO</font> expansion with other East-West security deals. It was reluctant in any event to ratify <font size=-1>START-2</font>, a treaty with America to reduce arsenals of strategic nuclear weapons, seeing it as an imposition. Now it is withholding ratification explicitly as a hostage against <font size=-1>NATO</font> expansion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Duma's jingoists seem to care little that the obligations of <font size=-1>START-2</font> are finely balanced. Russia would have plenty to lose were the treaty to lapse. Possibly, America might think it worth trying to change the Duma's mind by offering to open negotiations on a <font size=-1>START-3</font> even without a ratification of its forerunner. But an offer of that sort would probably need a bilateral summit, and it is far from clear that Mr Yeltsin will be fit enough to keep a planned date with Bill Clinton in March.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After some early mutterings about abandoning the agreement on Conventional Forces in Europe (<font size=-1>CFE</font>), which was signed in 1990, Russia has settled for trying to revise the treaty through talks launched in January. It seems to view <font size=-1>CFE</font> as a possible way to obstruct both overall growth in <font size=-1>NATO</font> forces and any shift of resources towards new <font size=-1>NATO</font> members. At the same time, Russia wants more flexibility in the disposition of its own conventional armed forces near its borders. There is sympathy in the West for some of Russia's difficulties with <font size=-1>CFE</font>, since it was designed for confidence-building in a cold-war Europe. Yet Russia may still not get all it wants. Either way, it has set in motion a haggling match liable to run well into 1998. 
<br></p><p><b><b>A hug for old comrades?</b>
</b><br>Fresh tension with the West over <font size=-1>NATO</font> could, however, create some useful foreign-policy opportunities for Mr Primakov. One such would be to develop closer ties with "old friends" of Russia that are suspicious of, or hostile to, the United States. The list would include China, Iran, Iraq, North Korea (with which Russia is preparing a new friendship treaty, though it will not include the promise of military help enshrined in the old one) and perhaps Cuba. An alliance with China would offer the richest potential for mischief, though at some risk to Russia itself.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;An expanding <font size=-1>NATO</font> would also give Russia, in its own eyes at least, more cause for interfering with the belt of countries immediately to its west--the aim being to "deny" these countries to <font size=-1>NATO</font> for the future. The Baltic states would face harassment designed both to worry away western investors and to remind <font size=-1>NATO</font> that the "Russia risk" here is a real one. Ukraine would face pressure to follow Belarus into much tighter relations with Russia.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For Russia's arms dealers and nuclear-power engineers, renewed tension with the West would be a definite blessing. They would have even less reason to feel inhibited about selling to all-comers. If that upset America, or other <font size=-1>NATO</font> countries (as with the recent proposed sale of a missile system to Cyprus), so much the better. Russia's generals, too, would exploit a new <font size=-1>NATO</font> "threat" in their struggle with the government for money to keep Russia's armed forces at their present hypertrophied size. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Security tensions might also affect foreign investment. Russia thinks of its natural resources as "strategic" assets, not just commercial ones. Foreign investors seeking stakes in oil and gas fields could find themselves suddenly less welcome.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this need not change <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s mind about expansion. Most of the responses available to Russia carry a heavy price-tag for Russia itself. Given that Russia is weak and poor, as well as irritable, it might decide, wisely, that it could not afford to row too much with a West on which it still depended. But since there would also be strong Russian interests poised to profit from tension with the West, the possibility must remain of a tricky time ahead.
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?854758800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="br7717.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>
1997 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>

</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT09-B15-181</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA096-001030-B008-282</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.europe.economist.com:80/issue/01-02-97/br7717.html 199.173.162.110 19970215014803 text/html 6313
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 01:43:58 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 30-Jan-97 19:05:34 GMT
Content-length: 6126
