</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Steady as she sinks</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>

</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<h1>Steady as she sinks</h1>

<p><b>The Conservative campaign is barely out of port, and it's already in trouble</b></p>
<br>FOR the Tories to botch one relaunch might be regarded as misfortune. To botch them serially requires real carelessness, as events on January 27th demonstrated. Even as Stephen Dorrell, the health secretary, was briefing the press in a pub near Chequers on the manifesto agreed by ministers earlier that day, his work was being undermined by a Labour ambush in the House of Commons which led to a headline-grabbing one-vote defeat for the government on its education bill.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The vote took place only because the government had lost a previous vote in a Commons committee when Tony Coombs, a Tory whip, missed it while hunting for an absent colleague. The government lost the vote on the floor of the Commons only because Mr Coombs had no one ready to keep speaking until Tory reinforcements could arrive. Indeed, it may really not have lost the vote at all, since Mr Coombs also appears to have miscounted the number of votes by one. The vote itself does not matter. But what does is the fact that, just as ministers wanted the public to contemplate five more sparkling years of Tory rule, the party itself was displaying, yet again, an almost comic incompetence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The truth is that the state of the Tory party is such that, whatever it tries, something goes wrong. Its problems include:
<br><font size=-1><li></font> <b>No majority</b>. The government and opposition parties are level-pegging in the Commons. Moreover, Labour has withdrawn co-operation after the government cheated in a pre-Christmas vote. The government is now permanently vulnerable to ambush.
<br><font size=-1><li></font> <b>Europe.</b> Every effort to pull the party together on the <font size=-1>EU</font> falls foul of its intrinsic divisions. Take the cabinet's decision on January 23rd to announce that it was "very unlikely" that Britain would join any European monetary union on January 1st 1999. Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, agreed because he thinks that the rest of Europe will not go ahead then. Cabinet Eurosceptics emphasised that Britain would probably stay out even if it did. Result: yet more stories of Tory splits. 
<br><font size=-1><li></font> <b>Post-election leadership manoeuvring.</b> At first glance the decision of Michael Portillo, the defence secretary, to spend &#163;60m ($97m) on a new royal yacht to replace the clapped-out <i>Britannia </i>looked odd. This involved more public spending, just when the Tories are trying to pin the high-spending label on Labour. And it always threatened to provoke public ire. Sure enough, an <font size=-1>ICM</font> poll in the <i>Guardian </i>newspaper found a three-to-one majority against the idea. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However Mr Portillo was not trying to court the favour of the broader public, but of Tory activists and <font size=-1>MP</font>s. Saving the royal yacht was a plank of the platform on which John Redwood stood against John Major for the Tory leadership 18 months ago. Mr Portillo, who will compete with Mr Redwood for the right-wing vote in any post-election party-leadership contest, wanted to show that he does what Mr Redwood only talks about. His manoeuvre backfired badly. After he sought to make capital against Labour for questioning the project, the queen made known her concern at being dragged into politics.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Similarly, the prospect of a post-election leadership contest hampered the government's response to the lost education vote. Gillian Shephard, the education secretary, was the obvious person to deal with it. But the government faced another embarrassing vote the next day on bringing back corporal punishment in schools. This is against government policy. Nevertheless Mrs Shephard recently courted right-wing support by backing it. So she had to make herself scarce while nearly 100 Tory <font size=-1>MP</font>s defied the government in the caning vote. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Beyond these tactical problems, the Tories are struggling with a debilitating strategic problem. Voters seem fed up with Tory radicalism. So Mr Major has announced that the big reforms are done. His draft manifesto, which abjures a full sell-off of the Post Office and of Channel 4 television, is broadly a consolidators' manifesto.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, voters also think that the Tories have run out of steam. So the party also needs to offer something new. After 18 years in office, the popular things have been done. Those things left to do, whatever their merits, are unpopular: privatising London Underground, putting more public services out to tender, more spending cuts. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Tories have chosen their slogans: "The Enterprise Centre of Europe"; "Opportunity for all"; "New Labour, New Danger". But these remain mere slogans. What the public actually sees is a divided party without a majority in the Commons and half of whose ministers are obsessed with a leadership contest which will come only if the Tories lose the election.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
