<html><head><title>Election flutters</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<h1>Election flutters</h1>

EVERY punter knows that two-horse races with a long odds-on favourite are a short cut to bankruptcy. Ladbrokes, one of Britain's biggest bookmakers, is now quoting Labour six to one on to win the 1997 general election. That means if you bet &#163;600 ($970) on Labour and the party wins, you gain &#163;100. Except you don't: there is a levy of 9% to pay on your return of &#163;700 (winnings plus bet), leaving you a meagre profit of &#163;37 on the &#163;600 you have risked. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why then does the betting industry still expect to take &#163;6m in bets on the 1997 election? To win customers, the bookies are offering more interesting bets--some of which are set out in the table. Already you can bet on Lib Dem seats (Ladbrokes is offering a mouthwatering 16 to 1 against "fewer than 13 seats" for third-party pessimists, or 14 to 1 against 32 or more seats for optimists). Hills, another bookmaker, offers 100 to 1 against a February election. For ultra-pessimists Ladbrokes offers 25 to 1 against two elections in 1997. (See <a href="br1.gif">table</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As the election approaches, the offerings will get weirder and more wonderful. Odds against individual cabinet ministers keeping their seats are promised, as well as on different results in Scotland.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The most knowing punters will avoid them in favour of "spread" betting. This works like spreads in financial markets. You could, for example, currently buy Labour seats with <font size=-1>IG</font> Index for &#163;10 a seat. For every seat Labour wins above 355 (which would give it an overall majority of 51), you win &#163;10; for every seat they fall short, you lose &#163;10. Or you could sell them at 349, winning &#163;10 for every one by which they fall short and losing &#163;10 for every one by which they exceed it. The margin between 349 and 355 provides the firm with its profit. The beauty of spread betting is that the stake is not fixed, and so, by a quirk of the law, tax is not paid on any winnings.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<i>The Economist</i> hopes to make a few bob of its own with the bookies during the campaign. Our first bet: three to one against the Liberal Democrats taking Harrogate in competition with Norman Lamont, the former chancellor, offered by Ladbrokes. Mr Lamont may look home and hosed with a notional majority on the 1992 result of more than 9,000. But our correspondent on the Yorkshire gallops says that the Liberal Democrats have been making ground by branding Mr Lamont a southern carpetbagger, and there is a Labour vote of nearly 7,000 there to be squeezed. Remember: you read it here first.
<br>
