<html><head><title>In the mire</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>The Wirral South by-election
<h1>In the mire</h1>

</b></p><font size=1>WIRRAL SOUTH
</font><p>TONY BLAIR, the Labour Party leader, says he wants to make education a big issue at the general election, calculating that it is a vote-winner for Labour. The Tory campaign managers in the Wirral South by-election, due to be held by March 6th, are happy to oblige. In what promises to be a bitterly fought, perhaps even dirty, dry run for the general election, the Tories believe--against the polls and most expectations--that education can help them hold what was once a safe Tory seat. (See <a href="br2.gif">map</a>).
<br>On January 30th Eric Forth, an education minister, turned up at a local grammar school to confront David Blunkett, Labour's shadow education and employment secretary, who was visiting the school. Mr Blunkett would shut this school down, claimed Mr Forth, pressing home the government's claim that Labour intends to abolish grammar schools (ie, those that select pupils using an entrance exam) and grant-maintained schools (those that have opted-out of local-council control, often in order to keep their entrance exams). Council officials asked Mr Forth to leave because he had not been invited.
<br>Mr Blunkett insists that grammar schools will not be abolished unless local parents vote for it in a ballot, and proposes fairly small changes to the status of grant-maintained schools. Nevertheless, Tory big guns visiting Wirral South have been blasting away at Labour's education policy: Virginia Bottomley, the heritage secretary, lambasted Mr Blair and Harriet Harman, the shadow social-security secretary, for sending their children to grant-maintained and grammar schools while supposedly seeking to deny that opportunity to others.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With so much at stake, both parties are gearing up for a battle. Labour has filled a disused supermarket with computers and staff from London; the Tories have done likewise in a couple of small factory units. So far, though, all this effort and imported talent has not lifted the campaign above the level of mud slinging. Since Barry Porter, the local Tory <font size=-1>MP</font>, died in November, Labour's first-choice candidate, a union official, had to quit following allegations of domestic violence. The Liberal Democrats are on their third candidate after the second quit because of claims that his employers were investigating him. The Tories have managed to hold on to their first choice, but they were knocked sideways on January 27th when a Tory councillor in the constituency was jailed for five years for rape.
<br>Labour's misfortune allowed the party's National Executive Committee to impose a candidate more likely to please the wealthier locals: a former civil servant named Ben Chapman. Somewhat embarrassing, however, is the fact that Mr Chapman joined the Labour Party only last year. Les Byrom, the Tory candidate, promptly labelled him a "carpetbagger". Some disgruntled members of the local Labour Party agree, although they are loth to say so in public. Aides to Mr Chapman, who lives in the constituency, replied by claiming that Mr Byrom, a councillor on the other side of the Mersey, is the outsider.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Tories are staking their hopes on education because selective schools have proved popular and successful in Wirral South. In the industrial Merseyside towns of Wallasey and Birkenhead, the secondary schools are all mixed-ability "comprehensives". But in the greener commuter-beltlands to the west and south of the Wirral peninsula, primary pupils who pass tests go to local grammar schools and those who fail (or do not sit the tests) go to secondary moderns. About half of the area's primary-school children sat the tests on January 28th, although only about a third of these aspirants will get into the four local grammar schools, two of which are also grant-maintained.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many of Wirral South's middle-income voters do not want their grammar schools tampered with. They make up most of the constituency's electorate (81% of the 60,500 voters own their home, 74% have at least one car, 46% have professional or management jobs) and are exactly the kind of people Mr Blair has to persuade to vote Labour if he is to win power nationally. Labour's policy towards grammar schools has shifted a long way since the Labour government of Harold Wilson--Wirral Grammar School for Boys' most famous ex-pupil--abolished many of them. Now, says Mr Blunkett, abolition is not on the agenda. He claims it is more important to get on with improving standards in England's 4,000 comprehensive schools than to fight over the 161 grammar schools.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, the Tories in Wirral South argue that recent claims by Graham Lane, chairman of the Council of Local Education Authorities, that councils will start phasing out selection soon after Labour is elected, reveal the true state of affairs. Rubbish, says Mr Chapman: "I can categorically state that is not the case." Nevertheless Labour remains sensitive about the issue, and the party's press officers are edgy whenever education is mentioned.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ironically, both parties may be over-estimating the importance of education to the constituency's voters. Even in Heswall, the poshest part of Wirral South, where the electorate has always chosen Tory councillors, disillusionment with the government seems to run as deep as it does in the rest of the country. "They say one thing one minute and do another the next," says Florence Johnson, a life-long Tory voter who is now undecided. Her view bears out one poll in the seat which found a 16% swing to Labour, twice what Labour needs to win.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This may be because people think it is time to give Labour a chance to tackle other more urgent problems. Despite the Tories' claim to be the party of law and order, crime levels in Wirral South, like the rest of Merseyside, remain stubbornly high. A review by Wirral Health Authority, aimed at cutting the number of hospital beds for old people, does not sound like an inducement to vote Tory either.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is difficult to believe that Tory attacks on Labour's education policy can, alone, turn this tide. The last time Wirral Metropolitan Borough Council tried to change the grammar schools into comprehensives was in February 1988. Labour councillors, supported by the then alliance of Liberals and Social Democrats, pushed a plan to abolish selection through the council.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This scheme, vigorously opposed by the local Tories, was eventually vetoed by the government. But that was after local people showed they were not all that upset by it. In the local elections in May 1988, Labour gained five seats, four from the Tories and one from the alliance parties. It seems that local issues do not necessarily win votes, even in local elections.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
