<html><head><title>Labour approaches a minefield</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>British defence policy
<h1>Labour approaches a minefield</h1>

</b></p><p><b>If elected, the Labour Party has promised to carry out a fundamental review of Britain's defence priorities. The result would probably be a smaller defence budget--and perhaps the withdrawal of the British army from Germany</b></p>
<br>DEFENCE used to offer the Tories one of their strongest electoral cards. Even after the Labour Party scrapped its policy of unilaterally getting rid of nuclear weapons, in 1988, Conservatives claimed that Britain's security would not be safe in Labour hands. Over the past five years, however, while David Clark has been shadow defence secretary, Labour has by and large supported government policies, blunting Tory attacks. Defence is thus unlikely to be much of an issue in the coming election.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If Labour wins the election, however, defence could become one of the hottest political potatoes that Tony Blair has to handle. For Labour has promised to complete a strategic defence review within six months of taking office. "We want to assess the security risks facing Britain and its allies and ensure that we have the means to address those risks," says Mr Clark, who will probably be Labour's defence secretary. A modest but assiduous Cumbrian who gets on well with military men, Mr Clark resigned from Labour's front bench in 1981 to protest against the party's decision to support unilateral nuclear disarmament.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clark argues that the Conservatives' defence cuts have been driven by Treasury demands for cash, rather than a serious attempt to balance commitments and resources. "Our review should not be seen as a cost-cutting exercise," he says. "We want to keep, roughly, to current levels of spending." Mr Clark is doubtless sincere when he says that. But if the review concluded that some of Britain's military capabilities were superfluous, a smaller defence budget would surely follow. (See <a href="br3.gif">chart</a>)
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although there has been no formal, strategic defence review since 1981, the armed forces have been subject to continual reappraisal since the end of the cold war. In real terms, defence spending is a fifth less than it was in 1990. The number of personnel in uniform has shrunk from 306,000 in 1990 to 216,000 today. Britain has scrapped two of its three armoured divisions and is pulling the <font size=-1>RAF</font> out of Germany. Last year, in an effort to make the three services work more closely together, the governent established a "Joint Rapid Deployment Force", suitable for dealing with sudden crises, and a "Permanent Joint Headquarters", to manage any expeditionary force.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since 1990, British defence has evolved from being "threat-based"--focused on how to stop a Russian invasion of Western Europe--to "capability-based". The annual defence white paper lists 50 military tasks which the armed forces may have to perform, together with the personnel and equipment the tasks would require.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Each task supports one of three broad defence roles. The first is "the protection and security of the United Kingdom and its dependent territories". Tasks that fall under that heading include, for instance, ensuring the security of Northern Ireland and the Falkland Islands. A second role is "promoting Britain's wider security interests through the maintenance of international peace and stability". That means contributing to multilateral peacekeeping missions, as well as tougher operations such as the liberation of Kuwait and some oddities like reinforcing the Sultanate of Brunei.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is not a lot of scope for cutting back on commitments to those two broad roles, given the likely need to maintain troops in Northern Ireland and to provide peacekeepers. So much of the review will focus on the third: "to insure against a major external threat to the United Kingdom or our allies". This covers the tasks fulfilled by British forces within <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s military structure--tasks that are ripe for scrutiny now that Russia is less menacing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite successive rounds of defence cuts, Britain has retained, in theory, virtually all the military capabilities it had ten years ago. Only the ability to deliver nuclear bombs by aircraft has been lost. But capabilities have been shaved and shaved again--sometimes to the bone.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Over the past few years, for example, the <font size=-1>RAF</font> has been so short of spare engines that many of its fighters have been grounded. And the army faces a real problem of "overstretch". Under Ministry of Defence rules, units are supposed to spend 24 months between spells of active duty, so that they can rest, train and prepare for future missions. But for many regiments this period is much shorter: engineers are down to 12 months. One tank regiment has spent the last five summers on missions away from its base, and marriages have suffered.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ministry of Defence officials argue that Britain must retain a full range of military capabilities. Once a skill, such as the ability to run aircraft carriers, disappears, they claim, it may take 15 years to regain it--and no one can be sure that the world will be benign that far ahead. And then foreigners simply cannot be trusted to provide the things that Britain lacks, say officials: remember the perfidious Belgians, who would not sell Britain ammunition during the Gulf war?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Thus the defence establishment hopes for a modest defence review. But many defence academics hope for radical changes. They argue that, if Britain keeps trying to do everything in a period when resources are likely to diminish, the ability of the forces to fight effectively could be impaired. For instance there would be less time and money for training, while constant cash cuts could sap morale. They argue that Britain's forces are no longer large enough to fight a serious war alone, and that it would be better to drop some capabilities and share roles with allies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact there is already some role-sharing: the British have neither spy satellites nor aeroplanes large enough to carry armoured vehicles, but count on the Americans to provide them. And the Germans, who are keeping a conscript army geared mainly to territorial defence, will never want to do as much peacekeeping as the British and the French. Philip Sabin of King's College, London, argues that, since the Germans have a large army and lots of good tanks, they could look after armoured warfare on the continent but lean on the British for naval protection. Similarly, the British have excellent attack submarines and the French large aircraft carriers; could not each rely on the other's ships?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The services' complaint about all this is that the quality of other European forces--with the possible exception of the French--is not up to scratch. And one sceptical <font size=-1>RAF</font> officer invokes the following scenario: "Suppose the French are involved in a Central African war and call on us to provide equipment--but we disapprove of their actions. What do we do?" Europe's slow progress towards common foreign policies certainly makes role-sharing difficult. Despite this, some senior Labour Party figures like the idea.
<br></p><p><b><b>Attacking armour</b>
</b><br>The defence review's first question should be to ask: what role in the world does Britain want to play? The military and diplomatic establishment will argue that it should be capable, like France, of projecting force globally, and of playing a leading role in allied coalitions. Then Britain could maintain its claim to a permanent seat at the <font size=-1>UN</font> Security Council. Some would argue, however, that Britain should imitate Japan or Italy--countries which focus on commercial interests, spend little on defence and, when world crises blow up, follow the lead of others.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour will want Britain to remain a European power. But how strong a power? The answer would have a big influence on what are certain to be the defence review's most contentious arguments: should Britain retain a serious commitment to armoured warfare, and should the army remain in Germany?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The British army has eight tank regiments (with a total of 500 tanks), three armoured reconnaissance regiments, 12 armoured and mechanised infantry regiments and 16 regiments of artillery. There are only 21 general infantry batallions. Recent equipment orders--such as the Challenger 2 tank, the Apache attack helicopter, a new tank-busting missile and the <font size=-1>AS90</font> self-propelled gun--have been geared to the heavy end of warfare.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Thus much of the army is still orientated towards a major armoured conflict in Europe--the one sort of war it is now less likely to fight. Some defence analysts believe that, because anti-armour weapons are increasingly potent, tanks may soon be as redundant as battleships. Royal Navy and <font size=-1>RAF</font> planners like to point out that Britain could not be defended without ships and aeroplanes, but that tanks are not essential to national defence. Mobility is now recognised as one of the greatest military virtues, yet tanks take weeks to move from one country to another. Should the army not focus on a smaller but more mobile armoured force--perhaps buying some large transport planes with the money saved from winding up a few armoured regiments?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Definitely not, reply the generals. They argue that soldiers trained in high-intensity conflict can still perform in "low-intensity" situations such as peacekeeping. But if they have trained only for the latter, they cannot do the former. And they argue that armour is increasingly relevant to peacekeeping: the lightly-armed <font size=-1>UN</font> mission to Bosnia proved ineffective, while the weightier <font size=-1>NATO</font> force which followed succeeded in intimidating all sides. In Bosnia the British army does have tanks--which, unlike attack helicopters, can hold ground.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The generals further claim that, if Britain did not have armoured forces of such quality and strength, its allies would not accept the leading role that it plays in <font size=-1>NATO</font> operations. If Britain could no longer mobilise a complete armoured division, as it did during the Gulf war, they say, it might have to give up command of the <font size=-1>ARRC</font>--the mobile <font size=-1>NATO</font> corps headquarters which ran Ifor, the "implementation force" in Bosnia last year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But such fears are probably exaggerated. Every <font size=-1>NATO</font> country--bar Greece and Turkey--has been cutting the strength of its forces. These days the best way to impress one's <font size=-1>NATO</font> partners is to provide big contributions to multilateral forces like that in Bosnia. Keeping hundreds of tanks in Germany is no longer so important.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The argument over armour cannot be separated from the argument over Germany. Britain's armoured division in Germany, with its equipment and 26,000 soldiers, costs the British taxpayer &#163;1.35 billion a year but serves little military purpose. In any case, if the Russians suddenly invaded, British attack helicopters--which may be more effective than tanks at stopping tanks--could support <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s defence. The short-term costs of repatriating a division would be considerable, but in the long run it would be cheaper to keep soldiers in Britain than in Germany. Some senior Labour figures want the army out of Germany.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One reason why the army is keen to stay is the paucity of barracks and training areas in Britain. If the division did return to Britain, many of its tanks would have to train overseas, creating extra costs. Thus many generals are convinced--probably rightly--that quitting Germany would in practice mean pruning the armoured regiments.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the biggest reason for staying in Germany, according to the defence establishment, is political. Britain's presence is a symbol of its commitment to the collective defence of Europe. The Germans want the British to stay--and not only because of their spending power. They have a visceral belief that defence should be multinational, and were thus annoyed by France's recent decision to withdraw its army from Germany. Even more important, the Americans will want Britain to stay. If Britain quits Germany, America will be the only country with foreign troops on German soil, and Congress may be less willing to maintain that commitment.
<br></p><p><b><b>Countless questions</b>
</b><br>The answers to the questions about armoured power and Germany will depend, to some extent, on the government's view of Russia. While it poses little threat today, could it be a menace in 20 years? It is probably too early to be sure that its government would be peaceful. Russia's nuclear arsenal and its warplanes will remain formidable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If Britain wants a fighter that can beat the likes of the Su-35, it will need something as capable as the Eurofighter. The present government plans to order 230, at a cost of &#163;10 billion (&#163;4 billion has already been spent on development). Labour would not cancel Eurofighter and buy a cheaper American alternative because that would destroy British jobs and damage Britain's ability to make advanced fighters in the future. But a Labour government might want fewer than 230. The Germans, after all, are buying only 180 Eurofighters. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On a range of other procurement decisions, Labour's policy is likely to be similar to the Tories': an uneasy compromise between attempts to save money through putting contracts out to international tender, and the desire to preserve manufacturing jobs and expertise in Britain.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour would have to decide whether to replace the ageing Tornado bombers with a new aircraft. Options now under study include the purchase of America's planned Joint Strike Fighter and the conversion of Eurofighter into a bomber--although neither would give the <font size=-1>RAF</font> an aircraft with the range it wants. There will probably not be enough money to develop a new bomber from scratch. It is not self-evident that Britain needs a long-range bomber, now that the navy is installing Tomahawk cruise missiles in submarines.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Britain's three small aircraft carriers--and the Harrier planes they carry--will be at the end of their working lives before the next decade is out. Because of the long lead times needed for building carriers, the next government will probably have to decide what sort, if any, it requires. Some analysts believe carriers redundant, on account of their vulnerability to cruise missiles. However the navy sees them as ideal vehicles for military operations far from Britain's shores. It would like to buy larger carriers and hopes to fly a version of America's Joint Strike Fighter from them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The navy will have its work cut out to convince Labour that all of its 35 frigates and destroyers are required. It will argue that the projection of power to distant climes is an increasingly relevant capability, and that surface ships are therefore more necessary than ever. But a lot of them were built to chase Soviet submarines that are no longer threatening. Many analysts believe that 25 frigates and destroyers would be ample for Britain's needs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The navy has a dozen nuclear-powered attack submarines, and the government is due to award &#163;1.25 billion-worth of contracts to replace the three oldest. One of their prime roles, the protection of the four nuclear-missile Trident submarines, appears less urgent these days. Labour may well conclude that Britain could get by with fewer--and thus forego new ones.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One of the navy's arguments for maintaining the size of its fleet is that it needs to be present in East Asia. As a signatory of the Five Power Defence Arrangement (with Singapore, Malaysia, Australia and New Zealand) Britain has moral but not legal obligations to help defend those countries. The navy often takes part in joint exercises with their fleets. Defence agreements with Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates and Qatar, as well as close military ties with Saudi Arabia, do--unlike the Five Power Defence Arrangement--bring the bonus of lucrative arms contracts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The navy hopes to find a new role for some frigates by fitting them with anti-ballistic missile radars and interceptors. The present government, having reviewed the danger of ballistic missiles to troops overseas and to the civilian population, has been promising to announce a policy on missile defence since last year. A Labour government would have to take awkward and perhaps costly decisions on this threat.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour's defence review would certainly scrutinise Britain's capacity to wage amphibious warfare--that is, to mount an opposed landing from the sea. Last year the government ordered two new amphibious landing platforms--designed to carry men, equipment and landing craft--for a cost of &#163;450m. But some senior figures within the Ministry of Defence argue that modern missiles make Normandy-style landings too risky to undertake. They would buy helicopter-carriers instead of the platforms.
<br>The army may try to make a case for increasing its current strength of 110,000. Given both the likelihood that peacekeepers will remain in great demand, and the Labour Party's strong commitment to the <font size=-1>UN</font>, the army should perhaps employ more infantrymen and engineers. Some of the army's senior officers would like to reduce the number of territorial regiments. These reserves have provided specialists such as doctors to serve in Bosnia. But most of the territorials serve no military purpose and they cost &#163;320m a year. Any attack on the territorials would prove controversial, for they have powerful defenders among backbenchers in the House of Commons.
<br></p><p><b><b>The way we were</b>
</b><br>The Labour leadership, busy with more pressing subjects than defence, appears not to have realised how many minefields surround the review. For a fundamental review might well conclude that Britain could remain a medium-sized, internationally active military power, and yet still spend substantially less on defence. In the opinion of Bradford University's Malcolm Chalmers, "Britain could reduce the defence budget by 15-20% &#91;&#163;3 billion-4 billion&#93; over six years, and yet still remain a military power comparable to France." Even a senior Ministry of Defence official admits that savings of &#163;1 billion should be feasible over three to four years. If Labour is prepared to embrace bold options, the service chiefs will be up in arms. The Tories would certainly back the generals--and defence could become a contentious political issue, just like in the old days.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
