<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width="231" height="24" alt="Britain in Brief" border=0></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<p><b>March of progress</b> &nbsp; The North Commission, which was set up in response to violence during last summer's marching season in Northern Ireland, called for the creation of an independent Parades Commission to adjudicate on disputes over Protestant marches through nationalist areas.
<p><br><b>Food for thought</b> &nbsp; The government said it would appoint an independent food-safety adviser, in an attempt to restore public confidence following the scare over mad-cow disease and a recent outbreak of food poisoning in Scotland, caused by <i>E. coli</i> bacteria.
<p><br><b>Hazard warning</b> &nbsp; Toyota, a Japanese-owned car maker, which has a large factory in Derbyshire, said it might switch its future European investment away from Britain if it did not join a single European currency. 
<p><br><b>No refuge</b> &nbsp; The government said 14 of the 16 asylum seekers who went on hunger strike at Rochester Prison, Kent, had exhausted the appeals process and would be returned to their home countries. One of the protesters ended his hunger strike, but a further six started to refuse fluids as well as food.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><br><b>Blunderbus</b> &nbsp; A panel of government advisers said the privatisation of Britain's bus system had led to an increase in the disorganisation, expense and inconvenience of bus travel.
<p><br><b>Holocaust gag</b> &nbsp; Michael Gapes, a Labour <font size=-1>MP</font>, proposed a measure to outlaw denials of the Holocaust. Tony Blair, the Labour leader, said there was "a very strong case" for such a law.
<p><br><b>Run aground</b> &nbsp; Police and contractors cleared a camp of anti-roads activists from the new route of the A30 at Fairmile in Devon. But two protesters continued to hold out in an underground tunnel system.
<p><br><b>In a pickle</b> &nbsp; A food depot at Chepstow in Wales conducted elaborate tests to see whether spilt Branston pickle could cause a forklift truck to spin out of control, after a worker claimed to have been injured that way.

</td></tr></table></center>
