<html><head><title>Cut and paste</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Demergers and acquisitions
<h1>Cut and paste</h1>

</b></p><p><b>For all their complexity, markets can be simple-minded. Companies soon</b></p> <p><b>learn to give themselves a clear label if they want to please investors</b></p>
<br>LONG ago, in the 1970s and 1980s, markets admired the company that could stretch its brand and managerial flair across everything from widget-making to catering. Those days are gone. Woe betide the company that now tries to straddle the fences with which the capital markets are partitioned. As January drew to a close, the fashion for focus swept through PepsiCo, a maker of fizzy drinks and crunchy snacks, and on to Hilton Hotels. Depth, rather than breadth--sticking to lasts rather than spreading wings--is what investors crave. 
<br>Surrendering to the logic that says that running restaurants is not like making food and drink, and that the two are best kept separate, PepsiCo announced on January 23rd that it would spin off its sizeable fast-food business. The business has three main chains, Pizza Hut, Taco Bell and <font size=-1>KFC</font> (once called Kentucky Fried Chicken), and had revenues of $11.3 billion in 1995, more than a third of PepsiCo's $30.4 billion total revenues. Its share of operating profits, however, was closer to a quarter: $867m out of a total of $3.67 billion. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For Wall Street, the demerger is a relief. It likes to assess restaurant businesses by their cash flows, whereas packaged goods such as drinks and snacks are gauged by their earnings. Analysts tend to be either restaurant specialists or food and drink experts. They found it more of a headache to work out how well PepsiCo was doing than to assess Coca-Cola, Pepsi's great rival for fizzy drinks, or McDonald's, both famously single-minded companies. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The same monomaniacal urge--driving firms to unite, this time, rather than divide--lies behind Hilton Hotels' offer on January 27th to spend $6.5 billion on buying <font size=-1>ITT</font>, which owns the rival Sheraton hotel chain, a takeover that would create the world's biggest hotel and gambling group. <font size=-1>ITT</font> is itself one of the fragments of a big bang in June 1995, when a much larger <font size=-1>ITT</font>, with an annual turnover of $25.2 billion, split itself three ways, into an insurance company, an industrial manufacturer, and the future target of today's Hilton bid. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That break-up had symbolic power, as the old <font size=-1>ITT</font> had been a darling of management theory in the 1960s and 1970s, amassing disparate businesses into a huge conglomerate. Coincidentally, this week also sees the beginning of the final chapter of the demerger of Hanson, the British conglomerate which succeeded <font size=-1>ITT</font> in the 1980s as a model of diversified business, but which has spent the 1990s taking itself apart again. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When conglomerates were in vogue, there were two main arguments for them. First, they allowed managers to draw off cash from well-established parts of their firm and feed them into riskier operations with greater potential. Second, they were insulated from the business cycle: one part of the company might be being battered, but another part in an unconnected business would be doing well enough to carry the group through the rough patch.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Neither argument holds much sway any more. The first has been demolished by the growth of global capital markets. Investors today want to decide for themselves which new businesses to speculate in, and what share of their money to invest in stable cash-generators, rather than leave this decision to some mogul. And, as business cycles have moderated since the roller-coaster 1970s, the second argument has come to seem less important. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For all that, it is not clear that PepsiCo's shareholders will gain much extra value through having a stake in a separate restaurant business. Restaurants face tough competition in the United States, where PepsiCo has most of its businesses, and where fast-food shops have sprouted on every block. Besides, part of PepsiCo's original reason for buying restaurants was to gain distribution channels for its drinks. Although the terms of the spin-off will probably ensure that Pepsi is still favoured over Coke, too many restrictions on the restaurants will make it harder for the new company to thrive. So PepsiCo will lose one valuable aspect of restaurant ownership. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, Andrew Conway, an analyst at Morgan Stanley, argues that Pepsi should have sold Frito-Lay, its snack-food division, rather than the restaurants. The snacks business is a booming operation that made profits of $1.4 billion on sales of $8.5 billion in 1995--so it is fully capable of thriving on its own, or of attracting buyers. By spinning it off and by selling the stodgy American bottling division of its drinks business, Pepsi could have released more value for shareholders and still reduced the number of businesses for its bosses to concentrate on, another goal urged by demerger enthusiasts. 
<br></p><p><b><b>Focus, please</b>
</b><br>Hilton's move is less controversial. The hotel industry is consolidating, as global brands start to capitalise on the advantages of international marketing and computerised reservation systems. Stephen Bollenbach, Hilton's boss, is a zealous deal-maker. In his first year in charge he has already spent $3 billion buying up Bally's casinos; struck a deal with Ladbroke, a British company which owns the Hilton International name outside America, to reunite the hotel chain worldwide; and spent a further $500m on other hotels.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As it happens, Mr Bollenbach will still have to decide what to do with some extra <font size=-1>ITT</font> businesses that were tidied away into the hotel group in the 1995 split--some sports teams and a few publishing operations. They may need to be spun or sold or spliced into something else.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It undoubtedly makes sense for a company to grow in an area in which it has expertise. But arbitrarily restricting operations to one of the categories into which analysts like to sort firms can sometimes limit opportunities. The stockmarket's love of simplicity betrays its own imperfections. Its sheer size means that investors, advisers, and even whole institutions can know about only a small part of the global capital market: indeed, that is why they partition it. Pepsi will certainly look tidier after it clears away the fast food. But, by choosing the easy option, it may not in fact have hit on the healthiest diet. 
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?854758800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
