<html><head><title>Fads on wheels</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Japanese cars
<h1>Fads on wheels</h1>

</b></p><font size=1>TOKYO AND NAGOYA
</font><p>IT IS the typography of Honda's new <font size=-1>S-MX</font> that gives the game away. The <font size=-1>M</font>, turned on its side, resembles an <font size=-1>E</font>. But even without a name that looks remarkably like <font size=-1>SEX</font>, the car's dark windows show what Honda expects its customers to use it for. The seats fold down to make a double bed and, the marketing blurb helpfully points out, there is a handy place to store tissues. Unsurprisingly, Honda sold 15,000 of these motorised boudoirs in the first two weeks after their launch in mid November. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The success of the <font size=-1>S-MX</font> illustrates how rapidly the Japanese car market is changing. Standard saloon cars are losing their popularity as Japanese consumers turn to recreational vehicles (<font size=-1>RV</font>s) in ever greater numbers. But different sorts of <font size=-1>RV</font>s are proliferating. The winners in this segmenting market have been companies, such as Toyota and Honda, that have launched the most new models. The losers have been the other domestic manufacturers and foreign car makers. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The popularity of <font size=-1>RV</font>s is growing in most big countries, but in Japan it has been phenomenal. The definition of what constitutes an <font size=-1>RV</font> is a bit vague (in Honda's case, it includes a procreational vehicle) but the term seems to include any car that is not a coup&eacute; or a saloon. So the numbers call for caution. Nevertheless, the growth in the <font size=-1>RV</font> market has been eye-catching (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>). Last year <font size=-1>RV</font>s accounted for 45% of Toyota's and more than half of Honda's car sales.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why are they so popular? Partly, perhaps, because they provide the cramped Japanese with an extra room--be it lounge or bedroom. In addition, says Susumu Uchikawa, Toyota's head of domestic sales, Japanese consumers are increasingly choosing their cars according to their lifestyles. Last year Honda launched, among others, cars targeted at women, the elderly and the rich in their late 30s or 40s.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And, yes, <font size=-1>RV</font>s are popular because they are "cool". Mitsubishi's Pajero is rugged enough to cope with the great outdoors. Yet few of those being driven around the streets of Tokyo are likely to see a speck of mud. The brochure for the <font size=-1>CR-V</font>, a sort of jeep introduced by Honda last October, sports a cowboy leaning on his car against a backdrop of tower blocks--an urban cowboy if ever there was one. The car has become a fashion accessory.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To keep up with fashion means, says Matthew Ruddick, an analyst at <font size=-1>HSBC</font> James Capel, a stockbroker, carving niches in a crowded market. Launching lots of models helps. Last year Toyota launched 11 models (many of them <font size=-1>RV</font>s), compared with eight models the year before and six in 1991. It expects to introduce at least as many models this year as last. This, and an aggressive marketing campaign, helped the firm to claw its way back to a one-third share of Japan's car market at the end of last year. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Honda, too, has been bringing out new models by the trunkful. Last year it introduced seven new or completely remodelled cars, compared with three the year before. In October, the company overtook Mitsubishi as Japan's third-largest carmaker. Both Mitsubishi and Nissan, the second-largest, launched fewer models. Mazda managed just one--and its share of the market slipped to around 4.5%. Henry Wallace, Mazda's newish and <i>gaijin</i> (foreign) president, says that the company must come out with new products and do so more quickly than in the past.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Fickle fashion has been unkind to foreign car makers. Their share of the Japanese market, after rising strongly for several years, slid from almost 10% in June to just over 7% in November, although it blipped up in December. A weak yen has not helped: since the beginning of 1996, the yen has declined 13% against the dollar, making imported cars more expensive. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But there is a more fundamental problem: foreign cars are not designed for the Japanese market. The Japanese buy <font size=-1>BMW</font>, Mercedes and Porsche for snob value, but American cars hold little cachet. Between them, the big three American manufacturers sell only a couple of <font size=-1>RV</font>s in Japan. Most of their offerings are saloon cars. Small wonder that in December the three American car makers between them sold 3,913 cars--barely 1% of the market. Still, it would be strange if another trade row erupted partly because American car firms had failed to design a love hotel on wheels.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?854758800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="fn6559.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>
1997 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>

