<html><head><title>Watch your step</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/fn.gif" width="360" height="26" alt="Finance and Economics" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Watch your step</h1>

<font size=1>CHICAGO
</font><p>COMMON wisdom has it that futures trading is best done by a lot of screaming people jammed together in a pit. Economists call it a "continuous double auction" and it is widely regarded as the most efficient way of matching buyers with sellers. But in practice, of course, the process might not work that smoothly. Witness the rancour at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange (<font size=-1>CME</font>), where in elections on January 16th a quarrel over floor practices led to a heap of directors being dumped.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The trouble centres on floor brokers, whose job it is to buy and sell contracts for clients. Increasingly, they have been clubbing together to share profits. But the "broker associations" have been accused of collusion and market domination--not by their clients, but by other traders who complain about the "street gangs in the pits". It was those independent traders who staged the electoral uprising.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Last year regulators renewed investigations into whether the associations inhibit competition. Strictly speaking, any order to the floor should be yelled out in the "auction", so that any trader in the pit can offer a price. The <font size=-1>CME</font>, however, allows 25% of trades to be transacted within an association. That is odd enough in a market supposedly dedicated to obtaining the best price for investors. But competitors charge that association members regularly overstep the limit.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are also complaints that the associations have too much control over the flow of customer orders into the pit. This gives them excessive economic power over independent brokers or people in the pits who are trading for themselves. Last year, in a much discussed case, a trader at the <font size=-1>CME </font>sold his prime spot on the top step of a pit for a whopping $1m. And how did he claim ownership of a spot to which every trader supposedly has an equal right? Tacit rules, influenced by the broker associations, determine who stands where. In this case, those rules turned a piece of common property into a valuable private asset--proving once again that a good trader can make money in any market. 
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?854758800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="st4142.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>
1997 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>

</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT09-B15-189</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA096-001030-B008-452</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.europe.economist.com:80/issue/01-02-97/st4142.html 199.173.162.110 19970215014950 text/html 13123
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 01:45:38 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 30-Jan-97 19:05:35 GMT
Content-length: 12935
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Testing testing</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width="371" height="26" alt="Science and Technology" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Testing testing</h1>

<p><b>Clinical trials are an essential--and expensive--part of drug development. Moves to make them more efficient are welcome news for patients and pharmaceutical companies alike</b></p>
<br>IN DEVELOPING a new drug, there are few quick fixes. First, an original design has to be dreamed up. Then its potential needs to be demonstrated in test tubes and laboratory animals. After that it must go through three separate phases of clinical trial on human guinea pigs to show that it is safe, and that it does what it is supposed to do. Only then will patients start to get better, and the money begin to roll in.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For drug developers, half of the waiting--and the paying--lies in those trials. In America it takes, on average, $86m and just over nine years to go from the first human tests of a substance to final regulatory approval. Figures from Europe are similar. And for every five compounds entering the initial stages of human testing, only one will cross the finishing line into the market.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The consequences of failure can be stark, particularly for smaller companies. This January the share price of Regeneron Pharmaceuticals, a biotechnology firm based in Tarrytown, New York, fell 43% in one day when clinical trials showed that its main product--brain-derived neurotrophic factor--did not work as a treatment for Lou Gehrig's disease (a degenerative neuromuscular disorder). Now the health of Regeneron, as well as that of the participants in the trials, is in doubt.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Speeding up the testing and approval process, thus enabling the duds to be dropped more quickly, would help both people and companies--as long as it could be done without compromising safety.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until recently, America's Food and Drug Administration (<font size=-1>FDA</font>)--the federal organisation that gives new drugs the go-ahead--was famous both for its stringency and for its slowness. By the late 1980s it was taking over two and a half years, on average, to trawl through all the data from the clinical trials of a drug before approving it (see <a href="$link next.html chart"></a>). 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For some drugs it was worse. New cancer medicines would often reach British patients almost three years before they got to their American counterparts. Certain respiratory drugs were available in Britain more than half a decade before American doctors were allowed to use them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The justification for this was thoroughness. But there is little evidence that Britain was courting more risks by being swifter. Indeed, a study by Kenneth Kaitin of Tufts University in Boston, and his colleagues, found that the recall rates of drugs after they had been approved for sale were only slightly higher in Britain (4%) than in America (3%).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Things improved somewhat after 1989 as a result of special "fast-track" rules that had been introduced for <font size=-1>AIDS</font> drugs. Then, in 1992, Congress gave the <font size=-1>FDA</font> five years to speed up its act across the board, and the power to collect more than $300m from drug companies to help in this. The money has been used to computerise the system (until a pilot study in 1994, applications had to be sent in as bundles of papers) and to hire 600 new reviewers. This seems to have worked. Computerisation alone has cut 11 months from the approval process, and in 1996 the agency passed almost twice as many new compounds as it had done in 1995, with an average review time of only 20 months.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is a good start. But no amount of bureaucratic reform will make the trials themselves any faster. If anything, recent pressure has been the other way. The diseases being tackled today are no longer simple infections whose course runs for a few days or weeks, but complex, long-term ailments such as Alzheimer's and atherosclerosis. According to Joseph DiMasi, a health-care economist who also works at Tufts, new drugs approved by the <font size=-1>FDA</font> in 1994-95 spent an average of 7.7 years in trials on people--more than twice as long as such tests took in the 1960s, and a year longer even than they took in the early 1990s.
<br></p><p><b><b>Fast-track, false trail?</b>
</b><br>There may, however, be a faster way. Traditional trials have relied on clinical end-points--clear signs of medical efficacy or a lack of it. You get better, you get worse, you live longer, or you die sooner than people on existing treatments or on no treatment at all. Now, more reliance is being placed on "surrogate" end-points--biological markers that may be able to predict how a patient will fare. In the past four years, surrogate end-points have been used by the <font size=-1>FDA</font> to approve 25 new drugs for life-threatening diseases such as <font size=-1>AIDS</font> and cancer. The new rules have led to rapid trials for drugs such as the new anti-<font size=-1>AIDS</font> protease inhibitors. Saquinavir, the first of these, took less than three years to test and under 100 days to approve.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Surrogate end-points tend to be bodily changes that can be measured easily in a test tube or a clinic. Some anti-cancer drugs, for example, have been approved in the past ten months because they are able to slow down the growth of tumours, not because they have a proven ability to prolong patients' lives. Better understanding of how cancers develop has allowed the response of the tumour to speak, as it were, for the whole patient, and thus to persuade the <font size=-1>FDA</font> to approve drugs before their clinical usefulness is established beyond doubt. The agency does, however, require a manufacturer to come up with this proof eventually if its drug is to stay on the market.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Using surrogate end-points has certainly speeded up trials. It has also allowed trials to be more flexible: since survival is no longer the bottom line, it is possible to include those who are a little further from death's door when a trial starts. Though simple to measure, however, surrogate end-points are not always easy to accept. This is particularly true in the controversial world of <font size=-1>AIDS</font>. Some drugs designed to slow down the disease, such as dd<font size=-1>C</font>, were approved in the early 1990s because they were able to maintain levels of <font size=-1>CD</font>4 immune cells in people's bloodstreams. Since these cells are prime targets for <font size=-1>HIV</font> (the virus that causes <font size=-1>AIDS</font>) it was thought that such cell counts could reliably predict the clinical outcome of the disease. The more <font size=-1>CD</font>4 cells a patient had, the longer, it was presumed, he would live. But this is not always so, as later research has shown. So now there is another surrogate--viral load. How much a drug lowers the number of virus particles in the blood ought, on the face of much laboratory research, to be a good indicator of future health. But it is not yet formally proved, a fact that troubles many <font size=-1>AIDS</font> activists.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such surrogate short-cuts are useful for dangerous diseases, where the desperation of patients and a lack of alternative treatments outweigh the risk of a new compound being approved before its time. But they are not so easily applied to most new drugs--those destined for the thousands of less serious woes that flesh is heir to. Here the balance between safety and speed is different, and disagreement stronger. <font size=-1>P</font>h<font size=-1>RMA</font>, the American pharmaceutical industry's trade association, thinks that far more potions should be given rapid nods: treatments for heart disease, arthritis and strokes, at least, should join the list. But no regulatory agency or drug firm wants the blame for another thalidomide tragedy.
<br></p><p><b><b>Less haste, more speed</b>
</b><br>Still, subtle changes in clinical trials can smooth the way for less spectacular remedies. Much time and money is wasted in unnecessary and uninformative tests. According to a continuing study by the Centre for Drug Development Science at Georgetown University in Washington, <font size=-1>DC</font>, the average new drug submitted for <font size=-1>FDA</font> approval in 1994-95 ran the gauntlet of almost 70 tests. Up to a third of these tests, however, were rejected by the agency on scientific grounds. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is a curious lapse on the part of drug companies. Being sent back to the drawing board is a costly journey to make. Much of a firm's revenue will come from being the first or second on to the market with a new compound. Finishing even third hardly warrants having run the race. Some of this lost time is being made up by better communication between drug makers and the <font size=-1>FDA</font> in the early stages of clinical development, so that companies know exactly what will be expected of their drug on the day of judgment. And better ways of collecting and processing the data also help. According to Hugh McDade, head of European antiviral clinical research at Glaxo Wellcome--Britain's biggest drug company--his firm's new computer system has made research more efficient simply by cutting the proportion of data that needs "cleaning" from 30% to 1%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But tests can also be made more effective by asking the right questions from the beginning. Carl Peck, director of the Georgetown Centre, believes that even early trials (the first and second phases, when a drug is tested on small numbers of volunteers to see if a big trial is justified) could be milked for a lot of extra information if they were designed better. He says that they should be looking for more than just a rough connection between the highest dose of a drug that can be taken on board and its beneficial or harmful effects. Studying how different doses spread out into tissues, how long they linger in the blood, and the sort of encounters they have while travelling through the body yields information that can be used to build computer simulations of clinical trials.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Early attempts at simulation borrowed software from the engineering and aerospace industries. Now three companies--<font size=-1>MGA</font> in Boston, Pharsight in Palo Alto, California and <font size=-1>SCI</font> in Apex, North Carolina--are offering simulation programs specially designed for clinical trials. Depending on the class of compound they are testing, drug developers can begin to understand how changing a range of variables--such as the doses tested, the number of patients enrolled, or the number of drop-outs--will affect the outcome of a trial. All these inter-related factors would be far too expensive and time-consuming to test in a real clinic.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such simulations are not intended to replace human testing, any more than the computer models used to test aircraft are a substitute for real flight. Rather, they allow a drug developer to design the best trial to give its product the most effective run for its money. This is particularly important in the third phase of the clinical-trial process--the costly point where a drug is tested on hundreds, thousands or even tens of thousands of subjects. Companies cannot afford to make mistakes at this stage, especially since two such trials, carried out independently of each other, are usually demanded by the <font size=-1>FDA</font> as proof of a compound's real worth.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tools like trial simulations are still in their infancy. But their potential to streamline things is considerable. And they have a bonus. In virtual reality, unlike the real reality found in clinics, nobody gets hurt when things go wrong.
<br>
<br>
