<html><head><title>Knowledge or certainty?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width="371" height="26" alt="Science and Technology" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Knowledge or certainty?</h1>

WHAT'S in a name? A great deal, apparently, if the subject in question is experimenting on people. When America's Advisory Committee on Human Radiation Experiments (<font size=-1>ACHRE</font>) asked 1,800 patients recently what they thought of human medical experiments, the answer was clear: they were against them. Such experiments were thought of as highly risky and potentially harmful. If the term "clinical trials" was used instead of "experiments", however, the same group voted in favour of them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Clinical trials, it seems, are now seen by potential subjects, particularly in America, not as the risky medical experiments that they are, but as a short-cut to the latest treatment. This enthusiasm certainly makes the job of testing new drugs easier. But it also brings questions. For, though more stringent tests on cell cultures and animals mean that the chance of a really dangerous drug slipping through the net into human trials is minimal, a test drug is guaranteed neither to be better than existing treatment, nor to have no harmful long-term side effects.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Robert Levine, a clinical-trials specialist at Yale University, says that people stopped seeing trials as a source of risk and started seeing them as a potential benefit when the anti-<font size=-1>AIDS</font> drug <font size=-1>AZT</font> started tests in the early 1980s. <font size=-1>AIDS</font> patients--often supported by their doctors--queued, clamoured and sometimes cheated their way into trials, desperate to try out this experimental compound.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Given that <font size=-1>AIDS</font> is fatal, and no other treatment existed, this was understandable.<b> </b>But basing a general principle on the peculiar circumstances surrounding <font size=-1>AIDS</font> is dangerous. Today, such is the flood of new drugs to be tested and the rising tide of confidence in their powers, that enthusiasm for clinical trials is spilling over into other patient groups.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ruth Faden, a bioethicist at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore, is the chairman of <font size=-1>ACHRE</font>. She is one of many researchers who fear that doctors are overselling the benefits of trials to their patients. Although people do not join such trials until they have given their "informed consent", the consent forms have become so complex that few read them through to the end. And both doctors and the institutions they work for have a stake in a trial being large and successful. The doctor wants his name on the research paper and the institution wants the glory (and money) that running trials brings.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact, shopping for a chance to join a trial has become as easy as dialling a telephone number or visiting a few handy websites on the Internet. In America alone, over 2,500 clinical trials are clamouring for subjects. They offer potential remedies for almost every affliction, complete with user-friendly descriptions, eligibility criteria and contact details.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Several countries are attempting to tidy up this state of affairs. In November 1996 the Council of Europe adopted a Convention on Human Rights and Biomedicine designed to ensure ethical medical practice (including tight controls on trials) in member states. In Canada, a new "Code of Conduct for Research Involving Humans" is raising hackles among the country's academics; subjects who withdraw in mid-trial can also "withdraw" their data if they feel they were tricked into joining the trial in the first place. And America's National Bioethics Advisory Committee has just begun the task of revamping institutional review boards, consent procedures and other safeguards for the "well-being, autonomy and privacy" of patient-subjects. A reaction, it seems, has set in.
<br>
<br>
