<html><head><title>Burchfield's modern English usage</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/mo.gif" width="157" height="26" alt="Moreover" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>
<b>JOHNSON</b>
<h1>Burchfield's modern English usage</h1>

THE winners of our Christmas crossword have recently opened their prizes: not least, copies of Oxford University Press's new version of "Fowler's Modern English Usage"*, edited by R.W. Burchfield. And if, like Johnson, they are addicts--if not always adherents--of the original Fowler they may have had a shock. Is this the Fowler they have known and loved since 1926? It is not.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Not that they should complain. If anyone, Mr Burchfield, for years chief editor of the Oxford English dictionaries, might do that. For though the name Fowler may sell books, this, in reality, is Burchfield's modern English usage.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some of its quirks are pure Fowler, such as the citation of three entire <i>sonnets</i> to illustrate that word. But most are Mr Burchfield's own: an entry, for instance, on <i>epistemic modality</i> (come again) or a remark on Britain's shrinking number of Christian sabbath-keepers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The result--like its original--is a curate's egg. Strangely, Mr Burchfield calls Fowler's discussion of <i>literary words</i> outdated, observing that nowadays few words are barred from fine writing--which is true, but in no way whatever invalidates Fowler's discussion of those words that are confined to it. His entry on supposedly ambiguous uses of <i>too</i> is almost pure Fowler, and it is tosh; that on <i>irrelevant allusion</i> owes not a word to Fowler's ponderous page on that topic, and is the better for it. His entry on phrases like <I>women's having the vote </I> (as against <I>women</I>...) shines with both common sense and nicety of judgment, where Fowler mainly froths. And his discussion of what he calls <i>sentence adverbs</i> such as the much derided <i>hopefully</i> (whose use this way is too recent even to figure in Fowler) deserves to become a classic mind-broadener for those, like Johnson, who do the deriding.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As with the original Fowler, at times you could wish for more: it is odd to cite past use of <i>they </i>and <i>their</i> as singular pronoun/adjective without a hint (in that entry) that its recent wildfire spread owes so much to feminist correctness. In contrast, Mr Burchfield makes neatly the subtle distinction between <i>politics</i> as a singular noun and a plural; a pity he did not do the same for <i>economics</i> (which <i>is </i>a dismal science, albeit <i>the economics</i> of writing textbooks on it <i>are </i>attractive). 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Justly, Mr Burchfield hopes the 1926 Fowler will long remain in print. But his own book has a far stronger claim to be called a "dictionary of usage" than Fowler had. Henry Fowler--68 when his work was first published--used that phrase, but in fact he was consciously steering his readers, and his guiding star was the English of a classically educated public-school Briton of his day. Mr Burchfield is less prescriptive, readier (though not over-ready) merely to describe, with all the resources, not least the electronics, of Oxford and of modern lexicography to aid him. Notably, he also takes American English into account, as Fowler did not purport to. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In sum, there is good reason for both books. The 1926 Fowler is already a period piece, though no one has ever gone wrong by taking its advice. The same, no doubt, will in time be true of "Burchfield"--as, perhaps, by 2097 the publisher of its latest revision will dare to call it. Johnson will stick shamelessly to his old friend: it is less useful, more fun, and, in both senses, less weighty.
<br>
<br><font size=-1>* 864 pages, 16.99 and $25.</font>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?854758800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
