<html><head><title>NATO goes a-wooing</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>

<h1 align=center>NATO goes a-wooing</h1>


FROM Tallinn to Tirana, from Vancouver to Vladivostok, the hope everywhere as the cold war ended was for a Europe "whole and free"--its people, all its people, freedfrom conflict and division and, in Eastern Europe and Russia, free to choose their destiny and to rebuild their economies from the ruins of communism. Some have done better than others. Nowhere has it been easy. But dismantling the iron curtain gave easterners the chance to share in the greater wealth and stability of Western Europe. Now there is a worry that what is in store is not peace and opportunity all round, but a "new Yalta". That is shorthand for a new division of Europe between Russia and the West--if not into armed camps, then into rival spheres of influence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Irked by <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s plans to start taking in new members, Russian officials have for months been growling about"counter-measures". In an effort to reduce the growing tension, talks opened this week in Moscow to try to establish a new and special <font size=-1>NATO</font>-Russia relationship. The talks will be tough. But even if a deal can be struck--and that is by no means certain--those easterners not among the first <font size=-1>NATO</font>-joiners fear they will be left with the breath of a grouchy and unpredictable Russia on their neck.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since there can be no going back--to abandon long-standing promises because of a Russian tantrum would bust the alliance--<font size=-1>NATO</font>'s enlargement will start, as planned, after a special summit in July. The new members, all being well, could be in by 1999. But, if enlarging <font size=-1>NATO</font> to admit the Poles, Czechs and Hungarians (to name the front-runners) is to add to Europe's security, rather than diminish it, Russia's legitimate concerns need to be addressed. And just as important in avoiding a division of Europe into a western "us" and a Russia-centred "them" will be finding ways to reassure the countries in between.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If Russia is ready to strike a deal, there is plenty on offer. <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s glue remains the commitment of its members to treat an attack on one as an attack on all. That is why countries such as Poland, in the past shoved about all over the map, have clamoured to join. But <font size=-1>NATO</font> has already cut down its clanking cold-war armies into much smaller, get-up-and-go forces that, as in Bosnia, can form the nucleus of broader European efforts to promote peacekeeping rather than war-making. Indeed, the Bosnian operation has already brought Russian officers right into the heart of <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s military planning.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Meanwhile, recognising that a larger <font size=-1>NATO</font>, albeit one with smaller forces, was bound to make Russia feel crowded, the alliance announced last year that it had no plans to put either bases or nuclear weapons on the territory of new members. Work is starting to rejig the treaty on conventional forces in Europe more to Russia's liking. Deeper cuts in nuclear weapons may also be in prospect. But so far Russia has pocketed all this poker-faced. What it really wants is a right of co-decision--diplomat-speak for a veto.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That would be going too far. <font size=-1>NATO</font> is a defence alliance of like-minded countries that needs to be able to act in the interests of its members, whether those interests are threatened in Europe or beyond. Russia is a continent-sized power with interests of its own. Even with the best will in the world, the two are unlikely always to see eye to eye. What <font size=-1>NATO</font> is ready to offer, however, is an unprecedented special relationship that will include Russia in <font size=-1>NATO</font> discussions on a wide range of common concerns, from peacekeeping to nuclear proliferation. Not a veto, certainly, but exploited co-operatively this new <font size=-1>NATO</font>-Russia council could help underpin the stability that Europe's fledgling democracies--including Russia's--sorely need.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If there is a danger in <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s offer to Russia, it lies in the neglect not of Russia's interests, but of those of the smaller fry. That danger is all the greater since <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s first enlargement may well be its last for a long time. Taking in the first newcomers will be time-consuming and costly. Each one needs agreement from all 16 (soon perhaps 19 or 20) parliaments. And defence guarantees, if they are to stick, should not be given lightly. Indeed, if <font size=-1>NATO</font> is to operate effectively, then it is probably unrealistic to expect it to expand much more at all. In which case, what about other countries with security worries, including the Baltic states and Ukraine?
<br></p><p><b><b>Partners or rivals?</b>
</b><br><font size=-1>NATO</font> is not Europe's cavalry. It cannot right every wrong, protect every minority or guarantee every border, nor should it. But it can help avoid creating the sort of security vacuums that in Europe have always spelled trouble. Its "partnerships for peace", at first ridiculed as an empty gesture, have already become a valuable vacuum-filler for countries that choose to make good use of them, for instance, by honing peacekeeping skills and learning how to keep generals under civilian control. But if they are to thrive and expand, these partnerships will need more cash.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Stretching the edges of <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s security blanket, however, can do only so much. Other organisations--Europe hasplenty of them--need to take more of the strain. And since the greatest threat to Europe's struggling democracies comesfrom the sheer difficulty of pushing on with reform, for many countries it is the prospect of eventual membership in the European Union, not <font size=-1>NATO</font>, that could do most good. Unfortunately, however, the <font size=-1>EU</font> is moving at a snail's pace. It is unlikely to take in its first batch of easterners until perhaps 2005, well after <font size=-1>NATO</font>. Sadly, negotiations are not even due to begin for another year. When they do, they should start with as many countries as possible, even if some proceed faster than others. Meanwhile, the <font size=-1>EU</font> could be more imaginative in helping out its "partner" countries--by, for example, opening its markets more generously to their goods.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the end, though, whether or not Europe slips back into old rivalries depends on how Russia now reacts. The offer from <font size=-1>NATO</font> to co-operate in building a more secure and stable Europe is a genuine one. But is Russia ready to leave its lair?
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
