<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Closing time
</h2>(See <a href="bw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>A chain of sushi restaurants collapsed on cue just as <b>Japan's bankruptcies </b>were forecast to rise again toward 1995's record level. The total fell in 1996, but there was the single biggest bankruptcy since the war: the collapse of Sueno Kosan construction. 
<p>Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve, hinted that <b>American interest rates </b> may rise. Robert Rubin, the Treasury secretary, reaffirmed America's wish for a strong dollar. The dollar put in its best performance for years against the yen and <font size=-1>D</font>-mark.
<p><h2>In credit
</h2>America's tenth-biggest bank, Banc One, is set to become America's third-largest issuer of <b>credit cards </b>with the purchase for $7.3 billion of First <font size=-1>USA</font>. But bad debt on credit cards is rising. In declaring otherwise good profits, Citicorp, the country's largest credit-card issuer, and Chase Manhattan reported increased write-offs in that area.
<p><b>Salomon Brothers</b> and <b>Fidelity Investments</b> formed an alliance that will allow equities underwritten by Salomon to be distributed through Fidelity's brokerage operations. Salomon gains access to 1.5m customers and Fidelity, a mutual-funds giant, gets its customers access to Salomon equity research. 
<p>The Italian government gave control of <b>Banco di Napoli</b> to Banca Nazionale del Lavoro and <font size=-1>INA</font>, an Italian insurance group, after the two largely state-owned institutions bid 61.6 billion lire ($38.6m) for 60% of the stricken bank.
<p>The Jewish Anti-Defamation League opened a SFr50,000 ($35,000) Swiss bank account for a guard suspended by his security firm for removing soon-to-be shredded historical documents from the Union Bank of Switzerland. <font size=-1>UBS</font>, which along with other Swiss banks is under pressure to reveal its <b>war-time dealings </b>with the Nazis, admitted it had made a serious error but said other documents had already been shredded.
<p><h2>The sky's the limit
</h2>Boeing dropped plans to build a 550-seater aircraft, citing lack of demand. But Europe's Airbus carried on with its plans for a <b>superjumbo</b> by bringing Belairbus of Belgium and Fokker Aviation of the Netherlands into the initial study.
<p>As expected, Raytheon bought <b>Hughes Electronics</b> from General Motors for $9.5 billion. The deal will put Raytheon behind only Lockheed Martin and Boeing in America's restructured defence industry.
<p>Britain still excels at attracting inward investment. Days after Ford said it was cutting 1,300 jobs at its Halewood plant, <b>Nissan</b>, Japan's second-largest car maker, said it would invest a further &#163;215m ($356m) in Britain to allow production of a third car model for the European market. The expansion will create 800 jobs in Sunderland and another 4,000 jobs for Nissan's European components suppliers.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>Three of America's eastern <b>railways </b>are battling for dominance. Conrail shareholders scuppered plans for a $9.4 billion merger with <font size=-1>CSX</font>, leaving the way open for Norfolk Southern to pursue its $10.5 billion hostile bid for Conrail.
<p><h2>Daimler reverts
</h2><b>Daimler-Benz</b>, Germany's biggest industrial company, put the finishing touches to a reorganisation restoring its focus on cars. Helmut Werner had already resigned as chairman of Mercedes-Benz after a power struggle with J&uuml;rgen Schrempp (above), the chief executive responsible for the plan to merge Daimler-Benz with Mercedes-Benz, its biggest subsidiary.
<p>In one of Asia's biggest privatisations, two concessions worth a total of $7 billion were awarded to upgrade and run <b>water and sewerage</b> in Manila, the Philippines' capital. The local Ayala group, teamed with America's Bechtel and Britain's Northwest Water, won both. But under the terms of the bid it had to cede one to the next best offer: that of Benpres, a local firm teamed with France's Lyonnaise des Eaux.
<p><b>Olivetti</b>, a troubled Italian telecoms group, agreed the sale of its loss-making <font size=-1>PC</font> unit to Piedmont, a company set up by Centenary, a British industrial-holdings company, and other investors, for 250 billion-300 billion lire ($157m-188m).
<p>Pieter van der Wal resigned as head of <b>Grundig</b> under pressure from unions outraged at his plans to cut a quarter of the electronics firm's jobs and move some production out of Germany.
<p><b>Pharmacia & Upjohn</b>, the world's tenth-biggest drug group, also lost its chief executive. John Zabriskie quit suddenly, a mere 18 months after America's Upjohn and Sweden's Pharmacia came together in a merger, which has produced weak third-quarter results and two profit warnings in the fourth. 
<p>George Simpson, its new managing director, is splitting Britain's <b>General Electric Company</b> into five divisions, sweeping away the structure built by his predecessor, the long-serving Lord Weinstock.
<p>The first shots in a war likely to lead to a big shakeout in Japan's <b>video-game</b> companies have been fired. Sega, the largest arcade-game maker (but behind Nintendo in <font size=-1>TV</font> games), is to absorb Bandai, Japan's top toy maker. The combined firm will have global sales of &#165;600 billion ($5 billion) a year.
<p>Some ideas just catch on. Japan has run out of <b>lovable eggs</b>, an electronic bird which should sell for &#165;1,980 ($16) in the shops but which now fetches 20 times that on the street. The creature grows up if nurtured, and jumps up and down when its droppings are cleared up. But neglect the virtual beast and it wastes away and dies.

</td></tr></table></center>
