<html><head><title>Buddy can you spare a lung?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>

<h1 align=center>Buddy can you spare a lung?</h1>


<p><b>Governments could save lives by being clearer, and less squeamish, about organ transplants</b></p>
<br>IN A typical day, thanks to a shortage of organs available for transplants, ten Americans will die waiting--waiting for a kidney, heart, liver, pancreas or lung. In most other countries the demand for organs also far outstrips the supply. That is one reason why doctors have been tempted into the dangerous business of using animal parts for transplant--and why even modest proposals such as those in America this week to change the rules governing organ allocation tend to becontroversial (see <a href="am3198.html">page</a>). 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And yet there are several promising ways to make more organs available, the simplest of which is merely to promote more vigorously the carrying of donor cards. Most people say they are happy to bequeath their organs after death, but far fewer make these wishes known in a formal way. In many countries a start has recently been made by asking people to state on their driving licences whether they would be willing donors. But more could be done. There is no reason (apart from terrifying their patients) why doctors should not ask people what their wishes are during routine medical checks. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Second, law-makers need to make it clear that people have an absolute right to decide how their organs are used after death. At present, families are allowed to stop doctors from transplanting the organs of people who, when alive, had expressly indicated their wish to be donors. This is as absurd as it would be for relations to reverse a dead person's will. Only in the case of people who die without making their wishes clear should the decision devolve to the next of kin.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A third change is more technical. Some countries are squeamish about keeping organs "alive", even when their owners are brain-dead. In Britain, for example, the introduction of "elective ventilation" (attaching brain-dead people to respirators) doubled organ-harvest rates. In 1994 this was banned on the grounds that English common law prohibited treatment that did not benefit the patient. But elective ventilation is not "treatment" at all. It is a way to implement an individual's wish to make their corpse available in a useful way. Cadavers have been used as a teaching aid since the days of ancient Greece. Why not use them in this way too?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The case for some sort of financial incentive, as mooted recently by Gary Becker, a prominent American economist, is less straightforward. This could well save money, as well as lives; a kidney transplant, which accounts for the great majority of transplants, costs $85,000 less over six years than dialysis. But everything depends on the detail of any scheme. People are justifiably queasy about any policy that might create a market in body organs. And even a scheme under which only governments were allowed, say, to pay families of potential donors to allow organs' use could weaken the principle that the likely wishes of the organs' owner are paramount.
<br></p><p><b><b>Anyone who had a heart . . .</b>
</b><br>None of this is to encourage compulsion. Rather, the point is to establish the right of people to decide for themselves what is to become of their corporeal selves after death. In this respect the Austrian and Belgian practice of "presumed consent"--hospitals may recover organs unless the deceased has explicitly forbidden them to--is a step too far. The state has limited authority to tell its citizens how to treat their bodies before death and should not be allowed to extend that role after it. Organ donation gives individuals a wonderful opportunity to feel that the end of their own life may help to prolong somebody else's. The role of governments is merely to help people to make that choice in a free and timely fashion.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?854154000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
