<DOCHDR>
http://www.europe.economist.com:80/issue/25-01-97/am3198.html 199.173.162.110 19970215015056 text/html 5305
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 01:46:52 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 23-Jan-97 19:03:06 GMT
Content-length: 5118
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Liver spats</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Organ transplants
<h1>Liver spats</h1>

</b></p>ORGANS for transplant are scarce, so how should they be allocated? Back in November, boffins at the United Network for Organ Sharing (<font size=-1>UNOS</font>), the non-profit agency that looks after America's organs under a contract with the federalgovernment, jiggered their computer models to see if they could make the allocation of livers more efficient. They concluded that by moving people who suddenly lost liver function up the waiting list, America could manage 65-70 more liver transplants a year (see <a href="am1.gif">chart</a>). And the number of patients dying as they waited for a transplant--954 lastyear--would fall. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The reason for this is that acute liver failure tends to happen to otherwisehealthy people who may, for example, have eaten a bad mushroom. Chronic liver failure, on the other hand, tends to be part of a process of general physical deterioration. Patients in this condition may be less likely to weather the trauma of a liver transplant. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The boffins had two other bright ideas. First, local hospitals would no longer have first claim to organs landing directly on their patches; instead, these livers would be made available to the neediest within a much larger region, usually across a couple of states. This move would go some way towards evening out the big geographical disparities in liver allocation. <font size=-1>UNOS </font>considered but rejected the idea of allocatinglivers according to a centralised national list. Livers have a short shelf-life, and flying them around America is no way to keep them at their best. Second, <font size=-1>UNOS</font> planned to standardise the rules that determinewhen a patient should be added to the waiting list. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The unexpected result of these technical fixes was uproar. Several transplant centres, including the University of Pittsburgh, New York's Mount Sinai Hospital and Baylor University in Houston, argued in favour of a single national list. The larger centres tend to get sicker patients, they argued, and thus should have higher priority in allocation. (Sceptics note that transplants areboth profitable and good for medical reputations, and wonder if the big centres are not guilty of simply wanting to increase their market share.)
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Others objected that moving acute patients up the priority list was a moral judgment that had no place in medicine. This is because much, though not all, chronic liver failure can be traced to drug and/or alcohol abuse. Patients on the waiting list withchronic liver failure feared that the regulatory tweaking meant they would never see a liver. In fact, the new policy, like the old one, will see 95% of liver transplants going to the chronically ill.
<br>As the argument heated up, the federal Department of Health and Human Services (<font size=-1>DHHS</font>) held hearings on the proposed changes in December. They were inconclusive, so on January 20th the new rules went into effect for all future entrants to the waiting list. But a panel named by the <font size=-1>DHHS</font> may well devise its own regulations; in that case, these federal rules will supersede current practice. This would be somethingnew for the department, which approves changes in transplant policy but leaves<font size=-1>UNOS</font> to make them. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The idea that the <font size=-1>DHHS</font> may decide to take over allocation is not popular in transplant circles. Despite controversies like the one over livers, the system generally works as intended. Transplant experts worry that the government will not do as well and that the process might be politicised. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The fundamental problem, of course, is simply that there are not enough organs to go round. This is a worldwide problem (see <a href="ld4522.html">page</a>). On January 15th, 7,511 Americans were waiting for a liver, but last year only 3,925 got one; without a functioning liver, which is the body's chemical processor,death is swift and certain. Bureaucraticfixes cannot do much to change that.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
