<html><head><title>Rebel alliance</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/ir.gif" width="224" height="26" alt="International" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Sudan
<h1>Rebel alliance</h1>

</b></p>THE recent advances of rebel forces in eastern and southern Sudan signal an alliance that could threaten the government. The new offensive started on December 28th with an attack on a mechanised brigade near the Eritrean border. Rebels from the south and north are fighting together--and are backed by outside powers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Guerrillas from the Sudan People's Liberation Army (<font size=-1>SPLA</font>), the mainly southern movement that has been fighting for 13 years, have joined up with the Beja Congress Armed Forces, one part of a new alliance of northern Sudanese rebels known as the National Democratic Alliance (<font size=-1>NDA</font>). Sudan's eastern neighbours, Ethiopia and Eritrea, helped to bring the two together, and now keep them supplied. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Eritrea gives the <font size=-1>NDA</font> a home and provides it with weapons. The United States, which holds Sudan guilty of sponsoring terrorism, has announced that it is supplying "defensive" weapons to Eritrea, Ethiopia and Uganda to help them protect themselves from Sudan. One way or another, these arms have been reaching the rebels. And rebel spirits have been raised by the arrival in Eritrea of Sadiq el Mahdi, the Sudanese prime minister who was overthrown by the Islamists in 1989.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Sudanese government, facing astrong enemy, finds itself short of both fuel and weapons. Morale in the army is said to be low. In early January, <font size=-1>SPLA</font> fighterscrossed from Ethiopia, taking several small towns. More important, they have begun to threaten the Roseires hydroelectric dam on the Blue Nile which supplies 80% of Khartoum's electricity (see <a href="ir1.gif">map</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The regime, in near-panic, has called on fellow Arab governments to support it,playing on their fear that the <font size=-1>SPLA</font> is a pawn of western powers trying to break up Sudan. Its call has split the Arab world. A few, including Syria and Jordan, have supported Sudan with strong statements. Eritrea, with close links to Israel, is seen as an aggressive interloper in the region. Egypt, Sudan's big neighbour, is far more ambivalent. The Egyptians, deeply suspicious of Sudan's Islamists (though also horrified at the thought of fighting on the Nile), prefer to see the conflict as an internal one, denying Eritrean or Ethiopian involvement.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If the rebels were to cut off Khartoum's electricity supply, or to cut the road from Port Sudan to Khartoum, the days of the Islamist regime in Khartoum could be numbered. What, then, would replace it? The current north-south alliance would be unlikely to survive victory. Sudan, huge, disparate and surrounded by interfering neighbours, would find it hard to stay together, democractic or peaceful.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
