<html><head><title>Save our survey</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Statistics
<h1>Save our survey</h1>

</b></p>ON JANUARY 30th, the governmentwill publish the 1997 edition of its "Social Trends", a compilation of key social statistics admired and imitated around the world. At the foot of many an illuminating chart, the quoted source will be the government's own General Household Survey(<font size=-1>GHS</font>). Perhaps for the last time: the government has just announced its intention to suspend fieldwork for the next <font size=-1>GHS</font> pending a review, as the Office for National Statistics (<font size=-1>ONS</font>) struggles to meet tough budgetary targets. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A belated consultation of outside users has fomented a campaign to save the survey led by Denise Lievesley, director of "the definitive data archive" at Essex University. Outraged academics argue that the survey is irreplaceable--and that to scrap it would fly in the face of the government's policy of providing good statistics for outsiders, and not just for its own use.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>GHS</font> is the only survey that produces compatible figures over a span of years going back to 1972. It provides the most detailed information on social developments essential to policy planning--for example on cohabitation, which affectshousing provision, leisure activities and contraception. The survey is irreplaceable in getting at what Sue Richards, a professor of public management at BirminghamUniversity, describes as the "wicked problems"--those which cannot be solved by one government department alone. This is because the <font size=-1>GHS</font> enables researchers to put together a rounded statistical picture ofBritons, bringing together details of their housing, income and jobs. The government now proposes to dispense with this valuable tool to save a mere &#163;500,000 this year, which is what it spends on social security every three minutes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Still, <font size=-1>ONS</font> officials deserve some sympathy. Their budget problems are severe. They must save &#163;2m this year on top of &#163;10m last year out of a budget of around &#163;120m. Admittedly, some of these cuts could be found from administrative savings, following last year's merger between the Central Statistical Office and the Office of Population Censuses and Surveys to form <font size=-1>ONS</font>. But better statistics do not rank highly among ministerial spending priorities. If there must be cost cuts, they prefer to achieve them by ditching whole surveys than by cuttingquality corners across-the-board.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, some outsiders think that the compilers of the <font size=-1>GHS</font> are their own worst enemy: slow to produce its results, and resistant to changing its scope. Outsiders recognise that the government is trying tomake the myriad of social surveys carried out by individual departments and by the <font size=-1>ONS</font> compatible. The more this effort succeeds, the less essential will be the <font size=-1>GHS</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It would be a great loss if the survey were never repeated. Equally, there is no compelling reason why it should be carried out every year. A decision to conduct the <font size=-1>GHS</font> every couple of years from now on would be the most sensible outcome.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?854154000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
