<html><head><title>Top gear</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<h1>Top gear</h1>

SOMEWHERE in the middle of the Channel, ships heading for the continent, laden with British-madeLand Rovers and NissanMicras, are passing others, bound for Britain, with cargoes ofFrench-made Renault Clios and Belgian-built Ford Mondeos. Both exports and imports of cars have grown sharply in recent years. British factories have been taking advantage of their improved efficiency and the European single market to boost their sales to the continent. But at home, buyers are less concerned than they used to be about buying British.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On balance, this growing trade has been good news for Britain: while 62% of the 2m cars sold in Britain last year were foreign-made (up from 59% in 1995), exports grew twice as fast as imports. Figures published on January 20th show that British car factories' booming exports more than made up for their cuts in production for the home market. Almost 1.7m cars were made in Britain, 10%more than in 1995 and the highest number since 1973 (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>). While the 15% rise in sterling's trade-weighted index last year hurt other exporters, it has not so far dented car makers: their production for export in the last quarter of 1996 was a third higher than in the same period of 1995.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Two significant moves this month mean that the two-way traffic in cars should continue growing. On January 21st, it was announced that the Nissan plant in Sunderland is to build a third model--the Almera--mainly for export, alongside the existing Micra andPrimera models. Five days earlier, Ford said that it would stop making the Escort at its Halewood assembly plant, which mainly serves the home market.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So Britain's trade deficit in cars and motor parts, which has been around &#163;5 billion in each of the past two years, is expected to fall sharply in coming years. Professor Garel Rhys of Cardiff University Business School says that Japanese car makers are steadily expanding their distribution networks on the continent, to receive the growing output of their British plants. He predicts that the deficit will be one-tenth of its current size in around five years.
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?854154000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
