<html><head><title>Poll axed?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Election timing
<h1>Poll axed?</h1>

</b></p>FOR a few hours in February, Phil Manson, the borough solicitor of the Metropolitan Borough of the Wirrall, could find himself the most important political actor in the country. For Mr Manson is also the returning officer for the area, which includes the Wirral South constituency,where the government has promised to call a by-election not later than March 6th.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What happens however if, after it is called but before it is held, John Major calls a general election? By a quirk of Britain's electoral law, that may be down to Mr Manson. If parliament was not yet dissolved, he could let the by-election go ahead. The Liverpool Edge Hill by-election was held on March 29th 1979 despite the fall of the Callaghan government the night before. Or he could call it off. Why should Wirralites have to vote twice--once for an <font size=-1>MP</font> who might never take his seat? An election court could review whether his decision was "reasonable", but not until much later. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Manson will of course take his decision without regard to politics. But it could have profound political consequences. Labour needs an 8% swing to win the seat. If the Tories lost it early in a general election campaign--as a <font size=-1>MORI</font> poll on January 14th-16th suggests they would--their moralewould be shattered. If they won, they could claim to be making ground. Their fate may lie in Mr Manson's hands.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That seems odd. But so is much in Britain's patchwork quilt of electoral law. It pales into insignificance beside another oddity: the prime minister's power to decide on election timing. Believe it or not, and in strict legal theory, Mr Major could even guarantee himself three more years. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Robert Blackburn, an academic lawyer, describes how in a recent book ("The Electoral System in Britain", Macmillan &#163;15.99). As every schoolboy knows, the monarch (advised by the prime minister) must by law dissolve Parliament after five years.However there is no such legal compulsion to then immediately call a general election. The 1694 Triennial Act (now re-titled the Meeting of Parliament Act), lays down that the monarch need not call an election for a new Parliament for three years after the expiry of the old one. Mr Major could dissolve Parliament and then legally carry on governing without one for three moreyears, says Mr Blackburn.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of course, if Mr Major were to try this, the people might rise up and throw him out of Downing Street--or the queen would refuse his advice. Yet short of that, the law gives a British prime minister extraordinary control overelection timing. He can go to the country at any time he chooses before the end of a Parliament's five years. When he does go, he alone decides the length of a campaign. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The law requires that 17 days mustelapse between the end of a Parliament and the holding of an election, excluding Saturdays, Sundays, bank holidays anywhere in Britain and Maundy Thursday. But if it suits him, the prime minister can let the campaign roll on. In 1945, for example, the election was announced on May 23rd, but not actually held until July 5th. By contrast, in February 1974, Edward Heath gave only a day's notice of his intention to dissolve, and the election was over three weeks after it was announced. He lost. Official election campaigns have tended to become shorter rather than longer, although Britain is currently in the middle of one of its longest ever unofficial campaign periods. If MrMajor remains far behind, he may want to drag out the official campaign as well.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<i>The Economist</i> has argued for fixed-term Parliaments, such as exist in most democracies. That argument is reinforced by experience this time with Mr Major's lame-duck administration, and by the constant speculation as to when he will finally face the electorate. But this is not the only reform that is needed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One priority stands out: to remove control over electoral law from the Home Office. It is in principle wrong that it should remain there, notionally under the control of the home secretary, who is an elected politician. Mr Blackburn proposes instead that responsibility should pass to an independent electoral commission, whose remit might include campaign financing, the drawing of constituency boundaries and finding ways of increasing voter turnout. Something similar was recommended in a report on campaigning by the all-partyHansard Society in 1991, which waschaired by Sir Christopher Chataway, a former Tory minister. Jack Straw, the shadow home secretary, has also indicated support for the idea--which may mean that Mr Major's startling prerogative will soon be a thing of the past. 
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?854154000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
