<html><head><title>Victory</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Road protests
<h1>Victory</h1>

</b></p><font size=1>FAIRMILE CAMP, DEVON
</font><p>WHEN the police helicopter appears overhead, the road protesters atFairmile in Devon snap into action: one disappears, dreadlocks bobbing, down a mineshaft marked "This one's for the badgers"; another pulls up the drawbridge over the dry moat; and a third prepares to padlock himself to the trunk of an old oak. Half a dozen tarpaulin tree-houses rustle with activity, while underground the alarmwhistles through five separate tunnel networks. On this occasion, the camp wins a brief reprieve. But even if the police, bailiffs, security firms, professional climbers, potholers and sonar operators do manage to dismantle Britain's last camp of road protesters in the next few days, the campaigners will still be celebrating the success of their tactics.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since capturing the country's attention during their campaign against theNewbury bypass in 1995, anti-roads activists seem to have lost their momentum. Apart from Fairmile, there are now active camps at only a few obscure sites, such as the A320 near Woking and the Bingley bypass in Yorkshire. Whereas the Newbury protests resulted in nearly 1,000 arrests, there have been only a handful since. The much-publicised recent scuffle on the first anniversary of the start of construction at Newbury only highlighted how little has happened in the interim.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet the protesters claim that this slowdown is a sign not of waning enthusiasm, but victory. Certainly they are right to point out that few controversial road-building schemes are currently under way. Public expenditure on roads has fallen from over &#163;8 billion in the three years to 1996 to just &#163;6 billion budgeted for the three years to 1999. The number of major new roads started has fallen from 55 in the 1990-91 financial year to just one in 1995-96. The government has in effect deferred the decision on the proposed Salisbury bypass, the next potential flashpoint, until after the general election. Even John Watts, the roads minister, has conceded that "our intention is to make better use of the existing roads network."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government nevertheless deniesthat the protesters have had any effect,putting its new policy down to tighter budgets. This is implausible. Despite all their antics, the protesters have often attracted support from otherwise law-abiding citizens. And the direct action campaigns have undoubtedly added to the expense and difficulty of building roads. The costs to the taxpayer of security and policing on the &#163;95m bypass at Newbury have reached&#163;19m and are still rising. The price-tag for clearing the camps in Devon is also climbing into the millions, diverting moneyfrom other Highways Agency schemes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the construction firms, too, the difficulties of building in the face of protests are increasing. Both Costain, the company behind the Newbury bypass, and Tarmac, another big road-builder, have had shareholders' meetings disrupted by activists.Workers have been threatened, equipment has been vandalised and the bad publicity has seemed endless. When the government was considering bids for the Newbury bypass, Sir John Banham, Tarmac's chairman, tried to pre-empt the activists by demanding stronger environmental standards.Other industry executives privately admit that protests have pushed up their costs and caused them to hesitate over projects likely to cause trouble.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And the protesters? "I think you'll see the direct action movement beginning to diversify more and more," says Rob, one of the Fairmile residents. Some speak of shifting their focus to open-cast mining, or large quarries such as that at Whatley in Somerset. But most are even more ambitious: one campaigner, Kit, declares, "Fairmile is the university of direct action. We are teaching our methods to people from all over the world." Good grief.
<br>
<br>
<p align=center>
