<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<p><b>Euroshift</b> &nbsp; Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor of the exchequer, said that Britain is "very unlikely" to join Europe's single currency on its starting date in January 1999, although the government would continue to keep its options open.
<p><br><b>Bugbear</b> &nbsp; The government was defeated in the Lords on two different amendments to the Police bill, which grants the police broad surveillancepowers. Amendments by both Labour and the Liberal Democrats would ensure that judges reviewed police applications to bug private property before the devices were planted.
<p><br><b>Dead heat</b> &nbsp; Martin Redmond, the Labour <font size=-1>MP</font> for Don Valley in Yorkshire, died, leaving the government and opposition parties evenly balanced in the Commons with 322 votes apiece.
<p><br><b>No contest</b> &nbsp; An Old Bailey jury decided that Szymon Serafinowicz was mentally unfit to stand trial, bringing Britain's first war-crimes trial to an end. Mr Serafinowicz had denied charges of murdering three Jews in Belarus during the second world war.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><br><b>Unsporting</b> &nbsp; Danish police arrestedseven neo-Nazis who had mounted a letter-bomb campaign against various British targets, including several sports stars in mixed-race marriages. TheSwedish authorities intercepted anddefused three of the packages.
<p><br><b>Selling short</b> &nbsp; Retail sales in December fell by 0.8% compared with November's figure. But the disappointing results were still an increase of 2.9% on last year's level.
<p><br><b>Ruling on Britannia</b> &nbsp; The government said that it will build, solely at taxpayers' expense, a replacement for the royal yacht, <i>Britannia</i>, in time for the queen's golden jubilee in 2002, at a cost of &#163;60m. It is searching for a suitable use for the current ship, which it has refused to sell to a private owner.
<p><br><b>Eurotartan</b> &nbsp; The European Unionhas given a &#163;200,000 subsidy to a new school which will teach the Scottishhow to make kilts.

</td></tr></table></center>
