<html><head><title>Suited, surfing and shopping</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Suited, surfing and shopping</h1>

FOR all the blather about shopping on-line, the number of success stories is remarkably small. Name Amazon.com(books), <font size=-1>CD</font>now (music) and Virtual Vineyards (wine) and you are almost at the end of the list. As for Internet publishers, they are loth to charge for access to their web-sites. On January 11th, <i>Slate</i>, an on-line magazine owned by Microsoft, announced that it was postponing subscription charges indefinitely. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact, plenty of goods are being sold on-line. But companies are mostly selling not to consumers, but to each other. In three years' time, reckons Forrester Research, a consultancy based in Massachusetts, business-to-business Internet commerce will be worth $67 billion a year, whereas consumer retailing will bring in less than a tenth as much. Last year, Forrester estimated that each sector was worth just over $500m.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These numbers underline the on-line triumph of Cisco, a Californian computer firm that makes specialist hardware for the Internet and other computer networks. In the second half of 1996, Cisco's sales through its web-site were worth $100m--or 11% of its total sales. Forrester's figures suggest that Cisco alone was responsible for 10% of all the business done on the Internet in 1996. This year Cisco expects to make 30% of its sales (probably around $2 billion-worth) through its web-site, even though only its largest customers and its resellers can buy products that way. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another success of Internet commerce has been General Electric, America's largest firm by market capitalisation. Last summer, <font size=-1>GE</font> launched its web-based Trading Process Network to allow around 1,400 suppliers to compete for <font size=-1>GE</font> contracts. Admittedly <font size=-1>GE</font> already used old-fashioned electronic trading (so-called electronic document interchange, or <font size=-1>EDI</font>), so moving to the Internet was more an evolutionary step than a revolutionary one. But most of the deals made through the Trading Process Network are worth several million dollars. By June this year, <font size=-1>GE</font> expects to have done $1 billion-worth of business using its web-site.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So why have companies flocked to do business when consumers have stayed at home? One reason is that on-line shopping for individuals sometimes has to compete with the social pleasures of the real thing. Business buyers simply want the right product at the right price. Another problem is that more people have access to the Internet at work than at home. According to <font size=-1>IDC</font>, a market-research firm in Massachusetts, 20% of Internet users who have access at work have bought goods on-line compared with 14% of home users. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In addition, selling to ordinary people has been plagued by payment problems. Even though credit-card transactions over the Net are probably safer than real-world ones, many users are still reluctant to use plastic to pay for goods on-line. Companies have no such problems: their bills tend to be settled by monthly accounts. An ordinary shopper may fret that his $50 credit-card transaction will be intercepted; meanwhile, Cisco has made some 4,000 sales worth an average of $25,000 each to corporate buyers. It is always easier to spend the company's money than your own.
<br>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
