<html><head><title>Think big, Mr President</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>

<h1 align=center>Think big, Mr President</h1>


<CleverDrop>AFTER his second inauguration, in 1973, Richard Nixon confided to his diary that he felt melancholy. He could not think why. Even Ronald Reagan felt uncharacteristically grim after his second swearing-in: it was "back to work", he wrote later, to try to salvage something from his first four years. The beginnings of second terms are like that. Rather than the excitement and possibilities of power, presidents see drudgery and obstacles. Where once they might have clambered confidently up the cliff-face to hammer out their monument in history, they now creep out nervously over their own half-finished creation, daring a nick there and a polish there, before that jerk on the rope signals that their time is up. <br> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Bill Clinton too is more cautious now, with more sober people round him. If he has carried away any lesson from his first four years, it is that grandiose ideas are dangerous, and that little things (sick leave, emergency numbers) are vote-winners. In fact, it goes deeper than that in the Clintonian psychology: little things that mean a lot to ordinary people are really big things, for which history will give him credit. This comforts him. The shock of November 1994, when the Republican avant-garde seized control of Congress, taught him the value of staying in the centre and embracing incremental change. A bold, unbridled second term? Forget it. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Besides, his past is haunting him. Although some of the scandals may subside and others may never become inflamed (see <a href="sf0814.html"> page</a>), their range is both impressive and depressing. Something will cause damage. And before long Mr Clinton will be hobbled in any case, unable to get his political way even with sterling effort. Listeners to next week's inauguration speech should not be deceived: under the portentous phrases will lie a commitment to nothing very much.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the new Congress, the mood is much the same. The Republicans held both houses in November, but took a battering. Newt Gingrich, the speaker and the source of much of their radicalism, is in trouble and has lost authority. Far from pushing their revolution, with its useful (though sometimes hair-raising) questioning of the status quo, the Republicans are waiting for the president to take the lead on policy. But Mr Clinton, whose boldest recent initiatives have been filchings of Republican ideas, has nothing particular to offer them.<br>
<b><br>
</p><p><b>Big problems, bold solutions</b></b><br>
This diffidence and pragmatism on both sides might be touching, if America's problems were as small as the horizons of its politicians. But they are not. At home, budget priorities are in a mess. Taxes are in urgent need of simplification. The two giant entitlement programmes, Medicare (health care for the elderly) and Social Security (state pensions) must be put on a solvent footing before the baby-boomers start to retire. America's schools are feeble by international standards, and many of its cities are intolerably violent. Abroad, America faces a world in which a period of unnatural tranquillity seems bound to end; in which China is newly aggressive, Russia unsettled, and the old alliances are weakened by lack of confidence. In short, there is a lot to do.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And so far, in almost every case, Mr Clinton and the Republican Congress are favouring the fiddle-and-tinker approach. On the budget, the laudable aim of balance by 2002 is to be achieved by squeezing discretionary spending as hard as it can bear, in order to bring in new tax cuts and tax breaks promised during the campaign. This spending (for such things as roads, parks and schools) could be spared, in part, if at least a start was made on entitlement reform. But on Medicare, Mr Clinton prefers the "quick fix" (his term) of transferring some of its costs into the general budget; while on Social Security, on which a commission has just reported, the president looks likely to demand yet another commission that will reach one conclusion, rather than several, and will thus give both him and Congress a political shield to cower behind.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What would a bold man do? The options on Medicare include means-testing, raising premiums and capping rising costs. On Social Security, they include raising the retirement age, raising the income limit on the payroll tax that funds the system, privatisation, investment in the stockmarket, and adjusting the consumer-price index to ensure that inflation is not overstated in benefits payments. Few politicians in either party will touch these notions. Yet Mr Clinton should be the man to try; not least because, as a Democrat, he can be trusted to support the principle of adequate social provision. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He should also be encouraged into bolder thinking towards the world outside. This does not suggest unilateral interventions, although the new secretary of state shows some enthusiasm for them. It means a greater effort by both Mr Clinton and his team to put his actions in a global context, and to acquire a true feel for America's power and potential on the world stage. Case by case and piece by piece, Mr Clinton's foreign policy has come together over the past four years into something that is broadly respectable. What it still lacks is an understanding of America's role as the world's pre-eminent enabler and enforcer, and an appreciation of how alliances and multilateral institutions can enhance and legitimise that power, rather than hamper it. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton may well still feel that the time is not right for boldness. But for him, it will never be better. He has been re-elected, an event that is rare for presidents these days. This gives him capital, however short-lived. He is presiding over a smoothly growing economy with consistently low unemployment; Americans feel better about their prospects, and even crime figures are down. It is probably vain to tell this president that he need not pander to the voters any more; the urge to ingratiate lies too deep in his character. And it is vain to think that, even with the most acquiescent Congress, large reforms will be accomplished. But Bill Clinton, president, leader, commander of the bully-pulpit, long-odds candidate for Mount Rushmore, can at least set necessary changes in motion; and what is equally clear is that no one else can.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
