<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width="271" height="24" alt="Politics this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>A deal is done</h2>
The Israelis and Palestinians, with a lot of help from America and, at the last minute, a little from Jordan, signed a deal on Israel's withdrawal from a large part of <b>Hebron</b>. They also agreed on three (still to be defined) stages of further redeployment in rural areas of the West Bank. World leaders praised them. One Israeli minister resigned.<p>
Some 270 Palestinians, stranded on the <b>Libyan- Egyptian border</b> since September 1995 when Muammar Qaddafi ordered Palestinians out of his country, were allowed to return to Libya.<p>
A<b> letter-bomb</b> exploded at the London head offices of a Saudi-owned pan-Arab newspaper,<i> al-Hayat</i>, injuring a security guard. Another dozen letter-bombs were delivered to the paper in New York and Riyadh. Nobody claimed responsibility.<p>
<b>South Africa </b>responded sharply to an American threat to cut aid if it went ahead with the sale of arms to Syria. President Mandela said South Africa would sell where it chose and not be dictated to by anyone.<p>
After a brief visit home, President Mobuto Sese Seko of <b>Zaire </b>returned to France.<p>
Rebels in southern <b>Sudan </b> captured several towns on the Ethiopian border. The Sudanese government blamed Ethiopia for the attack. <p>
<h2>Above the law</h2>
The Supreme Court considered arguments that President Bill Clinton should be immune while in office from a private lawsuit brought by <b>Paula Jones</b>, a former Arkansas state employee who alleges that the president sexually harassed her in a Little Rock hotel in 1991. <p>
The top Democrat on the House Ethics Committee resigned over his handling of a taped telephone call involving <b>Newt Gingrich</b>, the speaker, who is under investigation on ethics charges. <p>
Two women cadets left the <b>Citadel</b>, a military college in South Carolina that was forced by court order to admit women, complaining of harassment by male colleagues. Two women remain.<p>
Mr Clinton made <b>Roy Romer</b>, the governor of Colorado, chairman of the Democratic National Committee.<p>
A step ahead in <b>Peru's hostage affair</b>. The Tupac Amaru guerrillas accepted a government idea for a committee to oversee negotiations.<p>
<h2>Japan's overtures</h2>
On a visit to South-East Asia, the Japanese prime minister, <b>Ryutaro Hashimoto</b> (right), sought new ties that would cover security as well as trade and investment. The proposal was received warily in the Association of South-East Asian Nations, partly for fear of upsetting China.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
Widespread strikes against <b>South Korea's new labour laws </b>moved into their fourth week. Though the government expressed regret for the way it passed the laws, it refused to scrap them, as unions demanded. Three union leaders were arrested.<p>
Datta Samant, an <b>Indian trade-union leader </b>well known for his militancy, was shot dead in Mumbai.<p>
<b>Mother Teresa </b>resigned the leadership of the mission she founded in India 47 years ago. The 86-year-old Roman Catholic nun is in poor health.<p>
In <b>Singapore</b>, a veteran opposition politician, J.B. Jeyaretnam, who failed to win a seat in a general election held earlier this month, accepted a seat as a nominated member of parliament.<p>
<b>Hong Kong </b>newspapers claimed that the former director of immigration, Lawrence Leung, gave China information about the British colony's residents. Mr Leung, who has denied the reports, resigned last year.<p>
<h2>By the people</h2>
<b>Bulgaria</b>'s Socialists agreed to hold elections by the end of 1997, a year early. Opposition parties, which have been staging large demonstrations outside parliament for several weeks, are still demanding an immediate poll.<p>
Electoral officials ruled that opposition parties had won municipal elections in <b>Belgrade and Nis</b>, Serbia's two biggest cities. But the Belgrade chief of the ruling Socialist Party said it would challenge the ruling.<p>
<b>President Yeltsin</b>, in hospital with pneumonia, suggested that Russia and Belarus should unite.<p>
After raising tensions with Turkey by ordering a Russian missile-defence system, Glafkos Clerides, president of <b>Cyprus</b>, lowered them by saying it would not be delivered for 16 months.<p>
A former president of Switzerland, Jean-Pascal Delamuraz, now its economics minister, apologised for accusing Jewish groups of <b>"ransom and blackmail" </b> in demanding that Swiss banks compensate victims of the Holocaust for losses.<p>
A Spanish conservative, <b>Jose- Maria Gil-Robles</b>, was elected president of the European Parliament.<p>
Germany's federal <b>budget deficit</b> in 1996 was DM18.4 billion ($11.6 billion) higher than projected. The public-sector deficit as a whole was 3.9% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>, well above the target of 3% for countries wanting to join Europe's planned single currency.<p>
<p>

</td></tr></table></center>
