<DOCHDR>
http://www.europe.economist.com:80/issue/18-01-97/bw0770.html 199.173.162.110 19970215015332 text/html 6725
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 01:49:26 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 16-Jan-97 18:11:29 GMT
Content-length: 6538
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Alliance under fire</h2>
The European Commission said it would take Britain to the European Court of Justice if it allowed <b>British Airways </b> and <b>American Airlines</b> to form an alliance. That, said Karel Van Miert, the competition commissioner, would hurt competition in Europe and eliminate competition on 13 transatlantic routes. He dismissed as "completely inadequate" a plan for the two airlines to shed 5% of their "slots" at London's Heathrow airport. <p>
Federal safety officials in America announced modifications, suggested by Boeing, to the rudders of all 2,700 <b>Boeing 737s </b>in operation worldwide. The craft has had two unexplained fatal crashes in America. <p>
<b>Lufthansa</b> is set for full privatisation this year after the German government gave the go-ahead to a draft bill that will ensure that the airline will remain majority-owned by Germans. The 36% stake still held by the state is worth about DM3 billion ($1.9 billion). The news limiting foreign ownership shook the price of Lufthansa's shares. <p>
<b>General Motors </b>and <b>Volkswagen </b>settled their long-running feud over alleged industrial espionage out of court. <font size=-1>VW</font> agreed to pay $100m in damages to <font size=-1>GM</font> and to buy $1 billion-worth of <font size=-1>GM</font> components over seven years; and both companies will drop all civil actions against each other. Jose Ignacio Lopez, who defected from <font size=-1>GM</font> to <font size=-1>VW</font>, is barred from working for <font size=-1>VW</font> for three years. <h2>Still bullish<p></h2>
 
Underlying inflation in America of only 2.6% last year and higher-than-expected retail sales in December boosted the Dow Jones industrial average to a new record. European <b>bourses </b>followed, with a dozen also setting record highs. Italy did not, though it has gained 14% already this year. Hong Kong's Hang Seng reached a record, but Tokyo's Nikkei failed to stabilise. <p>
(See <a href="bw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>The battle for control of the vast<b> Busang gold field </b>in Indonesia raged undiminished. Placer Dome, a Canadian gold producer, made an offer for Bre-<font size=-1>X</font> Minerals, the tiny Canadian firm that discovered Busang (and which is now worth around C$5.5 billion, or $4.1 billion). Last year Bre-<font size=-1>X</font> had Barrick Gold, yet another Canadian producer, imposed on it as a partner by the Indonesian government. <p>
The <b>price of gold </b>was rattled, again, by the Dutch central bank's admitting that it had sold 300 tonnes of gold last year, more than recent estimates had suggested for European central banks as a whole. The central bank said it had reduced its holdings by about a fifth to bring it in line with other big European central banks. Jumpy investors fear copy-cat selling, and the price of the metal sank towards $350 an ounce. <p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
Mexico has repaid, three years early, the $12.5 billion it borrowed from the United States after the <b>collapse of the peso</b> in 1994, and will shortly repay the last part of the $17.8 billion it borrowed from the <font size=-1>IMF</font>. Meanwhile, Mexican authorities arrested the leader of a powerful debtors' group formed when the currency crisis sent interest rates soaring. <h2>Trying again<p></h2>
 
The French government said <b>Thomson Multimedia</b>, the bit of Thomson <font size=-1>SA</font> that France refused to allow to be sold to Daewoo of South Korea, would soon be recapitalised. It also promised a decision on the sale of Thomson-<font size=-1>CSF</font>, the defence-electronics unit, by the end of the month. A French envoy, sent to grovel to Daewoo, said he had urged it to bid again for the multimedia unit. <p>
(See <a href="bw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>Last year <font size=-1>IBM</font>, for the fourth year running, received more <b>American patents</b> than any other company, the highest number ever. <p>
Germany's <b>Gehe</b>, a drug wholesaler, beat Unichem in a year-long struggle to win control of <b>Lloyds Chemists</b> with a &#163;684m ($1.15 billion) offer. It now surpasses Boots as Britain's biggest chain of chemist shops. <p>
<b>Rupert Murdoch</b>, a media tycoon, and <b>Kerry Packer</b>, his arch-rival in the Australian media industry, settled a legal dispute over the screening of rugby league matches. <h2>Staffing problems<p></h2>
 
Deutsche Bank is reeling again only months after several directors at its <b>Deutsche Morgan Grenfell</b> unit in London were dismissed following a unit-trusts scandal. <font size=-1>DMG</font> suspended Nicola Horlick, top-performing head of its &#163;18 billion ($30 billion) British pension-fund operations, after allegations that she tried to persuade 20 colleagues to follow her to another bank. <p>
The seven-year saga of the privatisation of <b>Creditanstalt</b>, Austria's second-largest bank, juddered to a farcical close when the government announced the ASch17.2 billion ($1.54 billion) sale of its 49% stake to another state-owned bank. The sale to Bank Austria, its bigger rival, was the only option, said the government. Bank Austria must maintain Creditanstalt as a separate unit for five years. The European Commission is investigating the deal for illegal state aid after complaints from foreign suitors. <p>
<b>British Telecom</b> is cutting the cost of international calls to 33 countries, including America and Australia, by up to 37% to meet regulatory requirements. <p><p>

</td></tr></table></center>
<p align=center><a href="ww0237.html">POLITICS THIS WEEK</a></p>
