<html><head><title>Monkey business?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif" width="447" height="26" alt="Special feature">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Monkey business?</h1>

<p><b>Bill Clinton's second term begins on January 20th. It is already being overshadowed by scandal</b></p><br>
A PRESIDENT'S second term should be more predictable than his first. Voters and politicians have had four years to study him. Policy surprises should already have been sprung. Upsets should presumably be confined to external events.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With Bill Clinton's hard-won second term, however, things look different. A cloud of unpredictability hangs over it, deriving mainly from an assortment of scandals which complicate the outlook for the next four years. At worst, these scandals could turn Clinton <font size=-1>II</font> into a miserable replay of Nixon <font size=-1>II</font>, though few people expect the president to be driven from office under threat of impeachment or prosecution. But even at their mildest, the allegations promise to be an unwelcome distraction from the business of government.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And an unnecessary and damaging one, say Mr Clinton's supporters. On all fronts, both they and the president insist he has done nothing wrong, let alone anything unlawful. To them, the scandals industry is little more than a media concoction gleefully exploited--even masterminded--by the president's political foes. "Possibly the most politically charged case of journalistic malpractice in recent American history" is how one group of writers, Gene Lyons and the editors of <i>Harper's </i> magazine, have dubbed the accusations. Whatever the origins, though, the outlook is for more media probing, more court challenges, more congressional hearings and more special investigations. (See <a href="sf1.gif">table</a>)<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The scandals fall into three categories. One is the sexual-harassment case brought by Paula Corbin Jones, a former Arkansas state employee. Another is "Whitewater", shorthand for the range of matters being examined by an independent counsel, Kenneth Starr. Then there is the relatively recent controversy over the Asian money which poured into Democratic campaign coffers for the 1996 elections and into the Clintons' legal-defence fund. Awkwardly for the president, all three are coming to a crunch in 1997, which is the very worst time for his second-term presidency.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Keeping up with the Jones case</b></b><br>
Paula Jones now lives in Long Beach, California, with her husband, an airline-reservations clerk, and their two sons. On May 8th 1991, she was unmarried Paula Corbin, an eye-catching 24-year-old with a clerical job at the Arkansas Industrial Development Commission. That afternoon, she says, she caught the eye of Governor Clinton (as he then was) while she was working at the registration desk of the "Governor's Quality Management Conference" at the Excelsior Hotel in downtown Little Rock. By her account, one of Mr Clinton's state troopers came to tell her that "The governor said you make his knees knock"; the trooper later returned with the number of a suite in the hotel where Mr Clinton wanted to meet her. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the Jones version of what followed, she naively allowed herself to be accompanied to the room, where she found herself alone with Mr Clinton. After some small talk--including a remark by the governor that her boss was his "good friend"--he put his hand on her leg and tried to kiss her, saying "I love your curves." Despite her rejections, she claims, Mr Clinton exposed himself and asked for oral sex. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Horrified, she jumped up, saying she was not that kind of girl and had to go. According to her lurid complaint--complete with a reference to "distinguishing characteristics" in Mr Clinton's genital area--the governor "looked sternly" at her as she left the room and said: "You are smart. Let's keep this between ourselves."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nearly three years passed. Mrs Jones said nothing in public. What then made her tell her story? She claims it was an article in the January 1994 issue of a conservative magazine, the <i>American Spectator, </i>in which a state trooper recounted how he had arranged a rendezvous at the Excelsior hotel between Mr Clinton and a woman called Paula, and that on her way out she had told the trooper "she was available to be Clinton's regular girlfriend if he so desired." Mrs Jones claims to have been outraged, and determined to clear her name. She went to a Little Rock lawyer who, unhappily for her subsequent credibility, helped her present her allegations at a press conference organised by a right-wing political group.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For his defence, the president hired Robert Bennett, a $475-an-hour Washington superlawyer. Mrs Jones graduated to a couple of Virginia litigators, Gilbert Davis and Joseph Cammarata. They failed to settle. (Under a deal proposed by Mr Bennett, Mr Clinton would issue a statement that he had "no recollection" of meeting Mrs Jones but did not challenge her claim that they had met. He would also confirm that she "did not engage in any improper or sexual conduct.") Mrs Jones filed suit, claiming damages of $700,000, in May 1994.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Bennett adopted a twin strategy of attacking Mrs Jones's character and delaying her case. He derided her lawsuit as "tabloid trash". With her permed hair and painted lips, she seemed to fit the Clinton-defenders' depiction of her as a gold-digger: "Drag $100 through a trailer park and there's no telling what you'll find," said James Carville, a consultant to Mr Clinton. Even one of her own sisters questioned Mrs Jones's motives. Meanwhile, Mr Bennett sought to delay the lawsuit until after Mr Clinton's second term by invoking presidential immunity.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The strategy seemed to work. Most television networks and newspapers tiptoed around Mrs Jones's story. Mr Bennett's manoeuvres kept action on the substance of the allegations in check until after the 1996 elections.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But things are now changing, for two reasons. One is that the media are giving Mrs Jones's tale more credence, starting with a powerful article in the November issue of the <i>American Lawyer </i>by Stuart Taylor. Mr Taylor, a former sceptic about Mrs Jones's veracity, argued that her case gained credibility from corroborative interviews with two of her girlfriends in whom she says she had confided on the day of her encounter with Mr Clinton. Mr Taylor pointed to the absence of specific personal denials from Mr Clinton about what, if anything, happened between him and Mrs Jones. Mr Taylor also chided political commentators for hypocrisy; many, he said, had supported Anita Hill's "far less serious" allegations against Clarence Thomas, yet--apparently out of political or class bias--had failed to back Mrs Jones's "far stronger" case. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Journalists have been taking another look at Mrs Jones for a second reason: the march of the legal process. On January 13th, the Supreme Court heard arguments in the case of <i>William Jefferson Clinton v. Paula Corbin Jones</i>, a dispute with weighty constitutional implications. The court is not concerned about the substance of Mrs Jones's allegations, but about whether a sitting president should have temporary immunity from civil lawsuits relating to his unofficial acts. The Clinton side argues that Americans elect a full-time president, not a part-time litigant. Mrs Jones's lawyers argue against what they see as a dangerous extension of presidential privilege. A district judge ruled in December 1994 that Mr Clinton should not have to go to court while in office, but that lawyers could start interviewing witnesses, lest their memories fade. A year ago an appeals court, stressing the importance of equality under the law, said the case should proceed.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Supreme Court is expected to reach its decision by July. An outright victory for either side may be less likely than a compromise: delaying the trial, but allowing some pre-trial testimony to go ahead. If so, then Mr Clinton need not fear a verdict in the Paula Jones case, at least while president (even if Mrs Jones is telling the truth, it is not clear that she has a strong legal case for redress). But the case could still undermine his presidency through excruciating public humiliation and trial by television of "the character issue". That danger could prompt renewed efforts to reach a settlement. Then again, Mrs Jones seems keener than ever on having her day in court.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Starr-gazing</b></b><br>
James Carville, the soundbite-smearer of Paula Jones, recently set his sights on Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel. Soon after last November's election Mr Carville said he would form a group to spread information on the background and hidden agenda of Mr Starr, a Republican. The plan has since stalled, but the "ragin' Cajun" had achieved his aim of splashing publicity about. Whitewater-watchers interpreted the move as a warning to Mr Starr--and a sign of Clintonite worry.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton did nothing to discourage this bit of public intimidation. The president himself, in an interview before the election, had spoken of the "obvious" political aim of the probe. Whether they judged the matter too partisan, or just impenetrable, voters did not seem to worry much about Whitewater on polling day.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Is Whitewater really so complicated? Certainly it stretches far and wide. In Arkansas, the institutions and people involved include the Whitewater Development Corporation, the Clintons' failed land venture in the Ozarks; James and Susan McDougal, their former business partners; and Madison Guaranty, a McDougal-owned savings & loan institution which went expensively bust. In Washington, the net of accusation stretches from the firing of White House Travel Office staff to the events surrounding the 1993 suicide of Vincent Foster, the White House deputy counsel. It also embraces the improper gathering of more than 900 <font size=-1>FBI </font>files by the Clinton administration. Other than at moments of high drama, such as Hillary Clinton's appearance before a grand jury, the eyes glaze over in boredom and bafflement.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet at heart, Mr Starr told an audience in Detroit last November, Whitewater is not so difficult. It is about lies and fraud. These contributed to the demise of Madison Guaranty and helped lawyers, judges, politicians and business people in Arkansas borrow money for one purpose and use it for another. It is also about the integrity of government in Washington, including whether officials deceived Whitewater investigators. In short, said Mr Starr, it is about public trust.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So far, Mr Starr's efforts have led to guilty pleas by nine people, to the conviction in an Arkansas court of the McDougals, and to the conviction and resignation of Jim Guy Tucker, Mr Clinton's successor as governor. While friends and associates of the Clintons have tumbled, the first couple has yet to be accused of any wrongdoing. Is that about to change?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After 14 months of inquiry, Republicans on the Senate Whitewater Committee last June issued their conclusions, which told a tawdry tale with the First Lady as the central character. It spins a story of dubious legal work in 1985 when she was a partner in the Rose Law Firm in Little Rock; of apparent attempts to cover her tracks by ordering the destruction of records; of her pivotal role (concealed by loyal allies) in the handling of documents from Vince Foster's office after his death; and of her presumed involvement in the handling of long-sought billing records, which mysteriously resurfaced in the White House and which detail her work on a matter she had once denied under oath knowing anything much about. Yet looking at the same evidence, Democrats on the committee concluded, in their minority report: "No credible evidence has been put forward to show that Mrs Clinton engaged in any improper, much less illegal, conduct." <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Which side will Mr Starr come down on? The question is likely to be answered in 1997. For the Clintons, the possibilities range from the benign (vindication) to the embarrassing (a blistering report) all the way to the horrific (indictment of the First Lady for obstruction of justice).<br>
</p><p><b><b>The Asian money trail</b></b><br>
If neither the Paula Jones case nor Whitewater made much impact on last November's election, the more recent revelations about improper Asian contributions to the Democratic National Committee (<font size=-1>DNC</font>) did catch voters' imagination (see <a href="sf2.gif">table</a>).  But the stories came too late to make a decisive difference and the Democrats were adept at minimising the damage before polling day. Afterwards, under press scrutiny, the trickle of revelations became a torrent.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton and the Democrats needed lots of money for the election, and businessmen of Asian origin wanted lots of access to the president. It seemed like the perfect match, but for one tedious problem: the law. Political contributions from permanent residents using their own money are fine. So are donations out of money earned in the country by American-based subsidiaries of foreign firms. Other types of foreign contributions are not fine. In their push to raise a target of $7m last year from Asian-Americans, the Democrats accepted money from improper sources, including such bizarre conduits as the Hsi Lai Buddhist Temple in Hacienda Heights, California. Yet to be determined is whether these contributions were accepted as a result of lax vetting (the official claim) or as part of a deliberate strategy.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>DNC</font> has returned some $1.5m that it belatedly recognised to be against the rules. For example, it returned $325,000 to Yogesh Gandhi, an Indian-born Californian (who last May presented Mr Clinton with the 1996 "Mahatma Gandhi World Peace Award"). It returned $253,500 to Pauline Kanchanalak, a Washington-based consultant who brought her Thai-conglomerate clients to coffee with the president in the White House; $250,000 (since returned) bought a photo-opportunity with Mr Clinton for a South Korean entrepreneur with thoughts of building a factory in California.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The man who helped bring in much of the Asian money is John Huang, a Taiwanese-American and former employee in the Lippo empire of the Riady family, Indonesian businessmen with contacts to the president going back to his Arkansas days. Mr Huang, with a $900,000 pay-off from Lippo, joined the Commerce Department in 1994. In September 1995 he suggested to Mr Clinton that he be moved to a fund-raising post. In December he joined the <font size=-1>DNC</font> and energetically set about soliciting Asian-American donations.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Also energetic was another Taiwanese-American, Charlie Trie, whose Chinese restaurant in Little Rock Mr Clinton used to frequent. Last March, a few months after he learnt that the president would be appointing him to the Commission on United States-Pacific Trade and Investment Policy, Mr Trie dropped off two manila envelopes containing $450,000 in contributions from supposedly varied sources for the Clintons' legal-defence fund. The money has since been returned. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this and more gives congressional investigators (not to mention the Justice Department) plenty to get their teeth into. In the Senate, hearings will probably begin in March under the formidable chairmanship of Fred Thompson of Tennessee, a former Watergate counsel and possible Republican presidential contender in 2000. Dan Burton of Indiana, a confrontational conservative, will chair hearings in the House of Representatives.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How damaging could this be for Mr Clinton? Very, if he is shown to have knowingly played a part in illicit fund-raising, or to have helped provide a specific <i>quid pro quo--</i>such as favourable policy decisions-- in return for Asian money. But any such knowledge or linkage, even if they existed, would be hard to prove. Meanwhile, Mr Clinton can seek to rise above the row by calling for campaign-finance reform.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Still, it smells bad. Americans do not take kindly to the idea of foreign money polluting their politics. Like the other scandals, this one promises to be both embarrassing and distracting for the president.<br>
</p><p><b><b>The politics of scandalitis</b></b><br>
Although the outcome of all three categories of scandal remains unclear, the political peril for Mr Clinton is all too obvious. Scandals threaten to devalue that precious but volatile commodity called political capital. A run of scandals can have much the same effect on a presidency as a run on a currency: it can send it into freefall.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"A president in his second term really has only his first year--his fifth year in office--to be creative," says Stephen Hess, a presidential scholar at the Brookings Institution. His plans are ready, his staff is up to speed, he has the legislative initiative. By his sixth year, Congress is preoccupied with its mid-term election. Thereafter, the president is a lame duck. Alas for Mr Clinton, all the scandals are crowding together in his fifth year. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For a president elected with less than half the popular vote, who is owed little debt of loyalty among Democrats in Congress, and who scores poorly with the public on matters of "trust", this looks especially worrying. Mr Clinton is vulnerable. But he is also resilient. And he knows that this year could well be the one that defines his entire presidency.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
