</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>The mistaken temptation of tax cuts</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>The mistaken temptation of tax cuts</h1>

<font size=1>WASHINGTON, DC</font><p>
THE inaugural podium outside the White House will barely be dismantled before Bill Clinton begins the first big battle of his second term. On February 6th the president presents his budget to Congress, beginning the months of horse-trading and hubris that mark America's fiscal process. It will, he promises, be a "credible" budget, and one that reaches fiscal balance by 2002. What he does not add is that on many counts it will be a bad budget, with a smorgasbord of tax breaks that make budget balance harder to achieve, complicate the tax code yet further, and yield scant economic benefits.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is a disappointment. A year ago, the debate in Washington was all about tax reform. Inspired by the Republicans, the idea was to simplify the tax code in ways that would promote economic growth. The proposals were radical; the goals laudable. No longer. Mr Clinton's tax-cutting ideas stem from his budget proposals of last year and from assorted campaign promises. Unlike the irresponsible Bob Dole, who proposed enormous across-the-board tax cuts (though also tax reform), candidate Clinton had more modest suggestions. They included a $500 child tax credit, deductions and tax credits for post-secondary education, an expansion of tax-based saving incentives and the removal of capital-gains taxes on $500,000 of gain from the sale of a home. Tax cuts, the administration pledged, would be safe, would be paid for and would target sensible goals such as education and saving.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Given these promises, Mr Clinton's budget is unlikely to yield many surprises, at least on the tax side. The total tax-cut bill is likely to be around $100 billion over the next five years. (Much of this, supposedly, will be offset by the extension of expired excise taxes and the closing of corporate loopholes). Although the exact price-tag of each initiative is still unclear, they will all be included. The administration takes the need for tax relief as a given. Politically, it is easy to see why. Mr Clinton would find it difficult to break campaign promises to cut taxes a second time. He did, after all, run on a promise to cut middle-class taxes in 1992, only to raise them--on the richest--in 1993. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nonetheless, many of this year's potential tax goodies are policy mistakes. Take the child tax credit first. The idea, at least in last year's version, was to give middle-and lower-income taxpayers a $500 tax credit for every child under 13. It would benefit around 19m families with 37m children. No one pretends that this tax break will have any growth-enhancing effects. It will erode the tax base, without any guarantee that families will even spend the extra money on children. Worse, it will not even help the neediest families, since they already pay no income tax. For all its pro-family posturing, this credit is no more than a middle-class tax break.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Evidence of the economic logic behind Mr Clinton's proposed tuition tax breaks is just as elusive. Two ideas are on the table: a $10,000 tax deduction per family for college tuition fees, and a $1,500-per-child tax credit for the first two years of college. To be eligible for the tuition tax credit, a student must earn at least a "B" average in college and stay away from drugs. The suggestion sounds good. American colleges are expensive, and investing in education is surely a valid fiscal priority. But that does not mean that these proposals are the best way to spend scarce federal dollars.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For a start, it is not clear that college education, rather than, say, pre-school or primary education, is where extra money is most required. Nor is it clear that either tax credits or deductions will spur more people to study. They are just as likely to provide an extra tax subsidy for those people who would have gone to college anyway. Some experts worry that the tuition tax credit will simply pass through into higher college fees or smaller financial-aid packages. And, besides all that, the education tax-relief proposals are bedevilled with practical difficulties, as a detailed analysis in a recent edition of <i>Tax Notes</i>, a specialist tax-policy magazine, points out. Take the need for a "B" average to qualify for tuition credit, for instance. Will this be defined by tax year or by academic year? Will summer school be included? And what will stop a general inflation of college grades so that every student earns a "B" average? <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton's next idea is to help home-owners. By removing up to $500,000 of gain on house sales from capital-gains tax, he would make life simpler for those who worry about moving to a smaller property (capital-gains taxes are currently deferred if you buy a house of greater or equal value). But again the economic benefits are doubtful. Since mortgage interest is tax-deductible in America, residential housing already receives a huge tax subsidy. The case for expanding it is far from obvious.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Superficially, the idea of expanding Individual Retirement Accounts (<font size=-1>IRA</font>s) looks more sensible. These are special savings accounts to which individuals can contribute a certain amount each year tax-free. Taxes are due only when the savings are withdrawn at retirement. The idea is to make more people eligible for <font size=-1>IRA</font>s, to loosen the rules for withdrawal of savings (so that people could use their <font size=-1>IRA</font> savings for, say, the purchase of a first home, without incurring financial penalties), and, perhaps, to introduce a new type of "backloaded" <font size=-1>IRA</font>, on which taxes are paid up front, but which are tax-free upon withdrawal. If these incentives spur people to save more than they otherwise would, then <font size=-1>IRA</font>s could, in theory, help to raise America's paltry personal savings rate. Though economists are divided on this, there is not much evidence that they have a big impact. Rather, expanded <font size=-1>IRA</font>s will probably give yet more tax breaks to people who do not need them and will further complicate the tax code.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps the best that can be said of the administration's tax proposals is that they will be more modest than the Republicans'. Congressional Republicans have lost much of their tax-cutting extremism, but still look likely to go for bigger tax and spending cuts than Mr Clinton. They, too, want to extend <font size=-1>IRA</font>s and like the child tax credit. Education tax relief they are less keen on, largely because it is so closely identified with Mr Clinton. But many Republicans would like to see a much broader reduction in capital-gains taxes than Mr Clinton proposes. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Just as expanding <font size=-1>IRA</font>s might increase saving, so reducing capital-gains taxes could spur investment. But even here the potential economic impact is often overrated. One estimate of the effect of halving the capital-gains tax to 14% (as Bob Dole proposed) was that investment might rise by 0.2% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>. Cutting capital-gains taxes also raises asset prices: not an obviously sensible thing to encourage with the stockmarket at dizzying heights. Moreover, its benefits accrue overwhelmingly to the top 5% of taxpayers. Aside from its expense, the most powerful argument against a big capital-gains tax cut is that it reopens the attraction of tax shelters, through which high-income taxpayers exploit a large difference between their marginal rate of income tax and the rate of capital-gains tax.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Washington's budget pundits reckon, however, that the final budget package will include some capital-gains tax cuts, probably in return for some of the president's education tax relief proposals. In fact the only constraint on a bipartisan bonanza of tax cuts is the commitment to a balanced budget by 2002 and disagreements on the depth of potential spending cuts. The goal of simplifying America's tax code, let alone truly reforming it, has receded fast. <br>
<br>

<p align=center>
