<html><head><title>Teddy Roosevelt rides again</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Teddy Roosevelt rides again</h1>

FOUR years ago, as he prepared for his inaugural address, Bill Clinton was inspired by Woodrow Wilson. The inspiration served mainly to keep Mr Clinton's speech short and to the point: Wilson's opening line was, "There has been a change of government." This time, Mr Clinton has a different predecessor in mind. On January 20th, when he gives his second inaugural speech, the ghost at his elbow will be Theodore Roosevelt. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is easy to see Roosevelt's attraction. When he became president in 1901 he was a dashing 42-year-old, younger even than first-term Clinton. He was passionate and sharp; of one opponent he said, "Every time he opens his mouth, he subtracts from the sum total of human wisdom." And he exuded superhuman energy. Before becoming president, he commanded a cavalry unit called the Rough Riders; like Shakespeare's Henry V, he would spend the night before a battle circulating among his men and brooding on life's great questions. Roosevelt even appeals to Mr Clinton's sentimental side. The president, when in family-values mode, likes to boast of how he read stories to his daughter when she was young. Roosevelt recited the Song of Roland in French to his children.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is not just Roosevelt's personality that appeals to Mr Clinton. The president has recently seized upon the idea, peddled by E.J. Dionne of the <i>Washington Post</i> a year ago, that America's current challenges resemble those faced by Roosevelt. Then, a farm economy was giving way to a new factory age. Now, a shift of similar size is under way, as factories cede dominance to information industries. Then, Roosevelt worried that new means of communication--the telegraph, the telephone, the high-speed press--were flooding small-town America with disruptive ideas. Now, Mr Clinton fears Hollywood's corrupting influence on family life, and fights porn on the Internet. Then, as now, Americans worried that the vast wealth spawned by technological advance would be unevenly distributed.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a perverse way, Mr Clinton delights in this mix of technological shift, moral upheaval and growing class resentments. In both eras, to be sure, fast change undermined conventional politicians. Republicans and Democrats alike were riven by internal disputes; third parties (the Populists then, the Perotistas now) sprang up to challenge their duopoly. But Roosevelt took advantage of all this flux. He embraced a new vision of government for a new age, and so secured his place in history.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton fancies he can do the same. The dawn of the information age presents a challenge of respectable size, and so a chance to be remembered. It also makes a virtue of many unpopular Clinton traits. Mr Clinton has stolen his opponents' ideas, betrayed his own party's ideals, talked big and acted modestly. But Teddy Roosevelt, facing similar economic flux, did these things too. Indeed (and here you can almost see the Clinton visage glow), the refashioning of established party views is the essence of flux-surfing greatness.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Teddy Roosevelt (unlike his cousin, Franklin) was a Republican, and the Republicans of his time had little taste for economic regulation. But Roosevelt stole the Populists' anti-business ideas, arguing that the new concentrations of industrial power needed to be checked by a newly powerful government. He created the Commerce Department; he imposed the first federal rules on railways, drugs and meat; he founded the National Parks Service and quadrupled the federal government's land holdings. He promised Americans a "square deal", spawning a long line of slogans ("new deal", "fair deal", "great society") that sold successive expansions in government.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton, for his part, sits atop a Democratic Party long fond of big government and indifferent to big deficits. But, like Roosevelt, Mr Clinton has stolen his opponents' views, arguing that the information revolution makes old Democratic ideas obsolete. Just as computers have compelled big companies to shed staff, so the era of big government is over. Just as conglomerates are giving way to networking firms, so government should form partnerships with private groups to improve schools and slum housing. Just as business can be done by Internet or telephone, so the Clinton administration takes pride in its web sites and 1-800 numbers. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To Mr Clinton's most hopeful supporters, this has the makings of a history-sized idea. Since the 1980s, they maintain, Republicans have wisely tried to slow government's growth, but have lacked a balancing vision of government's potential. Mr Clinton, they say, has a chance to make government leaner and more helpful at once. Computers allow smaller government to do more. Public-private partnerships allow Mr Clinton to cut welfare payments to poor mothers, while at the same time badgering business to find jobs for them. And Mr Clinton can also slim government spending by demanding more from those whom government assists. "A man can occasionally be helped when he stumbles, &#91;but not&#93; when he will not or cannot walk," Roosevelt declared. The words could almost have been Mr Clinton's. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These ideas may make for a grand inaugural address. Yet there is a darker side to the Roosevelt analogy. As he founded America's regulatory state, Roosevelt said, "I am for men and not for property," and "I rank dividends below human character." Mr Clinton can be equally guilty of seeing false conflicts between human well-being and capitalism. As he promised a new kind of government, Roosevelt side-stepped pressing but less glamorous issues such as the tariff. Mr Clinton is a side-stepper as well. He may want to refocus government on helping those who help themselves. But he shows little sign, in the coming budget fight, of cutting the other things that government now does. Mr Clinton's surest route to history lies not in techno-talk. It lies in tackling middle-class entitlements with the courage of Roosevelt's Rough Riders. <br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
