<html><head><title>Political plaything</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Education</b></p>
<h1>Political plaything</h1>

IT WAS a packed press conference, with reporters from almost every national newspaper and broadcasting network. The minister sat down in front of the bank of microphones and announced, "I am here to outline the government's policy on homework." The fact that Robin Squire, an education minister, felt compelled, on January 14th, to make such a high-profile pronouncement on such a matter of fine detail shows how big an issue education has become in the run-up to the general election. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ministers had hoped to wrest the initiative on education policy from Labour by unveiling at the press conference a study showing that the most successful schools are the ones that set the most homework. But two days earlier, Tony Blair, Labour's leader, upstaged them by announcing that a Labour government's first piece of legislation would be an education bill, including national guidelines on homework.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Curiously, education has become a hot political topic just as the differences between the two main parties have narrowed. This is mostly due to Labour's big policy shift since Mr Blair became its leader. Having opposed most of the government's education reforms, Labour now accepts the need for a national curriculum, and for the regular testing of pupils and inspection of schools. It no longer argues that inadequate public spending is the main cause of educational under-achievement. Only the Liberal Democrats still say this.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even the biggest remaining difference between Labour and the Tories--over selective schools--is overstated. Labour opposes the government's plans for more grammar schools, which select their pupils by overall academic ability. But it would let schools specialising in, say, music or languages give preference to pupils with a flair for those subjects. And existing grammar schools would not be abolished unless parents demanded it. For their part, many Tories oppose academic selection because it means that they cannot ensure their children a place at a good state school merely by buying a house nearby.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite this convergence on policy, education is at the top of the political agenda because it is one of the few areas in which both parties can promise change without pledging much extra money. Moreover in recent years the government has given itself unprecedented powers over what schools teach. These reforms have also resulted in far more data being published on the performance of schools, colleges and universities, providing a steady stream of new information to fuel people's concerns. There has also been an increasing number of international studies highlighting the weaknesses of British schools compared with those in other countries.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Finally, there is the current atmosphere of concern about morality and the need to build a more cohesive society. The most obvious institution for affecting this is the family, but politicians have learnt to their cost how difficult and dangerous it is to dabble in "family values", so the education system is the next best means to this end.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is a drawback to the parties' sudden enthusiasm for education. Micromanagement of schools by central government is a recipe for disaster. And the scramble to appear to have distinctive policies in spite of the broad consensus is already leading to bad decisions. For instance, the government rushed through the introduction of its nursery-vouchers scheme, so that parents will get their &#163;1,100 voucher by polling day. Labour prematurely dismissed vouchers just because the Tories favour them. Both should have waited for the results of the current pilot schemes for nursery vouchers before making their minds up. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But overall, it is welcome that after years of neglect politicians now take an interest in the state of Britain's schools. The bi-partisan agreement means that, after the election, there is likely to be a great deal of continuity in the way schools are run. And the next government, whichever party wins, will be under great pressure to live up to its promises, and to get to grips with Britain's poor educational record.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
