<html><head><title>Bliss and bother</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Liberal Democrats</b></p>
<h1>Bliss and bother</h1>

BLISS is it to be a politician when self-interest and conviction coincide. Bliss is it therefore to be Paddy Ashdown, the leader of the Liberal Democrats. Mr Ashdown believes in spending on public services, and in levying the taxes to pay for them. But, with Labour and the Conservatives both insisting they will keep taxes and spending down, he has also spotted a niche market among consumers and producers of public services for a party that articulates that belief--as he did in a thoughtful speech on January 15th.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"The next election is being turned into an auction of fantasy promises in which the Labour and Conservative parties try to outbid each other with bigger and better promises of tax cuts which no one believes," he said. "What people want is better services--and the knowledge that the taxes they pay are being wisely spent." He repeated a promise to give education &#163;2 billion extra a year, financed, "if necessary, with an extra penny on income tax". He also promised free eye and dental checks, paid for by 5p a packet on cigarettes.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Ashdown deserves some credit for standing apart from the auction of "fantasy promises" by the other two parties. And he has tried to offer some genuinely new ideas. For example, in his speech he proposed that the National Audit Office and the Audit Commission work together to "monitor rigorously every extra pound spent to see that it raises standards, improves services and gives the taxpayer real value for money." The aim is to stop the money leaking out into more bureaucracy, or unjustified pay rises for public-service workers.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This proposal, however, bristles with difficulties. The National Audit Office is at present concerned with financial propriety rather than with efficiency, although the Audit Commission, which looks at local authorities' spending, is more efficiency-oriented. It would be difficult for either body to focus on what the extra pounds of spending will buy without also looking at what existing budgets are buying. How could anyone tell whether a school that is building a new classroom was using Mr Ashdown's new money for it, or simply using money from its existing budget?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, Mr Ashdown seems to envisage "ring-fencing" the new money, so that local councils are forced to spend it on education rather than on, say, roads. But councils, and Liberal Democrat-controlled councils in particular, value their right to set their own priorities. It is called local democracy, and it used to have no more passionate supporter than Paddy Ashdown. <br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?853549200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
