<html><head><title>Bye Bye?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Politics</b></p>
<h1>Bye Bye?</h1>

AFTER much havering, the Tories have decided to risk a by-election before the general election in the vacant seat of Wirral South. It will take place by March 6th. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To duck the contest would have been risky. Barry Porter, the local <font size=-1>MP</font>, died on November 3rd. Delaying the by-election for months until the general election would have defied parliamentary convention. At best, the Tories would have seemed cowardly. At worst, the Commons might have defied them by voting to hold the by-election anyway.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But even if the Tories were prepared to run that risk, standing and fighting makes better sense. If they hold on, they will be able to claim momentum. If they lose, the general election is almost certainly beyond them anyway.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The seat is no pushover for Labour. There are 98 other Conservative seats that are more vulnerable. In last May's local elections, Labour polled more votes in Wirral South than the Tories but only just: an extra 0.8% of the vote, with the Liberal Democrats a further 12.3% adrift.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour requires a swing of 8.1% to win. Although this is far lower than the swing of 22.1% in the last Labour-versus-Tory contest in Staffordshire South East last April, close to the election things are tougher. If Labour achieved an 8.1% swing at the general election, it would have an overall majority in the Commons of 65 or more. Labour could easily fail to take Wirral South and still win the general election.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If the Tories lose, however, their general-election chances will be remote. A detailed analysis of the last by-elections before a general election since 1951 by John Curtice of the Centre for Research into Elections and Social Trends, which conducts academic research on voting, shows that no government has won after suffering an adverse swing of more than 5% in the last by-election. Indeed, unless the result at Wirral South suggests that the government is no more than two percentage points behind Labour nationally, precedent suggests that the Tories will lose.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This sounds right. In mid-term by-elections, voters register protest votes against the government. Towards the end, they focus on choosing who rules. Moreover, governments generally recover support nationally as general elections approach. This should be reflected in by-election results.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By-election failures late in a Parliament have been omens of disaster for big parties in the past. In 1983, Labour went down to general-election defeat months after losing Bermondsey, where the party chose a controversial candidate. It then managed to repeat the trick in Greenwich in 1987. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But success in by-elections does not guarantee success in general elections. Labour lost in 1992, despite winning the Langbaurgh by-election in 1991. And, should John Major feel tempted to go to the country at once if he wins in Wirral, he should remember what happened to his distinguished predecessor, Benjamin Disraeli. He rushed to the country in 1880 following a Tory win in a by-election in Southwark. At the general election, he lost.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?853549200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="br7688.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
