</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Jam tomorrow</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Road traffic</b></p>
<h1>Jam tomorrow</h1>

EVERY political party in Britain acknowledges that traffic congestion is already intolerable. None dares propose even the smallest measure of restraint. A mass rally of Parliament by environmental groups on January 22nd will seek to persuade politicians that it could be even worse to do nothing. <br>
<PARA>The rally coincides with a private member's bill, introduced by Don Foster, the Liberal Democrat <font size=-1>MP</font> for Bath, requiring the government to achieve a 10% reduction in traffic miles by 2010. A parliamentary motion backing the bill has attracted the support of nearly a third of all <font size=-1>MP</font>s. The target is an extremely tough one. Current official forecasts predict that road mileage will increase by at least 27-44% over the next 15 years. <br> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Achieving Mr Foster's target is probably impossible without widespread road pricing. But that is still a long way off. In the meantime, traffic growth could be restrained by higher petrol duties. Two years ago, the Royal Commission on Environmental Pollution was widely criticised when it suggested that fuel duties should be raised so as to double the price at the pump within a decade. The commission is reconsidering this recommendation for its second report which is due to be published this summer--after the general election. Whichever party is in government by then, the commission should stick to its guns. Increasing the cost of petrol and diesel is an important element of any sensible approach to curbing traffic growth. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government's promise to increase fuel duties by 5% in real terms each year in part recognises this. But the actual increase in pump prices has averaged less than 1% over the past three years because of weak oil prices and intense retail competition. Raising duties by 9% a year, as the commission recommended, would send a much clearer signal to the market (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>). It would also help curb pollution, although the government can meet its pollution target--reducing the level of greenhouse gases to the 1990 level by 2000--without higher duties because of the decline in coal usage. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The scope for raising fuel duties is considerable. Pump prices are currently at their lowest post-tax level since the early 1960s. British prices are also low compared with the rest of Europe. The average price of unleaded petrol in Britain is 62p a litre compared with Italy (72p), Holland (71p), France (71p), and Belgium (69p). A study published last month by the Automobile Association found that the proportion of an average household's gross income required to own and operate a car has fallen by 40% since 1964. At the same time the fixed costs of owning a car such as insurance and vehicle duty have increased relative to the running costs--precisely the wrong signal to encourage restraint. The widely touted view that raising fuel duties would have no effect on traffic growth is not borne out by research. Studies suggest that a 10% increase in fuel prices would result in a 7% fall in petrol use. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Using higher fuel prices to restrain traffic is a cruder instrument than road pricing. But road pricing is years away, at best. Even with road pricing, the level of fuel duties would have a big impact on traffic growth. Without road pricing--or direct measures such as restricting the number of parking places--higher duties are just about the only tool left to restrain traffic growth. Higher duties might be more easily sold to the public if the Treasury would waive its traditional objections to hypothecation and allow the proceeds--roughly &#163;1 billion a year for each 5% increase--to be spent on improving public transport. <br><br>

<p align=center>
