<html><head><title>The Heathrow of the north</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Airports</b></p>
<h1>The Heathrow of the north</h1>

<font size=1>MANCHESTER</font><p>
NOT many decisions by the government raise a cheer in the north of England, but the announcement on January 15th that Manchester airport could build a second runway did. Graham Stringer, a Manchester councillor and chairman of the airport company, proclaimed that the &#163;172m construction project was the most significant boost to the region's economy since the Manchester ship canal was built in the 19th century. The airport--owned by ten Labour-controlled councils which stand to make a handsome profit if the airport is privatised--says that it will be able to double the number of passengers it handles to 30m by 2005. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Less delighted, however, are people who live near the airport, and environmental protesters, who argued at a nine-month public inquiry that the noise and damage to Manchester's green belt was too high a price to pay. John Gummer, the environment secretary, decided that jobs were a more pressing concern.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The economy of the north-west, which stretches from Cheshire to the Scottish border, badly needs a shot in the arm. A study by Cambridge Econometrics in 1995 forecast that in the next decade it would have the lowest rates of economic growth and job creation of any region in Britain apart from Northern Ireland. The north-west also lags well behind Scotland, Wales, the north-east and the Midlands in the amount of foreign investment it attracts.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A report prepared for Manchester airport by York Consulting in 1991 reckoned that building a second runway would be the biggest single thing that could be done to improve the region's economy. It reckoned that adding 15m passengers would create 15,000 jobs at the airport and another 30,000 in firms servicing it. The indirect effects would be bigger still.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The airport confidently expects a big increase in direct flights to European and other international destinations, which should also reduce the number of its passengers who have to make connections at London's airports. This, says Samantha Grief, assistant director of <font size=-1>CBI</font> in the north-west, is why local businessmen have been enthusiastic about the second runway. Many of them, she claims, have delayed expanding their businesses until a decision had been made.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However Mr Gummer's decision is a blow to other regional airports, which will find it difficult to expand if Manchester becomes a northern Heathrow. Manchester's nearest rival, Liverpool airport, had put forward a plan, supported by those opposed to expansion at Manchester, to rebuild its runway and expand passenger numbers from 625,000 in 1996 to 12m by 2030.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Rod Hill, director of Liverpool airport, says he has now ditched this plan. Together with the announcement by Ford on January 16th that it is to cut 1,300 of the 4,500 car assembly jobs at Halewood on the outskirts of Liverpool--raising fears that the factory might be closed altogether in a few years-- Manchester's good news caused nothing but gloom on Merseyside. More than a century ago Manchester mill owners dealt Liverpool a crushing economic blow when they built the Manchester ship canal to avoid high cargo-handling charges at Liverpool's docks. Manchester looks set to do it once again.<br>
<br>

