<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<p><b>Dubious privilege</b> &nbsp; The House of Commons Standards and Privileges Committee summoned Andrew Mitchell, the social-security minister, to testify under oath about his role two years ago in the cash-for-questions scandal. David Willetts, the former Paymaster General, resigned last month after being criticised by the committee for giving less than frank evidence.<br>
<p><b>Nuclear leak &nbsp; </b>A &#163;2 billion project to dispose of Britain's nuclear waste is in doubt. The chief scientist for Nirex, the company in charge of the scheme, said in a leaked memo that it might have to be abandoned.<br>
<p><b>Courting criticism</b> &nbsp; Sir Richard Scott, the head of the civil justice system, condemned increases in court fees for civil suits imposed by Lord Mackay, the Lord Chancellor, complaining that they would restrict access to justice.<br>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Jail break</b> &nbsp; Douglas Hurd, a former Tory home secretary, agreed to become chairman of the Prison Reform Trust, a lobbying group which in the past has attacked the government's prison policy.<br>
<p><b>Plagued</b> &nbsp; Scientists studying the new form of Creutztfeld-Jakob Disease, thought to be caused by eating meat from cattle infected with "mad-cow" disease, have predicted an epidemic of anything from 75 to 80,000 cases.<br>
<p><b>Millennial fears</b> &nbsp; Millennium Central, the organiser of the planned Millennium Exhibition at Greenwich, cut its proposed budget by &#163;120m to &#163;580m amid complaints of extravagance from Tory backbenchers. The scheme still requires &#163;200m of lottery funding and &#163;60m of business sponsorship.<br>
<p><b>Beer belly</b> &nbsp; A researcher was forced to cancel a lecture entitled "Beer, women, football and curry" because of an upset stomach. He claims his illness was brought on by the stress of writing.<br>

</td></tr></table></center>

