</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Remind me one more time . . .</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width="371" height="26" alt="Science and Technology" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Remind me one more time . . .</h1>

<p><b>The weight of evidence is turning strongly against the theory that traumatic memories of sexual abuse are repressed in childhood and can be "recovered" in later life with the help of a therapist</b></p><br>
FROM the age of seven to the age of 14, as Beth Rutherford remembered it, her father regularly raped her. Sometimes her mother helped him by holding her down. After impregnating her twice, her father, a clergyman, forced her to abort the fetus herself--both times with a coat hanger. Her therapist, a church counsellor named Donna Strand, in whose care Miss Rutherford retrieved these awful events from her memory, told the church elders of the accusations. Mr Rutherford was dismissed and both parents were sent for psychiatric help. But upon examination it was found that Miss Rutherford had never had an abortion. She had never even been pregnant. In fact, she was one of the few 22-year-old virgins in Texas. In 1995, she retracted her allegations and in November 1996 she won a $1m settlement from her therapist.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Psychoanalysts have a bad reputation with other scientists for making up untestable propositions, dressing them up with fancy names, and diagnosing people as suffering from them. This is not always justified, of course--and even when it is, the guilty parties are often fringe practitioners like Donna Strand. But "recovered-memory therapy"--the sort Ms Strand was practising--looks like a particularly black mark against the profession's name.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The theory behind the therapy suggests that memories of repeated traumatic experiences--particularly sexual abuse during childhood--can be totally repressed, even as they occur. In the worst cases, alternative personalities will be created to guard such memories from the outside world. Only in the hands of a therapist can the events be recalled, the <i>alter ego</i> revealed, and the trauma truly purged.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Scarcely a shred of real evidence supports this proposition. Nevertheless, proponents of recovered-memory therapy have managed to get courts of law in several countries to accept such "memories" as evidence. There are people in prison who have been convicted solely on the basis of alleged (but previously unrecalled) memories of events that took place decades in the past. Indeed, 28 American states have extended their statutes of limitation to allow such cases to be brought. In extreme cases the process has come to resemble the witch trials of 17th-century Europe and America: mere accusation has become proof of guilt.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Do, do, do, do, do you remember?</b></b><br>
The central proposition of recovered-memory therapy is fairly simple. According to Lenore Terr, a pyschiatrist and author of "Unchained Memories", one of the most influential books on the subject, there are two types of trauma. Type-<font size=-1>I</font> traumas are one-off. A terrible single event--a car crash, say--leads to sharp and accurate memories. Type-<font size=-1>II</font> traumas are serial--such as sex abuse that goes on regularly for years. The brain's response to such continuous assault is to push the memory away. In effect, the more frequently some awful thing happens, the less likely someone is to remember it. And the forgetting happens quickly. In one case a woman was said to have been raped in the cellar and to have forgotten the whole thing by the time she had reached the top of the steps. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This kind of repression is different from traumatic amnesia, a widely acknowledged phenomenon in which, say, a soldier in combat or a rape victim may never form a memory of a particularly horrifying portion of their experience. Since no memory is formed in the first place, nothing can ever be recalled in future.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As a speculation, recovered-memory theory is intriguing. Unfortunately it is not backed up by the sort of evidence that science demands. The woolliness of the subject is illustrated by the diverse and contradictory symptoms (depending on whom you consult) that are said to indicate a repressed memory. Sexual promiscuity is one. Not being interested in sex is another. Liking bananas is indicative. So is not liking them. Eczema, nightmares, daydreaming, low self-esteem, aversion to gynaecological examinations, anorexia, over-eating and (perhaps inevitably) denying the possibility of abuse are all seen as symptomatic of unrecovered memories.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This list speaks of confusion. But there is a more damning case against the idea that traumatic memories can be suppressed, and then reliably recovered. A large number of experiments by academic psychologists have attacked the theory's basic assumptions.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One of the most important of these assumptions is that recovered memories are not influenced by the process of recovery. Experimental psychologists have, however, shown how easy it is to alter recollection of real events, and to implant memories of false ones.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Elizabeth Loftus, of the University of Washington, in Seattle, demonstrated this in a series of experiments whose results have been published over the past two years. Her first experiments involved showing a group of people a simulated, fairly dramatic event, such as a crime or a car crash. After the simulation, half the group was offered new (and misleading) information in conversation about the event; the other half was not.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When asked to recall the incident, those who had been given the additional, wrong information--for example by having a blue car referred to as white--were many times more likely to get it wrong. The conclusion is that it is possible to use misleading information to create false memories after the fact. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another of Dr Loftus's experiments involved giving 24 people a booklet containing four stories supposed to be about events from their childhood. Three of the stories were true (they had been obtained from other family members). One, however, was a false account of getting lost at a specific place and time. The subjects were asked to read all the accounts; then they were given a week to write what they remembered. Seven of them "remembered" the fictional account of getting lost as true. Indeed, the more they talked about it, the greater the level of detail they thought that they recalled: which shop it happened in; what they were wearing; who found them and so on.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such suggestibility is not found only in the laboratory. In 1988, Paul Ingram, a police officer in Olympia, Washington, was accused of a series of horrifying misdeeds. He was said to have raped his children, forced them to have sex with animals, and even to have indulged in cannibalism. After appearing to go into a trance, Mr Ingram could hardly confess fast enough. Eventually he recalled his vocation as a high priest of Satan. When Richard Ofshe, of the University of California, Berkeley, (who is an expert on cults, and a critic of repressed-memory theory) was brought into the case, he was struck by Mr Ingram's readiness to spill the beans. As a test, he proposed a false memory--that Mr Ingram made his children have sex with each other while he watched. Mr Ingram promptly confessed to that, too, even adding descriptive details and bits of dialogue. Despite Dr Ofshe's intervention, though, Mr Ingram pleaded guilty. He is still in prison.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another assumption of repressed-memory theorists is that recollection is always accurate (even, as psychologists might add, in the absence of suggestion). This has been challenged experimentally by Ulric Neisser, a psychologist at Emory University, in Georgia. A day after the explosion of the space-shuttle <i>Challenger</i> in 1986, Dr Neisser asked his first-year students to write down where they were when they heard the news, what they were doing, and who told them about the accident. Three years later, he tracked down 44 of them and asked them again. None got all three questions right; 11 got all of them wrong.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A third assumption is that a child's memories are as reliable as an adult's. This is not true. Stephen Ceci, of Cornell University, has documented how easy it is to make children spin an elaborate tale (a trait to which most parents can readily attest). And very young children do not have the capability to carry memories of specific experiences into adulthood. The reason seems to be that the hippocampus, a part of the brain that is important for the formation of long-term explicit memories (as opposed to implicit ones, such as how to walk) takes time to develop. Until it matures (normally after the age of two), experiences do not get stored in a way that makes it possible for them to be recalled in adulthood. But many repressed-memory allegations, such as the accusation by Roseanne Arnold, an American actress, that both of her parents started sexually abusing her when she was six months old, are based on this claim.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Advocates of recovered-memory therapy dismiss such studies on the grounds that they do not deal with truly traumatic memories. But they offer little evidence of their own to prove the possibility of total, instant repression of repeated trauma. And the little that scientists do think they know about traumatic memory contradicts them.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The current thinking is that in a traumatic situation, the brain's "flight-or-fight reaction" is triggered. This releases two hormones, adrenaline and noradrenaline, which act on (among other things) nerve cells in the brain in a way that "burns" the incident into the memory. What may be happening is that these hormones stimulate a structure called the amygdala. This is believed to be the brain's emotional processor. Thus soldiers who suffer from post-traumatic stress disorder (or shell-shock, as it was first described) may have their memories triggered via the amygdala when they see something they associate with their experiences. The problem is not that they cannot remember, but that they cannot forget.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is other, more circumstantial, evidence of the dubiousness of repressed memories. One is the curious fact that while in proven cases of abuse, a sibling is the perpetrator in 13 instances out of 14, in the 900 cases of repressed memories brought to court in America, fewer than 1% alleged sibling abuse. Another is the sheer unbelievability of many of the allegations. Dozens of people have "recovered" memories of being abducted by aliens, and roughly one in five accusers included Satanic ritual abuse such as baby-breeding, cannibalism, blood drinking and infanticide among their charges--another curious echo of the 17th century.<br>
</p><p><b><b>The windmills of your mind</b></b><br>
Against the weight of this evidence, there is but one credible study that repressed-memory advocates frequently put in the balance. Linda Williams, of the University of New Hampshire, tracked down 129 women who had been brought to a city hospital to be treated for sexual abuse. Asked 17 years later about the reason that they had ended up in hospital, 38% of these women failed to report that it was a result of abuse. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This striking result is often taken as proof of repressed memory. But it is hardly that. First, the study did not say how young the women were at the time of the abuse. All those under two, and many of those under five, would not remember it for perfectly ordinary reasons. Second, it does not address the core belief of recovered-memory theory, which is that it is sustained abuse which triggers loss of memory. Almost three-quarters of the sample were brought in as the consequence of a one-off assault. Third, and perhaps most telling, most of those who did not report the particular incident that hospitalised them could nevertheless recall other abusive incidents.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This suggests, reasonably enough, that if victims are subjected to a lot of abuse, they may not remember every instance. It does not suggest that they are responding in a type-<font size=-1>II</font> way by repressing everything immediately. Mostly, then, Dr Williams's study confirms something that is already widely known: people forget things. They sometimes even forget very unpleasant things.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But they do not do so systematically. There is no empirical evidence for massive repression of memories of child abuse of the type hypothesised. Indeed, when James Hudson and Harrison Pope, two psychiatrists at Harvard University, did a computer search of the scientific literature in 1995 to find cases in which patients had survived a known traumatic event, repressed it for years, and then remembered it, they could not authenticate a single case.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Strong claims require strong evidence-- particularly when those claims are destroying families and putting people in prison. Alas, the evidence for recovered-memory theory can barely even be described as weak. Child abuse is certainly an evil whose existence was ignored for too long. That is no excuse for ignoring science to pretend to find more of it than actually exists.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
