<html><head><title>Can you trust it?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"> <table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img
src="../images/mo.gif" width="157" height="26" alt="Moreover" border=0> <td align=right valign=top><img
src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Electronic conflicts of interest</b></p> <h1>Can you trust it?</h1>

FOR readers of Suck, a daily column of vituperation published on the Internet, a column published nearly 15 months ago shows the best
and the worst of the Internet.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In it, Suck exposed an attempt by the Time Warner media
empire to copy it. The latter's Pathfinder site, it discovered, was constructing a feeble look-alike--but had cluelessly left its prototype
open to the world, as Suck demonstrated by publishing the address. This was guerrilla journalism at its best, evidence that the Internet
had spawned a new class of journalistic outsiders and armed them to outdo the greatest media operations with no more than a computer
and an Internet connection.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Except that it was not so simple. While the world now knew
quite a lot about Time Warner's nascent effort, it knew very little about Suck. Most readers did not know, for example, that Suck was
an after-hours effort by two production editors at <i>HotWired</i>, the on-line sibling of <i>Wired</i> magazine and perhaps
Pathfinder's main competitor. <br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is not a case of true journalistic conflict of interest; it
is an example of the appearance of conflict, exactly the sort of thing editors in the world of traditional journalism are so quick to
condemn and (usually) to avoid. And other examples of this sort of conflict are all over the Internet.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When Slate (<a href="http://www.slate.com">www.slate.com</a>) rubbished an on-line bookstore
called Amazon.com, it did not remind its readers that it is owned by Microsoft, which is pushing competing on-line shopping services. To
be sure, Slate usually makes no secret of its ownership and even has a tiny Microsoft copyright notice at the bottom of each page. But in
an article like this it might have been expected to go a bit further: Microsoft's interests in the market are considerable. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<i>Upside</i>, a Silicon Valley business magazine, recently ran an entertaining column in its
online edition (<a href="http://www.upside.com">www.upside.com</a>) revealing the bare shelves of <i>Wired</i>'s financial cupboard. The author was David Kline, who had
written a regular column for <i>HotWired</i> until a few months earlier. Was there a connection between Mr Kline's departure from
<i>HotWired</i> and his tough assessment of <i>Wired</i>'s financial health? Hard to say: Mr Kline did not discuss his relationship with
<i>Wired</i> in his column; it came out only when <i>Wired</i>'s owner brought it up in a protest.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even the very best defenders of journalistic ethics get tangled up on-line. When the <i>Wall
Street Journal</i> writes about Microsoft, it does not mention that the software giant has paid it to give free access to the
<i>Journal</i>'s Web site to users of Microsoft's Web browser; nor does the <i>New York Times</i> disclose that it has arranged a
similar, albeit smaller, deal with Microsoft's competitor, Netscape. <br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most publications
have financial and business interests they do not disclose in every story touching on the subject. No one bats an eyelid when the <i>Wall
Street Journal</i> runs advertisements from Microsoft, even though they probably bring in far more money than its browser deal. This
is because publications also have long-established internal divisions between editorial operations and advertising; sometimes they blur,
but more often they hold firm.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the Internet's upstarts are new to all this. Do they have
such Chinese walls? Doubtful: most are lucky to have office partitions. This might not be very worrying by itself--most of them are
less than two years old, and <i>caveat emptor</i> is still the reading rule on-line--did not on-line journalism and business interests so
often clash.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are two main reasons for this conflict. The first is mere inexperience:
getting into print in the old media usually requires some sort of journalistic apprenticeship or education, where keen young writers are
indoctrinated in the rules of journalism's ethics. Publishing on-line requires nothing more than a modem, literacy, and something to say.
Ethical niceties rank in priority somewhere below hard-disk crashes.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Second, the Internet
has sprung up so quickly that the main viable business on it is, in one form or another, the media themselves. This leads to a sort of
journalistic incestuousness: the on-line upstarts distinguish themselves most from the old media by covering the Internet itself, which
often means writing about each other. <br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The result is that quite a lot of on-line stories could
be imagined to have ulterior business motives behind them if one were conspiracy-minded enough. What should one think of the
computer-industry coverage of <font size=-1>C/NET</font>, one of the Internet's largest news operations, now that it is setting up an
entertainment site with Intel, the world's largest chip-maker? Dig into the finances and alliances of most Internet media outfits, and the
resulting web of potential conflicts could keep journalism-ethics professors going for years. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The simple solution--disclose all conflicts or appearances of conflict in the article--asks a
great deal; among other things, it would drown most on-line publications' lively prose in a sea of parentheses. But ignoring the issue is
no answer either. <br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One of the Web's beauties is that any publication can be of almost any
length, and information can be hidden from view unless the reader asks for it. Many publications list the computers, software and even
music <font size=-1>CD</font>s they use while producing their issues. Why not include a page of financial
connections and business alliances, too? On-line readers are a savvy bunch, able to make up their own minds about the extent to which a
business deal might flavour a publication's reporting. But only if they know whom that publication is in bed with. Considering the
business promiscuity of much of the new media world, these pages might make interesting reading.<br> <br>

<p align=center> <a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a
href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?853549200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a
href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sfthrill.html">Next article</a> </p> <p align=center><font size=-1> <a
href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a> 1997 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights
Reserved</font></p> </td></tr></table></body></html>

