<html><head><title></title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sfthril.gif">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>IN THE final issue of 1996 we challenged our readers to complete not
just a crossword but also a <a href="http://www.economist.com/issue/21-12-96/story1.html">thriller</a> by Ruth Dudley Edwards. Highly entertaining
entries came from as far afield as Manila, Kiev and Singapore, but our winning author, receiving a
laptop computer, is from nearer home: Edwin Thomas, a student at Lincoln College, Oxford. The first to
recognise that the characters' names feature in the history of The Economist was Mrs Shaiontoni Bose,
from Mumbai (Bombay); she wins a Montblanc pen</b></p>

<img src="deathjan.gif">
<p>
<br>
<p><img src="sofar.gif"> <p><i>University-of-life Detective-Inspector Greg and his highly- educated
intellectual side-kick, Detective-Constable As quith, are struggling to discover why the corpse of the
gifted, arrogant, dangerously iconoclastic journalist, Thomas St Loe Rathbone, has been found on The
Economist plaza under a sculpture called "Market Forces". Another sculpture, "Fiscal Rectitude", has
recently come a cropper, and "The Pursuit of Reason" is the only survivor. Suspects include Edward
Strachey, the intellectually insecure editor; his dim-witted, sexpot secretary, Julia Barrington; her
husband, Donald, the newspaper's technological supremo; Geoffrey Hodgskin, a disturbed senior
journalist reverting to the economic orthodoxies of the 1840s; Sophie Hamilton, the bluestocking
Britain editor; Henry Lathbury, smart-alec South American editor; and Zoe, The Economist's
receptionist. Questions raised included how Rathbone could afford cashmere, why Hamilton tolerated him
when other section editors had sacked him, why the editor employed Julia and why such intelligent
people like such idiotic modern art.</i>
<P>
<img src="edwin.gif">
<p>
In the conference room, Strachey was nervously looking over an article on the instability of the
European Union, wondering whether publication would in retrospect appear prescient or alarmist. Around
the room sat all of the upper-level staff whom Inspector Greg, after disappearing for two hours, had
summoned to hear his conclusions.  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"How very Agatha Christie," remarked Henry Lathbury, studying
the paperclip he was sculpting into what looked, to Asquith, like a stainless steel giraffe. Perhaps
this was where the journalists got their strange ideas about art.  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Maybe, sir, but I felt that you would all want to hear the good news. Mr Rathbone's death was completely accidental."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Silence.  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Surely, Inspector", said Hodgskin, vocalising most of his colleagues'
expressions, "you don't expect us to believe that a ton of
iron . . . "  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Copper, actually."  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hodgskin briefly wondered whether the editor ever stopped tinkering with other people's work. "That a ton
of . . . metal . . . just lost its balance and fell over as Rathbone was walking past?"  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Please, sir. If I might explain. The sculpture fell on Mr Rathbone because, having pushed it over, he was trying to lift it up
again."  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"What, he just knocked over a ton
of . . . copper?"  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"No, madam. Carefully
took a crowbar and levered it up. When he'd accomplished his purpose he went to raise it back into
position, but tragically his energy failed him."  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Europe editor broke the incredulous silence
first. "I'm sorry, Inspector--and why was Tom fiddling around with 'Market Forces' at that time of
night?"  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Because he was planting a bomb in the base."  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He might as well have
suggested Tom had been trying to dig a tunnel to Ghana--the statement was so ludicrous that no one
would even dignify it with a challenge.  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"I have reason to believe that Mr Rathbone was in the
employ of an Ecuadorian Marxist terrorist organisation, the Brotherhood of the Red Iguana. They had
targeted the offices of <i>The Economist</i>, and retained Mr Rathbone for the task."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"No! But! Tom! Bombs? Terrorists? Henry," said Strachey, grasping for a verb,
turning to his South American editor for help. "Do you know anything about these people?"
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Indeed he does, sir," came Greg's cool voice. "He was the one who recruited Rathbone."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"But how, how do you know--guess--all this, Inspector?"  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"The mail room, Mr Strachey. Over the last few months, several packages, postmarked Quito"--Asquith was sure he had
looked that up in the atlas--"and marked 'flammable', arrived for Mr Lathbury. Later more letters
arrived, many for Mr Rathbone as well, which my source assures me contained a considerable volume of
bank notes. "Money", he continued over the buzz that was spreading across the room, "is in my
experience surprisingly quick to make its presence known, even through a brown envelope."  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Greg paused to take a breath; everyone else jumped into the vacuum. The usually sedate conference room
erupted in a cacophony of protestations, accusations, denials, and a few rather personal insults. It
was Lathbury who eventually silenced them, by rising to his feet.  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"It's all true," he said, with
what many felt was a slight condescension. "Congratulations, Inspector. It looks as if you've caught
me. Well done."  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"But Henry!" spluttered Strachey. Again verbs failed him.  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Except that you haven't got it quite right, Mr Greg." He chuckled, in a tone which suggested to Asquith that he had
seen one too many James Bond films. "In fact, you're rather dishonouring the dead. Tom Rathbone may
have sold his newspaper--God knows he didn't have any principles--for bundles of cash and romps in his
office with Mrs Barrington, but in the end he was crushed by the burden of his conscience. And 'Market
Forces'. He was actually trying to remove the explosives when, ironically, he came to such a
depressing end."  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Inspector Greg did not miss a beat. "Thank you for clearing that up, sir."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"But Henry, why <i>The Economist</i>?" wondered Hodgskin. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"As a symbol of western capitalist oppression. It's the only English language newspaper that the leaders of the
movement get in their village."  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"What an extraordinarily cultured village it must be," mused
Strachey.  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"That's as maybe, sir. Now Mr Lathbury, if you'll let Mr Asquith take you outside."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hodgskin suddenly had a rather unsettling thought. "Just a minute," he stammered. "What about
the bomb?"  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"The bomb squad will have taken care of that, sir," the inspector reassured
him. "Now, Mr Lathbury . . . "  
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Not so fast,Inspector," said Lathbury, whose composure made Asquith wonder if he was not about to press some
hidden button and drop Greg into a pool of piranhas. "Although you've discovered the invisible hand in
'Market Forces', I'm afraid that your pursuit of reason is still one step short. You see after all
this fuss about 'Market Forces', last night I took the precaution of moving the explosives to the
other sculpture, just to make sure." He smiled a chilling smile. "Set to go off just in time for the
evening news. Right about . . . now." 
<p><p align=center><img src="bomb.gif"></p>
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It was
fortunate, Inspector Greg remarked at the trial, that the bomb squad had had no more appreciation for
modern art than Toby, the Alsatian sniffer dog who had led them straight to the 'Pursuit of Reason'.
Although, he added, it might be just as well for <i>The Economist </i>to ban all such
potential bomb receptacles from its premises just in case, a suggestion which Zoe lost no time in
implementing. On another of Greg's recommendations, Asquith was promoted to the Counter-Terrorism
Office--"Wouldn't want to waste that educated head of yours, would we now?" he had said. Only
the terrorists, who had hoped that even failure would bring them some media attention, were left
disappointed: on Friday night they were pushed out of the Six O'Clock News five minutes before
broadcast, on reports that France had just announced her withdrawal from the
<font size=-1>EU</font>.
<br>
<p>
<img src="andacc.gif">
<br>
THAT Julia was sexual dynamite had been obvious to Greg from the outset. The editor was so besotted with her that he put up with her slovenliness and illiteracy. She had cost him dearly in other ways, for Rathbone had been blackmailing him from the evening that he had spied them <i>in flagrante </i>on the editor's desk: both their spouses were notoriously vindictive. Taking advantage of the paper's secretive approach to salary negotiations, he had secured a doubling of his salary and a weekly wad of notes from the editor's own wallet.
 <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When Rathbone found Julia was also having an affair with Hodgskin, he moved in and acquired her for himself. Even Julia couldn't manage three affairs in the same building in which her husband worked; she had chosen the dashing and dangerous Rathbone over her other two lovers.
 <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Rathbone, cruel by nature, had rubbed salt in Hodgskin's wound by telling him why she had left him. The unstable Hodgskin had become more and more overwrought and convinced that Rathbone was out to destroy <i>The Economist</i>.
 <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Rathbone had also broken the heart of Sophie Hamilton, with whom he'd been having a torrid affair, by telling her he was leaving her for the younger and sexier Julia. He warned her that if she tried to get rid of him from the Britain department he would tell her husband of her infidelity.
 <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When Donald Barrington intercepted a sexually highly-explicit message telling Julia to meet Rathbone at midnight by "Market Forces", he sent her a cancellation message. At 11.30, entering Sophie Hamilton's office to deal with a technical problem, he found her in tears, after a row with Rathbone. They were both exchanging overwrought confidences when the editor entered and got the story out of them.
 <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Let's do for the bastard," he said in his most authoritative voice. "It will just take one heave."
 <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And so it was that at midnight the three of them overturned "Market Forces" on top of Thomas St Loe Rathbone. Stealing the crowbar later to confuse the issue was a clever move, typical of the practical Barrington.
 <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Greg was never to find out the answer to his question about modern art.<br>

<hr>
