<html><head><title>How safe is your airline?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>

<h1 align=center>How safe is your airline?</h1>


<CleverDrop>WITH the possible exception of the nuclear bomb, no modern invention has inspired such a perverse mixture of gratitude and terror as the jet airliner. From one perspective, the modern passenger aircraft has made the world smaller: Sydney is now only a day's journey from London, Los Angeles an afternoon away from New York. And it has made long-distance travel far more secure, in terms of accidents for distance covered, than any other form of transport--15 times safer than cars in Britain. Yet there are few passengers who do not silently make a prayer every time that they enter an aeroplane, or do not glance up nervously at least once from behind their newspaper during the safety demonstration.
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Airlines, aircraft manufacturers and air-safety authorities all like to blame this "irrational" fear on misinformation. Because air crashes are both big and infrequent, they always make the news headlines, whilst the steady, far greater carnage on the world's roads and railways is largely unreported. Besides, add the airlines, customers know that they are being irrational: if they were really frightened of crashes, they would give up flying. Instead, the number of passengers taking to the skies is growing rapidly.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet rationality is not always on the airlines' side. If you measure the riskiness by comparing deaths with the number of trips made rather than the miles covered, aircraft score worse than cars. And, thanks to those rising passenger numbers, large air crashes could soon become weekly occurrences (see <a href="wb8532.html">page</a>). In the next decade, worries about safety could become the airline industry's biggest headache--and one of the key battlegrounds between carriers. So it should: this is a matter far better dealt with by the airlines themselves than by bureaucrats or politicians.<br>
<b><br>
</p><p><b>You take the high road</b></b><br>
Air travel seems to have stopped becoming safer. From 1960 to the early 1980s the introduction of jet engines helped bring down the rate of fatal accidents per 1m landings from around 50 to two (excluding the Soviet Union). For the past ten years, however, the figure for scheduled flights (again excluding the former Soviet Union) has remained stuck at around 1.5 fatal accidents per 1m departures. Indeed, thanks to disasters like the ValuJet crash in Florida and the <font size=-1>TWA</font> crash off Long Island, 1996's figure will probably be considerably higher than 1995's figure of 1.3 fatal accidents per 1m departures.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Can this be improved upon, at an acceptable cost? Most crashes, including the many that go under the frightening acronym <font size=-1>CFIT</font> (or "controlled flight into terrain"), are the result of "pilot error". In a few cases--such as when a pilot handed over the controls to his son or when a pilot's English was too poor to communicate properly with the control tower--the error appears to be blatant. But in most cases, the term "pilot error" is more complicated: it means only that if the crew had reacted differently, then the crash would not have occurred.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At present, aircraft are driven by an uneven mix of computers and people. So-called "fly by wire" technology means that pilots have less to do; but the new gizmos still need some human help. There is evidence that older pilots in particular have found it difficult to adapt to the new technology: rules should be changed so that seniority counts for less than competence. Pilot training, too, needs to be tweaked. At present, training focuses on how to avoid errors in the first place: fair enough, but greater emphasis should also be placed on how to deal with errors when they are made, as they inevitably will be.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If training needs to become a little more reactive, then exactly the opposite seems to be required in terms of air-safety standards. The cause of air safety currently advances from crash to crash: each disaster ushers in a new range of checks. Rather than waiting for accidents to happen, air-safety organisations should take up the initiative themselves. One good example is promoting new global-positioning satellite technology that should give pilots much more accurate information about their exact position.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Rising on the wings of reason</b></b><br>
These changes would probably make air travel a little safer, but never perfectly safe. Indeed, in the foreseeable future, thanks to the increase in the number of flights, the number of crashes is bound to increase. This is a problem of success-- more demand, more flights--rather than failure. The solution to it must lie in information and openness. What consumers will want is not information about whether air travel is safe but about which airlines are safest.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ideally, that information would be provided voluntarily by airlines; but in practice if it is to be trusted it will have to be required by and certified by regulators. This means forcing carriers not only to reveal their number of crashes but also their number of safety-fault violations, average age of planes, near misses and so on. Virtually all these statistics are already collected by air-safety authorities; they are just kept secret.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Airline league tables will be greeted with just as much horror by people in the industry as they have been by doctors. This is both naive and arrogant. The naivety comes in imagining that league tables will not evolve anyway. Consumers already have their own informal ideas of how safe airlines are (remember the character in "Rain Man" who will fly from Cincinnati to Los Angeles only via Australia because Qantas, Australia's main airline, has never had a crash).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The arrogance comes from assuming that consumers are not sensible enough to weigh statistics properly, balancing long-term safety records against particular recent crashes. Yet, from hospitals to stockmarkets, consumers have usually reacted perfectly intelligently to information. Indeed, once they were better informed, they might well feel more rational about air travel. Once again, this will not bring certainty. "How safe is your airline?" is a question that will always have an incomplete answer. But it is worth asking.<br>
<br>

