<html><head><title>Arguing about the monarchy</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>

<h1 align=left>Arguing about the monarchy</h1>


<p><b>It makes little sense to discuss monarchs and republics in isolation from other constitutional issues</b></p><br>
BRITAIN has had what would once have been unthinkable: a full-scale debate about whether its monarchy should stay or go, conducted on prime-time television, followed by a phone-in poll, supposedly of 2.5m viewers. That, at least, is the grandiose way to describe it. In truth, it was little more than a shouting match with theatrical trappings. And the poll should not be taken seriously by anyone, either by republicans crowing that Scotland voted against the monarchy and that "record numbers" of English and Welsh did too, or by monarchists crowing that two-thirds of Britons voted to keep the crown. Such self-selecting polls have been known to be appallingly misleading ever since 1936 when an American magazine's postal ballot of 2.2m votes predicted that Alf Landon would beat Franklin Roosevelt for the presidency (Roosevelt won by a landslide).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All that said, the television debate may have had two uses, apart from mere entertainment. The first is that ventilating the arguments, albeit messily, does serve some purpose; even from the monarchy's point of view it is better to encourage people to think about the institution and its function than to leave them chatting merely about the latest piece of royal tittle-tattle in the tabloids. The second is that the debate ought to have left thoughtful republicans with the following conclusion: that if there is ever to be any change in Britain's method of choosing its head of state, the burden of proof in justifying such a change lies with them, not with the monarchists.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Too many republicans think it is enough to cry "anachronism!" or "indefensible hereditary privilege!", and that the argument will then be won. That might be the case if the monarchy were being set up today from scratch. But it is not. The emotional case for keeping such a long-established institution is a strong one: it is a link to tradition and to history, and is a powerful trademark for Britain. Some love it deeply, whatever the foibles of the present royal family. Others, perhaps the largest group of all, feel less strongly, but think of it rather as they might an old building: it may not be very practical, but they like the look of it just the same. And in the end, even if people resent royal behaviour and the cost of the monarchy, their contempt for those with royal blood is mild compared with their view of ordinary, elected politicians.<br>
</p><p><b><b>The real villains</b></b><br>
As if to prove that point, a <font size=-1>MORI</font> poll conducted in December offered a choice between 13 candidates for an elected president. The clear winner, ahead of politicians and businessmen, was the queen's own daughter, Princess Anne. And therein lies a lesson for any budding constitutional reformer.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is that the basic problem in Britain's constitution lies with the politicians, not the royals. The government, formed by the majority party in Parliament and elected by a minority vote of the country, is simply too powerful. Most of the time, it can whip its party into voting through any measure that it cares to. Since 1911 the House of Lords has been able to offer only the scantest of checks on the government and the Commons. Local government has been emasculated. The judiciary has no written constitution against which to hold the government accountable. In most democratic systems there would still be an ultimate check: the head of state. And that is where the monarchy comes in. Its shortcoming is not that it is too powerful, or too privileged. It is that it is too weak to serve its purpose: that of acting as a check on the politicians.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On principle, <i>The Economist</i> is republican: it prefers promotion through merit and achievement to a system of deference based on inheritance. In practice, however, the priority should lie elsewhere, in reforming Britain's constitution in order to restore the checks on governmental action that were originally supposed to be there. That can be done in a number of ways: through the second chamber, a bill of rights, or indeed through the head of state. Over-mighty politicians are the real problem. Reforming the monarchy should be thought of, and argued over, as part of the solution.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
