<html><head><title>Telemedicine </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"> <table width=100%><tr><td
align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey"
border=0> <td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78"
height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Telemedicine </b></p> <h1>Big Sister is watching you</h1>

<font size=1>HAYS, KANSAS </font><p> <p>

<p>WEARING a telephonist's
headset, Kathy Rupp sits in a small office at Hays Medical Centre, a computer keyboard at her
fingertips, a television screen in front of her. Mrs Rupp is not a telephonist but a nurse, and
appearing on her screen is one of her patients, Idonna, an elderly lady sitting at home. Mrs Rupp asks
Idonna how she's been feeling, and taps the answers to a series of questions into Idonna's computer
records. Using simple electronic gadgets, Idonna takes her own blood pressure, measures her pulse rate
and holds up a thermometer to the camera so that the nurse can read her temperature. 
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"It takes a
bit of getting used to because you're not there and you don't have the hands-on contact," says Mrs
Rupp. "But you learn to use your other senses." Administrators at Hays Medical Centre reckon that
these televisits are as good as the traditional, hands-on version, and much more efficient. Patients,
reassured by the link-up, may make fewer visits to the hospital. Mrs Rupp can see some 15 patients in
four hours, whereas a nurse physically travelling from house to house may see only five or six
patients in a day. Each televisit costs $36, compared with $135 for a home visit by a registered nurse
such as Mrs Rupp or $60 for a visit by a certified nursing assistant. Under a managed-care system,
with a fixed fee paid per person insured, telemedicine offers huge potential savings. 
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is such
calculations that make many people in rural America see telemedicine as a miracle cure. At the click
of a button, distances disappear and the most advanced health care can be delivered, promptly and
affordably, to the most remote areas. Hays Medical Centre, which serves a vast area of the western
Kansas plains, has become a telemedicine pioneer. 
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At Hays, teleconferencing is used for
teaching, for administration, for observing the behaviour of patients, and even--with the help of
close-up cameras that can focus sharply on an area the size of a dime--for detailed clinical
diagnosis. The doctors at Hays teleconsult with colleagues at distant primary-care hospitals, as well
as with specialists at Kansas University. A team of radiologists examine <font size=1>X</font>-rays
transmitted to them, either at home or at the medical centre, from 12 sites in Kansas and neighbouring
Colorado; they are thus instantly available to communities that could not afford a radiologist of
their own. 
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Standing in the way of these new-fangled possibilities is an old-fashioned problem:
money. The trouble is the rules governing payment for services performed under Medicare, the
health-care system for the elderly. With the notable exceptions of teleradiology and telepathology,
only services performed the traditional way--that is, in person, face-to-face--currently qualify for
Medicare reimbursement. State governments, which provide health services to the poor through Medicaid,
and private insurers could in theory be bolder. But for the most part they are cautiously waiting to
take the lead from the federal government and Medicare. 
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It could be a long wait. The Health Care
Financing Administration (<font size=1>HCFA</font>) has only just begun a three-year trial of Medicare
reimbursement for teleconsultations involving "hub" hospitals and distant "spokes". The project is
confined to four states (Georgia, Iowa, North Carolina and West Virginia). It will take five years or
so before the recommendations are assessed and turned into law. The <font size=1>HCFA</font> has no
plans--and no money--for similar trials in telenursing such as Mrs Rupp is practising, under a
Department of Commerce grant, in Hays. 
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Officials in Washington want to have an idea of how much
telemedicine, once sanctioned under Medicare, is likely to cost. They have not forgotten their mistake
in drastically underestimating the bill for reimbursing dialysis for end-stage renal disease. If
getting an expert consultation becomes as easy as picking up a telephone, the volume of services seems
bound to rise. There are also worries about the scope for fraud and abuse. 
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the potential
benefits in rural areas are so great that pressure for faster action in Washington is bound to grow.
In the final days of the previous Congress, Senator Kent Conrad of North Dakota introduced a bill that
would provide reimbursement for telemedical services by January 1998. Mr Conrad says telehealth holds
"incredible promise" for rural America. So it does--provided someone will pay for it. 
<br<br>

<p align=center> <a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
