<html><head><title>Facing facts</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/as.gif" width="67" height="26" alt="Asia" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Hong Kong</b></p>
<h1>Facing facts</h1>

<font size=1>HONG KONG</font><p>
<p><b>There is plenty of unfinished business to settle before Hong Kong is handed back to China on July 1st. We look at the dispute over China's plans for the territory's government and the problem of the Vietnamese boat people</b></p><br>
QIAN QICHEN, China's foreign minister, recently said that Britain should have the courage to face facts in Hong Kong. Despite opposition from Britain and Hong Kong's liberals, China has approved a "provisional legislature" for Hong Kong, to replace the body elected last year under the political reforms sponsored by Chris Patten, Hong Kong's governor. Since the provisional legislature is now in place, Mr Qian reasoned, further opposition has become pointless.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The British, Hong Kong's Democratic Party and other liberals do not agree. They continue to challenge the body's legality. Is such opposition futile, as Mr Qian suggests? Not necessarily. Hong Kong's liberals think they may get somewhere with their legal challenges. In any event, their determination to press ahead with their protests, combined with Britain's refusal to accept the provisional body, guarantees that the run-up to the handover to China on July 1st will be difficult.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Britain argues that there is no legal basis for the provisional legislature either in the Chinese-British Joint Declaration on the future of Hong Kong, or in China's post-1997 constitution for Hong Kong, the Basic Law. It has challenged China to seek an opinion from the International Court of Justice. However, Tung Chee-hwa, who will be Hong Kong's first chief executive in the new era, has stated that the new body is both essential and legal.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Tung, who was selected by the same group of Beijing appointees who "voted" in the provisional legislature three weeks ago, went to Beijing recently to seek ways to bolster the legitimacy of the body. His flying visit was hailed by China's critics as an admission of the provisional legislature's legal defects. Mr Tung rejects the idea that his journey cast doubts on the assertion that the interim body is already legal. But both he and sympathetic lawyers in Hong Kong admit something should be done to "consolidate" its legal basis. Elsie Leung, a lawyer, says China's National People's Congress, to which she is a local delegate, should take action by issuing a statement clarifying the legality of the body.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The shadow legislature is to hold its meetings across the border from Hong Kong in Shenzhen until it takes over from the present Legislative Council on July 1st. But, even then, Mr Tung's legal headaches may not go away. Hong Kong's liberals are preparing to launch a host of legal challenges against any legislation passed before or after the transfer of sovereignty. A senior official in the Hong Kong government warns of a "legal crisis" caused by the expected avalanche of lawsuits. In effect, Hong Kong courts will be asked to pass judgment on the legality of the provisional legislature. Martin Lee, the leader of the Democratic Party, understands that the initial feedback from expert opinion in London has given him grounds for believing that the legal challenges will be successful.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The legality of the interim body is not the only problem facing Mr Tung; there is also the question of paying for the government-in-waiting. China has promised to finance it until the handover--and then to get the money back from Hong Kong's taxpayers. In theory, budgetary demands are meant to require the legislature's approval. But Mr Tung obviously expects few difficulties on that score.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Both Mr Tung and Mr Patten have pledged to co-operate for the final six months of the transition but, with the governor's refusal to have anything to do with the interim legislature, such co-operation may not extend very far. The pre-and post-handover leaders have met only once since Mr Tung's position was confirmed last month, when the pair agreed to disagree.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?821322000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
