<html><head><title>Staying on?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/as.gif" width="67" height="26" alt="Asia" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Staying on?</h1>

<font size=1>HANOI</font><p>
IF THERE is one thing that China does not want to see when it takes over Hong Kong on July 1st, it is former Vietnamese boat-people roaming the streets of its gleaming new possession. This week Shen Guofang, the spokesman for China's foreign ministry, once again said that the asylum-seekers left in the territory's camps should be sent home by the time Hong Kong is handed back to the motherland.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The British, keen to tidy up before making a dignified exit from their last major colony, are doing all they can to rush the repatriation of all the Vietnamese left in Hong Kong. Efforts to send them back have gone fairly smoothly in the past eight months. Numbers in the camps have dwindled to about 5,500 from 18,000 a year ago. They have gone home either voluntarily or under a forced programme. This month Hong Kong closed one of its last big detention camps, Whitehead. Only last year, it was the scene of ugly riots as Vietnamese protested at their return to the communist country they had fled.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet, even as the numbers fall, the realisation grows that the hard part is yet to come. Mr Shen's comments were prompted by a legal action being taken on behalf of the Vietnamese in the camps. The case brought against the Hong Kong government alleges that many of the remaining refugees are held illegally. At issue is a particular group of about 2,600 refugees, who are still in Hong Kong because they have not yet been "cleared" for return: the Vietnamese authorities are finding it hard to check their last known addresses in Vietnam. Nor are their identities clear, because many refugees disguised who they were in the hope of avoiding repatriation. If the case is successful--it is being heard at the moment--hundreds of Vietnamese will be allowed to walk free and melt into Hong Kong society, a prospect that appals China.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another issue is even thornier. About 250 of the refugees are ethnic Chinese with Taiwanese identity papers issued in the early 1970s, when Taiwan had a mission in what was then South Vietnam. Vietnam refuses to take them on the ground that they are "non-nationals". The reason goes back to China's war with Vietnam in 1979.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One of the nastier side-effects of that war was that Vietnam booted out thousands of ethnic Chinese from (mostly) northern Vietnam. About 280,000 of them still live in south-western China. Although the majority have found jobs and settled into Chinese society, none have Chinese identity papers. China still regards them as "Indochinese refugees" and would prefer them to go home. About 6,000 have said they would like to, because they still have families in Vietnam. But Vietnam says they are Chinese and must stay in China.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Vietnamese say they cannot take back the 250 non-nationals in Hong Kong, as this would hand the Chinese the precedent they may be looking for to force the 6,000 "Indochinese refugees" back home too. The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees has tried to mediate but has been fended off.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As the clock ticks, the British may be hoping that the Vietnamese will blink first. Insisting that leaving the 250 "non-nationals" in Hong Kong is not an option, Britain argues that Vietnam should take them back at once. Aid workers mutter that a deal may still be possible, but no one can say what form it might take. It looks more and more likely that, come July, China will have to accept some Vietnamese on the streets of its repossessed territory.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?821322000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
