</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT09-B15-233</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA096-001030-B010-410</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.europe.economist.com:80/issue/11-01-97/br7671.html 199.173.162.110 19970215015905 text/html 4452
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 01:55:04 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 10-Jan-97 12:23:33 GMT
Content-length: 4267
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Big spenders</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"> <table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img
src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0> <p><font size=-1> These articles in the Britain section are
published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions. </font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist"
border=0> </td></tr></table>

<h1>Big spenders</h1>

THE Treasury's decision to consider privatising its economic forecasts, announced on January 7th, officially stems from a desire to cut
costs rather than concerns about quality. But the Treasury's forecasts are always controversial. Its most recent forecast, for
example, in last November's budget, was upbeat about consumer spending in 1997, which it expected to rise by 4.25% (see <a
href="br1.gif">chart</a>). This prompted some commentators to accuse the Treasury of talking up the feel-good factor in the run-up to
the general election. <br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact, recent data suggest that consumer spending may well be even
higher than the Treasury then thought. Eyebrows are now being raised at its prediction that this rapidly growing demand will not mean
higher inflation.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The final estimate of <font size=-1>GDP</font> in the third quarter of
1996 showed that consumer spending was 1% higher than in the second quarter. Consumer credit rose by &#163;1.1 billion in
November, compared with an expected &#163;900m. Average new borrowing for September to November was 46% higher than during
the same three months in 1995. Data published on January 6th showed an unexpectedly large increase in the volume of cash circulating
in the economy in December. And the Confederation of British Industry's survey of retailers, published on January 10th, reported that
retail sales, although below some of the most bullish forecasts, were extremely strong in December.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such upbeat numbers are making the financial markets nervous about inflation. They want
Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor of the exchequer, to raise interest rates to restrain demand, perhaps as soon as January 15th, the date
of his next monetary-policy meeting with Eddie George, the governor of the Bank of England.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Kevin Gardiner, an economist at Morgan Stanley, an investment bank, reckons that the sort of
increase that Mr Clarke might be willing to contemplate--a quarter of one percentage point, say--may be too little, too late. Real
after-tax income, employment and house prices are all rising. The ratio of total personal wealth (including property, pension rights and
insurance policies) to annual disposable income is likely to reach 5.2 this year. This is up from 4.7 in 1992, and near the all-time peak
of 5.4 in 1989. Consumers are likely to spend some of this wealth as well as their higher incomes. Indeed, the ratio of savings to
personal disposable income has already started to fall.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In particular, the spending power of
those consumers who borrowed most heavily during the 1980s--and so were most hurt by the 1990s recession--has increased
dramatically. Between 1988 and 1994, someone with earnings of &#163;15,000 and a mortgage of &#163;50,000 would have seen
his disposable income after tax and mortgage payments fall by 30% in real terms. In 1997, such disposable income will be double its
level in 1994. Either interest rates will go up sharply, or inflation will--hardly a comfortable prospect for a chancellor with a general
election ahead.<br>

<p align=center> <a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a
href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?821322000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a
href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br7677.html">Next article</a> </p> <p align=center><font size=-1> <a
href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a> 1997 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights
Reserved</font></p> </td></tr></table></body></html>

