<html><head><title>Years of living dangerously</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"> <table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img
src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0> <p><font size=-1> These articles in the Britain section are
published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions. </font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist"
border=0> </td></tr></table>

<p><b>Mortality</b></p> <h1>Years of living dangerously</h1>

DEAD men do tell tales--or at least the statistics about them do. And the news that British men aged between 25 and 40 are more likely
to die than they were a decade ago is a particularly sorry tale.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Male mortality as a whole
has continued to decline, thanks mostly to the better health of infants and of the over-40s. Indeed, life expectancy for men, currently
74 years, is now increasing faster than it is for women--although the allegedly weaker sex can still expect to last five years
longer.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is getting to 40 that is the problem for men. According to new figures from the
Office for National Statistics, in 1992 there were over two more deaths per 100,000 men aged 25-29 than a decade earlier, one more
death amongst those aged 29-34, and a chilling six more deaths per 100,000 in the 34-39-year-old group (see <a
href="br3.gif">chart</a>). This is not cause for panic, but it is a rude surprise: other than during war, says Michaela Benzeval, an
analyst at the King's Fund, a health-policy research body, age-group mortality has fallen across the board for a century. This kind of
reversal is unprecedented. <br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why has it happened? A bit less than half of the increase in the
death-rate is due to <font size=-1>AIDS</font>, which disproportionately affects young men: since the first British <font
size=-1>AIDS</font> death was recorded in 1982, 9,447 Britons have died of it, about 90% of them men. Being murdered is a young
man's game, too; the increase in total British homicides, from less than 400 in 1972 to around 700 in 1992, took its toll. The rest of
the increase in mortality is due to suicide. <br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Which brings us to wealth. The least-skilled
men (whose death rates have been rising since the early 1970s) are more than three times as likely to commit suicide as professional
men. The incidence of suicide among the least skilled has doubled since 1972; indeed, among the four lowest occupational categories
ranked by skill, which account for two-thirds of British men, suicide rates have increased markedly.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One possible reason is that male suicide is closely linked to unemployment (curiously, this is
much less true of women); as joblessness has increased since the late 1970s, so has the number of men taking their own lives. And
because a disproportionate number of the less skilled are unemployed, suicide rates are higher at the lower end of the occupational
ladder. A second factor could be marriage--or lack of it. Divorced and single men are known to be less mentally healthy than married
ones; rising divorce rates could be contributing to the increase in male suicide. <br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The good
news is that the proportion of men categorised as low skilled is falling steadily (from 22.9% in 1971 to 18.9% in 1991), and the
number in the highest grades is increasing (from 22.9% to 32.9%). The moral of the story, then, is to stay in school, find a good job and
get married (or at least be sexually responsible). Otherwise the consequences may be deadly.<br> <br>

<p align=center> <a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a
href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?821322000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a
href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br7679.html">Next article</a> </p> <p align=center><font size=-1> <a
href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a> 1997 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights
Reserved</font></p> </td></tr></table></body></html>

