<html><head><title>Keep polishing</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Apple Computer</b></p>
<h1>Keep polishing</h1>

<font size=1>SAN FRANCISCO</font><p>
THE world loves an underdog, which is what Apple Computer is in the computer industry. Whether facing <font size=-1>IBM</font> in bygone days or Microsoft of late, Apple has always been far more visible than its small share of the crowded computer market would justify. But affection goes only so far--and not, these days, all the way to the average consumer's buying decisions.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On January 3rd Apple announced that it will declare a quarterly loss of as much as $150m at the end of the month, which will bring its cumulative losses since the end of 1995 to about $1 billion. That alone is something of a distinction: no other American company has lost so much in the same period. Consumers are fleeing the troubled Macintosh in favour of <font size=-1>PC</font>s, and Apple's share of the world market has shrunk to about 5%--two-thirds of what it was just a year ago.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Part of Apple's problem is that the Betamax/<font size=-1>VHS</font>-style battle for the computer industry is over, and the <font size=-1>PC</font>, rather than the Mac, has won. But Apple is even having trouble retaining its customers in normally loyal niches such as media and education. Its one claim to superiority--advanced technology and ease of use--is wearing thin. After pulling off the fiendishly difficult trick of switching to an entirely different microprocessor in 1994, Apple now finds itself stuck with the equally difficult problem of replacing an aged operating system. Its new software chief, Ellen Hancock, has ditched the company's efforts to develop a new operating system internally. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Rather than start again from scratch, Apple in December agreed to buy <font size=-1>N</font>e<font size=-1>XT</font>, a software company founded by Steve Jobs, Apple's charismatic co-founder, for $400m. Mr Jobs himself comes back just as a part-time consultant, but his reappearance, a reminder of former glories, has at least cheered the troops. The technical object of the deal is less obviously cheering, but far more important. Apple wants to use <font size=-1>N</font>e<font size=-1>XT</font>'s software technology, called OpenStep, to regain a technological lead for the Mac operating system. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On January 7th Gil Amelio, Apple's boss, explained to a packed house of the remaining faithful at the annual Macworld conference how he wants this to work. In mid-1998, Apple plans to release a mass-market version of its next operating system, code-named Rhapsody. It will be based on OpenStep and, Apple promises, will be able to run today's Macintosh software on today's Macintosh computers. That will allow current owners--not to mention prospective buyers--to keep using their hardware and software.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such "backward compatibility" is essential: without it, Apple would be launching a completely new kind of computer, and trying to build from scratch a network of independent companies writing and selling compatible software. That would be unimaginably difficult in a market already settled on the <font size=-1>PC</font> standard.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But ensuring that the new operating system is compatibile only avoids making a ruinous mistake. To regain ground that Apple has already lost, the new operating system will have to do more--in particular, more than its competition, Microsoft's Windows <font size=-1>NT</font>. OpenStep, despite being based on a design more than a decade old, seems to be modern enough. And with the Mac's beloved desktop interface, rubbish bin and all, grafted on to it, current Apple owners will feel at home.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The pairing with <font size=-1>N</font>e<font size=-1>XT</font> will also have some appeal for independent software developers--a group that Apple cannot afford to continue losing. It needs these people to produce enough good--and preferably unique--software for the Mac. The new operating system is based on a building-block technology that makes writing software easier than for Windows, and that will also be useful to corporate buyers, a market where Apple has not found much support in the past. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Apple's demise in the near future is unlikely. Although its recent quarterly projections drove its shares down by nearly 20%, the company will still have more than $1 billion in the bank after buying <font size=-1>N</font>e<font size=-1>XT</font>. But, although the new operating system may keep Apple in business, it is not enough to win back some of its lost glory.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What should Mr Amelio do? To revive Apple's reputation, the company will have to consider more radical steps. At the moment its products are a weird mix: at one end it still produces innovative gizmos, such as its much-improved Newton personal digital assistants, that recall Apple's inspired launch of the Mac in 1984; at the other it churns out run-of-the-mill stuff such as laser printers and scanners. Some make money; some do not. Like other companies in a mess, Apple needs to focus on what it does best.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At least three parts of Apple might be better on their own or in another company's hands. Apple's low-end computer division (the main source of the latest losses) is a natural candidate: this is in head-to-head competition with nimble upstarts such as Power Computing, which have none of Apple's massive research-and-development overheads. Spun off, it might concentrate on improving its manufacturing efficiencies and market forecasting.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The firm is loth to lose its profitable printer, scanner and digital-camera division. But if the company must shrink to survive, now--when such a rich division can still command a generous selling price--is not a bad time to shed it.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Third, Apple's consumer-electronics products, such as the Newton and Pippin, might well fare better on their own. The company's greatest talent has arguably been the ability of its designers to come up with beautiful gadgets that stir the souls of nerds and artists alike. But the result is that Apple cannot decide whether its core business is computers, operating systems, research or consumer electronics. Its elegant toys would do better in the hands of companies such as Sony, which know these markets better. In a similar position, Netscape, the leading Internet software firm, spun off a subsidiary to work with a consumer-electronics firm rather than try to serve two quite different markets simultaneously.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Keeping its research and development, software, and high-end Mac hardware in-house would allow Apple to be a well-rounded company without overextending itself. Apple's new management has shown a willingness to make hard decisions. The question is whether it will go far enough to keep both the company and its flagship, the Macintosh, alive into the next century.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?821322000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
