<html><head><title>Lost toys</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Lost toys</h1>

APPLE'S purchase of <font size=-1>N</font>e<font size=-1>XT</font> will give Steve Jobs, founder of both firms, work probably for no more than a day a week. That will leave him more time to spend with his third--and now main-- company, Pixar, creator of "Toy Story", a computer-animated film. This is no bad thing: much as Apple needs him, Pixar needs him more. Despite the film's massive success, the firm is barely profitable, with several lean years ahead. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is strange: "Toy Story" brought in $350m--including $100m in profit-- at the box office alone. Yet Pixar made only $16m in the nine months after the film's release. Add in video and merchandise sales, including the Christmas rush to buy the film's star, Buzz Lightyear, and total profits may reach $400m. Of that, Pixar may get around $40m. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Where does the rest go? To Disney, which marketed the film and the products. Pixar, which wrote, animated and produced the film, gets only about 10% of the profits; Disney gets the other 90%. Worse, this deal is for three films, the next of which, "Bugs", will not be out until late 1998 at best. No wonder Pixar's share price has fallen by two-thirds since the firm went public a year ago.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lawrence Levy, the firm's chief financial officer, acknowledges that Pixar has what looks like a raw deal. But when the firm started, he says, the animated-film business was essentially a Disney monopoly; upstart Pixar had little negotiating clout. Now it has proved itself, it hopes for something more like 30-40% in its next deal, although that may not be for years. Meanwhile, Pixar has the comfort of knowing that Disney is better at wringing money out of a character than any other firm on earth: Buzz is already hugging kids at Disneyland.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The agreement between Pixar and Disney looks curiously like a throwback to the 1940s, where actors were contractually bonded to a single studio. For, although Pixar created the characters in "Toy Story", Disney owns them. Today, actors are usually free agents, yet cartoon characters remain indentured servants. Computer animation brings one bit of relief, however; Pixar still owns the data files and computer-rendering technology. If Disney wants to create another Buzz cartoon without Pixar, it will have to draw the helmeted one by hand.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?821322000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
