<html><head><title>Eight little Virgins</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Eight little Virgins</h1>

VIRGIN, with an overall turnover of about &#163;1.8 billion ($3 billion), has eight main divisions, which operate autonomously:<br>
<font size=-1><li></font> &nbsp; Virgin Travel Group, which owns Virgin Atlantic Airways, flying 2m passengers a year to America, Japan, Hong Kong, South Africa and Athens; Virgin Holidays, a tour operator; Virgin Aviation Services, a cargo service; and Virgin Express, a budget airline connecting Brussels and other European cities. <br>
<font size=-1><li></font> &nbsp; Virgin Retail, which is joint owner of the Our Price record-shop chain in Britain and operates Megastores, large music and entertainment media shops, in several parts of the world. Other subsidiaries include Virgin Trading Company, which owns Virgin Cola.<br>
<font size=-1><li></font> &nbsp; Virgin Communications has a book business, and several television and software production companies in America, Britain and Mexico. Virgin Net, an Internet service, was started in Britain at the end of 1996.<br>
<font size=-1><li></font> &nbsp; Virgin Hotels Group owns, manages or markets more than 30 hotels and clubs in Britain, most of them, such as Heaven, a London night club, or Le Manoir Aux Quat' Saisons, a smart restaurant in Oxfordshire of which Virgin owns 50%, operating under names other than Virgin. <br>
<font size=-1><li></font> &nbsp; Virgin Radio owns 75% of a British pop music radio station.<br>
<font size=-1><li></font> &nbsp; Virgin Cinema is a joint venture with several investment companies, 45% owned by Virgin, which includes the remains of <font size=-1>MGM</font> Cinemas, bought in 1995. It runs multiplex cinemas in Britain with an estimated 1996 turnover of &#163;66.9m. It is gradually restyling the cinemas and labelling them Virgin.<br>
<font size=-1><li></font> &nbsp; Virgin Direct is a 50:50 joint venture with <font size=-1>AMP</font>, a financial-services firm, set up in March 1995 to sell personal financial services, including pension schemes and tax-exempt savings plans known as Personal Equity Plans. Its turnover to the end of 1995 was &#163;28.9m.<br>
<font size=-1><li></font> &nbsp; Voyager Investments is the development arm of the group. It has a stake in the Eurostar London-Paris train service. It also houses smaller oddities, such as Virgin Airship and Balloon (of which it owns 75%), a &#163;2.2m-turnover business (1996 estimate) that gives hot-air balloon rides.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?821322000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="st4115.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>
1997 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>

