<DOCNO>WT09-B15-248</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA096-001030-B011-196</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.europe.economist.com:80/issue/04-01-97/sf0805.html 199.173.162.110 19970215020210 text/html 13316
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 01:58:01 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 10-Jan-97 12:29:17 GMT
Content-length: 13130
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Costing a bomb</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="defence.gif" alt="Special feature"><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table><h1>Costing a bomb</h1><p><b>The peace dividend vanished years ago; now the costs of defence are becoming evident once more. The first of two special articles looks at the continuing burden of nuclear weapons--both of keeping and destroying them. The second turns to the growing threat of missile proliferation</b></p><br>WHAT price peace? That is not a trick question. The cold war is over and nuclear arsenals are shrinking. The biggest nuclear powers, with the partial exception of China, co-operate where once they competed; they have struck agreements to cut the numbers of nuclear weapons, to stop pointing those that remain at each other and, by ending nuclear testing, to stop the race to design ever fancier warheads. Yet winding the nuclear-arms race safely down will be enormously costly, just as the race itself was. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As stockpiles of nuclear weapons shrink, surplus warheads and bombs must be dismantled. That is expensive enough. In addition, there are the costs of cleaning up the environmental mess weapons leave behind. According to America's Department of Energy, the United States will have to spend over (possibly well over) $230 billion during the coming decade or two to clean up contaminated sites, from old test ranges and storage sites to disused weapons-assembly plants.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are no comparable figures for the former Soviet Union. No one knows--or is ever likely to know-- just how much was spent building its nuclear arsenal. In the end, the general burden of military spending on the civilian economy proved crippling--and in many ways remains so for today's Russia. What is certain is that the nuclear-weapons industry did its bit to make the territory of the former Soviet Union among the most polluted on earth. The explosion and fire at the Chernobyl power station in Ukraine in 1986 focused international attention on the poor safety standards of the Soviet civilian nuclear industry. Standards at military plants were no better. Vast tracts of land and water around weapons plants, research establishments and test sites are badly contaminated with radioactive residue. Russians and their neighbours will be paying this clean-up bill, in cash and in damage to health, for generations.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is necessary to keep such costs in perspective. The burden of building and maintaining nuclear weapons during the cold war was itself heavy, though finding reliable figures is hard since nuclear-weapons costs, from development and production to deployment and control, were scattered across the defence budget and beyond. A preliminary, unofficial guess by the United States Nuclear Weapons Costs Study Project, based at the Brookings Institution in Washington <font size=-1>DC</font>, is that, over the more than five decades from its inception in 1940 to 1995, the United States nuclear-weapons programme cost American tax-payers a minimum of $4 trillion (calculated in 1996 dollars). The study's final estimate, due out later in 1997, is likely to be "significantly higher", according to Stephen Schwartz, its editor. And the cold war was relatively cheap compared with the cost of real world war: one estimate made back in 1948 of the military, economic and commercial costs of this century's two world wars translates into about $22 trillion in today's money.<br></p><p><b><b>A long, expensive half life</b></b><br>All the same, by ordinary standards, the cost of disarmament is high. According to another recent study, over the years the United States built some 70,000 nuclear warheads and bombs, more than 6,000 strategic missiles and getting on for 5,000 strategic bombers. Its stockpile of usable weapons rose to about 30,000 at its peak in the early 1960s, dropping to some 20,000 in the 1970s and 1980s (see <a href="sf1.gif">chart</a>). The Russians have not disclosed exactly how many nuclear weapons they built in total, but their usable stockpile is thought to have peaked at around 45,000 weapons by the mid-1980s, dropping to about 33,000 in the early 1990s.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Under the <font size=-1>START-1</font> agreement the United States and Russia are obliged to reduce their arsenal of strategic nuclear weapons to some 6,500 apiece by 2001 (see <a href="sf2.gif">chart</a>); under <font size=-1>START-2</font>, which has yet to be ratified by the Russian parliament, these totals would drop to around 3,500 apiece by 2003. Although both treaties require the destruction of missiles and bombers only, not their warheads, and although both sides are likely to keep plenty of extra warheads in reserve, both America and Russia are busy dismantling thousands of surplus warheads.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Russia, with the larger stockpile, says it has the capacity to take apart up to 3,000 warheads a year, though it refuses to give an exact tally of the number disposed of so far. America has the capacity to pick apart up to 2,000. A typical American-built warhead has up to 6,000 parts, each of which needs to be properly catalogued and safely disposed of. America's current operational stockpile is now less than 9,000 warheads, its lowest since the 1950s. According to the Department of Energy, America has dismantled close to 4,000 warheads over the past three years and plans to dispose of another 1,700 or so by the end of the decade. However, the rate will then drop off sharply, unless Russia ratifies <font size=-1>START-2</font>.<br></p><p><b><b>Bombs away</b></b><br>But taking apart old nuclear weapons and cleaning up the places where they were made is not the only costly hangover from the nuclear past. To military strategists, the great attraction of nuclear weapons was that they were megatonnes more than the sum of their parts. Finding safe ways to store and then dispose of their plutonium or uranium cores is proving the biggest headache of all.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The hardest part of making a nuclear bomb is getting hold of the right sort of plutonium and highly-enriched uranium to make it explode. Thus, keeping the superpowers' surplus stocks out of the hands of nuclear wannabees, such as Iraq, Iran or North Korea, is becoming something of a costly industry in itself.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It takes about 15 kilogrammes of highly-enriched uranium, or up to about half that amount of plutonium, to make a standard-issue nuclear bomb. Until it stopped making the stuff in the late 1980s and early 1990s, America over the years had accumulated about 98 tonnes of bomb-usable plutonium and 994 tonnes of highly-enriched uranium. Russia has even larger stocks: an estimated 130-200 tonnes of plutonium and about 1,200 tonnes of highly-enriched uranium. Assuming the Russians are dismantling at full capacity, each year some 15 tonnes of weapons-grade plutonium and 45 tonnes of highly-enriched uranium shift from the relatively secure custody of the Ministry of Defence to the less certain control of Minatom, the civilian ministry that controls Russia's sprawling nuclear industry. If the process is to continue safely, there is a pressing need to find new, more secure methods of storage and disposal.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As part of a wider consolidation of its nuclear industry, the United States recently announced a $2 billion plan over 20 years to dispose of 52 tonnes of surplus weapons plutonium, more than half its stockpile. It will do this partly by immobilising the stuff--mixing it with other radioactive wastes and vitrifying it in glass or ceramic blocks for permanent storage underground--and partly by burning it in commercial reactors to generate electricity. America has long campaigned against using plutonium to fuel civilian reactors, since keeping the cycle going requires separating out the plutonium from spent fuel for re-use, creating a proliferation hazard. The new plan would burn the plutonium once as mixed oxide fuel and then dispose of the radioactive wastes without reprocessing, making it difficult and dangerous for any would-be black-market proliferator to retrieve the plutonium for bomb-making.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Russia (like Japan, Britain and France) is inclined to see plutonium as a commodity to be exploited for commercial purposes as part of the civilian fuel cycle. However, it did agree in 1994 to end its production of new plutonium by 2000 (like America, it has already halted production of weapons-usable uranium; both countries support the negotiation of a global agreement to end production of such fissile material). The deal still hinges, however, on finding other sources of heat and energy for the regions that depend on the three plutonium-producing reactors concerned. But the recently announced American plan for plutonium disposal should make it easier to co-operate with Russia in getting rid of surplus weapons stocks.<br></p><p><b><b>Getting a grip</b></b><br>Indeed, America's help--commercial, financial and technical--is crucial to Russia's efforts to prevent skills, technology and materials from its nuclear (and chemical and biological) weapons programmes being spirited away by middlemen for the various unrepentant members of Bomb-Builders Anonymous.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1992, the American government organised an imaginative $12 billion commercial deal under which Russia will release some 500 tonnes of highly-enriched uranium from its weapons stockpile over 20 years for blending down to lower levels of enrichment suitable for making into fuel rods of the sort commercial reactors can use. In 1994, America's Departments of Defence and Energy (the military and civilian controllers respectively of America's nuclear-weapons programme) secretly joined forces with the government of Kazakhstan in an operation, codenamed Project Sapphire, to transport to America some 600 kilogrammes of highly-enriched uranium, found lying around, virtually unsecured, at a nuclear-fuel fabrication factory in eastern Kazakhstan. According to American officials, the Iranian government had been showing an unhealthy interest in the stuff.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Over the past five years the American Congress has authorised some $1.6 billion to be spent helping secure Russia's "loose nukes", with more to come. This Co-operative Threat Reduction programme (known as the Nunn-Lugar programme, after its two sponsors) has been plagued by bureaucratic delays on the American side and Minatom's suspicion on the Russian side. Yet it has helped speed the transportation of thousands of nuclear weapons from Belarus, Kazakhstan and Ukraine back to Russia; consolidate the number of sites within Russia where weapons are stored; improve basic security, from locks to computer-based radiation-detection systems, at some of the storage sites; and, among other projects, is helping to build a new plutonium storage facility at Chelyabinsk, in the Urals. Meanwhile, collaboration between American and Russian scientists is helping to stem Russia's skills drain.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nunn-Lugar money is only a bucketful in the ocean of Russia's nuclear problems. So far, it is true, there have been few serious cases of nuclear smuggling from Russia, and then only in quantities too small for bomb-building. Yet the danger will persist, indeed will grow, if morale in the armed forces continues to plummet. A special summit of the <font size=-1>G7</font> industrial countries and Russia held in Moscow in 1996 came up with a list of resolutions to co-operate more effectively to prevent proliferation. This activity is also a priority for the big powers' intelligence services, and is claiming a growing share of their budgets. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Add all this up, the money and the effort, and cleaning up after the nuclear era will be a long and costly business. Paradoxically, to the costs of disarmament may soon have to be added a little rearmament. If Russia goes on refusing to ratify <font size=-1>START-2</font>, America and Russia both may end up maintaining in working order thousands more nuclear warheads than they know they need. The nuclear era may have a longer half-life than anyone expected.<br><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?852339600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="sf0796.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>1997 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
