<DOCOLDNO>IA096-001030-B011-217</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.europe.economist.com:80/issue/04-01-97/sf0796.html 199.173.162.110 19970215020222 text/html 20953
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 01:58:20 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 10-Jan-97 12:29:17 GMT
Content-length: 20767
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Circles of fear</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="defence.gif" alt="Special feature"><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table><p><b>An anti-missile shield</b></p><h1>Circles of fear</h1><p><b>The cost of destroying nuclear weapons is not the only growing problem of post-cold-war defence. The West also faces a threat from the proliferation of cruise and ballistic missiles. How should it respond?</b></p><br>IN 1944 and 1945 the Nazis used both cruise and ballistic missiles. German <font size=-1>V1</font>s flew low towards London, rather like aeroplanes. These, the first cruise missiles, killed over 5,000 civilians even though fighter aircraft shot down some. Then came the <font size=-1>V2</font>s, rockets which flew high out of the atmosphere and dropped onto their targets with such speed that no defence was possible. These "ballistic" missiles--called that after their curved trajectories--killed 2,500 Londoners.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The technology the Germans pioneered in the early 1940s is no longer difficult to acquire. The Falklands war revealed the military value of cruise missiles: Argentina sank two British ships with (French-made) air-launched Exocets. The Iran-Iraq war showed the power of ballistic missiles to intimidate and terrify civilians. During one six-month phase of that war, in 1987-88, Iraq rained down missiles on Tehran, killing 2,000 Iranians and driving half of the population from the city. During the 1991 Gulf war, Saddam Hussein's strongest card was his stock of Al Hussein ballistic missiles. His attacks on Israeli towns nearly provoked the Israeli retaliation which could have ruptured the allied coalition. Those attacks killed just two people, but a missile which hit an American base in Saudi Arabia killed 28. These weapons can also be used to try to frighten governments: last March China fired four <font size=-1>DF-15</font> ballistic missiles into the sea near Taiwan.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So it is perhaps hardly surprising that growing numbers of third-world governments are finding the case for developing or buying missiles irresistible. If your neighbour's military prowess is a worry, or if you wish to stop the West from pushing you around, missiles appear to offer a solution. They are easier to make and cheaper to acquire than squadrons of fighter aircraft. According to the defence studies centre at Britain's Lancaster University, 35 non-<font size=-1>NATO</font> countries have ballistic missiles, including Algeria, Belarus, Kazakhstan, Egypt, India, Israel, Pakistan and Saudi Arabia. And it reckons that 18 non-<font size=-1>NATO</font> countries are capable of installing either nuclear, biological or chemical warheads.<br></p><p><b><b>The infamous five</b></b><br>The greatest potential menace are the five "rogue" regimes, some of which have helped each other's missile programmes: Iran, Iraq (see <a href="sf5.gif">chart</a>), Libya (see <a href="sf3.gif">chart</a>), Syria and North Korea (see <a href="sf4.gif">chart</a>). The last is the most dangerous of all, for it has tested a ballistic missile with a 700-mile (1,120-kilometre) range, called the Nodong, and is probably developing a two-stage missile (the Taepo Dong 2) with a range of 2,500-4,000 miles. Iran has helped to finance North Korea's missile programme and is reported to be, like Libya, keen to buy the results. Fired from North Korea, Nodongs could reach Japan; from Iran, Israel would be in range; and from Libya, parts of Southern Europe would be threatened. From Pyongyang, the Taepo Dong 2 might reach parts of Hawaii or Alaska; from Libya, it could reach London.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Cruise missiles may pose as great a threat. Compared with ballistic missiles, they are often more accurate (some can use satellites to navigate), sometimes harder to shoot down (they can be stealthy and swerve) and about a quarter of the price. The Lancaster team estimates that 67 non-<font size=-1>NATO</font> countries possess cruise missiles (even though most of them are short-range anti-ship weapons). India is producing the Lakshya, a missile with a range of 350 miles, while China, Iran and North Korea have cruise missiles of similar ranges.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Slowly, politicians in the West are waking up to the dangers. Even if the missiles cannot hit western countries directly, they can have an impact on western foreign policies. Imagine the West were to send another expeditionary force to the Middle East. It could be attacked by more sophisticated missiles than Iraqi Al Husseins.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Should governments seek to defend not only troops on such missions, but also cities at home? Should they be prepared to counter Russian and Chinese missiles, as well as those of rogue dictators? Can they make missile defences compatible with the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile (<font size=-1>ABM</font>) treaty, by which the Soviet Union and the United States agreed to limit their defences against inter-continental ballistic missiles (<font size=-1>ICBM</font>s)? And which of the anti-missile technologies actually work?<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In America and parts of East Asia these questions are matters of serious debate. In Europe, few people are concerned. Yet it is Europe, not America, which faces the more immediate threat from missiles.<br></p><p><b><b>Four defences</b></b><br>Western governments can respond to the danger of hostile missiles in four ways. They can, through diplomacy, seek to reinforce the <b>Missile Technology Control Regime </b>(<font size=-1>MTCR</font>), an agreement among 28 states to curb exports of key components. Russia has joined; China has not, but says it will observe the regime's rules; none of the rogue states is a member. The regime has no enforcement mechanisms, and does not apply to civilian rocket technology, which is little different from the military sort. So the regime--like some bilateral agreements--has slowed but not prevented the diffusion of missile know-how.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Governments can hope to <b>deter missile attacks.</b> Any state which launched a missile at a western country could expect to be bombed. But deterrence works only if the regimes concerned can make rational calculations of their own self-interest; some dictators find that hard.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Governments can <b>attack missile launch sites.</b> But the Gulf war illustrated the difficulties: although a significant part of America's air power was deployed in search of Iraq's well-hidden mobile launchers, none was destroyed from the air.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The imperfections of these three responses have led America and Israel to pursue a fourth: <b>missile defence systems.</b> The interceptors and radars required are neither cheap nor easy to develop. The Americans have spent nearly $50 billion on missile defence since President Reagan launched "star wars"--officially, the Strategic Defence Initiative--in 1983, but have still not got the cleverer ideas, such as space-based lasers, to work.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ballistic missiles can be shot down at three points on their flight: during the early "boost phase"; in mid-course, when most of them are outside the atmosphere; and in the terminal phase, shortly before they strike. Ideally, a defender should hit a missile during the boost phase, before it can divide into multiple warheads (if it has them) and so that the debris falls on the enemy. But that kind of interception is hard to achieve, for the boost phase even of a long-range missile will last less than three minutes; by the time satellites have spotted the launch and informed the defender, that phase may be over.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The next best time to hit the missile is in mid-course: if an interceptor misses there is time for another shot. The terminal phase is the worst time, for any debris will fall on the defender's country. But terminal interceptions are the easiest to achieve with current technology. During the Gulf war Patriot, a short-range system designed to protect particular sites, engaged Iraqi missiles with some success. Such short-range systems can also hit cruise missiles.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the time being, America can deploy only short-range systems. But the possible shape of new anti-missile defences can be discerned there, in the work of the Ballistic Missile Defence Organisation (<font size=-1>BMDO</font>). Its chief priority is to defend American forces overseas. This is because America's intelligence agencies have concluded that no rogue regime will be able to develop ballistic missiles that can threaten the continental United States for at least 15 years.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>BMDO</font> is working on three short-range systems: an upgraded version of Hawk, an interceptor used by the Marines; an improved Patriot, with a new missile, for the army; and a sea-borne Navy Area Defence System. It is also developing two defences designed to protect larger areas through mid-course interception. They are called Navy Theatre Wide and, for the army, Theatre High-Altitude Area Defence (acronym: <font size=-1>THAAD</font>). Both these have undergone trials, but neither of their interceptors has yet succeeded in hitting a missile.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As for that ideal of blowing up a missile in its "boost phase", a ship armed with Navy Theatre Wide that was close to the missile launch site might achieve it. The Pentagon has just awarded a contract for a prototype jumbo jet-borne laser that will-- it hopes--destroy missiles in the boost phase. But the technical obstacles remain formidable. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A second and lower priority for the Clinton administration is a limited system of national missile defence, consisting of 100 interceptors linked to ground-based early-warning radars. This could protect against <font size=-1>ICBM</font>s from rogue states, though not much else. The administration says that it will spend the next three years developing this system and will then decide whether to spend a further three years deploying it.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The administration's final priority is to continue research on more advanced technologies, such as space-based lasers and sensors, descendants of star wars. It is surely developing more varieties of missile defence than will actually be needed. But the American defence budget--now $265 billion a year--has room for them all. In any case, each service demands its own sorts of missile defence.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Clinton administration insists that it wishes to abide by the <font size=-1>ABM</font> treaty, which permits theatre defences as well as a maximum of 100 interceptors aimed at <font size=-1>ICBM</font>s. However, some of the programmes under development would, if deployed, breach the treaty. For instance it permits only ground-based defences and outlaws those based on "other physical principles". That means that lasers--whether airborne or space-based--and satellite radars, if integrated with batteries of interceptors, would contravene the treaty.<br><b>Clinton in the middle</b><br>President Clinton's policy on missile defence faces two groups of domestic critics: those who think the government should do less, many of whom are on the left, and those who think it should do more, many of whom are on the right. The first group sees little point in spending money on missile defence: a dictator who wished to terrorise a western city, they say, would find it simpler to pack a lorry with explosives than to develop long-range missiles.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These sceptics also doubt the efficacy of missile defence systems. Ted Postol, a professor at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, claims that none of the Patriots fired during the Gulf war destroyed an Al Hussein (though classified army studies suggest a 60% success rate). Mr Postol believes that <font size=-1>THAAD</font><t--mode> </t--mode> interceptors (the army's theatre-wide anti-missile system) could easily be defeated anyway. A missile might split into several warheads and decoys to confuse the interceptors. <font size=-1>THAAD</font>'s defenders reply that such counter-measures would be neither cheap nor easy for a rogue regime to master: Britain spent 13 years and several billion pounds building Chevaline, a nuclear missile with multiple warheads and decoys.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lastly, the critics claim that America's theatre defence programmes are undermining the <font size=-1>ABM</font> treaty. Mr Postol argues that, if space-based radars were integrated with <font size=-1>THAAD</font>, America would have a shield capable of defending against strategic missiles, which the treaty forbids. He points out that General Malcolm O'Neill, the former director of <font size=-1>BMDO</font>, told Congress that one <font size=-1>THAAD</font> system could protect the British Isles, and that <font size=-1>THAAD</font> interceptors could in certain circumstances thwart <font size=-1>ICBM</font>s. Mr Postol reckons that a dozen such systems could cover the continental United States. That would seem to contradict the <font size=-1>ABM</font> treaty.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Pentagon retorts that <font size=-1>THAAD</font> could not be an effective strategic system because it has not been tested against missiles travelling faster than 5 kilometres a second; <font size=-1>ICBM</font>s travel at 7 kilometres a second (the longer the range, the faster the missile). It also points out that the Russians accepted, during recent negotiations on clarifying the <font size=-1>ABM</font> treaty, that interceptors which fly at less than 3 kilometres a second (<font size=-1>THAAD</font> ones go at just below that speed) are in accordance with the treaty.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But last October Russia pulled back from signing this clarification, saying it would not accept interceptors that fly more slowly than 3 kilometres a second until both parties had agreed whether faster systems such as the navy theatre-missile shield--with interceptors that go 4.5 kilometres a second--complied with the treaty. The Russians show no signs of accepting those faster interceptors.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Americans say they hope the Russians will accept that the Navy Theatre Wide system complies with the treaty; but that if they do not, it will be deployed anyway, because the administration has unilaterally determined that the treaty permits it. The Russians are livid.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;America's missile hawks do not care: they would like to scrap the <font size=-1>ABM</font> treaty altogether. They view it as a relic of the cold war, when, since both America and the Soviet Union lacked missile defences, neither would risk starting a nuclear war. They argue that it has no relevance in an unstable world of irrational dictators and rapidly proliferating missile technology. The administration's view that no third-world missile attack on the continental United States would be feasible for 15 years is, to them, misleading, for it assumes that neither Russia nor China will help a rogue regime and forgets that Hawaii or Alaska could be hit much sooner. They think the president is surrounded by peaceniks who are ideologically opposed to missile defence and will never allow him to deploy any form of national defensive system.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Heritage Foundation, a hawkish think-tank, proposes, for a start, upgrading the navy's theatre-missile defence system, which is based around the powerful "Aegis" radars carried on many warships. Then it would integrate space-based sensors with that system before switching, in the long run, to space-based lasers or interceptors. This would give America a lightweight shield, effective against missiles from rogue states, China or a mad Russian submariner, but not against the full force of the Russian arsenal. The Heritage Foundation claims that all this could be deployed for an additional $2 billion a year, beyond <font size=-1>BMDO</font>'s current budget of around $3.5 billion.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Bob Dole, the Republican presidential candidate, supported the idea of deploying a national missile defence system but did not specify the sort he wanted. He never made it an election issue, perhaps because most Americans seem unenthusiastic about space-based missile defence.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The chiefs of staff, who have other spending priorities, see merit in the argument of Bill Perry, the outgoing defence secretary, that there is no point in deploying a system before a threat emerges, for its technology would soon be out of date; and that it would be better to work on improving the technology until deployment is necessary. They recognise that, if America scrapped the <font size=-1>ABM</font> treaty, Russia would neither ratify the <font size=-1>START</font>-<font size=-1>2</font> treaty (limiting nuclear weapons) nor engage in further efforts at arms control.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In May 1996 the Congressional Budget Office reported that Mr Dole's "Defend America Bill"--which implied a need for space-based systems similar to those proposed by the Heritage Foundation--would cost an extra $30 billion-60 billion by 2010. That excludes operating costs (likely to be $2 billion-4 billion a year) and assumes no cost overruns. This report helped turn Congress away from star wars-style programmes and scotched the Dole bill. All the same, Congress has forced the administration to spend more on theatre missile defence in 1996-97.<br><b>Planetary problem</b><br>Israel is surrounded by potentially hostile states, brimming with missiles. So it is not surprising that it will be the first country to deploy a national missile defence system. For a country of Israel's size, theatre defence is national defence. With the help of American money, it has developed Arrow, a system designed to hit missiles in mid-course. And if Arrow fails to hit a missile, Patriot will take a shot.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Patriot system has been sold to Germany, the Netherlands, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Japan and, in modified form, to Taiwan. The Japanese, who lie within range of Chinese and North Korean missiles, are upgrading their Patriot interceptors and talking to the Americans about buying a theatre system. That has angered China, which fears that its own fairly limited strategic arsenal could be disabled by such a system or by America's plans for a national missile defence. But the more bellicose the behaviour of China and North Korea, the more likely are Japan, South Korea and Taiwan to invest in national defence systems.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Few European governments take the threat of missiles seriously. Three that did were France, Germany and Italy. A few years ago, they began work, together with America, on a "Medium Extended Air Defence System", a more mobile and powerful short-range system than Patriot. But the French pulled out in 1996 and, although the Americans are putting pressure on the British to join, the system is far from certain to be built.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since troops on expeditionary forces generally serve in multinational coalitions, it would make sense for <font size=-1>NATO</font> governments to develop a common protective system. And there would be little point in their seeking to protect their cities (if they reach that point) without collaborating. <font size=-1>NATO</font> has decided that it must protect expeditionary forces. But any decision to deploy a missile defence system will require consensus, painstaking negotiations, and lots of time. Unless, course, a rogue missile strikes a <font size=-1>NATO</font> city.<br><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?852339600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="xm0008.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>1997 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
