<html><head><title>Brain strain and the Gulf war</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width="371" height="26" alt="Science and Technology" border=0><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table><h1>Brain strain and the Gulf war</h1>THOUSANDS of British and American veterans are busy lobbying their reluctant governments to keep an open mind about "Gulf-war syndrome", a controversial collection of symptoms including respiratory disease, skin disorders and fatigue. It seems, however, that war may open some soldiers' minds, too--in many cases a little too literally. Research in Israel by Alon Friedman at Ben Gurion University of the Negev, in Beersheva, and Hermona Soreq at the Hebrew University in Jerusalem suggests that stress may cause soldiers' blood-brain barriers to leak.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a recent paper in <i>Nature Medicine</i>, Dr Friedman and Dr Soreq follow up an earlier observation that Israeli soldiers from the Gulf-war period are three times more likely than peacetime volunteers to experience central-nervous-system effects from a substance known as pyridostigmine. This chemical is an anti-nerve-gas agent widely used to protect troops from the effects of organophosphates in chemical weapons. It is designed to safeguard the peripheral nervous system from the effects of such weapons, thus keeping essential organs--particularly the heart and lungs--functioning.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But pyridostigmine cannot enter the brain (where it causes such tell-tale symptoms as headaches, insomnia and nervousness) unless the blood-brain barrier is breached. Dr Friedman and Dr Soreq believe that stress, of both mind and body, is to blame for the soldiers' fragile brain defences. They have found that mice put under pressure--by forcing them to swim a few laps of a small swimming pool, for instance--are 100 times more susceptible to the brain effects of pyridostigmine than those allowed to rest. This is primarily due to the increase in the amount of the drug that can cross the blood-brain barrier.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The biochemical basis of the connection between stress and the blood-brain barrier, though noted in other experiments, is as yet unknown. Dr Soreq speculates that neurotransmitters such as serotonin--a known disrupter of the barrier which has recently been implicated in anxiety disorders--may play a part.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Stress afflicts patients, as well as soldiers. If the blood-brain barrier does open up under duress, this creates new opportunities for delivering drugs to the brain and new complications for sending them to other organs. In medicine as in war, a weak defence demands a careful offence.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?852339600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="index.html">Contents</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>1997 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
