<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<!-- Changed by: manar hussain, 19-Dec-1996 -->
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="busthisyear.gif" width="268" height="26" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>On the defensive</h2>
 <p>
The reconstruction of <b>America's defence industry</b> reached a climax when Boeing announced its takeover of McDonnell Douglas-- which will make it the world's biggest aerospace group. Northrop Grumman bought Westinghouse's defence-electronics business and Lockheed Martin bought most of Loral. By contrast, Europe managed one joint venture, in missiles, between Matra and British Aerospace.<p>
<b>Asia's businessmen</b> worried about slower growth. A collapse in electronics exports hit Singapore and Taiwan. And in South Korea, a slowing economy forced conglomerates to cut back at home while pushing even harder overseas. The rising Asian star was the Philippines.<p>
Although a lower yen helped exports, record losses plagued <b>corporate Japan</b>. Sumitomo Corporation, a trading company, racked up the largest trading losses in the country's history, thanks to the activities of its head copper trader, who was accused of fraud.<p>
<b>Conglomerates </b>were out, focus was in. Lord Hanson, Britain's arch-predator of the 1980s, broke up his eponymous group. <b>Daimler-Benz</b> started dismantling the industrial empire it created in the 1980s and went back to cars and some aerospace, leaving Fokker, its Dutch subsidiary, to go bust.<p>
<b>Airline alliances </b>multiplied. Germany and America signed an "open skies" treaty freeing air traffic between the two, allowing United and Lufthansa to get together. British Airways, taxiing to a deal with American Airlines, is selling its stake in <font size=-1>US</font> Air. <p>
<b>America's tobacco industry</b> had a hard year. Its legal ramparts, impregnable for 40 years, were breached when a court awarded a man with lung cancer $750,000 damages against a cigarette maker. Bill Clinton warmed to a proposal to restrict sales and advertising on the ground that nicotine is a drug.<p>
<h2>Wired</h2>
 <p>
(See <a href="bw1.gif">table</a>)<br>A law opening America's <b>telecoms markets </b>brought mergers galore. Most notable was the $21 billion takeover of <font size=-1>MCI</font>, America's second-largest long-distance firm, by Britain's <font size=-1>BT</font>. In Europe, where liberalisation is due in 1998, progress was slower--though <b>Deutsche Telekom</b> was partially privatised. Japan pretended to split up <b>NTT</b>.<p>
<b>Microsoft</b> embraced the Internet, which had challenged the company's dominance of the computer-software industry. Microsoft's new Internet software threatened to dethrone Netscape, the Internet king of 1995.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
Consolidation continued in <b>drugs and health care</b>. Ciba and Sandoz, two Swiss drug firms, merged to form the world's largest life-sciences company, Novartis. Aetna took over U.S. Healthcare to become America's biggest medical-benefits group. Trials of protease inhibitors, a new type of <b>drug for AIDS</b>, brought hope that the disease might be controllable.<p>
France bungled two privatisations. The sale of <b>Thomson</b>, a defence-electronics firm, fell apart after the privatisation committee said Thomson's multimedia unit should not be sold to a South Korean firm; that of <b>CIC</b>, a group of regional banks, failed when the committee said the bidding had been mismanaged.<p>
<b>Olivetti</b>, a computer maker once symbolising Italian flair, drifted towards disaster, shedding its long-time boss, Carlo De Benedetti, on the way.<p>
<h2>Courting couples</h2>
<b>Rogue-watchers </b>were busy. Deutsche Bank bailed out Morgan Grenfell Asset Management after a unit-trust manager breached investment rules. A manager at Jardine Fleming caused the Hong Kong-based merchant bank similar embarrassment.<p>
<b>Lloyd's of London</b> settled with its names, the once-rich investors who supply the insurance market's capital. The agreement will allow the market to pay for past losses while underwriting new risks.<p>
<b>In court</b>: Ian and Kevin Maxwell were acquitted in London of fraud; Australia's Alan Bond wasn't, and was jailed; the European Court of Human Rights decided Ernest Saunders, ex-Guinness, had an unfair trial in 1990; German prosecutors indicted Jose Ignacio Lopez, General Motors' defector to Volkswagen, for betraying company secrets; and Swiss banks were pressed to reveal their holdings of war-time loot.<p>
Two <b>banking mega-mergers</b> were sealed: Bank of Tokyo's marriage to Mitsubishi Bank, and Chase Manhattan's to Chemical. A big new one in the pipeline: NationsBank's $9 billion purchase of Boatmen's Bancshares.<p>
Consolidation continued in <b>global insurance</b>. Two of the biggest deals: Munich Re, the largest reinsurer, purchased American Re; and France's <font size=-1>AXA</font> merged with Union des Assurances de Paris.<p>
<h2>Bullish</h2>
(See <a href="bw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>The rampant Dow set the tone for <b>stockmarkets </b>almost everywhere except Tokyo: the Nikkei rose only 1%.<p>
At the first pow-wow of trade ministers since the Uruguay round of <font size=-1>GATT</font>, the <b>World Trade Organisation</b> reached agreement in principle on scrapping tariffs on high-technology goods.<p>
<b>Oil prices </b>beat expectations. Brent crude rose from $18 a barrel in January to $25 in October, dipping later when the first exports of Iraqi crude for six years began after partial lifting of a <font size=-1>UN</font> embargo.<p>
<p>

</td></tr></table></center>
